cuses</head>
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis held a strong lead over jesse jackson as washington state party officials released results tuesday from last week's democratic presidential precinct caucuses
with about 68 percent of the precincts reporting the results of last tuesday's balloting, dukakis had 45 percent, jackson 35 percent, and 14 percent were uncommitted
all the other candidates were well off the pace, with illinois sen. paul simon a weak fourth at 4 percent, tennessee sen. albert gore jr. 2 percent and rep. richard gephardt of missouri 1 percent
the democratic party made no effort to collect results statewide on caucus night, gathering precinct returns slowly by mail instead
republicans say it will be at least another week before county chairmen submit the names of gop delegates elected in last week's precinct caucuses
the national election service reported last week that, with 71 percent of the republican precincts reporting, former television evangelist pat robertson led with 39 percent. sen. bob dole of kansas finished second with 26 percent and vice president george bush got 24 percent
a 24-year-old man has pleaded guilty to involuntary manslaughter in the death of his two children, who died last summer hours after he locked them inside his car
john shields of white township entered the plea monday, and faces a maximum 10-year prison term and $20,000 fine
judge francis searer deferred sentencing pending an investigation by probation officials
shields testified at his wife's trial two weeks ago that he agreed to watch their children, kristle, 3, and calvin, 1, on the morning of aug. 22, but instead locked them in the car and closed the windows
the children were discovered in the afternoon, when the temperature reached the mid-80s, authorities said
lisa shields pleaded guilty to reduced charges and also is awaiting sentencing
both parents were charged with two counts of involuntary manslaughter and endangering the welfare of children. the more severe counts against mrs. shields were dropped
the two endangerment counts were incorporated in shields' guilty plea, court officials said
good morning, vietnam'' was moviegoers' favorite for the the ninth-straight weekend, tying it with ``crocodile dundee'' for the longest consecutive time at the top
second in last weekend's box office survey was ``vice versa,'' featuring a judge reinhold transformation into a prepubescent kid, followed by ``masquerade'' in third and ``off limits'' fourth
all 10 top grossing films combined took in about $30 million, with ``good morning, vietnam'' ringing up a mere $4.36 million during the pre-easter vacation box office doldrums
it's another down week,'' said john krier of exhibitor relations co., which surveys the studios' weekly performance at the box office. ``it looks like we're marking time until easter.''
for the easter break, the studios are releasing the animated feature ``the fox and the hounds,'' alan alda's ``a new life,'' matthew broderick's ``biloxi blues'' and anthony michael hall's ``johnny b. goode.''
in addition to ``good morning, vietnam,'' the disney studios had two other pictures in the top 10. ``three men and a baby'' was seventh 7 after 15 weeks in release and ``shoot to kill'' ninth
the lure of romance between rob lowe and meg tilly gave ``masquerade'' a debut weekend gross of $3.5 million while the willem dafoe-gregory hines cop thriller ``off limits'' earned $2.8 million
in fifth was cher's critically-acclaimed ``moonstruck,'' which won her a golden globe trophy and an oscar nomination, followed by harrison ford's ``frantic'' in sixth and ``three men and a baby'' in seventh
moving,'' starring richard pryor as a new york engineer forced to relocate his family to boise, idaho, earned more than $2.4 million to place eighth, followed by ``shoot to kill.''
in 10th place was ``switching channels,'' a broadcast version of the venerable newsroom comedy ``the front page.'' it earned $1.9 million in its second week
here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by exhibitor relations co., with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater screens, average per screen, total gross, number of weeks in release and estimated production costs
1. ``good morning, vietnam,'' disney-touchstone, $4.36 million, 1,579 screens, $2,767 per screen, $91.5 million, 11 weeks, $21 million
2. ``vice versa,'' columbia, $4.05 million, 1,225 screens, $3,306 per screen, $4.05 million, one week, n-a
3. ``masquerade,'' mgm-ua, $3.5 million, 1,030 screens, $3,398 per screen, $3.5 million, one week, n-a
4. ``off limits,'' 20th century fox, $2.79 million, 1,366 screens, $2,047 per screen, $2.79 million, one week, n-a
5. ``moonstruck,'' mgm-ua, $2.66 million, 1,155 screens, $2,309 per screen, $49.37 million, 12 weeks, $17 million
6. ``frantic,'' warner bros., $2.60 million, 1,054 screens, $2,469 per screen, $13.2 million, two weeks, $20 million
7. ``three men and a baby,'' disney-touchstone, $2.55 million, 1,348 screens, $1,893 per screen, $147.6 million, 15 weeks, $18 million
8. ``moving,'' warner bros., $2.4 million, 1,404 screens, $1,732 per screen, $7.49 million, two weeks, n-a
9. ``shoot to kill,'' disney-touchstone, $2 million, 1,037 screens, $1,956 per screen, $24.2 million, four weeks, $18 million
10. ``switching channels,'' tri-star, $1.94 million, 971 screens, $2,002 per screen, $5.8 million, two weeks, n-a
cbs and nbc said they will broadcast half-hour news specials on illinois primary election returns tonight at 11:30 p.m. est
abc planned no full-length election special but will devote the first six minutes of its ``nightline'' program at 11:30 p.m. to election returns, abc said
cable news network said it will provide periodic reports and a half-hour program on election returns at 1 a.m. wednesday
abc, nbc and cbs also were broadcasting brief special reports on voting results
nbc planned five-minute news briefs at 8:55 p.m. and 9:55 p.m. and its half-hour special at 11:30 p.m., with ``nbc nightly news'' anchorman tom brokaw as host, said spokeswoman mary lou o'callaghan
cbs planned one prime-time news brief, with the time yet to be set, and an 11:30 p.m. special program, with ``cbs evening news'' anchorman dan rather as host, said donna dees, spokeswoman for the network
cnn will air five- to seven-minute reports at every half hour from 8 p.m. to 10:30 p.m. and will devote its ``inside politics'' program at 1 a.m. to election returns, said spokeswoman kitsie bassett
what shim min-sop is doing now conceivably could have landed him in jail not so long ago. he's drawing cartoons that poke gentle fun at south korean political leaders
and people are getting a laugh out of them, without worrying that something could happen to them as well
shim's cartoons seem tame by most standards. politicians and political parties are parodied as rival baseball teams and the jibes are never too strong. nevertheless, shim says, it is a remarkable change
in the past it was a taboo to caricature the big political names in this country,'' he said
ridiculing the president or making jokes about him, for example, were seen as anti-state acts
shim and other cartoonists have been able to take advantage of recent political liberalization in south korea to start injecting a little laughter and ridicule into politics
the cartoonists contend that political caricature is healthy and korean politics can benefit from it
cartoons and caricatures will bring the political leaders closer to the people,'' shim maintained
political cartoons have proliferated in newspapers and magazines and command large, enthusiastic audiences eager for a regular flow of material ranging from traditional editorial cartoons to long stories. literacy is very high in south korea but people prize cartoons for their humor
newspaper cartoons so far are low-key and ironic. some recent ones showed caricatures of the main political parties chasing each other in an unending circle, to symbolize ineffectiveness. another showed top leaders as squabbling babies
a favorite of cartoonists is to have bemused koreans staring at politicians battling for power and asking what is happening to the country
it is refreshing to see the taboos broken about the myths surrounding the political bigwigs,'' said han kye-su, a political analyst who has followed the growth of political cartooning
many cartoonists say they have always seen their work as a way of calling for reform and liberalization
korean cartoonists have been struggling for political change for a long time,'' shim said
cartoons are a valuable teaching tool that can vividly explain the meaning of an issue as well as amuse readers, shim added
the political cartoonist can present the issues in a more amusing, but understandable manner to the public.''
the newly installed president roh tae-woo, who pledged freedom of speech and expression after years of authoritarian rule, personally encouraged cartoonists to take up political subjects by saying he did not mind being caricatured
shim and other cartoonists say their work is still very gentle and restrained for fear of angering authorities and losing what freedom they have. but they say they expect to make their humor more biting as time goes on and liberalization expands
cartoonists are also restrained by fear of offending a politician's supporters, shim said. korea's factional politics stress loyalty and supporters tend to resent any joke at their leader's expense, he said
the reaction can be terrible from the supporters,'' shim said. ``people should learn to accept both positive and negative.''
anti-government students and dissident groups, which have long used cartoons in their political literature, also are making greater use of caricatures, but usually not in a humorous way
the cartoons distributed at anti-government rallies and meetings are biting and bitter. government and mainline opposition politicians are depicted as vicious tyrants suppressing the people with tear gas and clubs. some are more subtle, depicting the divided opposition leaders as crying infants quarreling over a toy
they are not jokes,'' said one dissident. ``they show the people the reality of the government and why there is no democracy in south korea.''
anti-government cartoons are distributed in pamphlets on college campuses or posted on trees and sidewalks at anti-government rallies
the united states, represented by a fiendish-looking uncle sam or a swaggering and bullying american soldier, is a fixture in the underground cartoons. dissidents claim the country's successive authoritarian governments have survived because of u.s. backing
one recent cartoon showed a tough-looking statue of liberty with a boxing glove on her upraised hand
shim and other cartoonists reject their underground competition and the radical politics behind it. they say change must be moderate
it's too early to expose politicians to a more revealing fashion,'' shim said
mayoral elections in colombia have left a small crack in the political fortress of the upper class, the power behind this latin american country since it won independence from spain in 1819
the elections on sunday marked the first time that mayors had been elected in colombia. previously, they were appointed by governors, who were appointed by the president
and the president always came from the liberal or the conservative parties that are manipulated by the rich
but a leftist coalition, the patriotic union party, won at least 14 of l,008 mayoral posts in sunday's election, which in some cases brought people from the poorer classes closer to the seat of power in local politics
the money and power of the traditional parties ruled out in most cases, such as in bogota where andres pastrana, the son of former president misael pastrana, was elected mayor on the conservative ticket
the liberal party of president virgilio barco won 430 of the mayoral races, and the conservative party won 402 mayoral posts. coalition candidates won 24 of the mayoral elections
other results may not be known for a week because of the remoteness of many towns
the showing by the new patriotic union was small. but the results were surprising given that the party was organized just three years ago
the leftist coalition also had to survive a wave of assassinations by right-wing death squads that killed 520 of the members of the party, including its president, jaime pardo
the patriotic union also had to confront a colonial attitude of patronage
entire towns and areas traditionally adhere to one of the two traditional parties. until recently, people did not join political parties. they were born into them
it is common knowledge that failure of a peasant to support the party controlling an area means virtual economic suicide. a loan application at the local bank for buying seed will be rejected. a worker will be turned away when looking for a job at a big hacienda
colombians still call the rich la rosca, a kind of intertwined pastry. the term refers to a loose intertwining of influential people _ politicians, businessmen, landowners, doctors and lawyers _ who control the lives of the poor
nowhere are the poor more aware of la rosca than in small towns, where the wealthy own most of the rural land
a 1970 government study showed that 4.3 percent of the people in colombia owned 68 percent of the land. ten percent of the farms held 80 percent of total farmland. those figures probably have not changed much
the government's concession to hold mayoral elections is an indication that colombia may be heading toward true democracy
the country has a long history of violence, perpetuated largely by a political elite that refused to reform partisan traditions
for example, elements of the liberal party resisted social changes in 1948. a charasmatic liberal leader, jorge elicer gaitan, broke away from the party and ran as an independent. gaitan was assassinated shortly afterward
people saw their only hope of bettering their lives cut down, and the frustration exploded into the worst disturbances ever seen in colombia
that period, known simply as the violence, has had an impact upon colombian politics ever since
so when former president belisario betancur offered peace talks to the country's leftist guerrillas in 1984, most people approved. perhaps they recognized that the need for social changes were again putting pressure on the system
the guerrillas said in 1985 they wanted a government more responsive to the poor people. for starters, they said they wanted the election of mayors
betancur agreed, and the congress approved a constitutional amendement to allow the first election in 1988
the peace talks collapsed last year, but the government went ahead with the elections
the army says there are about 5,000 leftist guerrillas in colombia. the rebels claim they have close to 20,000 combatants. whatever the number, their forces are growing each year
ten years ago the army said there were only about 2,500 guerrillas
the growth of guerrilla forces and the possibility of another upheaval probably will depend greatly on whether the wealthy will concede to such programs as land reform, housing programs and building more schools and hospitals in rural areas
the government's attitude toward social change continues to be cautious. the election of mayors is a beginning, but not a solution
tom wells is bureau chief for the associated press in colombia
a soviet dissident whose pleas for an exit visa were ignored until he stepped up his reporting of human rights abuses has found a new home in the west
theodore kizelov, 43, arrived in rhode island last tuesday after a journey that led from sverdlovsk, a town in the ural mountains, through vienna and rome to the united states
the tolstoy foundation, an international, non-profit organization that helps resettle political refugees, found him an apartment and gave him enough money to live on for a month, said maureen dalpe of the woonsocket chapter
kizelov, who had never been outside the soviet union before his expulsion, learned english by listening to british radio broadcasts and should have little trouble finding a job, ms. dalpe said
i will start with any job available,'' said kizelov, ``even washing dishes in a restaurant.''
kizelov had been a dissident since the late 1970s, when he wrote what he calls his first ``open letter'' opposing the government _ a statement against the soviet invasion of afghanistan. he sent the letter to the moscow monitor and helsinki group, which published it outside the soviet union
i didn't begin to hide until 1983,'' kizelov said, because in general, it is safe to risk criticizing the soviet government without reprisals for three years or so
but the kgb patrols that began following him that year did not deter him
to make himself a difficult target, kizelov began moving from city to city. he held odd jobs, and friends helped with money. meanwhile, he continued to gather information about soviet human rights violations, sending the information to groups interested in publishing it
last fall, kizelov found himself working as a theater decorator in sverdlovsk, a town whose former political boss, boris yeltsin, had been promoted to serve as the communist party's first secretary of moscow
yeltsin was drummed out of office by party officials last november after delivering a speech that reportedly rankled powerful officials in the communist party, including general secretary mikhail gorbachev
officials in sverdlovsk, however, took a dim view of one of their favorite sons being kicked out of office, and began demonstrating in public. kizelov wrote about it
he sent his 3,000-word report on the demonstrations and a cover letter to sergei grigoryants, editor of a moscow-based underground magazine called glasnost. the sporadically-published magazine takes its cue from gorbachev's policy of ``openness'' in public affairs
but grigoryants never received the report. kizelov assumes it was intercepted by soviet police. a short while after sending it, he received an ``invitation'' to report to the emigration office to talk about his desire to leave the soviet union
they say nothing until i was involved in the demonstrations,'' said kizelov
while americans seem to be cautiously optimistic about the policy of glasnost, kizelov calls it a ``mask.'' he says soviet society is intolerant of anything but the official line and there is no such thing as freedom of speech
i don't like the socialist way of life in principle,'' said kizelov. ``in my opinion, it is the wrong way of development.'' one of slain guerrillas, protestants pelt funeral procession with stones. pick up 6th graf pvs: police, relatives of...</note>
a funeral procession bearing the bodies of three ira guerrillas slain in gibraltar was met by thousands of people when it arrived early tuesday under heavy rain at roman catholic west belfast
jeering protestants waving british flags had hurled stones and bottles at the cortege in northern ireland as it made its way by road to belfast from dublin in the irish rep0ublic
mairead farrell, 31; daniel mccann, 30, and sean savage, 24, were unarmed and walking toward the gibraltar-spanish border when british commandos in civilian clothes shot them march 6
british officials said the three had planned to detonate a car bomb at a public military ceremony in britain's fortress colony at the southern tip of spain two days later
monday night british troops fatally shot a gunman near savage's belfast home. police identified the slain man as kevin mccracken, 33
a statement by belfast police headquarters said mccracken fired at an army patrol and the soldiers shot back. it said mccracken was jailed in 1978 for membership in the outlawed irish republican army and illegal possession of guns. the report said mccracken was released on parole in 1985
the coffins of the three slain guerrillas were carried into the homes of their families in west belfast
hundreds of police and soldiers, many in riot gear, were on duty as the funeral procession arrived in belfast
at newry, five miles north of the border town of carrickaron in the irish republic, the hearses with the bodies drove qround the predominantly catholic town for two hours monday night and were cheered by crowds of ira supporters
but on the outskirts of newry, 35 miles south of belfast, protestants threw bricks, bottles and stones at the vehicles, breaking some windows
farther north at loughbrickland and banbridge protestant crowds again pelted the cortege with stones and shouted abuse as police moved forward to disperse them
the hearses were escorted by police vehicles and followed by dozens of cars containing ira supporters
press association, britain's domestic news agency, said about 1,000 people met the coffins monday when they arrived from gibraltar at dublin's airport, many of them members of sinn fein, the ira's legal political arm
the cortege stopped briefly at the border at carrickaron when two senior officers of northern ireland's police force, the royal ulster constabulary, ordered the irish tricolors removed from the coffins
police, relatives of the slain guerrillas and sinn fein members reached a compromise after a 30-minute argument and the flags were folded up and left atop the coffins, covered with funeral wreaths
the ira is waging a guerrilla campaign to drive the british from northern ireland and unite the protestant-dominated province with the overwhelmingly catholic irish republic. at least 2,628 people have been killed since sectarian violence began in northern ireland in august 1969
sinn fein president gerry adams and other senior party figures led the airport reception. the coffins were draped in the green, orange and white irish flag and a priest recited prayers in irish and english
four women in black jackets and trousers formed an honor guard. a lone bagpiper played a lament
in the heavy mist, the coffins were transferred to three hearses. a cortege led by police, which grew to more than 100 cars, made its way along the 100-mile route to the border
about 20 cars continued from the border to belfast, capital of northern ireland, where the three will be buried wednesday or thursday
thousands of people lined the roads. scores of teen-agers held black flags at waist level as the convoy passed through the catholic town of drogheda. many drivers threw black flags from their car windows
on both sides of the border, black flags hung from lampposts along the route
the procession took three hours to cover the 60 miles to dundalk on the border, where 5,000 people turned out. another lone piper escorted the hearses through the town. an honor guard of four men and two women dressed in black marched beside them
royal air force soldiers loaded the coffins onto the jet in gibraltar because baggage workers would not handle them, british television networks reported
in northern ireland, the ira said it fired a three-volley rifle salute at a shrine in belfast to coincide with the bodies' arrival on irish soil
an ira statement circulated by sinn fein said the guerrillas wished the bereaved families ``peaceful and dignified funerals,'' which was seen as a possible hint that the funerals would be allowed to take place without demonstrations
in the past, funerals have been disrupted by hooded ira members firing salutes over the coffins and the police moving in to arrest them
police in the irish republic and british-ruled northern ireland were expected to mount a huge security operation to prevent such displays this time
sinn fein said the three guerrillas would be buried at milltown cemetery in belfast on wednesday or on thursday, saint patrick's day. relatives of the dead appealed for calm and a roman catholic bishop asked police and mourners to avoid violence
the royal ulster constabulary said it would intervene if necessary to stop armed displays at the funerals. with latest soviet comment. picks up 5th graf pvs, pakistan has .. . editing 11th graf pvs, in belgrade ... to conform. ^by mohammad aftab</note>
pressure mounted monday on pakistan to sign an afghan settlement aimed at securing the withdrawal of an estimated 115,000 soviet troops and end nine years of fighting in afghanistan
sources close to the talks said the pakistani chief representative, acting foreign minister zain noorani, received a message from the kremlin calling upon him to sign the documents without further delay
the chief afghan negotiator, foreign minister abdul wakil, scheduled a news conference for tuesday, the day soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev named as a target date for the conclusion of the nearly 6-year-old talks. gorbachev said moscow will bring home its troops starting may 15 if the settlement is signed tuesday
both sides have said they do not consider march 15 a rigid deadline. sources close to the talks, who declined to be identified, said that apart from pressing for the formation of an interim government, pakistan also felt that there are still some loose ends to be sorted out in the agreements that make up the peace package
the soviet deputy foreign minister, vadim loginov, told a news conference in belgrade, yugoslavia, on monday that moscow is still ``optimistic'' it can pull its troops out, but he acknowledged the geneva talks are encountering difficulties
nobody has set a definite deadline,'' he said. ``all that has been said is that if by the 15th (of march), the last of the four agreements has been signed, then we will begin to withdraw our forces.''
pakistan has been insisting that the formation of a transitional government in afghanistan be linked to the settlement
both kabul and moscow have adamantly rejected that condition
pakistan argues that only a broad-based government can guarantee implementation of the peace accords and the safe return of five million afghan refugees in pakistan and iran
we are ready to sign the moment our concerns are removed,'' noorani told reporters as his delegation left an afternoon meeting with u.n. mediator diego cordovez
before an earlier meeting in the morning, noorani had said, without elaborating, pakistan would ``announce something today.'' but there was no such announcement as the talks were adjourned until tuesday
in belgrade, where he was on a state visit, gorbachev was asked by a reporter if there was progress at the geneva talks. with a smile, he said, ``there is,'' and ``there will be,'' but did not elaborate
najib, president of afghanistan's pro-soviet government, accused pakistan monday of using tricks to block the final agreement
it can be said candidly that that people who resort to ruses and who don't want the document of the geneva talks to be signed are actually enemies of the refugees,'' najib was quoted as saying in an interview with the afghan news agency bakhtar excerpted by tass, the official soviet news agency
najib noted that pakistan once said the only issue between the two countries was an acceptable timetable for soviet withdrawal. he charged that pakistan raised questions about an interim government to delay the agreement
najib said the rebels are interested in the millions of afghan refugees only as a ``reserve of military force to be used as cannon fodder.''
noorani, meanwhile, was reported to be in constant touch with his capital, islamabad, where the cabinet held its third lengthy meeting in two days, presumably to weigh its next step. the swiss radio reported earlier that prime minister mohammad khan junejo had said a decision on whether pakistan would sign the settlement would be made monday
in another development, a spokesman for the fragile seven-party alliance of the anti-soviet guerrillas, revealed that moscow had rejected again any direct negotiations with the insurgents
the spokesman, gulbadin hekmatyar, who also leads the largest and most radical group in the alliance, said that no guerrilla delegation would be sent to geneva unless the soviets drop their opposition
hekmatyar, the leader of the hezb-i-islami group, is widely believed to be the next chief of the seven-party alliance following the resignation of yunis khalis for health reasons
unconfirmed reports indicated the 69-year-old khalis quit in protest over plans to send a guerrilla delegation to the geneva talks
hekmatyar said his appointment as leader of the alliance may be announced tuesday
but if there is a majority opposing my leadership, then i will not be chosen,'' he added, speaking in pakistan
only a month ago, bob dole looked ready to wrest the republican presidential nomination from george bush. now, he is desperately looking for ways to keep his white house hopes from being wiped out by bush bush in today's illinois primary
in mid-february, everything was looking up for dole. he had scored an upset win in the iowa caucuses, and as the new hampshire primary approached, polls were suggesting he could overtake the vice president in the state
but in one 48-hour stretch _ the final two days before the voting in new hampshire _ the dole campaign derailed, and has never gotten back on track
a combination of body blows _ weak organization, poor planning, a mean image and just bad luck _ has reduced the formidable minority leader of the senate to a battered, struggling candidate
with the vice president leading 2-to-1 in the illinois polls, the question dole faces over and over is when _ not if _ he will withdraw
dole said it will not be today or wednesday: ``i've made a judgment that illinois, whatever happens, we're going to keep going.''
from the start, dole was judged a tough contender for the 1988 nomination. a seasoned politician with national stature, the kansas senator was one republican who could match bush in fund-raising, name recognition and experience
but there were doubts about dole as well, doubts that all came to the surface the weekend before the new hampshire primary feb. 16 _ ``the 48 hours that cost them the campaign'' is how one republican professional described those days
he was ready to put bush away,'' said gop pollster lance tarrance, who worked for former candidate jack kemp
dole was riding the wave out of his big early win _ a triumph in the iowa caucuses on feb. 8. bush was a disappointing third behind former television evangelist pat robertson. that should have meant a big boost for dole for the new hampshire primary the next week
you need some luck...and dole didn't get much good luck out of iowa,'' tarrance said. ``the news of robertson beating out bush...was the big story.''
dole did start picking up strength in new hampshire. bush was down, and changing his style as his campaign struggled to recover
but by thursday of that week, bush was on the counterattack, readying ads accusing dole of ``straddling'' major issues. and the dole campaign could not get its act together to respond
one television commercial attacking bush _ called ``footsteps'' inside the campaign _ was ready thursday. but top aides viewed it and judged it ``unusable'' because of poor production and problems with the script, said two sources who spoke on the condition they not be named
dole tried twice that week to make a new spot, promising to veto any tax increases, but once again aides judged it not usable, a top dole adviser said, speaking on the condition of anonymity
when the new ads were ready late friday, the dole campaign couldn't get them on the air. the television stations were closing for the weekend, making it harder to switch the tapes at the stations
they couldn't get the old ads off the air and the new ones on,'' said the gop professional, who is not working for any campaign. ``that's what the campaign is supposed to be able to do. they didn't.''
then it was on to the south, where bush rode president reagan's popularity and his own solid organization to a wipeout win over dole on super tuesday
organizational problems have been a trademark of dole campaigns from the start. the wily senate operator was loath to delegate authority and had a penchant for snarling lines of authority, several dole aides said
former labor secretary bill brock was brought into run the campaign on nov. 1, but that was probably too late
the bush campaign has been working on strategy for years,'' said the gop pro
for example, the bush campaign had prepared long and hard for the possibility of an iowa loss. in contrast, the dole campaign found itself pumping up expectations of a victory in new hampshire, when even aides said the preferable course would have been to talk of how tough it would be to beat bush in his own backyard
and after the new hampshire loss, the image of a mean bob dole came back to haunt him. he snapped at bush in a television interview that bush's ads were lying about dole's record
the chaos in the final days of the new hampshire campaign was eerily echoed in illinois
dole went into the state saying he had to win, then backed off on that contention. he made deep cutbacks in his staff, and let the word leak out before he made an explanation. he abruptly moved to pull ads off the air, giving rise to rumors he was throwing in the towel
to top it all off, his half-hour address to the voters of illinois on saturday night was hit by technical problems
he did it to himself,'' said gop consultant eddie mahe of dole. ``the voters can't see any big differences between them on the issues. what they did is make their decisions on personality and style.''
mahe said the gop voters saw each man face defeat in a key early contest _ bush in iowa and dole in new hamsphire. and they liked what they saw in bush more
israel imposed a nightly curfew on more than 600,000 arabs in the entire gaza strip and reportedly sealed off entrances to the occupied territory after about 300 arab policemen in gaza said they would resign
the army on monday also closed one of the west bank's largest fruit and vegetable markets as israel tightened economic sanctions in the occupied lands
elsewhere in the west bank, israeli soldiers on monday shot and wounded 11 palestinians, hospital officials said. a 3-year-old girl was shot in the eye with a rubber bullet, and five israelis were injured by stones thrown by arabs
israel radio said the 300 arab policemen in the gaza strip announced monday they would resign. they joined 450 officers in the occupied lands who turned in their badges earlier following orders of plo-inspired underground leaflets
the curfew in gaza, announced monday, was a reaction to the resignations, the radio said. the 10 p.m. to 3 a.m. curfew also was designed to prevent ``the entrance of violent instigators ... and of written instigation material,'' it said. the army said the curfew was to prevent late night demonstrations
the curfew over the entire gaza strip was imposed for the first time since arab unrest started on dec. 8. it forces the residents to stay in their homes while entrances to gaza are sealed off by the army, the radio said
an army spokesman said the curfew would be imposed until further notice
at the erez checkpoint at the entrance to gaza, ap photographer max nash on monday saw 15 to 20 arab trucks and taxis prevented by the army from entering
he said soldiers would let in army vehicles and cars belonging to jewish settlers who live in gaza. other israelis and journalists were not permitted to drive in. ``where would we sleep? we want to enter, all our families are inside,'' an arab worker stopped at erez told israel radio
the situation in gaza's refugee camps was not immediately clear. on sunday night, the army cut electricity and telephone lines to 41,000 people in the beach camp, an arab reporter said
israeli authorities acknowledged that some policemen in the gaza strip quit but gave no figures. about 850 arab policemen work in the occupied territories
the police control crime and direct traffic, but they are not used to quell arab rioting in the occupied lands
it is clear their resignations were not handed in freely but because they fear for their lives,'' gaza police commander shimon levy said on israel radio
graffiti on the walls in gaza city called for the resignation of the israeli-appointed mayor and city council, israel television said
in response to the plo-backed unrest, israel stepped up economic sanctions. shipment of gasoline and other fuel to service stations in the west bank was banned as of sunday, and a regional fruit and vegetable market was closed on monday in jericho, 20 miles northwest of jerusalem
arab merchants said 70 trucks carrying produce were turned away monday. in addition, the army ordered jericho shop owners to close during the morning hours when plo leaflets said shops should be open. israel television said the arab merchants responded with a total commercial strike
the economic test of wills continued on monday in gaza city, where slogans painted in the red, green, white and black colors of the outlawed palestinian flag called for a two-day general strike starting today
protests were reported on monday in jenin and the nearby west bank village of yamoun, where troops using live ammunition shot and wounded 11 people, hospital officials said. according to united nations figures, at least 91 palestinians have been killed since anti-israeli rioting began dec. 8
witnesses said jewish settlers on monday drove through the west bank town of ramallah and nearby al amari refugee camp, honking their horns. witnesses said palestinians then held a similar car demonstration, during which soldiers shot 3-year-old rasha yussef said in the eye with a rubber bullet
advertising for all-terrain vehicles will begin stressing safety under a new agreement that also calls on makers of the off-road vehicles to set up new training programs and limit atv sales
the government on monday disclosed the new settlement, which could replace a preliminary agreement announced in december
the recreational vehicles have grown sharply in popularity in recent years, with more than 2 million currently believed to be in use
at the same time accidents have increased markedly, with more than 900 fatalities reported in the last five years, as well as 300,000 injuries, according to information collected by the consumer product safety commission
that led to a government safety investigation and the new agreement by the commission, the justice department, and the five manufacturers of the machines: honda, yamaha, kawasaki, suzuki and polaris industries
u.s. district judge gerhard a. gesell will hold a hearing on the settlement april 18 and could order it into effect immediately. it would replace the preliminary agreement between the government and the manufacturers announced on dec. 30
safety commission chairman terrence m. scanlon said through a spokesman that the settlement is the biggest safety accomplishment in the history of his agency
commission general counsel james v. lacy said the settlement will continue the ban on sales of new three-wheeled atvs and that manufacturers have agreed to buy back any of the three-wheel versions remaining in dealer inventories
the more stable four-wheel atvs will still be sold, he said, but marketing of the full-size versions with engines of 90 cubic centimeters and over will be limited to riders aged 16 and over. smaller machines will be allowed to be sold for riders ages 12 to 16, he said
the commission vote was 2-1, with scanlon and commissioner carol dawson in favor and commissioner anne graham dissenting. graham, who also voted against the preliminary settlement in december, said in a statement that the settlement should have allowed atv owners to obtain refunds
without the refund, consumers are not obtaining the remedies necessary given the nature and severity of the hazards presented by atvs,'' she said
the new 150-page settlement is much more detailed than the one announced in december, which drew criticism from congress and consumer groups as not being extensive enough. some consumer groups have said all the vehicles should be recalled because of safety problems
lacy said the settlement calls for the manufacturers to spend between $8.4 million and $8.6 million on advertising starting in the fall
the ads will stress the inherent safety risks of the vehicles, lacy said, and will be placed in a variety of media. included, he said, would be advertising on such broadcasts as the world series, cbs evening news and monday night football
in addition the manufacturers have agreed to set up a national headquarters to develop safety and training programs for riders, and to provide hands-on training for all new purchasers and for all consumers who bought the machines since dec. 30, 1986
buyers will be offered incentives such as $50 in cash, a $100 savings bond or merchandise certificates to induce them to take the training programs, lacy said
other provisions of the agreement, he said, include:
_new warning labels on the machines being sold, plus mailings providing these labels for all current owners for whom the manufacturers have addresses
_the hands-on training programs for new buyers will include their immediate families also
_development of new owners manuals with added safety information
_establishment of a safety hotline for consumers to get information and development of safety-related videos to be made available at dealer showrooms
_elimination of the safety verification form that had been required as part of the earlier settlement
this form, in which a buyer acknowledges knowing of the hazards of the machines, had been criticized by consumer groups, who said it could be used to protect the manufacturers in case of lawsuits stemming from accidents. syndrome</head>
doctors should rule out a long list of ills, such as aids and alcoholism, before they decide patients are afflicted with a baffling, newly recognized ailment called chronic fatigue syndrome, researchers say
in the past, the illness has been referred to as the yuppie disease, because some of its victims are young professionals, or more formally, epstein-barr virus syndrome or chronic mononucleosis
in a report published in the march issue of the annals of internal medicine, 16 top researchers in this field agreed to call it chronic fatigue syndrome, and settled on a definition for the afflication
the definition largely involves ruling out other illnesses that can cause similar symptoms, including the hallmark of the syndrome, extreme fatigue
it's a diagnosis of exclusion, and it has to be considered as such even after you've ruled everything else out,'' said dr. gary p. holmes, of the u.s. centers for disease control and chief author of the report
you have to continue to be concerned that there is something else going on,'' he added. ``you have to keep an open mind and not simply close the books.''
another co-author, dr. anthony l. komaroff of brigham and women's hospital in boston, said the new definition should help researchers as well as doctors who are faced with patients who have heard of the illness and think they have it
many of them have other physical illnesses, or they are depressed or anxious,'' he said. ``doctors need an anchor to help distinguish patients with chronic fatigue syndrome from patients who have other kinds of fatigue.''
according to the definition, people with the syndrome must have suffered debilitating fatigue for at least six months. it must be bad enough to reduce daily activity by at least half
doctors also must rule out a long list of diseases that can mimic the symptoms of the syndrome. these include cancer, tuberculosis, aids, depression, diabetes, alcoholism, poisoning and kidney disease, among many other disorders
in addition, patients must show signs of at least eight of 11 other possible conditions. these are mild fever, sore throat, painful lymph nodes, generalized muscle weakness, muscle discomfort, headaches, painful joints, sleep problems, sudden onset of the symptoms, such neurological problems as trouble concentrating, confusion or forgetfulness and general fatigue lasting at least 24 hours after exercise that the patient easily could have withstood when healthy
when the disease first received widespread attention three years ago, doctors believed it was somehow linked with the epstein-barr virus, because some victims showed signs of activation of that common virus. however, many experts now say that epstein-barr virus is not associated with the illness, since victims are just as likely to show exposure to the viruses that cause measles, genital herpes and cold sores, among other things
although the cdc has received thousands of questions about the illness from patients and doctors, no one knows how many people have it
its cause also is a mystery. some believe it can be triggered by persistant infections with a variety of viruses. among the suspects are a group of microbes called the enteroviruses as well as a newly discovered virus known as human herpes virus 6
researchers suggest it's a reaction to these lingering infections rather than the mischief of the viruses themselves that makes people feel poorly
my theory is that certain viruses are able to escape ever being fully eradicated by the body,'' said komaroff
they come back to fight again. you have a constant iran-iraq war where the battles are continual. the process of doing battle and mobilizing the body's immune system causes some of the symptoms of feeling ill.''
holmes noted that the symptoms of chronic fatigue syndrome are similar to those experienced by people treated with the natural hormone interferon
interferon is the body's normal response to a viral infection,'' holmes said. ``it may be that something like overproduction of interferon for a prolonged period may be causing the illness.''
the confrontation in the occupied west bank and gaza strip has increasingly become an economic test of wills between israeli occupation authorities and palestinians
underground palestinian leaders have persuaded many merchants and ordinary citizens to stop paying taxes and have enforced repeated strikes, keeping at home a large part of the 110,000 laborers who work in israel
the measures are designed to make israel bear more of the economic burden for occupation, which arab activists say will give impetus to israel's withdrawal. israel has adopted increasingly tough economic sanctions, some of which are designed to put the squeeze on the arab middle class
the army imposed an indefinite ban on trucks taking gasoline to the west bank's 50 service stations. the move crippled public and private transport
qabatiyeh, a west bank village of several thousand people, was banned from exporting its quarried rock to jordan and visitors from abroad will not be allowed to visit the village, israeli officials said
the move was punishment for the lynching of an alleged collaborator who was hung from an electricty pole after he fired into a crowd advancing on his home and fatally wounded a child
in jericho, the army closed a regional produce market and ordered shops to close during morning hours, when plo leaflets said the shops should be open
the military government is trying to tell the people here who is boss. they want to hurt the people economically. i think they intend to try to break the strike this way,'' said saeb erakat, a political science professor at al najah university
israeli authorities have selectively used other measures as well, such as cutting off electricity to areas placed under curfew
israeli officials say they hope such steps will encourage moderates to put pressure on palestinian militants, although there is no sign that such measures are having the desired effect
agitators on the arab side want to disconnect the population as much as possible from any connection with israel,'' said a senior official in the military administration of the occupied territories
he said the tax rebellion had minimal impact in january and february, leading to a 10 percent decline in revenues, or about $200,000 a month
but he said collections were expected to be far lower in march and that road repairs, garbage collection and other services in the occupied territories could suffer if there was not enough income to fund the $239 million budget of the army-run civil administration
to counter the tax boycott, authorities required arabs to obtain a certificate saying they paid their taxes before getting import-export licenses, driver's permits and other documents
israel also lowered the amount of money palestinians could bring from abroad without permission from $5,000 to $1,200
the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said more economic sanctions were being considered to quell the revolt, which began dec. 8. and has resulted in the death of more than 90 arabs. he declined to elaborate
but arieh shalev, former head of the army-run military government in 1974-76, said it might be necessary to stop arabs from working in israel or using the bridges to trade with jordan
violence has peaked, in my opinion, but it will continue and it's doubtful whether it will stop without taking brutal (economic) measures,'' shalev said on israel radio
ephraim kleiman, an economics professor at hebrew university, said israel was better positioned to endure a showdown than the palestinians
the occupied territories are dependent for income on three things: work in israel, the export of agricultural goods and quarried stone to jordan, and financial support from arab countries,'' he said in an interview
he said arab job boycotts would deal a ``serious blow'' to the construction industry, textile factories, restaurants and garbage collection. but overall, he said, the ``economic impact on israel is much smaller.''
arab economists disputed the contention. ``we are prepared to suffer more than the israelis,'' said samir hazboun, a bir zeit university economist
he said the tax rebellion had added to israel's cost of continuing the occupation and that bad publicity abroad had affected investment and tourism
the new austrian ambassador to the united nations came bearing gifts to mayor edward i. koch, but the mayor greeted him with a diatribe against austria's president, kurt waldheim
i think he's a bad guy. he was just one of those obsequious guys when he was here, before i knew he was a war criminal. and i had dinner with him a couple of times,'' koch on monday told peter hohenfellner, who became the permanent austrian representative at the united nations in february
you'll forgive me if i'm honest, ok, and it's not intended as anything but honesty because i have the highest regard for your chancellor.''
waldheim, who was secretary-general of the united nations, has come under fire since files were uncovered that suggest he had a greater role than he has admitted as an officer in the nazi army during world war ii. there are reports that waldheim knew about atrocities being committed against partisans and villagers where he was stationed
waldheim has stood fast against the accusations and refused to resign as president. he has been banned as an undesireable from united states
koch told hohenfellner that austrian chancellor franz vranitzky was invited to dinner the next time he comes to the united states
i'd like him to stay at gracie mansion,'' koch said of the mayor's residence. ``i wouldn't do that for the president. ... for the president, this city is off limits.''
the mayor gave hohenfellner a tie and the ambassador gave him a 19th century goblet koch said he would use at passover
country singer johnny cash ended a three-city south dakota tour here with an unwelcome non-musical sidekick _ the hiccups
this is an all-time first for me,'' cash told his audience in the corn palace. ``it's the first time i've done a show with the hiccups.''
cash, who also had a recent bout with the flu, sipped water during sunday afternoon's performance. he even left the stage for a short time to try unsuccessfully to get rid of his hiccups
he and his wife, june carter cash, performed to the audience of 2,000 for about two hours
doctors removed singer dennis day from the critical list after he responded to treatment for a head injury he suffered last week in a fall at home
his condition was upgraded to serious monday after surgery saturday relieved swelling of the brain, said armen markarian, spokesman for st. john's hospital
day, 71, was diagnosed last july as suffering from amyotropic lateral sclerosis, or lou gehrig's disease, a progressive nerve disorder that causes loss of muscle control
day became famous by performing with comedian jack benny starting in 1939. an accomplished irish tenor, day also was known for playing the innocent foil to benny's irascible character on television and radio
the rev. allan boesak, an anti-apartheid leader, says productions such as the movie ``cry freedom'' and the musical ``sarafina'' play important roles in publicizing the struggle of blacks in his native south africa
you cannot reach everybody by making a speech, or even by saying something on television,'' boesak said in an interview in april's essence magazine
some other people are more convinced by reading a book, by meeting someone face to face, by seeing a play, by seeing a movie. i believe that if you get all these different audiences, and you speak to them in a medium that they can understand, then so much the better.''
boesak, 41, is a minister in the dutch reformed church and president of the world alliance of reformed churches. under south africa's racially restrictive laws, which reserve most power for the white minority, he is considered of mixed race
the magazine said writer and former black panther leader elaine brown interviewed boesak when he and his wife, dorothy, and four children were in los angeles recently
having a newborn baby won't keep three-time grammy-winner deniece williams from the recording studio, her publicist says
miss williams, 35, who gave birth saturday, is planning to record an album next month, press agent bob angelotti says
mother and child are doing fine'' but will remain in the hospital for several days, he said
forrest matthew westering, who weighed 9 pounds, 3 ounces at birth, is the first child for the singer and her husband, brad westering, who were married in 1986. miss williams has two children from a previous marriage
miss williams began her career as a backup singer for stevie wonder. in 1978, she recorded a no. 1 single, ``too much, too little, too late,'' with johnny mathis. she recently won her third grammy, best female gospel performance, for ``i believe in you'' on the album ``water under the bridge.''
retired brig. gen. chuck yeager, the first man to fly faster than the speed of sound, will drive the pace car in the 1988 indianapolis 500, race officials say
the announcement was made monday at a ceremony in which general motors officials presented the keys for 66 black 1988 cutlass supremes to speedway president joe cloutier. the cars are replicas of the open-top cutlass that will pace the 72nd indianapolis 500 on may 29
yeager, who retired from active duty in the air force in 1975, set his flight speed record on oct. 14, 1947. he works as a consultant test-pilot for northrop corp., mcdonnell douglas corp. and the flight test center at edwards air force base in california
yeager also drove the pace car in the 1986 indy 500
former minister walker railey has decided not to contest a civil suit accusing him of choking his wife nearly to death, railey's attorney said monday
doug mulder told the dallas morning news that railey's decision was based on estimates that it would cost nearly $100,000 in legal fees to dispute the lawsuit filed feb. 2 by railey's mother-in-law, billie jo nicolai
he told me that he had decided his assets would be best used in the support and maintenance of his children,'' said mulder, who represented railey before a dallas county grand jury investigating the attack
railey, 40, missed a monday deadline for answering the suit, which seeks unspecified damages, said bill arnold, an attorney for mrs. nicolai
in absence of a response, a judge could rule against the former senior minister of the first united methodist church of dallas and award damages
peggy railey, 39, has been in a coma since she was found unconscious on the floor of her garage last april. she had been choked
railey was not charged, but both his attorney and assistant district attorney norm kinne identified the former minister as the prime suspect
railey denied any involvement but refused to cooperate with police, invoking his fifth amendment right against self-incrimination 43 times when questioned by a grand jury
mrs. railey remains in a tyler nursing home. railey, who now lives in san francisco, has assigned her guardianship to her parents, and that of his two children to family friends
the question now is when do i want to go to court and ask for a default judgment,'' arnold said monday. ``it could be tomorrow or it could be a couple of months. it depends on peggy's best interests.''
jane byrne and ed vrdolyak, once on the same team pulling the levers of city government, are on the comeback trail, this time by trying to throw a monkey wrench into each other's plans
mrs. byrne, the former mayor, says her last attempt at office will be today when she runs in the democratic primary for clerk of the nation's largest local court system
vrdolyak, a former alderman and former chairman of the powerful cook county democratic party, wants the same office. but he's now a republican running unopposed in the gop primary
a victory by either candidate in november's general election could give a jump start to his or her political future. but a loss could be politically fatal
it's a position that has some patronage, it has jobs,'' said paul kleppner, a social scientist at northern illinois university and analyst of chicago politics
more important than the number of jobs, if you're an office-holder, you can grab the media. as jane byrne once said, the new precinct captain in this age is television,'' kleppner said monday
mrs. byrne was in a tough primary race with aurelia pucinski, the county democratic party's endorsed candidate and daughter of fiery alderman roman pucinski
mrs. byrne, mayor from 1979 to 1983, was ousted by harold washington, who became the city's first black chief executive and then withstood an election challenge from her last year
besides announcing proposals to streamline the court system's bureaucracy and broaden services for county residents outside chicago, mrs. byrne and mrs. pucinski have mostly haggled over who had the late mayor's affection
washington supported mrs. pucinski and the party's slate of endorsed candidates just a few days before he died nov. 23
but in mrs. byrne's effort to appeal to chicago's powerful black voting bloc, she points to a unity breakfast she had with washington after he won the primary last february
mrs. byrne also pulls out a newspaper article that quotes mrs. pucinski as saying she wasn't washington's first choice for the clerk's job
mrs. pucinski has countered with a radio blitz featuring prominent black politicians and even washington's half brother, ramon price
harold believed we had come too far to go back to the days of the bosses. ... that's why harold chose aurelia pucinski,'' price says on the ad, broadcast on black-oriented radio stations
but mrs. pucinski's alderman father was viewed among blacks as an obstructionist during washington's reign as mayor
i would expect byrne to get the black vote,'' kleppner said. ``the question is how much.''
vrdolyak, an alderman for 15 years, lost power to washington in the city council and waged an unsuccessful bid against him on a third-party ticket last april. vrdolyak subsequently resigned from the chairmanship of the county democratic organization to become a republican
with no primary opponent, vrdolyak has spent most of his time talking about demanding integrity and honesty from the court system's 2,000 employees
he's also portraying democrats as big taxers and spenders, hoping to get conservative democratic voters to join his cause in november. at a rally sunday for vice president george bush, vrdolyak said ``they don't represent you.''
they don't hardly represent anybody any more,'' he said
if mrs. byrne survives the primary and meets vrdolyak in november, the clerk's race will feature two former allies. vrdolyak was her floor leader in the city council, and she once helped install him as chairman of the county democratic party
today, the affection is lost
he's devious. he's a wheeler-dealer,'' she told a newspaper last week. ``it's distasteful. ... i don't like him. he's not my cup of tea.'' update with later protest at booking site, picking up 4th graf pvs, `monday's arrests ...'</note>
two hundred arrests were reported monday as anti-nuclear protesters tried to block buses carrying thousands of workers to the nation's nuclear testing grounds
the protesters slowed traffic into the nevada test site, 65 miles northwest of las vegas, but failed to halt work, said energy department spokesman chris west
the majority of those arrested were carried away by officers after lying down on the main road leading into the sprawling desert site
later, many of those arrested had to be dragged by police off buses in tonopah, nev., about 135 miles away, where they were taken to be booked before being released
they weren't going to stand for being driven 135 miles away and being let loose,'' said protest spokeswoman trudy mason
the nye county sheriff's department said officers decided to remove the protesters from three buses and from the tonopah convention center, which was serving as a booking facility, after they refused for several hours to be released
they just sat down and went limp and we dragged them out of there,'' said capt. george gumbmann. mason claimed some of the protesters were injured, but gumbmann said he knew of no injuries
monday's arrests followed a demonstration saturday by up to 5,000 people, the largest in more than seven years of protests at the site. police arrested 1,240 people that day, mostly on misdemeanor trespass citations
a spokesman for the american peace test, which is sponsoring the demonstrations, said 50 protesters had infiltrated the 1,350-square-mile site, which is the size of rhode island
west said he was unaware of any such incidents, but said any infiltrators would not be able to reach sensitive areas
american peace test estimated there were 200 protesters at the site monday, but west said the number was closer to 400
he said 300 personnel from the nye county sheriff's office, the nevada highway patrol and wackenhut security remained on duty or on standby
the protests are scheduled to continue through sunday
the supreme court by a vote of 6-3 refused early tuesday to postpone the execution of willie jasper darden, scheduled to die later in the morning in florida's electric chair
darden, who was scheduled to be electrocuted at 7 a.m. at florida state prison, has maintained his innocence in the 1973 fatal shooting of a lakeland furniture store owner during a robbery
his case has been the focus of an international campaign against capital punishment. pope john paul ii and soviet dissident andrei sakharov had made appeals on his behalf
the dissenting votes were cast by justices william j. brennan, thurgood marshall, and harry a. blackmun
the following is a look at the main points of disagreement between israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir and foreign minister shimon peres on the middle east peace process

land for peace
shamir's right-wing likud bloc opposes giving up any part of the occupied west bank or gaza strip in exchange for peace. instead, shamir calls for the implementation of the 1978 u.s.-mediated camp david accords signed by israel and egypt
the agreement says palestinians should be granted self-rule on domestic matters while leaving security and foreign affairs to israel. after three years of autonomy, israel and the arabs would negotiate a final status for the occupied lands. shamir believes handing occupied territories back to the arabs would endanger israel's existence by leaving it smaller and more vulnerable
peres' left-of-center labor party is ready to enter negotiations with jordan, from which israel seized the west bank, which would involve returning parts of the occupied lands. peres says israel would insist on retaining arab east jerusalem and holding on to areas along the jordan river as a ``security border.'' his guiding principle is to hand back as much of the heavily populated palestinian areas as possible, above all the gaza strip, taken from egypt. the west bank and the gaza strip were occupied during the 1967 arab-israeli war
today 1.5 million palestinians live in the occupied territories along with 65,000 jewish settlers. peres is afraid that if israel keeps the territories, it will quickly lose its jewish majority because of the high arab birth rate

the international peace conference
the international peace conference idea calls for negotiations between israel and arab representatives under the aegis of the five permanent members of the u.n. security council _ the united states, the soviet union, britain, france and china
shamir rejects the notion outright. he claims four of the five powers side with the arabs and will have the power to force israel to give up the occupied lands. he believes the united states will side with them on this issue. he also fears the palestine liberation organization will be invited to join the talks
as a concession to international involvement, he has suggested the united states and the soviet union invite israel and jordan to talks, leaving them to negotiate on their own after a ceremonial meeting of the four delegations
peres believes jordan will negotiate only within an international forum and that israel must accept this condition if it wants to talk peace. he says the conference will be only an ``opening'' of direct talks between israel and a joint jordanian-palestinian delegation. he argues the conference will not have the power to impose its will or interfere in direct negotiations and says the plo will not attend the talks

the shultz plan
the peace initiative by secretary of state george p. shultz is an attempt to bridge the gap among moderate arabs, peres and shamir. it calls for convening an international conference in april, followed by direct talks between israel and a joint jordanian-palestinian delegation on palestinian self-rule. in december, even if autonomy negotiations were still going on, the sides would begin talks on a permanent settlement
shamir says the shultz plan is ``cumbersome ... and does nothing to guarantee the safety of israel.'' his aides accuse the united states of reneging on its commitment to the camp david agreement. shamir is against negotiating a permanent settlement while talks on the interim autonomy arrangements are still going on. he says the idea of autonomy was to see whether israelis and palestinians could live on a new footing before considering a permanent settlement
peres accepts the shultz plan, warning that it may be the last chance in the forseeble future to make peace with the arabs. he says talks would be conducted while the reagan government is in office. he describes the reagan administration as the freindliest israel has ever known

the plo
shamir and peres both refuse to negotiate with the plo. peres has left open the possibility of talking to the plo if it renounces violence and recognizes the jewish state. shamir will have nothing to do with the organization. showing</head>
sen. albert gore jr. stumped michigan today in hopes the state will demonstrate he can win in the north, while he kept his fingers crossed for ``a stronger result than people now expect'' from illinois' democratic presidential primary
gore was traveling to lansing today where he planned to appear with state legislators backing his candidacy before returning to washington
arriving in detroit monday night, gore described himself as a ``friend of organized labor'' and invoked the name of the state's democratic governor, who hasn't endorsed a candidate
i'm offering the politics of the future, very much in the way gov. jim blanchard has,'' gore said
as he campaigned across illinois earlier monday, the tennessee senator contended he was encouraged about his prospects in today's illinois voting, despite a dismal single-digit showing in pre-election polls
he pointed to illinois' ``two favorite sons'' of jesse jackson and paul simon, and the short time span since his crucial victories in the south last week launched him as a contender, as an explanation for his anticipated finish behind them and michael dukakis
the polls have been wrong quite frequently in this race because the voters are thinking for themselves,'' gore said. ``there's a large undecided vote and people are looking for an alternative
we've had only a few days to get the message out in illinois,'' he said later. he added that he hoped ``we're going to have a stronger result than people now expect.''
gore avoided setting expectations in michigan, where democrats hold caucuses on march 26, and where richard gephardt has chosen to make a last stand in hopes of salvaging his candidacy that was nearly knocked out in the south
i never single him out and certainly don't now,'' gore said of gephardt. ``... it's a three-person race now between myself and jackson and dukakis. that's the reality, regardless of what's happening in any one state.''
gore said that no matter what the illinois outcome, he and jackson and dukakis would fight for the nomination across the series of industrial states leading up to california's final primary
there are other contests on down the road in ohio, connecticut, pennsylvania and new york, and we're looking forward to those contests _ and michigan and wisconsin _ all the way to california,'' gore said
we're going to compete everywhere and look for an opportunity to punch through,'' he told reporters on his campaign plane
gore depicted himself as the alternative to dukakis and jackson ``to bring the democratic party back in the mainstream.''
at the university of illinois, gore appeared before the school's super computer, a machine capable of millions of computations in an instant, to call for increased federal money for computer research and education. he accused the reagan administration of starving civilian computer research while putting money into military applications
we are now on the verge of falling behind japan, once again in a field we pioneered,'' he said
gov. buddy roemer, who toppled political legend edwin edwards, opened his four-year term by challenging louisiana's residents to help ``clean up our politics.''
hope is diminishing. attitudes have been damaged. image is tarnished. pride has been wounded. we are down but we are not out,'' said roemer, inaugurated monday as louisiana's 51st governor
roemer did not cite the usual litany of louisiana's problems, including high national rankings in unemployment, teen pregnancies, high school dropouts, an almost bankrupt government of a state with a widespread image of political corruption
the former democratic congressman takes over a state with an accumulated budget deficit and cash shortfall of as much as $1.2 billion, much of it due to the depressed oil industry
roemer's legislative liasion, manny fernandez, said the governor's first order of business would be to order a special legislative session to give him wide budget-cutting authority for the rest of the fiscal year, which ends june 30
the governor grabbed a major political victory even before he took office when the legislature approved his choices for house speaker and senate president
roemer had said removal of the incumbent officers was needed to ensure that his legislative programs would receive a fair hearing
standing on the capitol steps, roemer was surrounded by 5,000 people. he was sworn in by former u.s. sen. russell long, the son of another legendary governor, huey long
louisiana's victory will not be limited to the few or the strong. that's not victory. that's just more of the same. we'll bring the whole family on this victory trip,'' roemer said
on behalf of our family, we declare war on ignorance, on racism, on joblessness, on business as usual, on environmental pollution and on dishonest political leadership. ..
do we have the character to clean up our politics, to free our political leadership from the stranglehold of the special interests? i say we do.''
roemer was interrupted frequently by applause, including spirited clapping from edwards, who conceded a runoff after trailing roemer in his oct. 24 primary bid for an unprecedented fourth term
edwards, who served as governor from 1972 to 1980 and returned for a third term in 1984, was occupied for much of his last administration defending himself successfully against federal racketeering charges
i'm going hunting tomorrow,'' edwards told reporters when asked how he felt at the moment. ``it's his now.''
capitol police seized 1,162 weapons from visitors last year, a 147 percent increase over 1986, and the house sergeant at arms is lobbying for $18.5 million to tighten security
capitol police are responsible for the capitol itself, six associated office buildings and the capitol grounds. sergeant at arms jack russ says the weapons confiscated last year included an uzi machine gun, a pistol disguised as a beeper and soda bottles containing explosives
the 1,162 total compared to 470 weapons seized in 1986
the security plan advanced by russ calls for installing bomb-proof glass in the house visitors' gallery and modifying floor seats in the chamber to protect against bomb blasts, at a cost of $4.2 million
other proposals include a $4.7 million emergency telephone system to alert every house office immediately to a terrorist attack, $413,352 worth of additional bomb detectors in house office buildings, a $3.5 million electronic card system for access to house garages, and a $5.7 million alarm system connecting home-district offices with local police
russ said most of the weapons were confiscated from visitors who were unaware of gun control restrictions at the capitol and had no criminal intent. but of the total, 63 people were prosecuted, up from 50 the previous year
strict anti-terrorist proposals, such as fencing in the capitol grounds or putting glass enclosures around the house and senate visitors' galleries, have been widely criticized in the past. many legislators argue that the capitol, as a symbol of open democracy, should be easily accessible to the public
russ says this view is unrealistic in view of growing security threats
i think everybody _ me included _ would like the easy-going atmosphere of a mayberry rfd police force, with a friendly cop directing traffic,'' he said in an interview. ``but in this day and time, you also need a high-tech, well-trained police department. you've got to have both.''
russ outlined his plan last week at a house appropriations subcommittee hearing on a proposed $1.96 billion budget for congressional operations during the fiscal year that starts oct. 1. his next step is to seek spending authority from a separate house committee
still awaiting final action by the house and senate leadership is a more sweeping security plan that calls for a wrought-iron fence around the capitol plaza, a parking ban on the plaza and gatehouses to screen visitors before they enter the capitol grounds
that plan, scaled down from an earlier version, has been approved by the capitol police board, consisting of the house and senate sergeants at arms and capitol architect george white, but a $13 million appropriation to implement the plan remains largely unspent
meanwhile, hydraulic steel street barricades have been installed at the main traffic entrances to the capitol to halt unauthorized vehicles, and large concrete flower and shrubbery pots have been placed along driveways and sidewalks to thwart any attempted truck bombings of the capitol
russ said he hopes the bipartisan house and senate leadership will meet with their sergeants at arms before the end of april to discuss the broader security plan. he said speaker jim wright, d-texas, has endorsed additional proposed security measures in the house
the army has secretly devised a new armor plating for its main battle tank that combines uranium with steel to produce an almost impenetrable skin, military officials say
we're talking about something so good the experts think it will take the russians almost a decade to catch up,'' said one official who spoke only on condition of anonymity
this is a major advance; a very major advance.''
the pentagon sources agreed to discuss the matter monday after the army released a brief statement announcing plans to produce ``a new model of the m-1a1 abrams main battle tank with significantly better armor.''
the armor design modification to the m-1a1 incorporates steel-encased depleted uranium,'' the service said
the development of the new armor has been under way for several years as part of a highly classified ``black'' program, the sources said. the army relaxed the classification somewhat on monday only because it had to provide information to production line workers and wanted to allay health concerns about using a radioactive material in a manned vehicle, they added
in monday's announcement, the service insisted that the depleted uranium would pose no threat to either the soldiers who operated the tanks or to the production workers who built them because of the manner in which the tanks would be fabricated
sealed within the tank, depleted uranium has a very low level of natural radiation, which is well within the acceptable range established by the nuclear regulatory commission,'' the army said
you would have to sit on this tank for 75 hours straight in order to get the same equivalent radiation as a single chest x-ray,'' added maj. phil soucy, an army spokesman
the abrams is made for the army by the general dynamics corp. at two plants _ in lima, ohio, and detroit _ employing roughly 5,000 production workers. the armor plates are being made at a secret location and then shipped to the assembly lines, the army said
depleted uranium is an inert, heavy metal that is unusually dense _ 2{ times more so than steel. the term ``depleted'' means the uranium does not have sufficient energy to be used for commercial purposes such as in power plants
depleted uranium has long been used for a variety of civilian and military applications, ranging from the production of canisters for the transport of more highly radioactive materials to certain types of ammunition
in the case of the m-1a1, the army refused to say how much uranium would be incorporated into each tank; where on the tank body the armor with uranium would be located, or how it would produce the new armor
the sources said, however, the new process involved ``weaving'' a thread mesh of uranium into the regular steel armor plating at the time of casting. the process produces an incredibly strong plate that adds ``an insignificant amount of weight,'' they said
it's not only the strength of the uranium but the way it's worked into the steel,'' said one official. ``the process is still highly classified and nobody's going to say more
but the experts say this plating can stop any known soviet anti-tank round, as well as any of their more advanced rounds in development.''
the army, in its statement, said, ``this improvement culminates several years of research and development to meet recent and continuing improvements in warsaw pact anti-armor weapons and will allow the abrams to meet the anticipated threat well into the 1990s.''
the army has already acquired about 1,500 m-1a1's and they will not be retrofitted with the new armor, the service said. but the remaining 3,000 tanks scheduled for purchase will incorporate the new armor
the majority of the improved tanks will be stationed in europe where they can most directly contribute to nato defenses,'' the service said. the first should arrive ``late this year.''
soucy said the new armor plating would begin showing up on the tank manufacturing lines early this summer. the first completed tank with the new armor will be delivered in october, the spokesman added
soucy declined to say how much the new armor would cost. each m-1a1 currently costs about $2.36 million. harsh</head>
george bush, michael dukakis and albert gore took relatively gentle pokes at their presidential rivals in today's illinois primary with television commercials that bore none of the ferocity of the super tuesday media assault
the three were the only candidates to wage substantial media campaigns in illinois. massachusetts gov. dukakis and tennessee sen. gore, both democrats, were spending in the $250,000 range while republican vice president bush reported a $400,000 advertising buy
sen. bob dole, r-kan., started running ads last monday but cut them off in a pre-weekend strategy shift and had nothing on the air in the final days before the primary. instead he bought a half-hour of time saturday night, but his broadcast was beset by technical problems
democrat richard gephardt was bypassing illinois to focus on michigan's march 26 caucuses. and neither of the favorite sons, democratic sen. paul simon and civil rights activist jesse jackson, were advertising in their home state
front-runner bush was running two ads he has used before _ one a biographical spot and the other showing him with world leaders and president reagan. the latter says there is a difference between congressional and presidential leadership _ the closest bush gets to criticizing dole
gore was on the air with several ads including a new one in which he stresses his youth and service in vietnam. ``there's only one choice for a new generation of leadership,'' says the narrator, echoing gore's frequent contention that dukakis can't get elected because he represents ``the old politics.''
for his part, dukakis is taking a poke at simon's insistence that the democratic race is wide open and ripe for a brokered convention
the ad never mentions simon, however. it merely says ``some people'' would like to go back to the days of brokered conventions ``when voters didn't really pick their nominee. ... but you don't have to do this. on tuesday, you can pick the next president'' by voting for dukakis
the low-key tone adopted by all three candidates was a dramatic change from the ads leading up to last week's super tuesday contests in 20 states. at that time, bush, dole, gephardt, dukakis and gore specifically attacked each other's records, character and campaign themes in barbed commercials that didn't hesitate to name names
dukakis held the lead in democratic delegates going into illinois and was making some late progress toward the upper tier of the contest, where polls showed simon and jackson neck and neck
in addition to his brokered convention spot, dukakis was using two ads he had run in super tuesday states _ one stressing his experience as a chief executive and another in which a union official says dukakis is not a ``shot-and-beer kinda guy'' but his economic policies put people to work
gore also was running two other ads he had used for super tuesday, when he won six states. one spot chides u.s. companies for investing in jobs overseas rather than at home and the other says big chemical polluters, price fixers, corporate law breakers and greedy drug manufacturers ``don't want al gore to be president'' because he's fought them in the past
democratic chairman paul kirk wants to head off a bruising battle for the party's presidential nomination and would mediate efforts to close ranks behind a probable nominee if nobody finishes the primaries with enough delegates to win
when you get to a point when there is someone who is somewhat shy of a mathematical majority, i think the opportunity exists to try to strengthen that person and not weaken him as you come into the convention,'' kirk said monday
the delegates who could tip the balance for such a candidate are the 645 so-called ``super delegates,'' the party leaders, members of congress and governors of states and territories who automatically will be convention delegates because of the offices they hold. four years ago, 568 convention seats were used for this purpose
when we increased those numbers, it was not tokenism,'' kirk said. ``their status is that they have to run with and govern with the ticket in the end.''
kirk, in a telephone interview from new york, said the super delegates have a ``special responsibility'' to help ensure that the democratic presidential nomination does not wind up in a political fight that damages the nominee
by the time the primaries and caucuses end in june, kirk said he believed that one candidate will be considered a clear front-runner and the eventual nominee. that candidate will have developed a consistent record of winning primaries and caucuses, even if he does not have the delegates needed for a first-ballot victory at the national convention, kirk said
at that point, kirk said he would meet with the candidates and ``say, `ok, here's where we are and here's where we have to be in november. now, what do we have to do to maximize those opportunities?'''
i don't want to leave the impression that kirk's going to be the broker,'' the party chairman said in a telephone interview from new york. ``i'm not going to dictate to anyone because it doesn't work that way.''
however, he said he would be ``in the middle'' of efforts to avoid harm that could be done to a probable nominee if a political battle erupted just before or during the convention
the democrats conclude their delegate selection on june 7 with primaries in california and new jersey, which combined account for more than 400 national convention delegates
the whole thing is to avoid that brokering process taking place in atlanta,'' said julie anbender, a spokeswoman for kirk. ``i think that he's been floating this idea with elected officials and party officials for some time.''
the democratic national convention is july 18-21 in atlanta
the suggestion that the democratic presidential nomination would have to be brokered came after a clear front-runner failed to emerge in contests to date. the party has already picked more than 40 percent of its national convention delegates
i don't discount the possibility that there will be a first-ballot mathematical majority after you get through with california,'' kirk said. ``i think that is still likely.''
winning the presidential nomination takes at least 2,082 delegates, and so far no candidate has even one-fourth of that number
the super delegates, some of whom cast just fractions of votes under party rules, are not required to pledge their allegiance to any presidential candidate before the convention, although some of them have
of the super delegates, 240.65 say they remain uncommitted, while another 115.35 have come out in support of one candidate or another. the remainder either have not responded to inquiries or have not yet been selected
in the latter category are 253 members of congress, who are to be picked at party caucuses april 19-20, when missouri rep. richard gephardt hopes to get a significant boost for his sagging presidential prospects
gephardt holds the no. 4 leadership position in the house as head of the democratic caucus
gephardt spokesman mark johnson declined to offer any opinion on kirk's statement, saying only that ``we have no problems with the party chairman at all.''
when asked whether the gephardt campaign supported a proposal to rally support behind whoever is the leader after june 7, johnson said the idea of some sort of brokering process in june was ``hypothetical.''
the current leader in the democratic presidential field is massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, who has 462.5 delegates, followed by jesse jackson with 423.55 and tennessee sen. albert gore with 352.8
the nikkei stock average closed at 25,475.67 points, up 42.16 points, on the tokyo stock exchange on tuesday
the government's new trade-and-aid program to help american farmers by sending emissaries to foreign countries is almost ready for launching
agriculture secretary richard e. lyng announced monday that the first trip will be this spring to indonesia and the philippines. the exact dates have to be negotiated with the countries
the mission will include representatives from the departments of agriculture and state, and the u.s. agency for international development. three to six representatives of the private sector also will be selected for the trips
during my recent trip to asia, i discussed possible missions with the leaders and key agricultural officials of both countries,'' lyng said. ``we agreed that these missions would not only address the food needs of these countries, but would help develop customers for u.s. agricultural exports as well.''
the trips are required by the agricultural aid and trade missions act, passed by congress late last year. it specified that 16 missions be conducted in 1988, with eight completed by june
by offering specially designed packages of u.s. trade and food assistance, the goal of the program is to help the designated countries develop and to become larger markets for american farmers
private sector involvement will ensure more effective identification of trade and investment opportunities for u.s. exporters,'' lyng said. ``the recipient countries will benefit from the technology and managerial expertise that can best be transferred by the private sector.''
lyng added: ``this exchange helps foster development in the recipient countries, which in turn expands the long-term demand for u.s. agricultural exports.''
orville l. freeman, a former secretary of agriculture and now head of the agriculture council of america, is an enthusiastic supporter of the trade-and-aid law, calling it ``the most promising agricultural legislation since the passage of public law 480 in 1954,'' the food for peace program
the bottom line is to use all existing resources to lay the groundwork for expanded business with developing countries which have the potential for explosive market growth,'' freeman said recently
as described by usda's foreign agricultural service, each mission will:
_meet with appropriate foreign and u.s. officials in each country to help in planning the extent to which u.s. trade and aid can be used to meet the food and economic needs in that country
_provide technical help and information on u.s. agricultural commodities and the trade and aid program
_help obtain firm commitments for food aid programs and commodity sales
within 60 days after completion of a mission, the representatives must report to the president and the congress on their findings and recommendations,'' the agency said
further, beginning in december 1989, the usda and aid must submit quarterly reports to congress about the progress made on each mission's recommendations
turkey production is rising faster than agriculture department economists had previously forecast
the number of turkey eggs in incubators on march 1 was estimated at 32.1 million, up almost 4 percent from a year ago, the agriculture department reported monday
moreover, 23.1 million new turkey poults were placed in flocks last month, a 2 percent increase from placements a year earlier, said the agricultural statistics board
in an earlier report, the department's economic research service said turkey output climbed 18 percent in 1987 to a record level. by the third quarter market prices had dropped below break-even prices. however, prices climbed dramatically in november and december, putting fourth-quarter returns close to the break-even level
because no two consecutive quarters had strong negative net returns, producers probably did not get an intense signal to slow growth,'' the agency said in the march issue of agricultural outlook magazine. ``production is now forecast to rise 10 percent in 1988, up from the earlier forecast of 6 percent.''
wholesale prices of hen turkeys weighing 8 pounds to 16 pounds averaged about 61 cents per pound in the east, the report said. prices in the first and second quarters of 1988 are expected to be in the range of 48 cents to 52 cents and then rise seasonally in the third and fourth
for all of 1988, the wholesale price may average 50 cents to 56 cents per pound, compared with 57.8 cents in 1987, the report said
a larger 1987 harvest and a bigger inventory have put pressure on potato prices this season, says the agriculture department
total output last year rebounded almost 7 percent to an estimated 385.7 million hundredweight, although still 3 percent shy of the 1985 record, the department's economic research service said. stocks of fresh potatoes on jan. 1 were up 8 percent from a year earlier
idaho russets sold for $13.50 to $14 per hundredweight at the end of january, compared with $17.50 to $19 the year before. maine round whites, at $5.80 to $6 per hundredweight, were down from $8.10 to $8.50 a year earlier, the agency reported
overall, the u.s. average grower price of potatoes in january was $3.60 per hundredweight, down 25 percent from a year earlier. louisiana inmate put to death.</note>
the u.s. supreme court early tuesday refused to halt the execution at dawn of convicted killer willie jasper darden, who survived an unprecedented six death warrants and became an international cause celebre
darden, who has maintained his innocence in the 1973 slaying of a lakeland businessman during a robbery, was scheduled to die in the electric chair at 7 a.m. at florida state prison near this north florida town
the high court, in a 6-3 vote, denied a stay, as did a federal appeals court in atlanta, a federal judge in tampa and florida's supreme court earlier in the day
i'm going to holler, i'm going to holler loud, and i'm not going to stop hollering, and i'll be hollering, `innocent, innocent, innocent' if they put me in the chair,'' darden said in an interview taped earlier monday and shown on abc's ``nightline.''
if i had committed such a crime, i would have a guilty conscience all these years. i could not have lived with it,'' he said
his case has become focus of an international campaign against capital punishment. pope john paul ii and soviet dissident andrei sakharov had made appeals on his behalf
darden's attorneys raised several claims on appeal, including reports of new evidence and arguments that the 54-year-old darden had ineffective legal counsel
in angola, la., meanwhile, wayne r. felde was put to death in the electric chair early tuesday for the 1978 slaying of a rookie policeman. the the u.s. supreme court on monday had refused in a 7-2 vote to halt the execution
felde had claimed his wartime service in the vietnam war had made him insane, and pleaded with the jury to impose the death penalty to keep him from killing again. he later withdrew the request and fought his execution
darden's appeals already had gone to the u.s. supreme court four times. the last was rejected march 7 and gov. bob martinez signed darden's seventh death warrant the next day
martinez on monday dismissed suggestions he was rushing the execution
it's been 15 years,'' martinez said. ``i think of the victim at a moment like this and the family which was destroyed. a hideous murder took place and that's what i keep in mind. just because it's 15 years later, that doesn't reduce a crime that was committed at the time.''
darden was condemned for the shooting of james turman, who interrupted a man robbing his wife, helen, of $15. mrs. turman later identified darden as the assailant
i think it was all very fair and darden was the one who did it,'' mrs. turman told lakeland radio station wonn. ``i was in the store alone with him for a long time before jim came in and was shot. ... his face is still impressed in the back of my memory. i can't get it out.''
a neighbor, philip arnold, also identified darden during the trial. arnold, then 16, entered the store after apparently hearing the shooting and mrs. turman's cries and was shot three times
if executed, darden will be the 18th man florida has put to death since may 1979. those men died after three or fewer warrants
death penalty opponents claim darden was railroaded because he is black, and that he is innocent of murder and has an alibi to prove it. they claim there is evidence _ statements from a minister and another person _ that darden could not have committed the murder
the signing of the warrant last week gave defense attorneys only one week to prepare
a lot of people feel the primary reason for the seven-day warrant was to limit amnesty international's ability to have sufficient time to mobilize a public opinion assault as they did very effectively for the sixth warrant,'' said larry spalding, chief of the office of capital collateral representative, a state-funded office of defense attorneys for death row inmates
several hundred phone calls and telegrams had been received at the governor's office in tallahassee, most in favor of clemency. the florida conference on the poor held a vigil in the capitol rotunda monday to press for clemency
in sweden, about a dozen people demonstrated monday outside the u.s. embassy in stockholm, urging florida to commute darden's death sentence
the protest was sponsored by the swedish chapter of amnesty international, which charged in a statement that ``death sentences in the united states are handed down with a great deal of discrimination and with a racial slant.''
since january, i have received close to 2,000 letters from around the world,'' darden said in an interview with the new york times published sunday in which he maintained his innocence. occupation</head>
prominent israeli peace activists say american jews who refuse to criticize the occupation of the west bank and gaza strip are hurting israel
by remaining silent, the activists said, many american jews have signaled endorsement of the policies of prime minister yitzhak shamir, thereby increasing the credibility of his views
shamir arrived here monday for talks with u.s. officials. the peace activists planned a prayer vigil outside the white house when shamir meets with president reagan on wednesday
but the activists said the americans jews opposed to shamir should make their views known. those expressions could help curb the ``terrifying phenomenon'' in which israeli voters are moving to the right, said yael dayan, daughter of the late israeli defense minister moshe dayan
on the whole, american jews are not behind shamir's policy,'' said mordechai bar-on, a founder of the israeli group, peace now. ``they must speak out now.''
shamir, head of the likud party, is reluctant to cede to the palestinians land in the west bank or gaza, two areas seized by israel in the six-day war of 1967. his views are opposed by many labor party officials in jerusalem, who favor a more conciliatory approach towards the palestinians
giora furman, former deputy commander of the israeli air force, said it is unrealistic for israel to hang on to the territories in the face of the determined palestinian uprising
the peace group wants shamir to endorse the return of some land to the palestinians, which is part of secretary of state george p. shultz's middle east peace proposal
i am very upset with what is happening to the american jewish community,'' ms. dayan said, adding it was ``rubbish'' for american jews to hold their tongues when israel does something morally wrong
ms. dayan said americans should write members of congress and israeli leaders. but using u.s. aid as a lever to force change could be counterproductive because the money _ about $1.5 billion annually _ is spent on worthy causes, she said
morris abram, chairman of the conference of presidents of major jewish organizations, said the peace activists should be directing its criticism at the arab leaders who refuse to meet with israeli officials
the group is misdirected as to where its criticism is being put,'' he said
secretary of state george p. shultz says that seven weeks of senate testimony have produced nothing to bar the speedy ratification of the new arms reduction treaty with the soviet union
testifying before the senate foreign relations committee on monday, shultz angrily dismissed an allegation by sen. jesse helms, r-n.c., that the administration's public defense of the pact is based on ``misrepresentation'' and is at odds with facts presented in closed-door secret sessions
shultz also said the senate should firmly discard all proposed amendments or reservations to the treaty, including one that would tie its implementation to reversing soviet superiority in conventional arms in europe
he ticked off objections that have been mounted to the terms of the pact, which bans medium-range nuclear missiles, and asserted that all those objections have been refuted
the secretary of state, whose testimony opened the committee's examination of the treaty in january, commented as he made a return appearance to offer a summing up
sen. alan cranston, d-calif., the senate's deputy majority leader and a respected vote counter, predicted that the pact will be ratified by the full senate by a margin far greater than the required two-thirds majority
cranston said the senate will act well in advance of a planned moscow summit meeting this spring between president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev
we believe the treaty stands on its merits,'' shultz said. ``it is self-contained and should not be made a vehicle for statements on other issues,'' including the soviet military occupation of afghanistan
but he bristled after hearing helms declare that there is ``a wide gap between the administration's public representations about the treaty and the information which we have received in closed session.''
indeed,'' helms said, ``after many hours of listening to testimony both private and public, the administration's public presentation of the treaty has been a tissue of confusion, misstatements and _ and i use the word advisedly _ even misrepresentations.''
shultz told helms: ``in a sense i don't know what i'm doing here. are you sitting here accusing me of deliberately misrepresenting? ... i can handle it fine when people say they don't agree with me, but when they say i have misrepresented, i have trouble with that.''
helms said he was not accusing shultz of ``deliberately'' misrepresenting, but he added that ``the contradictions are self-apparent.''
replying to questions, shultz told sen. larry pressler, r-s.d., that senate passage of an amendment delaying implementation of the treaty until the west achieved a balance with the soviet union in conventional arms would kill the pact
the pact, formally termed the intermediate-range nuclear forces or inf treaty, calls for the destruction of all nuclear missiles with a range of between 300 miles and 3,400 miles
shultz said he does not believe the treaty will cause west germany to demand the removal of all nuclear weapons from its soil _ a step that some fear could open europe to intimidation by the soviet union, which is said to have superiority in conventional, non-nuclear forces
interest rates on short-term treasury securities fell in the latest auction, with six-month bills dropping to the lowest level since last july
the treasury department sold $6.5 billion in three-month bills at an average discount rate of 5.65 percent on monday, down from 5.74 percent last week. an additional $6.4 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average discount rate of 5.78 percent, down from 5.93 percent last week
the rates were the lowest since three-month bills sold for 5.62 percent on feb. 29 and six-month bills averaged 5.54 percent on july 13, 1987
the new discount rates understate the actual return to investors _ 5.81 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for $9,857.20 and 6.04 percent for a six-month bill selling for $9,707.80
in a separate report, the federal reserve said the average yield for one-year treasury bills, the most popular index for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages rose to 6.72 percent last week from 6.63 percent the previous week. edits to conform</note>
stock prices rebounded in heavy afternoon trading, while the dollar rose slightly in tokyo trading tuesday as dealers awaited u.s. trade deficit figures
on the tokyo stock exchange, the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues fell during the morning session but rebounded and ended the day at 25,475.67 points, up 42.16 points, or 0.16 percent, from monday's close
the dollar, after temporarily dipping below the 127-yen mark, closed at 127.25 yen, up 0.02 yen from monday's close
an exchange dealer at a major commercial bank in tokyo, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the tokyo market ``seems to remain relatively calm'' until the release of u.s. trade figures for january, scheduled for thursday
large-capital industrials and steels traded actively, but most other sectors were quiet, according to an analyst who requested anonymity
the teamsters union has set a new march 29 target for its 6,700 member flight attendants to strike northwest airlines armed with a pledge that mechanics and baggage handlers will honor picket lines
anyone who is thinking of flying northwest during the easter holidays should forget it,'' william genoese, director of the union's airline division, told reporters monday after announcing the strike deadline
northwest officials expressed immediate skepticism that the union will carry out its threat, but said the airline has management workers and replacement attendants in training to keep the airline operating if it does
the teamsters have set many deadlines ... and flight attendants continue to work,'' said bob gibbons, a northwest spokesman. ``we'll just have to see if this deadline has any more validity than others the union has announced.''
genoese met several hours at teamster headquarters here with guy cook, president of the machinists union's district 143 in minneapolis, which represents northwest's 20,000 mechanics and baggage handlers
i have no doubt that the membership i represent will honor any work stoppage,'' said cook ``we've got our own problems in negotiations with northwest. if they want a war, they probably are going to get one.''
the teamsters earlier had threatened to strike northwest the last weekend of february, when a 30-day cooling-off period ordered by the national mediation board expired
northwest, based in st. paul, minn., has announced it will unilaterally impose a new policy manual on april 1 replacing the old flight attendants' contract and stretching out from five years to eight years the time required for a newly hired attendant to reach top scale
absent from monday's meeting were representatives of the air line pilots association, which represents 2,300 northwest pilots
the pilots have told us that when the time comes, they will do the right thing,'' genoese said
leaders of alpa's northwest locals could not be reached for comment. but john mazor, a spokeman at the pilot union's headquarters here, said its policy is to ``not announce any decision on whether to support a strike by another union unless or until a strike occurs and a picket line goes up.''
under the national railway labor act governing labor relations in the rail and airline industries, courts have frequently ordered members of unions not on strike themselves but honoring another union's picket line to return to work
terms of a two-tier, a and b, wage system at northwest under which new hires reach the pay level of veterans have been the major stumbling block in the bargaining talks between the airline and the teamsters
the union originally proposed eliminating the lower b scale entirely but had agreed to stretch it to six years before the talks broke off
northwest's last contract proposal included raising base pay for beginning flight attendants on the b scale would climb from $13,000 to $15,000 over a five-year period. base pay for full-time veterans on the top a scale would rise from $32,000 to $35,000 under the same offer
senators are starting to push their house counterparts in earnest to erase the trade plan that serves as the centerpiece of democrat richard a. gephardt's race for the presidential nomination
we decided to stick with our own super 301 plan and to oppose the gephardt amendment,'' sen. lloyd bentsen, d-texas, said monday after a meeting of senate conferees on the trade issue
as part of the action, the senate will ask the house to drop the gephardt plan from the final version of sweeping trade legislation passed by both houses last year
the decision was made by senate members of a house-senate conference committee seeking a compromise version of the rival 1,000-page trade bills. it came on a voice vote in a closed-door session of the senate conferees
the move represents step one in a compromise process involving proposals that go back and forth between the house and senate until both chambers agree on one version
gephardt spokesman mark johnson said the senate's action represented ``nothing new'' in the trade debate
it's merely an opening bargaining position,'' he said. ``we're confident that whatever emerges from conference will be new, forceful legislation to open foreign markets. and clearly the gephardt amendment paved the way.''
gephardt's plan calls for negotiations to reduce japan's and other nations' ``excess and unwarranted'' trade surpluses with the united states
if those talks failed, the plan would prescribe presidential action to cut the surpluses by 10 percent a year. such action could include tariffs or import quotas on japanese goods brought into the united states
the president could, however, take no action if there are considerations of ``national economic security'' or if the other country had a serious international debt problem
gephardt's amendment has been the chief basis of his appeal to blue-collar workers and others concerned over the impact on american jobs of products imported from japan and newly industrialized nations in east asia
the ``super 301'' provision that the senate is pushing would require the president to act to eliminate all of the unfair foreign trade practices listed on an inventory to be drawn up by the u.s. trade representative. it is named for the section of the trade act that deals with retaliatory steps against such unfair practices
before sending their offer to the house, the senators planned to return to the table today and fashion additional provisions involving steps to combat ``dumping,'' or selling foreign-made products in world markets at prices lower than those in home markets
the senators also intend to work on provisions involving ``countervailing duties,'' or tariffs that are imposed to offset the price advantage that some foreign-made products get from export subsidies in their home countries
on monday, the senators moved to expand from seven months to 12 months the time for the president to make a determination as to whether a foreign trade practice should be considered unfair
wayne robert felde, who had pleaded with a jury to impose the death penalty to keep him from killing again, was executed in the electric chair early tuesday for the 1978 slaying of a rookie policeman
felde, 38, went to his death at 12:14 a.m. after the u.s. supreme court late monday refused in a 7-2 vote to stay the execution
you can kill the messenger but you can't kill the message,'' he said in his final statement. ``sooner or later, you have to acknowledge it for what it means, not for what you want it to mean.''
he gave no indication what he referred to, but paused so that witnesses could write it down
felde was convicted of shooting a policeman in the back in shreveport while being taken to jail in handcuffs for drunkenness. an army veteran of vietnam, felde had claimed at trial that his wartime experience had made him insane
the execution occurred less than a day after gov. buddy roemer was inaugurated. felde's lawyers had planned to ask the governor to stop the execution until a new pardon board could consider the case
roemer had said earlier he would not intervene
in starke, fla., meanwhile, willie jasper darden, who survived an unprecedented six death warrants and became an international cause celebre, awaited execution in the electric chair early tuesday for the 1973 slaying of a businessman during a robbery
the last time there was more than one execution in one day in this country was aug. 28, when murderers were put to death in alabama, florida and utah
felde was the first person in louisiana to use his vietnam service as the basis for a criminal insanity plea
he said finding viet cong tunnels and being exposed to the chemical agent orange left him subject to flashbacks and unable to tell right from wrong when he pulled a gun hidden in his pants and shot officer glen thomkins while being taken to jail in handcuffs
in 1980, a jury convicted him of first-degree murder, which carries life in prison or death in the electric chair. felde asked for the death penalty, ``or other deaths will result.''
it's happened twice in eight years. there's been 10 years of proof shown to you,'' he told the jury. felde at the time of the slaying was a fugitive from a work release program in maryland, where he had been convicted of manslaughter
felde withdrew his request after the trial, and his appeal to the supreme court was based in part on his claim that he was denied competent representation because his attorney at trial joined him in asking for the death sentence
felde appeared unsuccessfully before the pardon board appointed by roemer's predecessor, gov. edwin edwards, two weeks ago
bill quigley, one of felde's lawyers, argued that the old board was tainted by a pardon-selling scandal that sent the board chairman to jail. he said roemer should refer the case to the new board he appoints
ninety-four people have been executed in the united states, including 15 in louisiana, since the death penalty was revived following a u.s. supreme court decision in the 1970s
the most recent occurred jan. 7 when robert streetman was executed by injection in texas for murdering a woman in 1982. the most recent execution in louisiana was aug. 24
sen. joseph r. biden's doctors are discussing treatment to prevent more blood clots like the one just discovered in one of the senator's lungs
peter esker, a spokesman at walter reed army medical center, said monday that the clot in the lung was dissolving, but treatment would likely be needed to prevent further clots
doctors could use anti-coagulant drugs or a surgical procedure, esker said
biden, 45, was admitted to the hospital sunday. he underwent an operation at walter reed on feb. 12 to repair an aneurysm _ the ballooning of an artery wall _ in an artery supplying blood to the brain
biden was recovering at home from that operation and waiting for an operation on a second aneurysm when he had to re-enter the hospital
medical tests show that the senator did experience a pulmonary embolism, or a blood clot, that lodged in one of his lungs,'' esker said
the clot, which could have resulted from decreased activity following major surgery, did no damage. medical tests are continuing to determine the method of lessening the chances of other clots developing,'' he said
esker said the alternative to anti-coagulant drugs is to insert a venous filter, a form of catheter, in a vein
students at the nation's only liberal arts college for the deaf greeted the week with jubilation, as they were formally introduced to the first deaf president and first deaf board chairman in gallaudet university's history
irving king jordan jr. and philip w. bravin received standing ovations monday from the same students who effectively shut down the 124-year-old institution over appointment of a woman with normal hearing to be president
people will look at us and study what we are doing,'' said jordan, a 44-year-old professor and dean of the college of arts and sciences at gallaudet. ``we will prove to them, not only can they choose a deaf president and chairman, but that these two will succeed.''
the two officials were joined at a news conference by student body president greg hlibok, one of the campus leaders in the week of protest over the hiring of elisabeth ann zinser as president
the students succeeded in pressuring zinser to resign last friday, less than a week after her appointment and in winning the subsequent resignation of board chairman jane bassett spilman, who can hear
we're back in business and back to business, but gallaudet will never again be what it used to be,'' said hlibok, who spoke in sign language and through an interpreter
only a few students were on campus monday, the first day of a spring break, but many people filled the auditorium for the press conference and wore their ``deaf president now'' buttons
jordan had endorsed zinser's presidency last week but then retracted it
jordan lost his hearing at age 20 in a motorcycle accident. he speaks clearly, but also uses sign language when he talks
we are continually impressed with him and we will give him our full support,'' said jerry covell, a leader of the protest
jordan received his bachelor's degree in psychology at gallaudet, then obtained his master's and doctorate at the university of tennessee
roman catholic church leaders, who have called on gen. manuel antonio noriega to step down, offered to mediate talks between the military strongman and opposition political groups demanding his ouster
but church officials also said on monday that it may be difficult ``to build a silver bridge for (noriega) to leave,'' now that the united states has indicted noriega on drug trafficking and money laundering charges
since then, the country has fallen into a deepening financial crisis that occurred after the united states imposed several new economic sanctions on panama, including the withholding of $6.5 million in panama canal fees due this week. it earlier cut off all economic and military aid to the country
the 118 local and foreign banks that do business in panama remained closed monday by government order for the 20th straight day
the church still hopes to act as a bridge. there is no question that noriega must go ... the problem is how he goes,'' the rev. fernando guardia, a top church spokesman and vicar of the archdiocese, said monday
archbishop marcos mcgrath, a native of philadelphia, has been criticial of the government in the past, but always avoided direct confrontation to protect his priests, nearly 75 percent of whom are foreigners
under panamanian law, they must have their visas renewed every three months by immigration authorities, which come under noriega's defense forces
noriega, the defense forces chief and the nation's de facto ruler, ousted president eric arturo delvalle on feb. 26 after delvalle tried to fire noriega
we are under pressure,'' said father guardia, a panamanian, explaining that foreign priests who tried to speak out in the past were often threatened and reminded that they can lose their visas. ``they have not expelled any of our priests, but they have us by the neck.''
the country's bishops, in a statements that mentioned no names, have accused the military regime of being responsible for panama's crisis
the bishops urged ``strict observance of constitutional norms, full and effective subordination of the military to civil authority,'' the creation of conditions for free elections, ``the restoration of civil liberties and human rights,'' and asked that ``news media be allowed to reopen.''
the bishops also lashed out at the military for resorting ``to false nationalism'' to whip up support for the noriega government, but called for a ``panamanian solution to the crisis without foreign intervention.''
the bishops also offered on monday to act as a ``liaison'' to seek a solution to the crisis, but there was no answer from the government. official government media accused the church of siding with the oppostion
people were fed up with noriega since last year,'' father guardia said, ``but the indictment by the united states was politically mishandled. the government party and other groups here threw their support to noriega and noriega will hang in there longer and eventually drag others with him.''
they (the united states) closed all avenues,'' father guardia added. ``it is very difficult for noriega now to go somewhere with the indictment hanging over his head. but he has to realize that he msut go
about 80 percent of the people of panama are roman catholic
