new england's economy would prosper under the u.s.-canada free-trade agreement, enjoying a more accessible canadian market and stabilized power imports that could entice new companies to the region, says a business group study
george macomber, chairman of the new england council inc., which released the report monday, said the study ``clearly demonstrates that the (pact) would benefit the region and in the long term improve new england's trade position with canada.''
the council, an association representing more than 1,000 businesses in the six states, supports the agreement, which was signed jan. 2 by president reagan and canadian prime minister brian mulroney. it still must win ratification by congress and the canadian parliament
various industries in the northwest and midwest have expressed concern about the pact, saying it does not do enough to eliminate canadian trade barriers. but many new england officials support the agreement
the agreement would eliminate all tariffs between the two countries by 1999 and would establish a new tribunal to settle future trade disputes. the united states and canada are the world's two largest trading partners, with two-way trade of nearly $150 billion a year
some handicapped protestors criticizing what they said are federal policies that result in inadequate mass transit services for disabled people have chained themselves to the doors of the department of transportation headquarters and vow to stay until officials agree to improve bus service for handicapped people
members of americans disabled for accessible transportation (adapt) gathered from around the country monday to protest the department's decision to appeal a january ruling that transit agencies must provide services to the handicapped regardless of cost
in the ruling, u.s. district judge marvin katz in philadelphia struck down a transportation department regulation requiring the nation's transit authorities to spend no more than 3 percent of their budgets on the disabled
the demonstrators timed their protest to coincide with a three-day meeting of the american public transit association, which represents local agencies that provide bus and subway service
timothy cook, a philadelphia attorney who represented adapt in the lawsuit, said the present system of allowing transit agencies to decide what services to provide to the handicapped ``gives individual states the option to discriminate.''
transportation secretary jim burnley said monday the department is ``fully committed to providing mass transportation to people with disabilities.''
the national oceanic and atmospheric administration has levied fines totaling $100,000 against three japanese firms whose ships were videotaped apparently fishing illegally in u.s. waters off alaska in early january
the civil fines of $25,000 per vessel involved are the maximum allowed under u.s. law
this underscores how seriously we viewed the violations,'' jim brennan, a deputy general counsel for noaa, said monday. he said the japanese companies can seek an administrative hearing on the fines if they decide to appeal
this action should send a powerful message to any fisherman who is thinking about fishing illegally in our waters,'' said rep. don bonker, d-wash
the fines were based on a review of the videotapes and depositions taken from commercial fishermen who chartered a plane and photographed the vessels with their nets down allegedly 38 miles inside the american fishing zone, said brennan
two of the vessels videotaped are owned and operated by hamaya suisan co., ltd., which was fined a total of $50,000, said brennan. the other two vessels are owned and operated by senkon gyogyo co., ltd., and taisei gyogyo co., ltd., those companies each were fined $25,000
in addition, the owners and operators of two unidentified fishing vessels that were also videotaped were fined a total of $100,000. the identification numbers on the vessels were covered at the time they were photographed
the sentencing of former presidential aide lyn nofziger has been postponed from march 25 until april 8 to give defense lawyers more time to study a report being prepared by the federal probation office
u.s. district judge thomas a. flannery on monday granted the defense request to postpone the sentencing. the request was not opposed by independent counsel james c. mckay
nofziger, who was white house political director from 1981 until early 1982, was convicted last month of three counts of illegally lobbying former colleagues in the reagan administration on behalf of private clients
he faces a potential two-year prison term and a $10,000 fine on each count
cardinal miguel obando y bravo was removed as mediator of the peace talks because he wanted the sandinistas to discuss political reforms as well as a cease-fire with the contras, sources said
president daniel ortega diplomatically eased obando y bravo from his job as mediator on march 2, thanking him for his efforts but saying the cardinal would not be needed for direct talks scheduled for next week
the manuever effectively removed the roman catholic prelate from pushing what were seen by the leftist sandinista government as pro-contra proposals
ortega has called for three days of face-to-face talks with the contras beginning monday in the nicaraguan post at sapoa on the border with costa rica
ortega said his brother, gen. humberto ortega, the nation's top military leader, would head the sandinista delegation. the contras countered by naming adolfo calero, their highest political leader, to head their delegation
sandinista sources and opposition figures, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said ortega ousted obando y bravo because he outlined a proposal that would force the government to discuss internal politics with the rebels
the government has refused to discuss anything but a cease-fire
during the last round of talks on feb. 18 in guatemala, obando y bravo called on the sandinista government to grant total amnesty, revise the military draft law, grant full press freedom and reopen stalled talks with internal opposition parties. he also suggested a 30-day truce
the contras quickly accepted the proposal. the sandinistas hesitated
obando y bravo, saying the two sides were at an impasse, broke off the talks the following day
ortega on feb. 23 sent the cardinal an angry letter, decrying the talks' ``abrupt suspension without consulation.'' the letter was the first in a week of exchanges between the government and the catholic leader
the letters also sent signals that church-state relations had once again deteriorated in nicaragua
the strong roman catholic church backed the 1979 revolution that ousted dictator anastasio somoza and supported the sandinistas. but the church later became the staunchest government critic and suffered repression
since the signing of a regional peace plan in august by five central american presidents including ortega, the situation seemed to be improving
the government allowed two exiled priests to return, permitted the catholic radio station to reopen and in november asked the cardinal to be mediator
the cardinal's last letter to ortega was sent march 2, hours before ortega removed him as mediator. in it, the prelate reiterated the need for talks to ``put an end to the grueling war that daily claims 50 or 60 young nicaraguans'' and said he was open to discussing a new outline for negotiations
a church source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the sandinistas hoped to pressure obando y bravo into backing out of his mediation role. when that failed, ortega made his move and visited obando y bravo that night
ortega made it look like he was deferring to the cardinal's wishes
the cardinal himself had suggested some time ago that a direct meeting (with the contras) and in our country would be very important,'' ortega said
for the past four years, obando y bravo has urged direct talks. but the sandinistas had repeatedly refused to sit down with the contras until they were forced to do so by the regional peace plan
the plan signed by nicaragua, el salvador, costa rica, guatemala and honduras calls for cease-fires, democratization, amnesties and an end to tactical or logistical support for insurgencies
the sandinistas say peace talks should be held with the u.s. government because it financed and trained the rebels. the reagan administration refuses
during the first few rounds of talks aimed at working out a cease-fire, the cardinal acted as a go-between in indirect negotiations
in january, ortega proposed direct talks but with a mediator
after obando y bravo was asked to step down as mediator, the contras demanded he be involved in the meetings ``as witness, moderator and guarantor of the talks.'' the president responded on march 7 by calling on the cardinal to act as a witness, a role he accepted and which satisfied the rebels
the first direct talks in nicaragua were scheduled for last week, march 9-11, but were canceled at the last minute by sandinistas after the contras backed out and pressed for a preliminary meeting
the contras later dropped that demand
more than 40,000 people have been killed since november 1981, when the contras began fighting the sandinista government
a brokered democratic national convention is possible, but it's too late for anyone but delegates to do the horse trading, according to rep. tom foley
foley, d-wash., the house majority leader who expects to be convention parliamentarian when the democrats meet in atlanta in july, said monday the party's nominee likely won't be determined beforehand
but if there is any brokering to be done at the democratic convention, it will be by the delegates, he said
i think there's a possibility that no candidate will go into the convention with a sufficient number of delegates to be nominated,'' he said. ``but i don't expect anybody else to be nominated, other than those four or five that are now in the race
brokering is largely going to be a decision of the delegates themselves, not any sort of backroom `kingmaking' operation,'' said foley, who supports house colleague dick gephardt of missouri
sen. lowell p. weicker jr., r-conn., has all but endorsed vice president george bush for the republican presidential nomination, saying that unlike the president, bush bases his decisions on facts and logic rather than ideology
speaking to business leaders monday, weicker, who faces re-election this year, also said the republican presidential campaign of senate minority leader bob dole of kansas has been defeated
weicker, a liberal republican often at odds with president reagan and other conservatives, has has not made a formal endorsement in the gop presidential race but when asked, he lavishly praised bush
i have respect for george bush,'' weicker said. ``he has an open mind that's guided by fact and logic, rather than ideology. he is also a compassionate man.''
connecticut's presidential primary is march 29. bush is considered the favorite in the gop contest in connecticut because he grew up in the state, his father was a u.s. senator from connecticut and his mother and brother still live in greenwich
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis named rep. dennis hertel as michigan chairman of his campaign for the 1988 democratic presidential nomination
dukakis announced the appointment on monday after being endorsed by hertel, a four-term congressman from the detroit suburb of harper woods
as industrial states, massachusetts and michigan face many of the same problems,'' hertel said in a statement released by dukakis' campaign. ``mike dukakis has dealt with these problems as governor of massachusetts and has successfully implemented innovative solutions to turn the massachusetts economy into one of the most productive and admired in the country
as president, mike dukakis can do the same for the entire nation.''
new york gov. mario cuomo says jesse jackson is ``electable'' as a democratic presidential candidate and ``has done extremely well'' at getting out an appealing message
of course he's electable,'' said fellow democrat cuomo monday during an inpromptu news conference following a speech to new york's county officials. ``if the democrats _ and that's a majority in the country, is it not? _ if the democrats say they want jackson, how can you say he's not electable?''
because he is black, some political analysts and fellow democrats have suggested that jackson couldn't be elected president
his message is appealing,'' cuomo added. ``he's saying to the people ... that we have many people who have been left out that we need to educate and house through job training because we can't make it without them. it's not just a matter of compassion, it's a matter of common sense.''
cuomo has said that jackson stands a good chance of winning new york's important april 19 primary but he has refused to endorse any of the active democratic candidates
cuomo, who announced more than a year ago that he wouldn't seek the democratic presidential nomination, also has refused to rule out accepting a draft for the nomination if there's a deadlocked national convention. negative</head>
a study of network evening newscasts from jan. 1 through super tuesday march 8 says democrat jesse jackson got the best television coverage and republican pat robertson got the most negative
the center for media and public affairs, a non-partisan study group, said it studied 532 news items involving the election and found:
_evaluations of every major candidate, based on clearly positive or negative statements from all sources relating to character, job performance, campaign performance or issue stands, became more negative after the new hampshire primary feb. 16
_ telecast comments involving jackson were favorable 74 percent of the time, compared with 90 percent this year before new hampshire. he also nearly tripled his share of the democrats' coverage, from 9 percent before new hampshire to 26 percent in the weeks leading up to march 8 super tuesday
_robertson dropped from 70 percent positive evaluations before new hampshire to 33 percent after it. comments about his prospects also became more negative
the analysts also said there have been four stories on the campaign horse race for every story on policy issues since the feb. 8 iowa caucuses and the issues most frequently mentioned are taxes and trade
the state board of elections has rejected challenges to illinois sen. paul simon's petitions for a spot on new york's april 19 democratic presidential primary ballot
the challenges had been filed by political extremist lyndon larouche and monday's ruling meant simon's name will appear on the ballot
board spokesman steven lafever said that after a lengthy hearing, the board ruled that simon had filed petitions containing the valid signatures of 21,263 registered democrats. his original petitions had contained 22,076 signatures and only 10,000 are needed to qualify for the ballot
the ruling in favor of simon means that the new york ballot for democrats will include all the major democratic candidates and larouche
larouche is also seeking the democratic nomination. his petitions have not been challenged
a chief accuser of impeached gov. evan mecham got legal advice on how to deal with mecham from the lawyer who has become acting gov. rose mofford's chief of staff
andrew hurwitz, who also served as chief of staff during part of bruce babbitt's governorship, confirmed monday that he provided legal advice to department of public safety director ralph t. milstead for reduced fees
the attorney-client relationship with milstead is not disclosed on hurwitz's conflict-of-interest forms but he confirmed it after the associated press learned of it
i just don't see that it was necessary,'' he said. ``there certainly is no personal interest here. i don't gain or lose anything at all
am i a longstanding friend of ralph milstead? that's pretty clear,'' he added. ``the fact that i like him i don't think is a big issue.''
milstead testified at mecham's impeachment trial that the governor ordered him not to cooperate with a state attorney general's inquiry into an alleged death threat. defense lawyers subsequently accused milstead of denying mecham a fair trial by attempting to intimidate defense witnesses
mecham, a republican, wrote a letter monday to mrs. mofford, a democrat, demanding that milstead and two assistants be placed on leave. hurwitz, who supervises milstead's department for mofford, said the three would not be placed on leave pending an fbi investigation and another inquiry he is supervising
hurwitz, a private attorney on loan to mrs. mofford by his firm, acknowledged it might be inappropriate for him to continue supervising the internal investigation
mrs. mofford, elected as secretary of state, became acting governor when the house impeached mecham and will become the permanent governor if the senate convicts him or if she wins a multi-candidate may 17 recall election against mecham
hurwitz, who only last friday said that full disclosure of potential conflicts was vital for public confidence, acknowledged that publicity about his relationship with milstead could harm mrs. mofford politically
hurwitz said milstead came to him and law partner jack lasota after mecham was elected in 1986
mecham was widely thought to be thinking of trying to fire milstead despite the state police chief's four-year contract, and milstead ``called us up and sought some legal advice,'' hurwitz said
he declined to elaborate, citing attorney-client privilege, but said he believed that the bill, discounted to ``something like half-rates'' because milstead was a friend, came to less than $2,000 and probably less than $1,000
hurwitz said he had not done any work for milstead in about six months, adding ``i don't represent him now.'' hurwitz said he stopped advising milstead before the events occurred that are at issue in the impeachment trial
but lasota said in a separate interview he considered the relationship to be ongoing
whitey bloom knows about life's ups and downs, and ups and downs, and ups and downs
bloom, a stocky junior high school teacher, knocked off 32,770 push-ups in 24 hours during the weekend, unofficially breaking by 197 the guinness book of world records' mark for the most push-ups in a single day
with about 60 friends and supporters cheering him on, bloom broke the record shortly after noon sunday. he plans to mail a log book and other papers to guinness for official confirmation
bloom said he slept about 20 minutes during the 24 hours. support from friends was essential
the last couple of hours, they were really cheering me on,'' he said monday. ``i was just dogged tired and i'm not sure i would have made it without them.''
bloom trained for months with a daily regimen of several thousand push-ups. in a practice session around christmas, he did 16,000 push-ups in about seven hours, ``just to get a feel for it.''
now he just feels sore
the best thing about it is when i woke up this morning, i didn't feel obligated to do my usual 1,000,'' he said
colossus, a 502-pound ape reputed to be the largest lowland gorilla in captivity, was adjusting well to his new home in a private zoo after moving from new hampshire, his keepers said
he's doing wonderfully,'' said pat quinn, director of the zoo. ``he's eating well, vocalizing, a lot of chest pounding and stomping on his bed.''
the 20-year-old gorilla was moved sunday night from hudson, n.h., where he had been purchased from benson's animal park when it went out of business
the ape was flown on a dc-3 piloted by stan brock of the ``wild kingdom'' television show to pensacola and then trucked to the zoo on monday
moving pads were put around and inside colossus' packing crate to keep him warm during the trip, quinn said. he developed an attachment for the blankets, taking a pair with him to his new home in two adjoining cages, or bedrooms as quinn prefers to call them
he's got those blankets with him all the time,'' quinn said, adding that no one has volunteered to try to take them away
we don't short sheet gorillas,'' he joked
quinn hopes to breed colossus with female gorillas, but the ape hasn't seen another gorilla since he was captured in the wild as an infant
his first introduction will be by television. he enjoyed a television in his cage in new hampshire, and zoo officials hope to install a tv and play videotapes for him in his new home, quinn said
one of the country's most wanted narcotics traffickers has been arrested and charged with importing 1,000 pounds of heroin into the united states from asia over a three-year period
kon yu-leung, 44, who was arrested sunday night outside a manhattan hotel, had been the drug enforcement administration's no. 1 heroin target for about 2{ years, said u.s. attorney andrew maloney
kon's drug ring was much larger than well-known heroin cases operated by traditional organized crime groups, said robert stutman, head of the dea's new york office. the ``french connection'' case involved 70 pounds of heroin, the ``pizza connection'' about 200, he said at a news conference with maloney
maloney said kon was believed responsible for bringing into the country twice the 1,000 pounds of heroin he was charged with importing
clearly, the levels of heroin we're dealing with here are almost mind-boggling,'' said stutman
the heroin from kon's drug ring was smuggled into the country between 1984 and 1987 through various means, including suitcases and in shipments of vases, ice buckets, t-shirts and wall plaques, maloney said
couriers then carried millions of dollars in drug proceeds back to hong kong to be laundered, authorities said. kon allegedly used $20 million to buy commercial real estate in the new york area and san francisco
stutman said kon sold the heroin to distributors at an estimated wholesale price of $100,000 per pound. authorities estimate the street value of one pound of heroin at $1 million
law enforcement authorities confiscated 570 of the 1,000 pounds alleged to have been imported by kon's organization in several seizures over the years, stutman said
kon first came to the dea's attention in november 1984 when a shipment of 250 pounds of heroin, believed to be destined for the united states, was seized in the hong kong harbor from a fishing trawler
kon, the alleged mastermind, eluded arrest by moving between thailand, taiwan, japan and the philippines, maloney said
assistant u.s. attorney catherine palmer said kon had at least six phony passports and traveled under numerous fictitious names
she said kon, who was born in mainland china and later moved to hong kong before becoming a fugitive, had numerous businesses in asia and the united states, including several fur companies and a firm called the kon china trading co. he also allegedly had a watch manufacturing company in paraguay
maloney said federal authorities lured kon to new york after a federal grand jury indicted him. he declined to give any details concerning the circumstances of kon's arrest
authorities also arrested john routollo, a former new york police officer, at his montclair, n.j., home sunday night. routollo, 50, was charged with picking up the heroin, usually at the new york hilton hotel, for distribution in the united states
maloney said that before routollo left the force in 1981 he supplied weapons to kon's organization through his position in the police department's office of pistols and licenses. cancer</head>
would-be assassin lynette ``squeaky'' fromme was convicted of escape after she told jurors she fled from prison because she thought her lover and mentor, mass murderer charles manson, had cancer
a federal jury on monday convicted fromme of the two-day escape from the federal correctional institution at alderson, where she is serving a life sentence for her 1975 attempt on then-president gerald ford's life
you don't have any choice,'' she told the jurors while acting as her own attorney. ``i'm guilty as charged, legally, and without remorse morally, so that's that.''
the jury returned its verdict within 10 minutes. u.s. district judge elizabeth hallanan set sentencing for april 28
fromme, 39, faces five years in prison and $250,000 fine for the conviction
fromme, who escaped dec. 23 and was recaptured two miles away on christmas day, has been described as the main member of the manson ``family.'' manson is serving a life sentence in san quentin prison in california for the 1969 murders of actress sharon tate and eight others
fromme told the jury monday she attempted to escape because ``i got word that (manson) had cancer
he needs a relative, somebody to check on him,'' she said of manson, whom she described as ``my husband, my brother, my father, my son, the man who's been my friend.''
she said she decided to escape because ``my access to him is so limited, i've been feeling helpless for years
if love means anything at all it means stop feeling helpless ... (and) take action if necessary.''
fromme called only herself as a witness. she carefully followed hallanan's instructions that her testimony had to be in the form of questions and answers
she questioned herself on the pronounciation of her name and cautioned: ``miss fromme, you talk too much,'' and ``wait a minute, you're getting ahead of yourself.''
fromme also cross-examined the four prison employees called as government witnesses. each indicated the institution _ which has an official capacity of 670 prisoners _ holds about 1,000 inmates. in her testimony, she told the jury the overcrowding was another reason she escaped
the prison has become more and more crowded, and the institution staff has become more and more tense,'' she said
ford was unharmed when a secret service agent grabbed the semi-automatic pistol from fromme on sept. 5, 1975. in san francisco 17 days later, ford again escaped injury from would-be assassin sara jane moore, who fired a revolver at him. she eventually pleaded guilty and received a life sentence
in 1979, moore also escaped from the alderson prison but was recaptured hours later. she is now at the federal prison in pleasanton, calif
a former methodist minister has decided not to contest a lawsuit by his mother-in-law accusing him of a near-fatal choking attack on his wife, saying legal fees would be too costly
he told me that he had decided his assets would be best used in the support and maintenance of his children,'' said doug mulder, a defense attorney who represented walker railey before a dallas county grand jury investigating the attack
mulder said the former minister decided not to contest the lawsuit because of estimates it would cost nearly $100,000 in legal fees. mulder called the lawsuit a ``publicity stunt,'' and said his client could win if he spent the money
the suit was filed by billie jo nicolai, seeking an undetermined amount of damages in the april attack on her daughter, peggy railey. mrs. railey, 39, never regained consciousness and remains in a coma in a tyler nursing home
mrs. nicolai's attorney, bill arnold, said monday he will seek a default judgment but will ask for a jury trial to determine damages
the question now is, when do i want to go to court?' it could be tomorrow or it could be a couple of months. it depends on peggy's best interests. i'm not going to run my schedule according to walker's schedule,'' arnold said
railey's father-in-law said he was disappointed there was no response to the lawsuit
we thought he might come through and answer some of our questions. it sure would help, but it didn't turn out that way,'' he said in a monday night telephone interview from his rural smith county home. ``it really is disappointing. i guess we're just going to have to keep waiting.''
without a response, a judge could rule against the former senior minister of the first united methodist church of dallas and award damages in his absence
railey, 40, was not charged, but both his attorney and dallas county assistant district attorney norm kinne identified him the prime suspect
railey refused to cooperate with police, denying his involvement and then invoking his fifth amendment right against self-incrimination 43 times when questioned by a grand jury
a psychologist, lucy papillon, reportedly told the grand jury that she and railey were romantically involved and had discussed marriage before the attack
railey is living in san francisco, where he rented an apartment with ms. papillon, arnold said
railey assigned his wife's guardianship to her mother, and that of his two children, ages 5 and 2, to family friends in dallas
iraq said it fired four more long-range missiles into tehran today, and iran said civilians were killed when iraqi missiles crashed into residential areas of the city
iran claimed its jet fighters ``heavily pounded'' iraqi troop concentrations in southern iraq today, inflicting substantial casualties and losses. iraq did not comment on the report
in another development, the soviet union acknowledged at the united nations in new york on monday that it had failed to win support for a security council resolution calling for an end to the deadly missile duel
the iraqi news agency, monitored in nicosia, said four missiles were fired into tehran today. it reported eight such missile strikes on monday
iran's islamic republic news agency, also monitored in nicosia, said ``a number'' of civilians were killed in missile attacks on residential areas of the city overnight. it did not say how many rockets hit tehran
on monday, iran said missiles killed 26 civilians and wounded 50 in tehran. iraq also reported civilian casualties in baghdad but gave no figures
iraq says it has fired 13 missiles into tehran since the duel with iran resumed with a single rocket fired into the iranian capital sunday night after a two-day truce. iran has fired two into baghdad since sunday
declaring an all-out offensive on iranian cities, iraq said it launched air raids on ``military and economic targets'' in six western border towns monday
irna also said revolutionary guards commandos pushed into northeast iraq to within 12 miles of the provincial capital of sulaimaniyeh early monday, seizing a dozen villages and killing or wounding 1,000 iraqis
iran also said its anti-aircraft gunners shot down an iraqi fighter-bomber in the northeastern battles, while iraq claimed its helicoptergunships downed an iranian helicopter
an uneasy two-day truce that ended sunday had brought a brief respite following a 12-day exchange of missiles, artillery fire and air raids by both sides that killed or wounded hundreds of civilians
iraq said it fired 71 missiles into tehran, the holy city of qom and the central city of isfahan, capital of ancient persia, between feb. 29 and march 11. iran said it shot 27 missiles into tehran and two into the northeastern city of mosul in that period
at the united nations, soviet ambassador alexander belonogov acknowledged on monday that the soviet bid for a new resolution on the ``war of the cities'' had failed after the council met behind closed doors
our personal preference would be a resolution of the security council,'' but the important thing is ``not the form but the essence'' of the council's action, he told reporters after a closed-door council meeting
the united states saw the proposal as a maneuver to deflect attention from the american push for a worldwide arms embargo against iran to punish it for refusing to honor the council's july 20 cease-fire resolution and peace plan
instead of a new resolution, the council is expected to issue a statement later this week calling for an end to the missile attacks. a presidential statement is the mildest form of council action
iran and iraq have been at war since 1980
the state department says an incursion of mexican soldiers into california was an ``infringement of u.s. sovereignty,'' but mexican officials played down the incident as a harmless mistake
mexican diplomats said the four members of the mexican naval infantry, carrying automatic weapons, crossed the border without realizing it while in pursuit of alleged drug smugglers. the four were arrested without incident near the border and were released to mexican military officials late monday
u.s. border patrol officials said no charges would be filed, but the state department said the incident warranted further discussion between the two governments
this action is an infringement of u.s. territorial sovereignty,'' said bud jacobs, a state department spokesman in washington, d.c. ``it's unacceptable regardless of their motivation or intention.''
i'm sure we'll take it up with the mexican government,'' he added
mexican military or police have no authority to enter the united states when pursuing criminal suspects, jacobs said
the international line is marked clearly. it was not just an inadvertent entry,'' said dale cozart, chief agent in the u.s. border patrol's san diego sector
the line there is not clearly marked and the marines were confused,'' said leonardo french, an official with the mexican embassy in washington. he added, ``what's important was that there were no shots fired or any violence.''
the four men were arrested late sunday night after a border patrol helicopter crew spotted them talking with a group of revelers, u.s. officials said. u.s. officials said the armed men admitted they knew they were in the united states when they crossed the border
border patrol spokesman mike nicley said the u.s. investigation was complete and no charges would be filed
he would not say whether u.s. authorities accepted the soldiers' explanation that they were pursuing drug smugglers. american authorities failed to locate the revelers to find out what happened during the encounter
nicley said he didn't know what punishment the soldiers might face in mexico. american authorities described the soldiers as being equivalent in rank to privates
in a similar 1986 incident in new mexico, border patrol agents arrested seven mexican judicial police agents who said they had accidentally strayed less than a mile into new mexico while on an anti-drug-smuggling assignment
u.s. officials seized the stolen car the police officers were occupying, several automatic weapons, 6 grams of cocaine and $10,000 cash. their commander said the officers probably didn't know the cocaine was in the car
the seven were sent home after questioning and were not charged
on july 16, 1977, an altercation between tijuana police and members of the a joint border patrol-san diego police unit left two mexican officers and one san diego policeman wounded
san diego police said the tijuana officers were on the u.s. side of the border, but mexican police accused the americans of firing across the border
a tijuana officer was charged with assault with a deadly weapon
hearses carrying the bodies of three irish republican army guerrillas home to roman catholic west belfast ran a gantlet of jeering, rock-throwing protestants early today
thousands of ira sympathizers waved black flags of mourning along the 100-mile dublin-belfast highway, mourning the three guerrillas who were shot by british troops while allegedly preparing a car-bomb attack in gibraltar
the march 6 killing of the unarmed guerrillas in the british colony sparked riots in belfast for much of the following week
in another development, an ira gunman and a catholic civilian were reportedly shot and killed in belfast on monday night and early today
the nine-hour procession for the slain ira guerrillas was marked by a confrontation at the border over irish flags on the coffins and accusations by the ira's political wing, sinn fein, that police tried to break up the cortege and twice crashed a vehicle into one of the hearses
crowds of protestants waving british flags threw rocks and other objects at the procession on at least six occasions as it traveled by road the 40 miles from the border town of carrickaron in the irish republic to belfast
sinn fein leader gerry adams said police deliberately slowed the cortege where protestants had gathered ``to allow them to throw stones and jeer.'' police denied the accusation, saying their concern was to ensure security
a few hours before the cortege arrived in belfast, police said british soldiers shot a gunman who fired on an army patrol near the home of one of the dead guerrillas. the man, identified by police as kevin mccracken, 33, died shortly afterward in the hospital
a police statement said mccracken was jailed in 1978 for membership in the outlawed irish republican army, illegal possession of guns and criminal damage and was released on parole in 1985
an unidentified catholic was shot today at point-blank range from a motorcycle as he arrived for work at a south belfast store, police said. no group claimed responsibility
in dublin, police said they were investigating a suspected letter bomb blast overnight at the city's central mail sorting office which blew a hole in the wooden floor and slightly injured two postal workers
news reports that the package was addressed to the british embassy in dublin were dismissed as speculation by detectives
the ira said its members fired a volley over a makeshift shrine in belfast as a farewell salute to mairead farrell, 31; sean savage, 24; and daniel mccann, 30, who died in gibraltar
the traditional paramilitary salute, which is banned in northern ireland as an illegal display of firearms, was fired monday afternoon as the bodies landed in dublin, the ira said in a statement issued through sinn fein
the royal ulster constabulary, northern ireland's police force, promised in newspaper advertisements not to interfere with the funerals if the ira did not mount a gunfire salute over the coffins
the funerals are expected to take place on wednesday in west belfast, with burial in the catholic milltown cemetery alongside many other ira guerrillas killed in nearly 20 years of political and sectarian strife in the province
the coffins arrived in dublin on a plane chartered by sinn fein to a reception by about 1,000 supporters. the slow procession to the border, with thousands lining the route, was uneventful
at the border, two senior royal ulster constabulary officers demanded the removal of the irish tricolors draped on each coffin
the tricolor, ireland's national flag, is regarded by northern ireland protestants as a symbol of the ira's fight to drive britain out of northern ireland and unite the mainly protestant province with the overwhelmingly catholic republic
after a 30-minute confrontation, a compromise was reached whereby the flags were folded, replaced on the coffins and covered with wreaths
at newry, fives miles inside northern ireland, the hearses were paraded around the largely catholic town for two hours in front of cheering ira supporters
on the outskirts of newry, crowds from a protestant municipal housing project jeered, waved british flags and hurled bricks, bottles and stones at the cortege. windows in some of the cars were broken by the missiles
similar scenes repeated themselves along the road to belfast
the coffins containing the bodies of the three guerrillas were taken into the homes of their families in west belfast. pvs ``carlucci was...''</note>
defense secretary frank carlucci wants his soviet counterpart to cut production of tanks, artillery and heavy missiles to prove he is seriously pursuing a new defensive military doctrine
carlucci, speaking to reporters today en route to a meeting in bern with soviet counterpart dmitri yazov, said that despite the extensive publicity surrounding the emerging kremlin doctrine of ``reasonable sufficiency,'' he has seen ``absolutely no practical change.''
if anything, their military continues to grow. they continue to modernize,'' carlucci told reporters aboard his air force jet
the plane refueled in ireland and then completed the flight to switzerland
carlucci was to attend a dinner with yazov tonight, and sit down wednesday and thursday for the first ever business session between u.s. and soviet defense secretaries
yazov and other soviet officials have said they are moving toward a new doctrine with a defensive posture. but they have never acknowledged that their past doctrine embodied an offensive posture, and various soviet commentators have offered different views on the meaning of ``reasonable sufficiency.''
that's a question, by the way, i intend to ask him,'' said carlucci. ``i'm still not sure what it is.''
if yazov wants to demonstrate that the kremlin is moving from an offensive to a defensive doctrine, the soviets should slack off in tank and artillery production and ``maybe'' desist from the ss-18 intercontinental ballistic missile that carries 10 nuclear warheads, said carlucci
one of the most important indicators, i would think, would be tanks. but tanks continue to pour out,'' he said. ``so there is no indication at the other end of the pipeline that there has been any change.''
the u.s. side also wants to discuss so-called ``dangerous incidents'' such as a collision involving u.s. and soviet warships off the soviet black sea coast last month, and the fatal shooting by a soviet soldier of u.s. maj. arthur d. nicholson on march 24, 1985, in east germany
one idea i have is for them to apologize for maj. nicholson, which they still haven't done,'' said carlucci
the reagan administration wants the soviets to agree on broad guidelines to curtail such incidents
the soviets last month rammed two u.s. warships as they passed through soviet territorial waters in an exercise designed to assert the ``right of innocent passage'' from international waters on one side of the crimean peninsula to the other
on a personal level, carlucci said he was ``looking forward'' to meeting yazov
the meeting, the first of its kind and perhaps the first in a series of high-level military consultations, ``is kind of an interesting idea,'' he said
he was....mildly critical of `glasnost' as applied to the military, which seems to be a bit at variance with the standard line,'' carlucci said
yazov, although generally supportive of the reform policies of soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev, has said the policy of glasnost, or greater openness, must be restricted in the armed forces
carlucci, dwelling on the meaning of the emerging soviet military doctrine, said that ``sufficiency is a word that has been around for a long time'' since the detente era of the 1970s
sufficiency can mean anything you define it to be, as best i can tell,'' he said. ``the (soviet) military is saying that sufficiency is sufficient to meet the threat ... and , `oh, by the way, you have to have sufficient offense so that if the other fellow attacks you, you can attack him all the way to the ocean
that doesn't sound to me like anything new. at the same time, gorbachev is saying that there is something new
some (soviet) academics are saying, `well, maybe this means we can rethink our military establishment and do the same thing with less.' so obviously there is some kind of debate going on.''
unseasonably cold air sent thermometers plunging across the south, producing record lows in some areas and bringing freezing temperatures early today as far south as midland, texas, shreveport, la., and atlanta
meanwhile, snow showers sprinkled the northeast, and reached from the upper mississippi valley across the great lakes region to the appalachians. snow also was scattered from southern new england into new jersey. the heaviest snow continued to fall along the shores of the great lakes
more than 14 inches of snow fell in the conneaut area of northeast ohio, with 8 to 10 inches reported in ashtabula, ohio, and 4 to 6 inches in geneva, ohio
more than 2 feet of snow has buried portions of the snow belt in northern wisconsin and upper michigan since saturday
another storm system over the northern rockies was spreading snow from idaho and western montana across western wyoming and northern utah. the central and southern mountains of idaho were expected to receive about 5 inches of snow by late this afternoon
winter storm warnings were in effect today over the mountains of montana and northwest wyoming, with up to a foot of snow possible
snow was forecast to increase southward into the central rockies by tonight. winter storm watches were been posted for tonight and wednesday across northern and western wyoming and the northern mountains of utah
a record low of 22 degrees was set in asheville, n.c., beating the old mark for the date of 24 degrees, set in 1979. greer, s.c., reached 23, one degree below the record set on march 14, 1968; and meridian, miss., hit 26, beating the 27-degree mark for the same date in 1970
for today, snow was forecast from new england to the ohio valley and great lakes region, and across the northern rockies, with scattered snow showers over the northern half of the plateau region and the central rockies. sunny skies were predicted over the plains, the pacific coast and the southern third of the nation. winds were expected to be strong and gusty over the northern rockies and the southern plateau
most of the nation will have highs in the 30s, 40s or 50s. highs will be in the 20s in the northern rockies and from north dakota across the great lakes region and the ohio valley. temperatures will reach the 60s and 70s from california across the desert southwest, from southern and central new mexico across southern texas, and over the florida peninsula
temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. est ranged from zero at lemmon, s.d., to 63 at key west naval air station, fla
