the attackers, suspected members of the separatist group eta, launched the grenades monday night from a light truck parked in the vicinity, police said
eta, the initials for the words basque land and liberty in the basque language, has claimed responsibility for the deaths of more than 600 people since it took up arms in 1986 to seek independence for the three-province northern spanish basque country
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev's book outlining his economic and political reforms is a runaway bestseller in east germany, officials said
the demand is impossible to meet,'' said guenter hennig, director of the state-run dietz verlag, a book publisher in east berlin
orders for more than 160,000 copies of the book, ``reorganization and new thinking,'' are expected to be filled by the end of next month, hennig said, speaking monday at the leipzig book fair
gorbachev's book has been on the bestseller list in west germany for several months
the first movement of ludwig van beethoven's lost 10th symphony, reconstructed from drafts found in west berlin, will be premiered in london later this year, a west german newspaper reported
the bonn express on monday quoted barry cooper, a professor at scotland's university of aberdeen, as saying the piece will be performed in london at the end of the year
the newspaper did not give an exact date or location for the performance
cooper and sieghard brandenburg, the director of the beethoven archive in bonn, have said they found musical sketches and notes by the composer
cooper said the first movement, about 15 minutes long, was put together based on the documents found in west berlin
safeway stores inc. agreed to pay $995,000 in penalties to the u.s. commerce department to settle charges that the company cooperated with a long-standing arab boycott against israel
it (the settlement) is equitable, and it indicated we take enforcement of the anti-boycott laws very seriously and will continue to vigorously enforce them,'' said paul freedenberg, undersecretary of commerce for export administration
the settlement announced monday was the largest of its kind, the los angeles times reported in today's editions
for more than 30 years, arab countries have boycotted israeli goods and companies that do business with israel. a u.s. law passed in 1977 forbids americans to comply with the boycott
the department filed charges against three stores licensed by oakland-based safeway, two in saudi arabia and one in kuwait
commerce officials alleged the three stores refused to do business with companies on an anti-israeli blacklist and store managers instructed suppliers and customers to avoid such business relations
safeway officials said the penalty, less than one-quarter of what the department originally sought, absolved the company of wrongdoing
the settlement terms clearly vindicate the position that safeway's conduct in its dealings with licensees in the middle east did not merit the harsh penalties originally sought,'' said peter a. magowan, chairman and chief executive officer
we agree with the purpose and the spirit of the anti-boycott laws,'' he said
three years ago citicorp was fined $323,000, the previous largest anti-boycott penalty
i was not guilty for the charge for which i was arrested and this morning i tell you i am not guilty of the charge for which i am about to be executed. ... i go this morning with a clear conscience. i bear no guilt. i'm at peace with myself, with the world, with each of you. god bless you.'' _ convicted murderer willie jasper darden, the focus of an international debate on capital punishment, in a statement just before he was executed in florida
the most profound and enduring legacy of the reagan period is its conversion of the united states from the largest creditor country in the world to the largest debtor.'' _ c. fred bergsten, director of the institute for international economics, commenting on the nation's trade deficit
if the taxpayer cannot read the instructions, how can the government expect compliance?'' _ james w. childs, director of the tax-clinic program at the university of akron school of law, testifying before a senate finance subcommittee on the complexity of tax-form instructions. percentage to grade-level figure.</note>
almost nine of 10 americans with less than a high school education can't understand the instructions for the simplest tax form, and irs forms in general require greater reading skill than the wall street journal, a study concludes
even more reading ability is required to comprehend an internal revenue service notice of taxes owed, says james w. childs, director of the tax-clinic program at the university of akron school of law
if the taxpayer cannot read the instructions, how can the government expect compliance?'' childs asked monday as the senate finance subcommittee that oversees the irs took testimony about the maze of tax penalties that americans may encounter
these penalties range from $1 for failing to file a statement on dividends paid, to 25 percent of the tax owed for failing to pay on time, to $10,000 for helping a corporation understate its tax liability
irs commissioner lawrence b. gibbs and o. donaldson chapoton, assistant secretary of the treasury for tax policy, pledged support for the subcommittee's investigation into whether the number of penalties should be reduced and enforcement changed
sen. david pryor, d-ark., chairman of the subcommittee, vowed a change. ``we've created some sort of a monster here,'' he said
he noted irs statistics that in 1987, the agency assessed 27 million penalties totaling over $14 billion and waived 4 million totaling $4 billion
pryor cited one business that underpaid employment taxes by 2 cents and was hit with a penalty for $400.29
gibbs noted that many of the levies were enacted by congress over the past seven years in an effort to increase compliance with the tax laws
a penalty system that operates based on the wrong principles may provide appropriate sanctions for some types of behavior and yet have an overall negative impact on taxpayer behavior because it is not perceived as fair,'' he said
chapoton rejected allegations that the irs is stiffening penalty enforcement primarily to raise revenue, rather than improve compliance
we certainly hope there's not any reaction ... by irs agents in the field ... that penalties should be used as means of raising revenue,'' he said
the university of akron study found that instructions for 1040ez _ the simplest tax form _ require an 8.45 grade reading level, compared with a grade level of 7.1 for the wall street journal
the study concluded that the penalty system is especially onerous for lower-income americans because in many instances they are not even aware of the need to comply
because congress has not given the irs sufficient guidance, said childs, penalties often are applied to taxpayers who have neither the money to hire a lawyer or accountant nor knowledge of how the system works
the low-income taxpayer has about as much knowledge of how to obtain abatement of a penalty through problems resolution (the irs' ``consumer advocate'') as he or she does of getting to the moon,'' said childs
abuses by high-income taxpayers have brought about a plethora of new penalties. unfortunately, the low-income taxpayer has been caught in this net.''
the university used a textbook-grading formula and statistics from the department of education to gauge the reading skill required to understand instructions for filling out tax forms 1040 and 1040ez, which generally are simpler than an irs notice of deficiency. sufficient skills were possessed by:
_19.8 percent of blacks
_37 percent of hispanics
_11 percent of those with less than a high school education
_22 percent of high school graduates
_50.2 percent of those with less than two years of college
_82.8 percent of those with at least two years of post-secondary education
the tunisian embassy denies reports that terrorist abu nidal is living in tunis despite claims that he moved there after the polish government shut down an arms export business operated by his associates
embassy spokesman oussama romdhani said monday there ``is no reason to suggest the existence of any ties whatsoever between tunisia and the abu nidal group,'' which is blamed for numerous terrorist incidents, including december 1985 attacks on the rome and vienna airports
the polish government announced in january that it had closed down an arms export business run out of warsaw by abu nidal associates, and east european sources said they believed that abu nidal had gone to tunis
state department sources said that according to their information, abu nidal has resided mainly in tripoli, libya, since leaving warsaw in 1985
but someone like abu nidal is on the move all the time, for business and security reasons,'' said one state department source. the state department had no reason to believe that abu nidal operated out of tunis, the u.s. official said. clashes, ban on travel by palestinians. no pickup.</note>
israeli authorities today banned palestinians from traveling between the occupied territories, and hundreds of people rioted after a nightly curfew on the 650,000 arabs in the gaza strip
hospital officials said troops shot dead one arab and wounded five today during clashes on the west bank. no injuries were reported in the rioting in the gaza strip
in jerusalem, police spokesman rafi levy said seven of 90 arab polie officers had quit. they were the first such resignations in the disputed israeli capital
their action came after 500 arab police in the west bank and gaza strip heeded a call by underground palestinian activists to turn in their badges
on the west bank, a general strike called for by the palestine liberation organization got under way with transportation halted and arab-owned stores closed
the travel ban between the gaza strip and the west bank represented an effort by the israeli army to stem the growing campaign against israeli occupation inspired by plo
an official of the military's civil administration said the measure applied to traffic in both directions. he said exemptions would be issued for hardship cases
they are allowed to work in israel, but they can't continue into judea and samaria or vice versa. they would be turned back at a checkpoint,'' said the official, using the biblical terms for the west bank
the policy is not to separate (the palestinians), but to make it more difficult for agitators to move and to help stop distribution of anti-israeli pamphlets that cause incitement,'' said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity
the ban was the most comprehensive travel restriction imposed since israel seized the areas in the 1967 middle east war. under israeli law, palestinians are allowed into israel to work but must have police authorization to spend the night
the israeli military also said it would to take punitive actions against foreign and local journalists it believed had filed false reports about incidents in the occupied territories. army officers declined to elaborate, saying a statement would be released later
officials at jerusalem's mukassad hospital said a 22-year-old palestinian from the west bank village of ain yabrud was dead on arrival with a bullet wound to the jaw. the arab-owned palestine press service identified the dead man as arafat hweih and said he was shot during a demonstration in deir jarir, 9 miles northeast of ramallah
troops also shot and wounded four palestinians in qalqilya, 16 miles west of nablus on the west bank, officials at qalqilya hospital said. the press service put the wounded at six and said two were women shot in the head
the army said it imposed a curfew on qalqilya
in ramallah, thick black smoke from burning tires rose above several neighborhoods. at least three handcuffed palestinians were detained by troops and sitting on the ground in the ramallah police station
in the gaza strip, the army imposed a 10 p.m. to 3 a.m. curfew over the entire coastal territory following the resignation of 300 arab policemen
soldiers at the erez checkpoint, the main entrance leading into the gaza strip, turned back arab residents during the curfew, which was imposed without advance notice. journalists saw 15 to 20 cars turned back in the first hour
after the curfew was lifted for the day, soldiers fired tear gas at hundreds of arabs who threw stones at an army administrative office in the jabaliya refugee camp in the gaza strip. no injuries were reported
army officers said the nightly curfew, which forces arabs to stay in their homes, would keep arab agitators from entering the gaza strip and provoking demonstrations
israel radio today said 300 arab police in gaza city had also resigned. they joined 450 officers in the occupied lands who turned in their badges earlier following orders of plo-inspired underground leaflets. the radio said that 40 officers who had handed in their resignations in the west bank city of hebron continued working after local arab leaders asked them to stay on
about 850 arab policemen work in the occupied territories
in response to months of plo-backed unrest in the occupied lands, israel stepped up economic sanctions. shipment of gasoline and other fuel to service stations in the west bank was banned as of sunday
according to united nations figures, at least 91 palestinians have been killed since anti-israeli rioting began dec. 8
vietnam says it is investigating 29 cases that may involve americans listed as missing in action from the vietnam war, u.s. military experts said today upon returning from hanoi
lt. col. joe harvey, commander of the u.s. joint casualty resolution center, made the announcement following four days of what he called ``positive and productive'' talks with vietnamese officials
the vietnamese told us they are investigating 29 instances where they have received information, material or remains,'' he said in a statement. ``but they said it will take at least three weeks for them to draw any conclusions from these investigations or to have remains to repatriate.''
he said the u.s. team provided new information to the vietnamese government, emphasizing cases mentioned by u.s. presidential emissary and retired gen. john w. vessey during his mission to hanoi last august
vessey had asked the vietnamese to accelerate progress on resolving 70 ``discrepancy cases,'' in which the united states says there is strong evidence that vietnamese officials know what happened to the missing men. the evidence includes photographs of the men taken after their capture
in all, nearly 1,800 americans remain unaccounted for from the war in vietnam, which ended in april 1975 with a communist victory over the u.s.-backed south vietnam government. progress on the issue has been slow principally because the united states does not have diplomatic ties with the vietnamese government
harvey said the u.s. team also visited a site near the major northern port of haiphong where a u.s. aircraft had crashed. haiphong, over which u.s. planes flew intense bombing runs during the war, is about 60 miles southeast of hanoi
the team was composed of six experts from the center and the army central identification laboratory. the laboratory and the casualty resolution center, both based in hawaii, are entrusted with resolving the fates of america's wartime missing
it was the fourth round of technical talks since vietnam told vessey during his visit that it would end months of deadlock and resume cooperation on the mia issue
for its part of the agreement, washington has on four occasions sent medical teams into vietnam to study how war-disabled vietnamese and other humanitarian cases could benefit from private u.s. assistance. there is an embargo on official aid because of vietnam's military occupation of cambodia
vietnam has returned remains it believes are those of americans three times since the vessey agreement
the last repatriation came on march 2, when it handed over 17 sets in a ceremony at hanoi airport along with reports on three other missing u.s. soldiers. it was the largest turnover in two years and the fourth largest since the end of the war
an 11-year-old boy who had been left alone after school shot and killed two men as they tried to steal a videocassette recorder from his family's home, police said
danny ray abernathy, 35, and broadus petty, 39, both of spartanburg, were found dead at the house monday afternoon. officers were searching for a third person they suspect may have been involved
william todd knight, the son of billy and ann knight, ``acted very wisely,'' said spartanburg county coroner jim burnett. ``his life was in danger, he looked for an escape and could not find one ... he was a very brave young man.''
spartanburg county sheriff's department capt. john blackwood said the boy was watching cartoons in his parents' bedroom monday afternoon when he heard noises at the front door of the family's brick, ranch-style home
todd told officers he was scared, so he went to his room for the .22-caliber rifle his father had given him for christmas and loaded four rounds
he then went to the front door and saw a man he described as ``rough'' pounding on the door. the man finally left in a white datsun
todd said he resumed watching cartoons and about 10 minutes later heard more banging, this time at a dining room window
he saw two men climbing through the dining room window. the boy said he went into the bathroom to climb out the window, but saw the white datsun was parked in the back yard
todd told police he went back to the hallway, peeked around the corner into the den and was spotted by one of the intruders as they were taking the vcr
todd then fired three rounds at the men, who dropped the vcr and fled
when police arrived, one of the dead men was found face down next to a woodpile in the back yard, approximately 50 to 75 feet from the house, while the second man was in the driver's seat of the white two-door datsun
todd's parents both work and his sister had gone to a school activity with plans to be home in about an hour, said blackwood
a british army officer killed in an avalanche that nearly engulfed his friend, prince charles, most likely died from a chunk of ice that crashed down a swiss mountainside, an inquest was told today
maj. hugh lindsay, a 34-year-old career army officer, died of a single blow to the head and probably was standing when he was struk, dr. esha sarvesvaran, a pathologist, testified
the pathologist told hammersmith coroner's court that the blow fractured lindsay's skull and caused severe bleeding. he said the object that struck lindsay probably was a lump of ice
lindsay, charles and others were skiing in switzerland on thursday off of a main trail at klosters when the avalanche broke loose. charles and other members of the party skiied clear but lindsay was caught in the avalanche. another friend, patti palmer-tomkinson, suffered broken legs and lung injuries
coroner john burton, who presided over the inquest, said he wanted to dispel speculation that lindsay suffocated in the snow
lindsay is to be cremated after a funeral thursday at the royal military college at sandhurst
burton adjourned the inquest until an unspecified date while a swiss examining magistrate completes his inquiries
if it proves necessary to seek further evidence, then that would be taken from those who can give the most helpful evidence,'' burton said, reading from a statement. ``that is the only consideration when one decides which witnesses one might call.''
he said nothing about whether prince charles, the 39-year-old heir to the british throne, might be summoned to testify
a passenger bus rolled into the kumar river and sank as it was attempting to board a ferry, and more than 50 people were feared drowned, news reports said today
newspapers said about 60 passengers were believed to be on the bus, which was en route from the southern town of barisal to dhaka. they quoted witnesses as saying only seven people jumped or swam to safety after the accident monday night
the janata, a bengali-language daily, said the bus' brakes apparently failed. it said the driver and two assistants were among the missing
a senior police official at madaripur said in a telephone interview today that five bodies had been recovered. ``some more bodies might have been trapped inside the bus,'' he added
the police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said rescue work was hampered by a lack of equipment. he said that the dhaka fire department had been asked to rush cranes and other equipment to the scene
three students accused of putting a foreign substance into a school official's coffee in an attempt to poison him have been expelled for the rest of the school year, school officials say
the school board took the action monday after two of the students, girls in the seventh and ninth grades at forest lake southwest junior high school, waived their right to hearings
the other student, a ninth-grade girl, had insisted on a closed hearing, which was held march 10 before a state hearing examiner. the examiner recommended that she be expelled, and the board accepted the recommendation
all three girls have been accused in washington county juvenile court of conspiracy to commit murder
they're accused of putting a foreign substance into vice principal robert espelien's coffee cup on feb. 25. espelien said he became suspicious when he saw a ``brownish-tan substance'' floating at the top of the cup and had it sent to a medical lab for analysis
the substance put in the coffee has not been revealed
forest lake district superintendent gerald brynildson said the students are entitled to return to school next fall unless the expulsion is extended. until then, the district is required to provide tutors
jan grippo, who in the 1940s and 1950s produced nearly two dozen ``bowery boys'' movies, has died at the age of 81
the new york native produced at least 23 films featuring the band of impish juvenile delinquents, whose ranks included wise guy leo gorcey and his naive patsy, huntz hall
grippo died saturday at a los angeles hospital
although the ``bowery boys'' started off as troublemakers in the films ``dead end'' and ``angels with dirty faces,'' it was grippo, as their agent, who cleaned them up for their popular series
jan wanted them to get into trouble, but to be good kids at heart,'' said his wife, paula grippo
born in beacon, n.y., grippo began his career as a cartoonist for the new york herald-tribune syndicate. he came to hollywood in 1937 to become an agent
during world war ii, grippo was active with the hollywood canteen, a gathering place for those in the military
a magician by hobby, he was a member of both the society of american magicians and the academy of magical arts and often practiced at the magic castle in hollywood
grippo is survived by his wife, three brothers, james, michael and henry, and a sister, bertha delucca. department</head>
a swiss oilman involved in a failed iraqi oil pipeline plan says a friend of attorney general edwin meese iii tried to bypass the u.s. state department by attempting to get meese's help on the project
bruce rappaport also said monday he had been ready to give israel a third of his profits from the $1 billion project in return for an israeli promise not to bomb the pipeline to jordan, which would have passed near the israeli border
speaking in hebrew on israel television, rappaport denied allegations he offered a bribe to foreign minister shimon peres, then prime minister, in return for a promise not to attack the pipeline
the pipeline project was prompted by iraq's war with iran. iraq backed out of the project because it was not satisfied with security arrangements
on sept. 19, 1985 peres wrote a letter to meese saying israel would not bomb the pipeline, and meese's friend, e. robert wallach, took charge of organizing meetings with officials in washington, rappaport said
he (wallach) apparently approached and told me: `look, if mr. peres confirms the (assurances) to mr. meese, then we will arrange such a meeting, and it will go up to the president' and so on,'' rappaport said
what i understand now is that the intention then was to bypass the u.s. state department,'' rappaport said
he was not clear in the interview exactly what the meetings in washington were about
wallach understood that if we want to receive support for such a guarantee which israel has no possibility or need to give ... and we had an alternative agreement with large insurance companies, with a group of bankers, with individuals, so if this had to pass through the senate, the congress or the state department it would not come into being,'' he said
he said president saddam hussein of iraq feared for his life if israel bombed the pipeline and in meetings hussein demanded a $400 million guarantee no bombing would occur
rappaport said he received the guarantee from the overseas private investment corp., a u.s. government-run export company, while israel was asked to provide ``a moral guarantee.''
at that stage, rappaport said, he was introduced to wallach, who organized a meeting with then-national security council head robert mcfarlane
he (mcfarlane) was very excited to get all possible assistance for ... israel,'' he said
a memo by wallach says that on oct. 16, 1985, meese, peres and wallach had a ``three-way discussion'' of the project at the israeli embassy in washington. on sunday, james rocap, one of meese's lawyers, said wallach's account ``totally exaggerates'' the discussion
rappaport said he was first told of the pipeline project in september 1984. he said he met in israel with peres, who confirmed the jewish state had no intention to bomb the pipeline
he said he also met with representatives of the san-francisco based bechtel group inc., which was to build the pipeline
rappaport said he had been prepared to give israel $60 million to $70 million a year, or a third of his profits from the project, over a 10-year period
wallach wrote a memo to meese saying that of $65 million to $70 million a year over 10 years which rappaport was going to funnel to israel, some would go to peres' labor party, although that would be ``denied everywhere.''
as a result, u.s. independent counsel james mckay is investigating in washington whether meese, wallach, rappaport and others conspired to pay an illegal bribe to a foreign official _ that is, peres and his party
mckay is trying to determine if meese was simply passing a problem on to the appropriate official _ as meese's lawyers say _ when he referred wallach to mcfarlane in may 1985, or if he was aiding a conspiracy to get funds for the guarantee despite opposition from the state department and overseas private investment corp
whatever he heard from meese, wallach and rappaport, mcfarlane endorsed the idea and assigned an aide to work on it while keeping progress of the proposal secret from the state department
public school superintendent leonard britton abruptly withdrew a districtwide plan for year-round schools by july 1989, conceding there wasn't enough support from the school board
frankly, it is very late to place the entire school district on a new calendar in july 1989,'' britton said monday, just before the seven-member board was to vote on the proposal
the board earlier had agreed to the july 1989 date, but tabled it last october after a fiery public outcry. the district adopted a policy two years ago phasing in year-round schooling for all students by the 1991-92 school year
those in favor of the proposal said it would ease overcrowding by putting some students in classes during the usually idle summer months. they also said it would provide educational advantages such as better retention of information
currently about one-quarter of los angeles unified school district students, those in the most crowded schools, are on year-round schedules. proponents say the selective policy is unfair, especially to the minorities who account for most of the student population
critics say year-round schools disrupt family vacations and students' summer jobs, make child care more difficult and force some students to spend summer days in hot, antiquated rooms
britten said the district will still aim for a year-round schedule, but he admitted a majority of the current seven-member school board may never agree
avalanches caused by heavy rain and snow buried homes and blocked roads in the northern state of kashmir, killing 66 people in six villages, news reports said today
the united news of india quoted official reports as saying that 49 people died monday in two villages in kargil district, about 90 miles northeast of the state's capital of srinagar
the other deaths occurred in four other kashmiri villages since saturday, the agency said
snowstorms and rains hit the mountain states on thursday, triggering landslides that blocked highways. over 5,000 motorists were stranded, united news quoted state officials as saying
indian air force aircraft were called in to help with rescue operations and to fly some stranded passengers to other regions, it said. comments. picks up 6th graf, `those elements ...'</note>
the afghanistan peace talks reached a soviet-set target date today but the u.n. mediator, citing difficult issues still to be resolved, said negotiations will continue
we are discussing very serious, difficult issues but we continue to negotiate and look for solutions,'' said u.n. mediator diego cordovez
soviet leader mikhail gorbachev has said that if an agreement was reached by march 15, moscow's estimated 115,000 troops would start leaving afghanistan by mid-may
neither side in the negotiations, which resumed today, has said the deadline was a rigid one or that the soviets would consider going back on their pledge to withdraw their troops if the deadline passed without an agreement
but in moscow today, the soviets said failure to meet the deadline will delay the start of a soviet troop withdrawal
foreign ministry spokesman gennady i. gerasimov said there was only a ``slim'' chance the accords could be signed by the end of the day. he blamed the situation on pakistan's insistence that a coalition government be formed in kabul before the agreement was reached
he accused pakistan of ``procrastination'' in the negotiations in an attempt to arrange a post-war government to its liking
pakistan has said it wants a transitional government in kabul before the soviets begin their withdrawal to oversee the soviet pullout and ensure the safe return of more than 5 million refugees from pakistan and iran
moscow and kabul say afghanistan should decide the makeup of its future government after the settlement is signed
the current round of talks, now three weeks old, has completed all main elements of the settlement aimed at ending nine years of fighting
those elements include the timetable and basic logistics of the pullout of the estimated 115,000 soviet troops, an issue that has eluded a solution for several years
sources close to the talks, who declined to be identified, said on monday the pakistanis also have reservations about some minor points in the complex agreement package
the sources said pakistan received a new kremlin message during the weekend, urging it to sign the settlement without delay
unconfirmed reports quoted pakistan's prime minister mohammad khan junejo as saying that a decision on whether it would sign would be announced monday. but there was no official word by nightfall. pakistan's cabinet has held three meetings since sunday, apparently to weigh its next step
meanwhile, the fragile seven-party alliance of moslem guerrillas failed to decide whether it would drop its demand to dominate a future afghan government
a guerrilla leader said on monday in pakistan that moscow again rejected direct talks with the moslem rebels on the afghan issue. the resistance is represented by pakistan in the geneva talks but its position has not always been identical with pakistan's
the guerrillas have started to form a government of their own which pakistan considers too hard-line
the soviet union began sending troops to afghanistan in december 1979 at the request of the pro-moscow government. the soviet troops and the kabul government's regular army of about 50,000 men are pitted against 200,000 moslem rebels, supported by the united states, china and pakistan
a protester who wanted to dramatize his cause by spending a week in a garbage can dangling from the golden gate bridge fell 220 feet into the icy water and was nearly washed out to sea
paul alarab, 29, of kensington, calif., suffered collapsed lungs and three broken ribs but was listed in satisfactory condition at letterman army medical center following monday's rescue
he was plucked from a rock by the coast guard nine hours after the fall
he's lucky,'' said his brother, chris alarab. ``now he has a second chance to give his message.''
paul alarab said he wanted to draw attention to the plight of the old and infirm by living for a week in a plastic garbage can suspended from the bridge
he complained that the elderly must stand in long lines in supermarkets and banks and are neglected by young people, the california highway patrol said
alarab had equipped the 33-gallon garbage can with clothing, two jugs of water, a life vest and some political pamphlets, the chp said
alarab said he lowered the can, attached to the bridge railing by 60 feet of nylon rope, sunday night and was shinnying down when he fell
the chp was called to the scene but found only the swaying plastic barrel. fearing it was a bomb, authorities closed the bridge for 40 minutes
monday morning a fishing boat reported a man clinging to a rock near point diablo, on the ocean side of the bridge's north end
highway patrol officials said they will seek a trespassing charge against alarab when he is discharged from the hospital. his brother said alarab has been unemployed for six months
vietnam today buried premier pham hung after eulogizing him as a dedicated revolutionary who defied torture and harsh battlefields in a 60-year struggle for the communist cause
guerrillas fighting vietnam's nine-year occupation of cambodia called hung ``a notorious murderer'' who brought widespread suffering to vietnam and cambodia
hung, who played a key role in defeating the u.s.-backed south vietnam government and rose to the no. 2 position in the communist party hierarchy, was buried in hanoi after dying of a heart attack last thursday. he was 75
vietnamese radio reports said communist party chief nguyen van linh and other top party officials carried hung's casket from the ba dinh conference hall to a gun carriage for the trip to mai dich cemetery, the final resting place of vietnam's revolutionary leaders
tens of thousands of mourners lined the six-mile route of the carriage, flanked by two rows of armed military honor guards, said the reports monitored in bangkok
the radio of the khmer rouge, the main anti-vietnamese guerrilla group, said hung died ``as one who brought endless misery and suffering on vietnam and on the vietnamese and cambodian peoples.''
the broadcast, a text of which was seen in bangkok today, said vietnam's leaders should rethink the line adopted by hung and communist party chief le duan, who died in july 1986
hung died while vietnamese forces were ``almost choking to death from their attempt to swallow cambodia,'' the broadcast on sunday said. vietnam's economy has ``hit rock bottom,'' and the country is internationally isolated, it said
vo van kiet, a vice premier and head of state economic planning, has been chosen acting premier to replace hung
linh and kiet are regarded by western analysts as the country's leading proponents of western-style reforms which the party has deemed crucial to overcome the nation's economic crisis. mention of pope; deletes 16th graf, ``it's obvious, for same reason; subs 26th graf, ``martinez rejected xxx, with two grafs, to show that pope has expressed concern about florida death cases, but darden's not among them</note>
convicted murderer willie jasper darden, who maintained his innocence through 14 years on death row and became the focus of an international debate on capital punishment, was executed today in florida's electric chair
darden, 54, was convicted of fatally shooting lakeland businessman james c. turman while robbing his wife of $15 in september 1973
i was not guilty for the charge for which i was arrested and this morning i tell you i am not guilty of the charge for which i am about to be executed,'' darden said in a final statement to 30 witnesses in the death chamber
i go this morning with a clear conscience. i bear no guilt. i'm at peace with myself, with the world, with each of you. god bless you.''
darden winked and nodded at one of his attorneys just before the hood was put over his head, and was declared dead at 7:12 a.m. after 2,000 volts of electricity flowed through his body for two minutes. two puffs of smoke rose from his right leg where one of the electrodes was attached
darden's case attracted worldwide attention, including pleas for clemency nobel peace prize winner andrei sakharov and other human rights activists. they said darden was railroaded because he was black and the victim was white
earlier today, wayne robert felde was executed in louisiana's electric chair for the 1978 murder of a policeman
it was the first time two inmates were executed the same day in the united states since aug. 28, when three murderers were put to death, in florida, alabama and utah
darden spent 14 years on death row, one month less than howard v. douglas, who has been on death row in florida since december 1973
darden refused his last meal this morning, said prison spokesman bob macmaster. by 6 a.m., darden had showered, and his head and lower right leg were shaved to facilitate the flow of electricity, the spokesman said
on monday, the u.s. supreme court, the 11th u.s. circuit court of appeals, a federal judge and the state supreme court rejected darden's appeals
his last hope was a reprieve from gov. bob martinez, who signed darden's seventh black-bordered death warrant last week and said monday he had no plans to issue a stay
i think of the victim at a moment like this and the family which was destroyed,'' martinez said. ``a hideous murder took place and that's what i keep in mind. just because it's 15 years later, that doesn't reduce a crime that was committed at the time.''
the governor's hands are now stained with the blood of a man from whom justice was withheld,'' amnesty international said in a statement from john g. healey, executive director of amnesty international usa in new york
early today, about 40 people gathered in a cow pasture across from the florida state prison to protest the execution
the opponents maintained silence after 7 a.m. while the execution took place, then began singing ``we shall overcome.''
i think it's long overdue. he did it to himself. i'm just thinking right now i want some peace of mind ... it's been a long time and i'm glad it's finally over,'' said turman's widow, helen turman baum, minutes after the execution. mrs. baum has remarried since the shooting
darden went into turman's furniture store on september 8, 1973, and had just robbed turman's wife of $15 when turman came on the scene
court records say that after shooting turman between the eyes, darden unbuckled his belt and unzipped his pants and ordered his wife to get on the floor, remove her false teeth and perform oral sex on him while turman lay dying just a few feet away
a neighbor, philip arnold, also identified darden during the trial. arnold, then 16, entered the store after apparently hearing the shooting and the woman's cries. he was shot three times but survived
darden became the 18th person executed in the state and the 96th executed in the nation since the supreme court restored capital punishment in 1976
death penalty opponents, led by amnesty international, have said darden had an alibi to prove his innocence. they claim there is evidence _ statements from a minister and a woman _ that darden could not have committed the murder
in sweden, about a dozen people demonstrated monday outside the u.s. embassy in stockholm, urging florida to commute darden's death sentence
martinez rejected appeals on darden's behalf by sakharov, democratic presidential candidate jesse jackson, actress margot kidder and others
jon peck, a spokesman for martinez, said pope john paul ii, through florida-based roman catholic leaders, has expressed concerns in the past about florida death cases, but never darden's specifically
ray mcdaniel, who prosecuted darden for the turman killing said friday, ``there is no question he is guilty.''
then-gov. bob graham signed darden's first death warrant in 1979 on the same day as a warrant for john spenkelink, the first man electrocuted in florida after the state resumed the death penalty
darden was born in snow hill, n.c., the second of four children. he graduated from high school in greene county, n.c. his conviction record dated to 1964 and included breaking and entering and attempted rape
douglas, at 51 the man who has spent the longest time on death row, was convicted of the july 1973 shooting death of his former lover's husband in polk county
his first death warrant resulted in the u.s. supreme court sending the case back in 1984. he was resentenced to death and the case is now pending on appeal
five men were pulled from a sinking boat this morning about 50 miles into the atlantic ocean off georgetown, the u.s. coast guard said
the 54-foot-long willie victor, based in murrells inlet, radioed the coast guard monday night saying it was taking on water and a coast guard helicopter was dispatched from savannah, ga., said a coast guard spokesman in miami
the helicopter arrived shortly after midnight and the men were lifted into the helicopter after coast guard pumps could not save the boat. the boat sank about 20 minutes later, the spokesmen said
the boat's owner and operator, gerald baston, suffered head injuries, and another man, tommy morehead, suffered a broken leg, the spokesmen said. the other men were identified as neal baston, art ashworth and dennis barrios
the coast guard did not know the men's ages or hometowns
at least four people were killed and more than 90 injured today during an opposition-sponsored strike to demand the resignation of prime minister rajiv gandhi
the strike closed offices and businesses in six of india's states but failed to achieve widespread support in the other 17 states
at least three people were killed and several others were hurt in street clashes in bihar state, united news of india said. violence also was reported in neighboring west bengal state, where at least 75 people were reported injured
in kerala state, the news agency reported a youth was killed and seven other people injured when a flour mill operator opened fire at opposition party supporters attacking his mill near the coastal city of ernakulam
united news also said 14 police were injured near the pakistan border in rajasthan state when they were pelted with stones while trying to remove roadblocks
the strike disrupted normal life in bombay, india's business center, and in calcutta, the country's largest city. but it drew little response in the capital at new delhi, where most businesses remained open
united news of india said police arrested at least 3,000 people from various cities for attempting to block traffic and close shops
but the opposition coalition that called the strike said at least 150,000 people were arrested. in a statement in new delhi, the eight parties maintained the strike was complete in all major towns and industrial areas
the strike was called by most major opposition parties to protest sectarian violence, rising prices and alleged corruption in government. the parties, which include two communist groups, demand that parliament be dissolved and new elections held
in parliament, proceedings were disrupted for more than an hour when opposition members raised anti-government slogans in the upper house. earlier, the entire opposition boycotted the first hour of business in both houses in support of the strike
on monday, at least 25,000 people were arrested in the southern state of tamil nadu and 500 others in orissa in the east in what police said was a move to pre-empt violence during today's strike
opposition members in parliament today criticized the government for monday's arrests, united news of india said
gandhi's congress party holds more than 400 of the 542 seats in the popularly elected lower house of parliament. the rest are divided among opposition parties which have failed to act jointly despite common demands that gandhi resign
