a grand jury has indicted mayor john fedo on 23 charges including theft, falsifying expense records and attempting to obstruct the state auditor
the indictment, made public monday after the mayor's arraignment in state district court, included 22 felony charges
fedo, 37, said the charges were a political ploy arranged by people who don't like him. the indictment, he said, ``is not going to have an effect on city hall.''
if convicted, fedo, 37, faces a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison on the theft charge and up to five years in prison on most of the other charges. fedo was freed on his own recognizance and scheduled to appear in court may 3, when a judge will determine whether enough evidence exists to proceed to trial
his lawyer, douglas sauter, said he will move for dismissal of the charges. fedo was ``tried once in the election and found not guilty,'' he said
fedo, a member of minnesota's democratic-farmer-labor party, won his first four-year term as mayor in 1979 and has been re-elected twice
the theft charge concerns $13,500 given to fedo by three businessmen to lobby for state funds for a convention center in the city
during the 1987 election campaign, fedo said he passed the funds to an unnamed twin cities businessman in 1985 in exchange for information about other cities' convention center proposals
but prosecutors say the mayor played a limited role in lobbying for a convention center he later claimed to have won almost single-handedly
duluth, a city of 85,000 on the western tip of lake superior, was never in competition for the $200 million convention center for which bloomington and minneapolis vied, the charges say. the state legislature awarded duluth a total of $17.2 million for its own, relatively small center. territories</head>
mayor edward i. koch of new york wrote in an israeli newspaper today that television cameras should be barred from the occupied territories
in a signed column published in the jerusalem post, koch said that in view of what is happening elsewhere in the world, israel would be justified in taking steps to bar tv crews from the west bank and the gaza strip
many other nations throughout the world are experiencing troubles similar to those now taking place in israel. should israel be the only nation to allow full television coverage of these troubles?
this creates a false impression in the minds of television viewers that such events are happening only in israel,'' wrote koch, a longtime supporter of israel
more than 90 palestinians have been killed by israeli gunfire and beatings in riots that started dec. 8 in the territories occupied by israel in the 1967 middle east war. the territories are home to 1.5 million palestinians
koch said he thought israel should use whatever force necessary to put down the palestinian uprising in the occupied lands
the mayor also criticized u.s. editorial writers and columnists for their ``relentless drumbeat of criticism against israel.''
he added that he had attacked u.s. involvement in the vietnam war but now had ``second thoughts'' about the wisdom of deserting south vietnamese allies
it's easy for columnists, and for all of us, to play god with the lives of other people, endanger them and leave them ultimately to be destroyed,'' he wrote
passengers spent longer than they bargained for today in the world's longest undersea tunnel, which opened to trains two days earlier
a power outage left them stranded for more than three hours 460 feet underground in the 37-mile-long seikan tunnel
the tunnel links japan's largest island, honshu, with hokkaido, the northernmost main island. it cuts two hours off a trip formerly made by ferry
it took 24 years to build at an estimated cost of $8.5 billion
most of the 166 passengers were asleep when the outage halted their 11-coach express train, bound for tokyo from sapporo, about 12 miles from the tunnel's south exit. a locomotive pulled the train from the tunnel, and it resumed its journey from the next station, at aomori, 3 hours and 50 minutes behind schedule, a hokkaido rail japan co. spokesman said
the cause of the power outage was under investigation, said the hokkaido representative, who spoke on condition of anonymity
six trains have been stopped by faulty fire detectors since the tunnel opened
