more than 50 independent production companies, including johnny carson's talk show, are seeking exemptions from striking scriptwriters, union officials say
that would allow some companies to work during the writers guild of america strike against the 200-member alliance of motion picture and television producers. no talks were scheduled in the 10-day-old strike by 9,000 guild members
brian walton, west coast executive director of the guild, said its board would consider appeals for an interim agreement with several companies. cheryl rhoden, a spokeswoman for the writers, said decisions on exemptions would probably be announced wednesday or thursday
walton declined to identify those seeking interim agreements, but ``the tonight show'' announced through its publicists that it was among them
a spokesman for the producers belittled the union's assertion about the number of independents seeking waivers
the overwhelming number of independents are actually a writer that employs himself for tax purposes. he produces nothing,'' said alliance spokesman herb steinberg. ``with the exception of carson, i don't know of any other independent producer looking to make a deal who is also member of the alliance.''
among shows already rejected for a waiver or interim contract was the academy awards, scheduled for broadcast on april 11
lobell-bergman productions disclosed monday that the strike has affected development of five of eight movies on its slate and stopped work on a network comedy series. previously postponed was a revival of ``the smothers brothers comedy hour'' and ``the dictator,'' a new series starring christopher lloyd
the guild is seeking an increase in creative control, an increase in residuals from foreign market distribution, and rejection of a producers' contention that residuals for hour-long syndicated television shows should be adjusted. problems</head>
the food and drug administration has released a new report sharply criticizing quality control procedures at lyphomed inc., which makes drugs to fight symptoms of aids and other diseases
an fda official said monday a re-inspection of lyphomed's main manufacturing plant found the same sort of problems that led the agency to take disciplinary action against the suburban chicago company last fall
lyphomed said monday it intends to respond to the latest inspection report later this week
we are committed to ensuring that our quality meets and exceeds the fda standards,'' said john n. kapoor, lyphomed's chairman and chief executive officer
lyphomed gained national prominence for its sales of pentamidine, a drug used to fight a form of pneumonia that frequently kills people with aids, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome
in november, the federal agency warned lyphomed it could be taken to court if ``serious violations'' of fda regulations were not corrected, and it suspended approval of the company's applications to market new drugs
the latest fda report listed 44 violations of ``good manufacturing practices'' found during a three-month inspection
violations cited included shipping products that had failed some sterility tests, changing the manufacturing process for several drugs without knowing the effect of the changes, distributing drugs without proper fda approval, and other quality control problems
george bailey, a compliance officer at the fda's chicago district, said the problems were the same type of violations as cited last fall, bailey said
the severity and degree of the violations is yet to be determined,'' he said
lyphomed said in a statement that it had appointed a new director of quality control and a new director of regulatory affairs since november
the discovery of new or continuing violations doesn't necessarily mean the fda will continue its suspension of work processing lyphomed's applications to market new drugs, bailey said
it depends on how significant the deviations would be and what they have done to correct them,'' he said
a former lyphomed employee, richard johnson, filed a lawsuit earlier this month claiming the company had fired him because he refused to release drugs that had failed quality tests. lyphomed has said he was fired for ``performance reasons.''
about 10,000 protesters marched through the streets of this communist capital today calling for democracy and freedom of the press
dozens of police patrols passed by, but authorities made no attempt to hinder the unofficial protest, which came on the anniversary of hungary's aborted 1848 revolution against austria
protesters carried signs that read ``we want democracy'' and ``we want freedom of the press'' and chanted anti-government slogans
groups of demonstrators whistled and applauded when police vehicles passed by, but authorities refused to act on what appeared to be attempts to provoke them
the protesters blocked traffic and attracted large groups of passers-by, some of whom joined the throng as it meandered through central budapest
dissident sources said four prominent activists were detained in advance of the unofficial protest. the sources earlier report three activists had been taken into custody
communist party authorities, meanwhile, held an official rally to mark the anniversary on the steps of budapest's national museum, where the 1848 revolution broke out
communist party officials laid wreaths and made speeches calling for greater national unity and economic progress
hungarian dissidents have marked the anniversay by staging unofficial rallies on march 15 since 1973, and have met with varying reactions from authorities
last year, police allowed thousands of people to march through downtown budapest, calling for democracy as part of one of the biggest unofficial protests here in years
but in 1986, police clashed with protesters on march 15, and broke up that year's unofficial demonstration
hungary has won a reputation as a relatively liberal soviet bloc country, although far less dissent is tolerated than in western countries
one dissident source identified three of the activists detained this morning as writer miklos haraszti, tamas mlynar and gabor demszky, hungary's biggest underground publisher
the source, who asked not to be named, said two other activists _ ottilia solt and writer gyoergy gado _ may also have been taken into custody. he said friends were unable to reach them early today
sources speculated the activists were detained to warn dissidents away from the unofficial protest, and predicted they would be relased later today
police have raided the homes of at least eight dissidents during the past two weeks, including gado, solt and demszky, sources told the associated press
during the police search, hundreds of copies of unofficial journals, political documents and books were confiscated, haraszti said
a former carnival worker has pleaded innocent to charges of murdering an eight-year-old girl in 1951
assistant public defender michael malloy entered the plea monday in delaware county common pleas court on behalf of his client, william henry redmond
redmond, 66, suffering from a heart condition and emphysema, sat in a wheelchair and said nothing during the arraignment
a pretrial hearing is scheduled for april 11
at a preliminary hearing in february, state police trooper malcolm murphy said redmond had confessed to smothering jane marie althoff. her body was found in a carnival truck in trainer, a small town about 15 miles southeast of philadelphia, on april 25, 1951
redmond, who was living in grand island, neb., at the time of his arrest, is charged with first- and second-degree murder, voluntary and involuntary manslaughter, kidnapping and assault with intent to ravish
redmond is being held without bail in delaware county prison. in</head> up 4th graf, between 2.5 million; subs 11th graf pvs, sen. paul; eliminates 14th graf pvs, simon was</note>
democrat jesse jackson said today ``we're going to have a good day,'' casting his ballot as the illinois presidential primary began with a light turnout in cold weather. on the republican side, george bush wondered aloud what was keeping rival bob dole in the race
i'm not sure i understand what he's doing,'' said bush during a final campaign swing in the state where polls were forecasting a landslide victory for the vice president over his gop rivals
but both dole and pat robertson were insisting they were staying in the race, though the former television evangelist said he would re-evaluate his status if he gets less than 5 percent of the vote
jackson voted at bryn mawr community church on the city's south side
we've been winning all the way and we'll keep winning,'' said jackson, the victor last saturday in south carolina and winner of five states on super tuesday
the state's other democratic favorite son, sen. paul simon, voted at the makanda fire station in rural southern illinois
after casting their ballots, simon and his wife went to their home and planted a tree in their yard, an election-day tradition
between 2.5 million and 3 million voters were expected to turn out for the primary on a wintry day. kel hudson, associate director of the state board of elections, said that would represent 46 percent to 48 percent of the registered voters
illinois does not have party registration so voters could choose a democratic or republican ballot at their polling place
initial reports from chicago precincts were of a light turnout
precinct captain william smar said that during the first hour and a half his polling place was open, only 15 of the 498 registered voters had cast ballots, nearly all of them democrats
it's more quiet than normal for this type of election,'' said thomas leach, spokesman for the city election commission
illinois voters express their presidential preference in a non-binding beauty contest and also elect convention delegates. it was possible a candidate would do well in the popular vote, but lose out in the contest for delegates to a contender who had stronger slates filed in the state's 22 congressional districts
as if to emphasize his determination to fight on, dole flew to wisconsin and connecticut to campaign in two of the states that follow illinois
simon said, ``i will win'' his home state's democratic primary, and conceded second place in either the popular vote or the delegate contest would not be good enough
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis said he has made ``significant gains'' in his effort to finish ahead of at least one of the state's two favorite-son candidates
an abc news-washington post poll done saturday and sunday suggested simon had the support of 39 percent of 328 likely democratic voters, with jackson at 34 percent. simon's lead was within the poll's 6-point margin of error. dukakis trailed with 17 percent
at stake in today's voting were 82 republican and 113 democratic delegates. another 10 gop delegates will be chosen at the party state convention in june. sixty additional democratic delegates will be allocated to candidates in the same proportion as they won delegates in the primary and 15 more elected and party officials will become super delegates to the democratic convention
the latest associated press delegate count gave bush 705, dole 165 and robertson 17 gop convention delegates, out of the 1,139 needed for the nomination. on the democratic side, dukakis had 462.5, jackson 423.55, gore 352.8, gephardt 145 and simon 35.5. there are 275.65 uncommitted democratic delegates
democratic chairman paul kirk suggested monday he would try to rally uncommitted delegates behind whichever candidate leads the field when the primaries have ended, if none has yet secured a numerical lock on the nomination
kirk said monday that the party leaders and other officials who automatically hold seats as national convention delegates have a ``special responsibility'' to help ensure that the nominating process does not turn into a political fight that damages the nominee
bush, in the aftermath of his super tuesday sweep of 16 primaries, saw illinois as a chance to take another giant step toward clinching the gop nomination. dole hoped the return to the midwest would blunt the vice president's momentum
jackson saw his home state primary as an opportunity to challenge dukakis for the leadership of the democratic field. for simon, illinois was a fight for survival, while sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee was looking for ``an opportunity to punch through'' with a victory in a northern industrial state
rep. richard gephardt of missouri did little campaigning in illinois, concentrating instead on michigan, which holds democratic caucuses on march 26
a poll published sunday in the chicago tribune gave bush a 34-point lead over dole among illinois republicans, with robertson a distant third
yet, the kansas senator insisted he had no plans to even consider dropping out if he does poorly in illinois
i've made a judgment that illinois, whatever happens, we're going to keep going,'' dole said at a news conference on monday
but he conceded candidates sometimes fail to understand when it is time to get out
now if you're out there and you've been twisting in the wind for six or eight months and you're starting to smell a little, somebody has to cut the rope,'' he said. background on investigation, picking up at the 6th graf previous, beginning ``two members.''</note>
jury selection began today for the trial of the first of 23 people charged with physically or sexually abusing their children or young relatives, but there were fears that impartial jurors might be in short supply
margie back, 33, sat hunched over in her chair, clutching her purse, when magoffin county circuit court judge john r. morgan called the court to order. she is accused of using lighted cigarettes to torture her three boys, ages 5, 8 and 10
ms. back, of the mountain hollow community of seitz, is charged with three counts of first-degree criminal abuse. she was not charged with sexual abuse
five trials have been scheduled through mid-june in this eastern kentucky coal mining county for 12 of the defendants, and the remaining cases could come to trial later this year
it is difficult to get an impartial jury for any trial in magoffin county,'' said deputy judge-executive marcella salyer, the county's top appointed administrator. ``people have a lot of connections, both politically and otherwise.''
the investigation began when state social workers asked kentucky state police for help on a complaint of suspected child abuse in 1986. the social workers say they cannot reveal details on the cases
indictments were returned by a county grand jury that was shown videotaped interviews with six children. the indictments were accompanied by hand-written notes from some of the children describing acts of sodomy and abuse among family members
two members of the state attorney general's staff began handling the case last august after a local prosecutor withdrew
the state prosecutors unsuccessfully sought in october to have the trials moved, claiming the defendants were members of ``five large, extended families'' that had too many friends and political allies in the appalachian mountain county of about 14,000 people. many of the defendants share the family name gipson
the prosecutors cited a courthouse demonstration in support of the defendants in november 1986 and a series of sympathetic letters to the editor of a local newspaper
judge john r. morgan said he would try to find an impartial jury without moving the trial. he said he expected the case to last three or four days, and was not sure if he would let the children testify on videotape or in person in a state where cameras are allowed in courtrooms
dr. lester fahrner, a lexington dermatologist, wrote in a pretrial report that ms. back's three sons had numerous scars on their faces, arms, backs and legs that ``suggest having been burned with a cigarette or similar sized burning object.''
the doctor reported that two of the boys told him their mother was responsible for the scars
the children, and others in the county ranging from age 1 to 11 who were alleged victims of incest, rape, sodomy, sexual abuse, physical abuse and assault, all have been placed in foster homes
customers at the coffee cup restaurant, across the street from the courthouse, said monday the trials are bound to bring bad publicity to a county that already has received more than its share
but magoffin county shouldn't be viewed as a hotbed of physical and sexual abuse against children, maintained flynn arnett, one of the customers
you see it in the papers every day all over the country,'' arnett said
john arnett, business manager of the salyersville independent and a distant relative of flynn arnett, agreed
this goes on everywhere but it just seems to fit into the stereotypical view of people here,'' in the mountains, john arnett said. ``but that stereotype just isn't true.''
widespread vote-buying in the county was the focus of an article in the lexington herald-leader and a series of stories on election fraud in the louisville courier-journal last fall
government services in the county also were shut down for five weeks last summer when the fiscal court, the governing body, could not reach agreement on an annual budget. correct name of tanker to gas prince, sted gas queen; picks up 8th graf pvs: the iraqi...; subs penultimate graf, bgng ``the 46,723-ton...,'' to correct tanker name; picks up last graf: the convoy...''</note>
iraq said it fired six missiles into tehran today and its air force bombed other iranian cities. iran said it pounded southern iraqi towns with shells, short-range rockets and warplane raids
iran said civilians were killed in iraqi missile attacks and iraq said iranian shelling killed nine civilians in the city of basra
in new york, the soviet union acknowledged it failed to win support for a u.n. security council resolution calling for an end to the deadly missile duel in the 7{-year-old war
the u.s.-flagged kuwaiti tanker gas prince was sailing up the persian gulf in the 17th convoy conducted by the u.s. navy this year
the iraqi news agency, monitored in nicosia, said six missiles were fired into the iranian capital today. it reported eight such missiles strikes monday
iran's islamic republic news agency, also monitored in nicosia, said ``a number'' of civilians were killed in missile attacks on residential areas of tehran overnight. it did not say how many rockets hit the city
on monday, iran said missiles killed 26 civilians and wounded 50 in tehran. iraq also reported civilian casualties in baghdad but gave no figures
iraq says it has fired 15 missiles into tehran since the duel resumed with a single rocket fired into the iranian capital sunday night after a two-day truce. iran has fired two into baghdad
the iraqi agency said warplanes pounded the western iranian cities of dezful, kermanshah and hamadan today in ``destructive'' raids. irna said sores of civilians were killed
iran said its artillery shelled basra province, whose capital is iraq's second-largest city, and fired 11 short-range rockets into the region. the iraqi agency quoted its correspondent in basra as saying nine civilians were killed and 10 wounded
tehran radio said iranian warplanes bombed al-amarah, about halfway between basra and baghdad, and the northeastern town of sulaymaniyah
irna said monday that revolutionary guards commandos pushed to within 12 miles of sulaymaniyah. it said the iranians seized a dozen peaks and several villages, killing or wounding 1,000 iraqis
iraq said the latest round of missile attacks was a reprisal for iran's shelling of iraqi border towns sunday night in which at least 21 civilians were killed and 80 wounded
baghdad earlier charged iran broke a friday cease-fire by launching ground attacks and bombarding iraqi towns
an uneasy two-day truce brought a brief respite after 12 days in which both sides fired dozens of missiles and artillery fire and launched air raids that killed or wounded hundreds of civilians
at the united nations, soviet ambassador alexander belonogov acknowledged monday that the soviet bid for a new resolution on the ``war of the cities'' had failed after the security council met behind closed doors
our personal preference would be a resolution of the security council,'' he said, but the important thing is ``not the form but the essence'' of the council's action
the united states saw the proposal as a maneuver designed to deflect attention from the american push for a worldwide arms embargo against iran to punish it for refusing to honor the council's july 20 cease-fire resolution and peace plan
instead of a new resolution, the council is expected to issue a statement later this week calling for an end to the missile attacks
