riot police using tear gas, shotguns and a water cannon today broke up a demonstration by unpaid public employees as panama's military government announced it would begin partial salary payments to thousands of government workers
more than 500 employees of the social security administration's main hospital in panama city blocked a divided highway this morning before three units of riot police dispersed them
fewer guns, more medicine,'' the workers chanted
a nurse, who declined to give her name for fear of reprisals, said the hospital's 9,000 employees had been given no explanation by supervisors of when or how they would be paid
reporters saw five or six people brought to the hospital with minor injuries from birdshot fired by police during the melee, which tied up traffic for more than two hours. the facility was offering only emergency services
the presidential press office said the partial payments would be made on a sliding scale that would give full wages to more than half of the public servants, with others receiving a percentage of their salaries
the action came a day after sporadic violence broke out in the capital and the caribbean port city of colon, the nation's second largest, after word spread that public employees would not be paid this week
directors of the national federation of public servants, which represents nearly all government employees, said they would reject the government plan and demand full wages
in another development, the panamanian government asked terrence kneebone, director of the u.s. information service here, to leave the country within 48 hours, a u.s. embassy source said
the government did not explain the expulsion, but kneebone, a leading embassy spokesman, has formally responded to several government accusations in the past week, including a formal charge that the united states was preparing to invade panama
his response to that allegation was that it was ``ridiculous.''
some teachers, telephone and dock workers struck monday to demand their wages and police put down a demonstration in panama city with tear gas and rubber truncheons
protesters lit fires in the streets of the capital and chanted ``noriega must go'' _ a reference to panama's military strongman, gen. manuel antonio noriega
the government provided no other details about its partial payment plan, but sources said the plan would provide full wages to employees making less than $30 every two weeks, while others would get a percent of their salaries
on monday, the government began selling sacks of food, called ``dignity bags,'' to unpaid workers
and the united states sent an additional 100 military personnel to beef up security around the panama canal. the united states already has 10,000 troops based along the waterway
more than 1,000 dockworkers walked off their jobs at ports in colon and in panama city, the entrances to the the 50-mile-long panama canal that links the pacific and atlantic oceans
alberto soto, administrator of the balboa port in panama city, said the action would not slow down shipping through the vital waterway, which normally handles about 30 ships a day
about 130,000 people, nearly one in every five working panamanians, are employed by the government. until now, they have supported noriega whose ouster as head of the panama defense forces has been demanded by the opposition
the nation's deposed president, eric arturo delvalle, told cbs television in a videotaped message that ``noriega will not be able to trick'' the government workers. ``he cannot pay them,'' said delvalle from the hiding place where he has been holed up since noriega engineered his ouster in a coup on feb. 26, the day after delvalle tried to fire the general
the reagan administration hopes the government's inability to pay its workers will bring down noriega, who is under indictment in the united states on federal narcotics smuggling charges
the united states imposed several new economic sanctions on panama last friday, including the withholding of $6.5 million in panama canal fees due this week. it earlier cut off all economic and military aid to the country
the 118 local and foreign banks that do business in panama remained closed monday by government order for the 20th straight day and there was no indication they would reopen today
the u.s. labor department has agreed to allow south carolina and north carolina limited use of 17-year-old school bus drivers through the end of the school year
the governors of the two states today announced the agreement overriding a february order that had required a halt to the young drivers by april 1
during our discussions with (labor) secretary (ann) mclaughlin, i think it became apparent that our school children would be a lot safer riding with 17-year-olds with seven or eight months of bus driving experience than it would be to have them riding with drivers who have little or no experience driving a school bus,'' north carolina gov. jim martin said
without the extension there wouldn't be enough trained drivers to transport students, the governors contended
under the agreement, all districts in both states may use drivers who will turn 18 before june 15. and certain districts that have had difficulty hiring older drivers may through the end of the school year use 17-year-old drivers who will not turn 18 by june 15
all 17-year-old drivers must have been hired and trained before the school year began and must have clean driving records, the agreement said
north carolina has about 2,100 17-year-old drivers; south carolina has about 1,200
tucker eskew, a spokesman for south carolina gov. carroll campbell, estimated several hundred 17-year-old drivers in that state would turn 18 by june 15
seventeen-year-olds have been permitted to drive school buses in the two states under an exemption to the fair labor standards act
that was repealed after labor department investigations found north carolina had violated the act 80 times in january and february, and south carolina had recorded 200 violations in that time
the investigation was triggered when a 4-year-old boy in west columbia, s.c., was struck and killed by a 17-year-old driver with a bad driving record
martin said in a statement today that he would seek a $24 million from the legislature in june to increase the school bus drivers pay so the state can attract more adult drivers
former national security council staff member roger robinson appeared before a federal grand jury today in the criminal investigation of attorney general edwin meese iii and a proposed $1 billion iraqi oil pipeline
robinson worked closely with longtime meese friend e. robert wallach in the summer of 1985, when supporters of the pipeline were seeking u.s. support for the project
robinson is the second nsc aide in two weeks to testify in the probe of meese being conducted by independent counsel james mckay. former nsc aide david wigg testified earlier
in addition, two former aides in meese's office, john richardson and john harrison, testified last week before the grand jury to which mckay's office is presenting evidence. richardson was meese's chief of staff before leaving the justice department several months ago. harrison worked on meese's staff in mid-1985
the probe of meese revolves around whether he may have violated the 1977 foreign corrupt practices act, which prohibits bribes by u.s. companies or their agents to foreign officials
wallach wrote a memo to meese in september 1985 saying that a portion of up to $700 million from the pipeline would be paid to the israeli labor party. meese says he doesn't recall reading the portion of the memo relating to planned labor party payments
wallach had been hired by swiss oilman bruce rappaport to assist in the project and wallach went to meese on the matter in may 1985. meese referred him to then-national security adviser robert mcfarlane, who directed that robinson assist the project
iraq was seeking an insurance package for the pipeline in the event it was bombed by israel. then-israeli prime minister shimon peres gave assurances that israel would not attack the line, but iraq wanted a financial package to back up that promise
the nsc aides assisted on a number of proposed packages, initially trying to promote a $400 million bank-backed package acceptable to the overseas private investment corp. the government agency insures foreign investments by u.s. firms such as bechtel group inc., which was going to build the project
robinson left the nsc and his place on the project was taken by wigg, who worked with wallach on alternative proposals. those included pledging u.s. aid to israel as a guarantee for the pipeline and seeking to put pentagon budget money for israel in an overseas escrow account as insurance. none of the insurance proposals was adopted and the pipeline wasn't built
an independent study group said today it could find little evidence that elevating the veterans administration to a cabinet-level department would help the agency do its job better
the group and the general accounting office, the investigative arm of congress, said changes in the way the va is managed should be made whether or not the agency is granted cabinet status
in a report to the senate governmental affairs committee, a panel of the national academy of public administration said it was not making a recommendation for or against a cabinet-level va
william fischer, chairman of the academy's seven-member study group, said the panel did not take a vote on elevating the va to cabinet status, but he said, ``we did agree on the report.''
we are not here to discuss the priority of meeting the needs ... of veterans,'' fischer told the committee. ``we are discussing ... structure.''
the panel, which did the study in seven weeks, found ``little evidence that the prospects of fulfilling the vital mission of providing for the present and future needs of veterans would be materially improved by elevating the va to a cabinet department.''
the panel also said it does not believe the elevation to cabinet-status ``would significantly improve either access to the president, the adequacy of necessary resources, or the organization, management and delivery of high-quality services and benefits
the panel does recognize the potential political value of raising the public visibility of the needs of veterans and the programs designed to meet these needs by making va a department in the president's cabinet,'' the report said. ``however, given the broad political support which already exists for the va and its programs, the gain would be at the margin.''
legislation to elevate the va has been endorsed by president reagan and was approved by the house on nov. 17. there has been strong support in the senate for passage
governmental affairs committee chairman, sen. john glenn, d-ohio, said at today's hearing: ``if the elevation of the va to cabinet-level status is accompanied by significant measures to improve the management and operation of the agency, as well as to ensure the fair treatment of all veterans seeking access to agency services and benefits, then the case for elevation becomes much stronger.''
glenn said improvements within the va legislation ``should be the goal of this committee over the next few weeks.''
the national academy for public administration, chartered by congress, provides independent advice on the organization and operation of government at all levels
two soldiers were convicted and given less than a month in jail for their role in the brutal arab beatings taped by an american television crew, the military said today
a military judge sentenced ronnen sasson to 21 days in jail and arieh moalem to 10 days in jail, the army said. they were sentenced monday following their convictions on charges of brutality and harassment
sasson and moalem, along with two other soldiers and an officer, were taped by a cbs news crew on feb. 25 as they beat and kicked two bound palestinian youths in nablus, the largest city in the occupied west bank
the soldiers kicked the two arabs in the head and chest, then picked up fist-sized rocks and smashed them on arms and legs. cbs said the beating lasted 40 minutes
the film produced widespread criticism and the west bank commander, maj. gen. amram mitzna, ordered the detention of four soldiers and their commanding officer, all from the elite golani brigade
the army said an investigation showed that moalem and sasson played a relatively minor part in the beating. the film did not show moalem taking part
the army said that the two other soldiers involved, yehuda angel and saguy harpaz, and their commander, capt. yossi haddad, will face more serious charges. wastes</head>
a man who spent months industriously burying stolen cars, trucks and other equipment in the back yard of his rural home was being sought today, officials said
the man, identified as korey cragg, jumped out a back window of his home when he was questioned by a deputy, sheriff's detective allan l. foreman said. cragg was being sought for an alleged role in a car-stripping operation
by monday afternoon officials had unearthed more than a dozen cars and trucks plus various equipment and car parts, officials said. they also discovered numerous buried 55-gallon drums containing motor oil, gasoline and transmission fluid
for months, residents living in the desert 65 miles northeast of los angeles had watched as cragg buried the vehicles with a backhoe, foreman said
a neighbor told us he was hauling out a trailer load of engines every other day,'' foreman said. ``he was a busy, busy boy. it appears he was working 24 hours a day. ... he could go through two or three cars a day.''
sylvestre carrillo, who lives in a home just east of the house, said he thought his neighbor was ``just a hard worker.''
he'd be at it day and night,'' carrillo said. ``he was a pretty good mechanic, or so we thought.''
someone finally called the sheriff after seeing cragg bury an almost-new car over the weekend, and a deputy confronted cragg on sunday
after answering a couple of questions, cragg excused himself to go to the bathroom. instead, he climbed out a back bedroom window and fled, foreman said
police found a stolen red corvette in the garage and secured a search warrant, foreman said
three people inside the house at the time were booked for investigation of grand theft auto, a jail deputy in victorville, 10 miles north of here, said. they were identified as cragg's wife, kathy, 27, of hesperia, and brian powell, 26 and sheryl vansanford, 28, both of los angeles county
bail was set at $200,000 each and the three were scheduled for arraignment wednesday in victorville municipal court, the deputy said
on monday, county detectives-turned-archaeologists returned to excavate the cache of stolen property
the car-stripping operation apparently started about five months ago, and foreman said officialos had not idea how many vehicles they might eventually find. he said investigators expect to find even more buried cars in the surrounding desert
that's just a guess at this time,'' said foreman. ``neighbors say he would haul the backhoe out into the desert to bury stuff.'' picks up 6th graf pvs, `he is also...' adds byline.</note>
monsignor eugene a. marino was named roman catholic archbishop of atlanta today and became the first black archbishop in the united states
marino called his appointment ``a great sign of hope to all of our people.''
blacks have a rich religious tradition, but ``not a rich tradition that enriches the catholic church,'' marino said today at a news conference in atlanta
marino said he was ``not one to dodge issues; at the same time i am not one to go out and look for issues for issues' sake.''
he said he would try to follow the example of jesus christ, who ``never quite went out of his way, either to address needs or to avoid addressing needs.''
the appointment was announced by the vatican and in washington by archbishop pio laghi, the apostolic pro-nuncio in the united states
marino, 53 and a member of the josephite order, succeeds archbishop thomas a. donnellan, who died oct. 15. marino has been an auxiliary bishop in washington, d.c., since 1974
he now will be titular head of the roman catholic church in georgia, north carolina and south carolina, although his responsibilities beyond the archdiocese in north georgia are limited
marino said he hopes to expand the number of black catholics in this country. there are about 1.3 million blacks among the 52 million u.s. catholics
marino is the first black catholic archbishop in the united states, said william ryan, spokesman for the united states catholic conference in washington
in 1971, marino became the first black priest to hold the major office of vicar general of a religious community _ the josephite fathers, who are headquartered in washington
he is also the first auxiliary bishop to be elected to high office in the national conference of catholic bishops and the united states catholic conference. his three-year term as secretary of the groups ends in november
marino was born in biloxi, miss., on may 29, 1934. he studied at epiphany apostolic college in newburgh, n.y., from 1952 to 1955, at mary immaculate novitiate, also in newburgh, from 1955 to 1956, and at st. joseph's seminary in washington from 1956 to 1962
he also received a master's degree in religious education from fordham university
marino was ordained the shrine of the immaculate conception in washington on june 9, 1962
he taught at epiphany college from 1962 to 1968, served as spiritual director of st. joseph's seminary from 1968 to 1971 and spiritual director of the permanent diaconate training program for the washington archdiocese from 1969 to 1971
marino was elected to a four-year term as vicar general of the josephite fathers on july 13, 1971, and was serving in that capacity when he was named auxiliary bishop of washington and titular bishop of walla walla, wash., on july 15, 1974
here, at a glance, are the methods for picking delegates from illinois to attend the 1988 democratic and republican national conventions this summer
method: primary
date: tuesday, march 15
candidates filed: bruce babbitt, michael dukakis, richard gephardt, albert gore, gary hart, jesse jackson, paul simon
pledged delegates:173 super delegates: 15 total: 188
delegates allocated: tuesday, march 15
selection of delegates:tuesday, march 15 and saturday, may 7

illinois is a direct-election primary, meaning its 113 congressional district delegates to the democratic national convention are elected directly from the primary ballot
ilinois democrats will be faced with a two-part ballot in the march 15 primary. the top part of the ballot will be a non-binding presidential ``beauty contest,'' and the second part will list the candidates for national convention delegate
the remainder of the state's pledged national convention delegates will be picked by the state central committee on may 7. they will be allocated among presidential candidates in proportion to the number of delegates from congressional districts pledged to the candidates
method: primary
date: tuesday, march 15
candidates filed: george bush, bob dole, jack kemp, pat robertson, pete du pont, alexander haig
delegates: 92
delegates allocated: tuesday, march 15 and thursday, june 16
selection of delegates: tuesday, march 15 and thursday, june 16

illinois republicans have the same kind of two-part presidential ballot as the democrats. the top part of the ballot is a non-binding presidential ``beauty contest,'' while the second part lists the candidates for national convention delegate
the candidates for delegate can have the name of a presidential candidate printed next to their own name on the ballot
eighty-two delegates will be elected directly from the ballot and will be apportioned among congressional districts, ranging from two to five delegates per district. the state's remaining 10 delegates will be elected at-large at the state convention june 16-18
greece will open its first embassy at the vatican in a move that comes in the wake of improving relations between the greek orthodox and roman catholic churches, a senior foreign ministry official said tuesday
the diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the move had no direct connection to easing of 900-year-old religious tensions and pope john paul ii's meeting with orthodox patriarch dimitrios i in december
he said the decision to open the embassy was made before the two met
greece established diplomatic relations with the vatican 10 years ago. its ambassador in paris has been accredited there
the greek orthodox church is one of the autonomous eastern orthodox churches organized mainly along national lines. it recognizes the leadership of the patriarch of constantinople, modern-day istanbul, turkey, rather than that of the pope
the greek diplomat said the decision to send an ambassador was approved by the greek parliament last month. he did not say when an ambassador will be picked
some people in the southern philippines still believe a serpent swallows the sun every night, but those who don't are buying ``eclipse viewers'' at about $2 each to watch a total solar eclipse
davao city is one of the best places to see the eclipse friday morning. it will be visible longer in mati, but you can hardly get there from here or anywhere else
the viewing devices are made of cardboard, in the shape of eyeglasses or scopes, with exposed photographic film as lenses
an estimated 1,500 scientists, journalists and observers from all over the world will bring more elaborate equipment to watch the moon blot out the sun
a department of tourism brochure says the rare phenomenon will be visible friday in three areas: sumatra, indonesia; kkalimantan, borneo, and the southern philippines, where it can be seen longest
nowhere will the view surpass that in the davao area, 600 miles southeast of manila on mindanao island
for three minutes, day will become night as the moon moves between the earth and the sun. darkness is expected to envelop neighboring general santos city at 9:05 a.m.; davao at 9:07 a.m., and mati in adjacent davao oriental province 38 seconds later
along with the makeshift glasses and scopes, the most popular items at sidewalk stalls in advance of the eclipse were baseball caps at $1.50 or less and t-shirts ranging in price from $1.75 to $6
some shirts proclaim ``i was there.''
others depict a man battling a huge serpent wrapped around the sun, representing the ancient belief that the sun disappears each day because the serpent bakunawa swallows it
friday morning could be noisy in davao and general santos city. people who still believe in bakunawa will bang pots and pans in hopes the noise will distract the serpent's attention from the sun
although the eclipse is expected to last longest in mati, the town has been all but ignored in advertisements because it has only two small lodging facilities and is much harder to reach than the davao and general santos, said roger layson, regional tourism officer
officials said most of the visiting scientists, journalists and other foreign observers would stay in general santos. they are expected to spend about $750,000
layson said most of the foreign astronomers are american and british, and most of the other observers japanese. all hotels and other facilities have been booked since january, and tourism authorities have arranged lodgings in private homes for $7.50 to $10 a day
there have been reports of threats by rebels to disrupt the event, but layson said news reporrts of some visitors canceling reservations were ``exaggerated.''
both the moslem rebel moro national liberation front and the communist guerrilla new people's rebels operate in the southern philippines
moslem insurgents said they plan a demonstration in general santos city on friday, the front's 16th anniversary, but rebel sources said it would be peaceful. jordanian citizen reported detained</note>
a woman and her daughter have returned to texas after retired u.s. commandos hired for $200,000 grabbed the girl in jordan where she had been taken by her father in a custody dispute, newspapers reported today
meanwhile, the united states expressed regret to jordan over the incident, and an american embassy officer in amman was recalled to washington for questioning about his knowledge of the affair, state department spokesman charles redman said monday in washington
the philadelphia inquirer reported on saturday that the woman and the commandos entered jordan and seized lauren bayan, 7, from a school bus jan. 28 in jerash, north of amman
the woman had been identified at kathy mahoon, but holly planells, head of american children held hostage, said her name is cathy phelps mahone, the dallas morning news and the dallas times herald reported today
the woman claims her ex-husband, jordanian-born mohammed ali bayan, kidnapped the child and took her to jordan although she was granted custody of the child following a divorce
dallas county court records confirm that a judge granted ms. mahone custody of her daughter, but police say they have no record of the reported kidnapping in september
she (ms. mahone) called me from texas and said they're alive and well and very happy,'' ms. planells, of white plains, n.y., told the morning news on monday
she's really getting assimilated back to american life,'' ms. plannels said, referring to the girl. ``it was a traumatic experience to be away from her mother like that. jordan is a strange place.''
ms. plannels declined to say where ms. mahone is, saying the woman fears her husband ``will try this again.''
ms. mahone, unable to get her daughter back through legal channnels, hired former army commandos to take the girl away from her father, who claimed legal custody of the child under jordanian law, the inquirer reported saturday
corporate training unlimited, a company in fayetteville, n.c., that specializes in ``hostage rescue training,'' plotted and carried out the seizure, the newspaper said
the times herald quoted ms. planells as saying the operation cost ms. mahone $200,000. ms. mahone has mentioned the possibility of a movie deal about the raid, ms. planells said
company president donald feeney denied the story, but other well-placed sources described the company's role, the inquirer said
bayan reported his daughter had been abducted by three americans and he published newspaper advertisements seeking information
sameer salem, a jordanian friend of bayan's, told the associated press that bayan had returned to jordan in fall 1987 after selling a dallas restaurant called the country skillet
the recalled american embassy official, who was not named, had some knowledge prior to the incident that the group had arrived in jordan, redman said. but the officer had been misled as to its intentions
we have expressed regret to the government of jordan for any role that an embassy officer might have played in this violation of jordanian law,'' redman said
there was no official comment from jordanian authorities. however, one jordanian official, who did not want his name used, said a jordanian citizen was involved in getting the girl out of jordan
he said the man was an employee of an agency which does security work for the u.s. embassy and that he had been detained for questioning. he did not give the man's name
about 300 protesters defied police orders and marched in a human chain to demand greater freedom from the communist government, witnesses said tuesday
police did not intervene except to order by loudspeaker that the demonstrators disperse, the witnesses said, speaking on condition of anonymity. the demonstration came monday on the second day of the leipzig trade fair, which draws visitors from 100 nations
the protesters came out of a ``peace prayer'' in the nicholas church in downtown leipzig, marched about 500 yards to another church where they sang songs, and then walked back to where they began, said the witnesses. the protesters voluntarily left after about 40 minutes
they were among more than 1,000 people who attended the prayer service at the lutheran church, according to the witnesses
church officials speaking at the hour-long prayer service were applauded when they demanded greater freedom for east germans and an end to legal actions against those who want to leave the country, the witnesses said
an unidentified church official was quoted as telling the congregation that the country needs laws in line with international conventions
officials of east germany's lutheran church have become increasingly outspoken in favor of improved human rights conditions in the country
the witnesses also said government officials banned a monday night rally where activists had planned to publicize the plight of east germans who are denied the right to leave the country
a nigerian official said tuesday the government will press ahead with its population control project over the objections of christian leaders who argue it favors moslems
the plan to curtail the growth rate in black africa's most populous nation, with about 95 million people, created considerable controversy when it was announced last month. christian leaders said it favored the country's moslem majority because christian men may only have one wife while moslem men can marry up to four women
several prominent women have demanded that the government also institute a plan to limit nigerian men to one wife
the government's population control plan attempts to limit women to four children through education campaigns
air marshal ibrahim alfa of the armed forces ruling council said the government intended to advance the plan anyway. ``this is a policy that will take some time to take hold, and we are quite aware of the problems it would face,'' he said. status</head>
significant changes in the way the veterans administration is being managed should be made whether or not it is elevated to cabinet status, a senate committee was told tuesday
a panel of the national academy of public administration, an independent study group, and the general accounting office, the investigative arm of congress, did not make recommendations on whether the va should become part of the president's cabinet
but in its reports to the senate governmental affairs committee, the seven-member academy panel said it found ``little evidence'' in its study that cabinet-level status would materially improve the va's mission of providing for the present and future needs of veterans
the panel does not believe that such an elevation would significantly improve either access to the president, the adequacy of necessary resources, or the organization, management and delivery of high-quality services and benefits,'' the report said
the panel said it ``does recognize the potential political value of raising the public visibility of the needs of veterans and the programs designed to meet these needs by making va a department in the president's cabinet. however, given the broad political support which already exists for the va and its programs, the gain would be at the margin.''
the gao said signficant changes are needed in the way the va is being managed, and that they should be made whether or not the agency is granted cabinet status
to appropriately manage any large, decentralized organization, top management must have reliable information on each unit's output and the resources used to achieve the output,'' the office said. ``gao reports have documented situations in which top managers were unaware of inefficient or poor quality services because they lacked complete, reliable and accurate data and the incentives to use those data to improve service delivery.''
the gao recommended that the va's deputy administrator, or the undersecretary if the va is made a cabinet department, be given the responsibility for the agency's day-to-day management
the academy panel said it had seen reports of internal weaknesses in the va. however, it concluded that a cabinet department is not required to make necessary improvements, ``although the creation of more presidential appointments could improve the quality of veterans programs by attracting better managers.''
a cabinet-level va could possibly achieve more uniformity of broad, cross-cutting national policy goals, the panel conceded. however, it said, ``there are other mechanisms now in place or available which have been, and could be, used to accomplish these purposes whether or not the va is elevated to be a cabinet department although cabinet status might make the current mechanisms work more effectively.''
president reagan has endorsed legislation to raise the va to cabinet status. the house passed a similar bill last nov. 17. there also has been strong support in the senate for passage of the legislation
the va is an independent agency created in 1930. it provides health, disability, pension and death benefits to veterans, as well as loans and educational programs
judges in john demjanjuk's war crimes trial granted a defense request tuesday to admit new evidence from 15 holocaust survivors who failed to identify the retired ohio autoworker as a nazi guard
defense attorney yoram sheftel said the new evidence casts doubt on testimony from five treblinka death camp survivors who identified demjanjuk from a 1942 photograph as ``ivan the terrible.'' prisoners used that nickname for the guard who operated gas chambers that killed 850,000 jews in nazi-occupied poland
there are 15 statements of treblinka survivors who did not identify demjanjuk as ivan versus five who did,'' sheftel told israel radio. ``this evidence is extremely substantial and extremely important.''
the three-judge panel interrupted its deliberations tuesday to consider the new evidence during a special session in jerusalem district court. demjanjuk's year-long trial ended feb. 18
the judges set a court session for monday to allow prosecutors and defense attorneys to address the new evidence in summary arguments, assistant prosecutor eliyahu avram said
the ukrainian-born demjanjuk, 67, retired as a cleveland-area autoworker and says he is the victim of mistaken identity
sheftel said the latest evidence also includes statements revealing there were at least six nazi guards who resembled demjanjuk at treblinka
sheftel said he received the new evidence last week. a federal judge in washington ordered the justice department to release the documents after demjanjuk's family sued for them under the freedom of information act
capitol police, who have arrested visitors carrying an uzi machine gun, a pistol disguised as a beeper and soda bottles containing explosives, are worried about a 147 percent surge in weapons seizures at the capitol last year
the police confiscated 1,162 weapons from visitors entering the capitol or six adjacent house and senate office buildings in 1987, up from 470 weapons seizures the previous year, according to house sergeant at arms jack russ
russ is citing these figures to lobby for an $18.5 million plan to tighten security on the house side of the capitol, including bombproof glass around the visitors' gallery overlooking the house chamber
russ said in an interview that most of the weapons last year were seized from visitors who were unaware of gun control restrictions at the capitol and had no criminal intent. these included constituents carrying out-of-state gun permits that are invalid on the capitol grounds
of the 1,162 arrests on illegal weapons charges last year, he said, only 63 were prosecuted, compared with 50 arrests prosecuted in 1986
the house security plan being pushed by russ calls for spending $4.2 million to install shatterproof glass shields around the house visitors' gallery and modify seats on the chamber floor to protect against bomb blasts
he also is requesting a $4.7 million emergency telephone system to alert every house office immediately to a terrorist attack, $413,352 worth of additional bomb detectors in house office buildings, a $3.5 million electronic card system for access to house garages, and a $5.7 million alarm system connecting home-district offices with local police
strict anti-terrorist proposals, such as placing a wrought iron security fence around the capitol grounds and glass enclosures around the house and senate galleries, have been widely criticized in the past
many legislators argue that the capitol, as a symbol of open democracy, should be easily accessible to the public. but russ says this is unrealistic because of growing security threats
i think everybody _ me included _ would like the easy-going atmosphere of a mayberry rfd police force, with a friendly cop directing traffic,'' russ said. ``but in this day and time, you also need a high-tech, well-trained police department. you've got to have both.''
russ outlined his plan last week at a house appropriations subcommittee hearing on the proposed $1.96 billion budget for congressional operations next year, and plans to seek spending authority from a separate house committee
still awaiting action by the house and senate leadership is a more sweeping security plan that calls for fencing in the capitol plaza, a parking ban on the east front plaza and gatehouses to screen visitors before they enter the capitol grounds
although only authorized vehicles are permitted to enter the capitol grounds, pedestrians may enter unhindered and are not screened for illegal weapons until enter the capitol building itself, or adjacent office buildings
the comprehensive security plan for the entire capitol area has been approved by the capitol police board, consisting of the house and senate sergeants at arms, the capitol police chief and the architect of the capitol
a $13 million appropriation to implement the plan remains largely unspent, awaiting a final go-ahead from congressional leaders. russ said he hopes the leaders will meet before the end of april to review the broader plan
meanwhile, police are using hydraulically operated, steel street barricades to halt unauthorized vehicles at the two main traffic entrances to the capitol grounds. in addition, large concrete flower and shrubbery pots stand along driveways and sidewalks to thwart any attempted truck bombings of the capitol. meanwhile, but deletes last 3 grafs pvs to trim.</note>
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir registered his objections today to a mideast peace conference and secretary of state george p. shultz said the two had been unable to bridge their differences on a u.s. proposal for negotiations on settling the arab-israeli conflict
but both pledged to continue their efforts. president reagan, in a speech to an american jewish audience, described the situation in the middle east as ``urgent.''
reagan also gave assurances in talking to the united jewish appeal that ``we will not leave israel to stand alone, nor will we acquiesce in any effort to gang up on israel.'' the president added: ``peace will not be imposed by us or by anyone else. it will and must come from the genuine give-and-take of negotiations. that's what we're working to set in motion now.''
emerging with shamir from a 90-minute session at the state department, shultz said ``we haven't found our way to bridge all of the differences.'' but, he said, ``i see quite clearly what the nature of the difference are and what they aren't.''
shultz did not offer any details, but shamir underscored a major disagreement with the plan for negotiations shultz devised two weeks ago and proposed to arab and israeli leaders
we are interested, first of all, to negotiate directly with all the parties concerned,'' shamir said. ``we don't see any positive role for an international conference.''
shultz's plan would have an international conference attended by the united states, the soviet union, china, britain and france convene last month and set the stage for negotiations between israel and a mixed jordanian-palestinian delegation by may 1
shamir is concerned the soviet union and china, which do not have relations with israel, would try to tilt the outcome in the arabs' favor
shultz called his session with shamir ``very constructive and worthwhile'' and said ``we feel encouraged to continue our efforts to work with israel and others in the middle east to seek greater stability, constructive and peaceful relations in the region.''
shamir said their talk was `'very serious and thorough.'' he pledged to cooperate with shultz and others in the u.s. government ``to get peace and to enhance the prospects for peace in our area.''
shamir, meanwhile, added pat robertson, a television evangelist seeking the repulbicn presidential nomination, to his afternoon schedule
in a tough speech monday night to an american jewish group, shamir said yielding territory on the west bank and gaza would invite another attempt by the arabs to destroy israel
these matters are questions of life and death, of our very existence,'' shamir told a united jewish appeal group
shultz's plan for peace talks anticipates israel relinquishing at least some of the territory in exchange for arab recognition of the jewish state
but shamir said ``the two most dangerous attempts to destroy us'' _ in the 1948 and 1967 wars _ were made when israel did not control the territories
during a stop in new york monday to meet with american jewish leaders, and then in an arrival statement at andrews air force base outside washington, the israeli prime minister made it clear he would not give shultz a yes-or-no answer on the peace plan
instead, shamir seemed intent on persuading the reagan administration to revise its blueprint. it calls for a peace conference by may 1 to set up palestinian self-rule for three years, and then negotiations by december on an overall settlement
a senior u.s. official, briefing reporters at the white house under rules of anonymity, appeared to rule out any major revisions in the proposal shultz gave 10 days ago to israel, jordan, syria and egypt
the official acknowledged ``it gives pain to all of the parties,'' but he said ``we won't let any aspect be eroded or compromised.''
so far, the official said, israel and the arabs had not rejected the plan, which he called an improvement over the 1978 camp david agreements that produced a peace treaty between egypt and israel but failed to resolve the palestinian problem
shamir, who met briefly monday with shultz and defense secretary frank c. carlucci, had a busy schedule today. it began with breakfast with shultz at his home, lengthy talks with him at the state department and meetings with treasury secretary james a. baker iii and congressional leaders
the israeli leader sees president reagan on wednesday
while shamir promised to keep an open mind in the talks, he took a hard line on israel's retention of the west bank and gaza in his speech monday night
i am astonished at some people's short memory,'' shamir said. ``did we have peace when we did not have these territories? don't they remember that the two most dangerous attempts to destroy us _ in 1948 and in 1967 _ were made when we did not control any of these territories? do they want us to go back to a situation which would inevitably invite another such attempt?''
referring to the recent violence on the west bank and in gaza in which 91 palestinians have perished, shamir said ``it is not a war for a palestinian state in those areas. it is a war against israelis, against the existence of the state of israel.''
he said israel's enemies, ``taking a leaf from the ayatollah khomeini's war manual,'' had incited women and teen-agers to fight a war of violence in the streets. ``i promise you,'' shamir said. ``they will fail again.''
his hesitation to respond directly to the u.s. plan for negotiations did not seem to distress the reagan administration. ``we are not pressing israel,'' the senior u.s. official said
however, he said, ``it is the situation in the area which is pressing israel and all the other parties in the area.''
shamir did not disclose the revisions he will propose to shultz, who devised the plan and set this week as a deadline for a reply from the israeli and jordanian governments. name and spelling of ``irvine.''</note>
the protective ozone layer over the united states appears to have shrunk about 2.3 percent since 1969, scientists said today in the most thorough study yet of ozone depletion
experts have estimated that a 1 percent depletion could mean a 5 percent to 6 percent increase in skin cancers
but today's report from the national aeronautics and space administration, the work of more than 100 experts over 17 months, put the annual ozone depletion over the mid-latitudes of the northern hemisphere at a much higher rate
those latitudes, 30 degrees to 64 degrees, take in all of the united states except southern texas, louisiana and florida and extend halfway up canada's yukon territory
the scientists laid the responsibility for the ozone depletion squarely on chlorofluorocarbons (cfcs), chemicals used to power some aerosol sprays
at this point there is no other culprit to blame,'' said sherwood rowland of the university of california at irvine. ``we have taken out all the natural phenomena that are believed to affect ozone.''
the report also said that the annual springtime depletion of ozone over antarctica appears to be diluting ozone yearround over the southern hemisphere to about 60 degrees southern latitude, a point midway between the tip of the antarctic peninsula and cape horn at the southern tip of south america
rowland, who headed one nasa study groups, said the scientists had re-examined years of ground-based and satellite observations of the atmosphere to remove the normal biennial fluctuations of many atmospheric characteristics and also the effects of the 11-year solar cycle
the ground-based observations were limited to mid-latitudes in the northern hemisphere because there are few stations elsewhere in the world. but never before have scientists re-analyzed the monthly data at differing latitudes to try to remove the solar and biennial fluctuations
ozone in the atmosphere 15 miles to 25 miles up filters out the sun's ultraviolet rays, making life on earth possible. the same ultraviolet breaks up the cfc compounds, liberating chlorine, which in turn destroys ozone
ozone is a pollutant on the ground, but cfcs don't break up there _ not enough ultraviolet gets through
cfcs were banned as aerosol propellants in the united states in 1978, and worldwide emissions declined. there was one report in 1983 from the national academy of sciences that said future ozone decline would be only 2 percent to 4 percent
but cfc use started growing again, in part because one compound turned out to be ideal for cleaning computer chips and other electronic parts. other major uses are for refrigeration fluids and as blowing agents in making plastic foams
then an annual ozone ``hole'' over the antarctic was discovered, and records going back to 1958 showed that it hadn't happened before the late 1970s
discovery of the ozone hole _ an annual antarctic springtime plunge in ozone concentrations, last year by a record 50 percent _ spurred treaty negotiators last fall in montreal
the environmental protection agency has estimated that a 1 percent thinning of the earth's ozone shield means a 5 percent to 6 percent increase in skin cancer. if cfc use continued increasing at 2.5 percent per year, epa said, 20 percent of the ozone barrier could be gone in the next century
today's report came one day after the senate, on a vote of 83-0, became the first major chemical-producing nation to ratify a 31-country treaty cutting emissions that damage the earth's protective ozone layer
the treaty commits the signers to a 50 percent cut from 1986 levels in production of compounds called chlorofluorocarbons, cfcs, by 1998
the treaty will be officially ratified when the president signs it. though the united states will be the first major producer of cfc compounds to ratify, it is not the first ratifier _ that is mexico
under the treaty, epa says, the decline would slow to the point where it would be swamped by the normal year-to-year fluctuations
the soviet union has several cfc plants under construction, and won concessions permitting it to exceed the treaty limits for a time _ which led to a soviet treaty signature in december. similar provisions were made for developing countries. if those exceptions are used, the environmental defense fund has estimated, the actual 1998 rollback in emissions could be 35 percent instead of 50 percent. after 3rd pvs with time of interview not stated</note>
in an interview with his biographer, porno actor john c. holmes said he did not know who was responsible for a multiple murder in which he was a suspect, a newspaper reported today
holmes said that during the hours before four people were bludgeoned to death and a fifth was maimed at a house in laurel canyon on july 1, 1981, he was held at gunpoint at another house
the los angeles times, relying on two unidentified sources familiar with the manuscript of holmes' as-yet-unpublished biography, reported that after his captors let him go, he went to the house where the killings occurred and discovered the bodies
the biography is based on extensive interviews with the actor, but it was not clear when those interviews were conducted. one of the sources said: ``john ... did not know up to the time of his death who did the murders. he was not there when it happened.''
holmes died early sunday at the veterans administration medical center in sepulveda at the age of 43. he died of pneumonia brought on by aids, his second wife, laurie, said monday
holmes, a leading sex film actor of the 1970s and early '80s, was tried and acquitted in the murders in 1982. at the time of the killings, holmes was a cocaine addict
within the last six weeks, homicide detectives again questioned holmes about his role in the killings, but he either refused or was unable to answer, the times reported
attorneys james m. eisenman and william d kibanow confirmed monday that a biography of holmes has been offered to several publishers, but they declined to discuss its contents. the lawyers represent mrs. holmes, 24, and her husband's estate. the biographer's name was not revealed
holmes had been hospitalized with acquired immune deficiency syndrome since november
authorities have theorized that the laurel canyon killings were committed to avenge an armed robbery of nightclub owner adel nasrallah, also known as eddie nash
former deputy district attorney ronald s. coen, who prosecuted the case, said holmes was a middleman between nash and a theft ring
coen said holmes set up the armed robbery of nasrallah and later was forced to lead the killers to the laurel canyon house where members of the ring were staying
