we've been visited by educators from norway, australia and japan. a lot of people are looking over our shoulder in this process,'' he said
warner burke, a professor at teachers college of columbia university, said phillips' emphasis on mimicking a corporate hierarchy hinders the students' understanding of how they come to their decisions
here our goals are understanding the group process, not just decision making,'' said burke, director psychology. ``the most important aspect of group processes is non-verbal behavior.''
two married department of corrections guards have been charged with conspiring to kill two robbery witnesses for $50,000, authorities said
the couple were to present their victims' index fingers as proof the contract was completed, prosecutors said
wayne lyle cox, 48, and linda rae cox, 36, both of navasota, were being held tuesday in harris county jail in lieu of $250,000 bond each
the coxes were correctional officers at the pack 1 unit in navasota. cox had worked for the prison system for nearly six years, while mrs. cox had been employed for nearly five years, said tdc spokesman david nunnelee
the case developed after a harris county prisoner fighting extradition to arkansas on charges of robbing a jewelry store began spreading word about seeking a contract killing for two store employees, said prosecutor jon munier
before long, an undercover officer made contact with the coxes, who discussed the planned killing in recorded conversations, munier said
on march 11, cox accepted $10,000 from the undercover officer as a downpayment on the job, munier said
the intended victims remain under guard in arkansas, munier said
those people aren't the only hit teams this guy's got,'' munier said. ``he's been robbing zales jewelry stores in texas and all over, and he's got a lot of money to spend.''
david bowie, jennifer rush, u-2 and other western rock groups will join soviet musicians for a series of concerts to raise money to fight drug addiction
the concerts, originally scheduled for this month, are to take place in late april, the novosti press agency said
novosti did not give a date, but said the three six-hour concerts will be held at the 30,000-seat olympic stadium in moscow
the agency did not say why they were delayed, but sources close to the organizers blamed the postponement on bureaucratic red tape
the sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said former beatles george harrison and paul mccartney, as well as julian lennon, the son of the late beatle john lennon, had been invited. it was unclear whether they would participate
the press agency said revenue from ticket sales will be donated to the united nations fund for the struggle against drug addiction and to the soviet toxicology research center
sponsors include several soviet organizations and trade companies from the united states, west germany and hungary
soviet officials denied reports of drug abuse in the country until mikhail s. gorbachev's campaign for greater openness. now, newspaper stories often point out the problems and have disclosed there are 50,000 diagnosed addicts and many more who may be undiagnosed
novosti said musicians from 10 north american and european countries will peform along with several soviet groups. among the foreign groups that have agreed to perform, novosti said, are level 42, supertramp, u-2, foreigner, tangerine dream, bon jovi, jennifer rush and david bowie
participating soviet groups are aquarium, bravo, brigade s, black coffee and others whose music ranges from heavy metal to traditional rock 'n' roll, according to novosti
tickets will be about $16, much more expensive than for the average soviet concert. when billy joel performed in moscow last summer, tickets sold for a little under $8
the crimefighting guardian angels illegally solicited $17,863 in florida last year and will be fined $450 for failing to comply with charity laws, officials say
the division of licensing cited the group last month for violations in the first half of 1987. the guardian angels were cited for soliciting funds without a license, hiring a private fund-raiser without reporting it, failing to maintain records of contributions and failing to have identification as a charitable group while soliciting, said division spokesman alan c. rollins
angels founder curtis a. sliwa, whose red-bereted army patrols subways and neighborhoods in several cities, blamed the violations on ignorance
the new york city-based alliance of guardian angels inc. now complies with florida laws, state spokesman rollins said. in reports filed last year, the group said it received $17,863 and spent about $10,000
new york state records show the angels received $117,139 nationwide last year, not including the value of free rent and services. the group has debts of $122,086
two postal clerks who survived the edmond post office massacre that killed 14 of their co-workers plan to marry in april
debbie smith and steven brehm said they will tie a yellow bow around a gazebo post at the park where they say their vows to mark the memory of those who were killed aug. 20, 1986, by gunman patrick sherrill
it is as if our friends will be there,'' said ms. smith
ms. smith and brehm had been dating before the shooting. brehm has since transferred to the lincoln, neb., post office, and ms. smith is on assignment in oklahoma city, although she has applied for a transfer to lincoln
we still have nightmares,'' ms. smith said. ``but it's time we get on with our lives,'' brehm added
the couple escaped sherrill's gunfire by running separately out doors before the gunman returned and locked them. sherrill fatally shot himself to end the siege
vietnam is investigating another 29 possible cases of americans who never returned home from the vietnam war, a u.s. military official said tuesday
the latest inquiry could represent a significant step in resolving the fates of nearly 1,800 americans listed as missing in action since the united states withdrew its troops in 1973
the vietnamese told us they are investigating 29 instances where they have received information, material or remains,'' said lt. col. joe harvey. ``but they said it will take at least three weeks for them to draw any conclusions from these investigations or to have remains to repatriate.''
harvey, commander of the u.s. joint casualty resolution center based in hawaii, returned tuesday from four days of what he described as ``positive and productive'' talks on accounting for the mias. it was the fourth round of negotiations since retired gen. john w. vessey, a presidential envoy, visited vietnam in august and the vietnamese agreed to end a deadlock on the mia issue
harvey said his team provided new information to the vietnamese. he said it also visited the crash site of an american aircraft near the major northern port of haiphong, about 60 miles southeast of hanoi, but he gave no details
at least 27 u.s. aircraft were shot down when the united states in december 1972 launched air strikes in the hanoi-haiphong area to pressure the communists into signing a peace agreement
harvey's team is composed of six experts from the casualty center and the army central identification laboratory. nguyen can, deputy director of the foreign ministry's north american affairs department, headed the vietnamese side at the talks
vessey had asked the vietnamese to give top priority to resolving 70 ``discrepancy cases,'' in which the united states says there is strong evidence that vietnamese officials know the fates of the missing americans. these include cases where americans failed to emerge from prisoner of war camps
since vessey's talks, vietnam has returned remains it believes are those of americans three times. the most recent, on march 2, involved 17 sets of remains _ the largest turnover in two years and the fourth largest since the war ended. the vietnamese also turned over reports on three other mia cases
in exchange for vietnamese cooperation on the mia issue, washington has sent medical teams to vietnam four times and encouraged private u.s. agencies to provide assistance to war-disabled vietnamese. it has rejected calls for official aid because of continued u.s. opposition to vietnam's 9-year-old military occupation of cambodia. successor; subs 18th graf pvs, bgng: in 1974, to correct that predecessor's defeat, sted death, gave rodino the chairmanship</note>
the changing face of his home district finally caught up with rep. peter rodino, an italian-american who spent 20 terms crusading for civil rights but who is now reluctantly giving up his house seat to make way for a black successor
the new jersey democrat, who gained national prominence when he chaired the impeachment hearings of former president richard nixon, yielded monday to calls from minority constituents who want one of their own to represent them
rodino, 78, one of the most senior members of the house and chairman of its powerful judiciary committee, issued a statement saying he would step aside in january
texas rep. jack brooks, the next ranking democrat on the committee the past 13 years, will be rodino's likely successor
chairing that committee would be an honor and a privilege should my colleagues extend me that opportunity next year,'' said brooks, who currently heads the house government operations committee
brooks would have to be officially named by the democratic steering and policy committee and elected by the democratic caucus. committee members said they expected brooks to be the next chairman
it is not without a sense of sadness that i am announcing my decision to retire from the congress at the end of this term,'' rodino said
although he did not mention the demands of blacks and other minorities, who now comprise the majority in his district, rodino had been under increasing pressure to step aside. a host of black leaders _ most notably democratic presidential candidate jesse jackson _ lauded his record but urged him to make way for what would be new jersey's first black member of congress
in his statement, rodino said, ``i believe that my part of the journey in this great american experiment is at its end. i feel i have served my time and a purpose.''
rodino arrived in washington in 1948, a 38-year-old lawyer from an italian neighborhood in newark, n.j., eager to represent the bustling city in congress
he became an institution in the intervening 40 years: fighting for liberal legislation, controlling one of congress' most powerful committees and helping write into history the downfall of a president
but in those same years, newark decayed from the heart of the garden state into the brunt of jokes. rodino's political base eroded, and three black democrats, including two newark city councilmen, announced plans this year to seek his 10th congressional district seat
rodino, respected even by those calling on him to retire, had survived earlier challenges. in 1984 and 1986, he won re-election even though jackson went to newark to lead the retirement calls himself
backers, both black and white, noted rodino served as house floor manager for the landmark civil rights act of 1966 and wrote the 1982 voting rights act. he is an honorary member of the congressional black caucus and has been honored by the naacp
rodino is a good man,'' jackson told the new york times in 1986. ``that's not the issue. we can have a good man and black man from new jersey at the same time.''
during his fight two years ago, rodino hinted strongly he would retire after another two-year term. he said said he wanted to stay in congress to counter the reagan presidency
but, as rodino began last year to raise campaign funds and plan for re-election, black and white leaders in his party accused him of breaking a promise
aides said he wrote the resignation statement in his capitol hill office on monday, then left for his home. the announcement brought immediate accolades for rodino
i will miss his knowledge and his friendship. he sets an extraordinarily high standard for whomever will succeed him,'' said sen. bill bradley, d-n.j
rodino served nearly 20 years as a representative before being thrust into the national spotlight
in 1974, barely a year after his predecessor's defeat in a renomination battle gave rodino the judiciary committee gavel, the panel was charged with reviewing nixon's role in the watergate affair
the televised proceedings won rodino respect for his evenhanded handling of an emerging national crisis. in an interview last year, rodino recalled weeping after he and a majority of committee members voted to deliver articles of impeachment to the full house
nixon resigned before the house voted
rodino also served on the house iran-contra committee, which investigated the reagan administration's handling of the sale of arms to iran and the funneling of profits to the nicaraguan contra rebels. he has been harshly critical of the reagan administration's handling of the arms-for-hostages debacle
president reagan today urged clemency for the ``sharpeville six'' in south africa, saying such action would be ``welcomed by all americans.''
the six blacks are scheduled to be hanged friday for being in a mob outside a home where a township official was killed
in johannesburg, south africa, the justice ministry said president p.w. botha has refused to block the hangings, but added that any further petitions for mercy would be given ``careful consideration.''
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater told reporters, ``the president urges clemency for the sharpeville six in south africa on compassionate and humanitarian grounds.''
we implore the south african government to respond favorably to these requests,'' fitzwater said. ``an act of compassion such as this by the south african government would be welcomed by all americans.''
our disgust for apartheid has been stated many times, and we continue to speak out for its total elimination,'' the spokesman said
he said the administration was appealing directly to south african officials for clemency, as well as making the paublic statement
he said the united states had previously appealed for clemency in the case through public statements, support of a resolution in the united nations and representations at diplomatic talks in geneva
we are making this view known officially as well as publicly to the south african government,'' he said
a federal official urged congress tuesday to eliminate the penalties that face states whose drivers ignore the 55 mph speed limit, but two senior lawmakers said they are writing bills that would do just the opposite
reps. james howard, d-n.j., chairman of the house public works and transportation committee, and glenn anderson, d-calif., who heads the public works surface transportation subcommittee, said they are working on measures that would extend the penalties to states that have adopted the 65 mph limit
states with 55 mph limits can lose up to 10 percent of their federal highway aid if monitors find that more than half their motorists are driving too fast. but when two laws were passed last year allowing 65 mph driving on many rural highways, the penalties were not extended to roads where states allow the faster speeds
the states are clearly in the best position to determine where speed enforcement is needed to enhance safety,'' diane k. steed, chief of the national highway traffic safety administration, said in a statement delivered to anderson's panel. ``they should be able to deploy enforcement personnel accordingly, without the threat of losing federal funds.''
lawmakers from the 11 states that have retained the 55 mph limit have complained that it is unfair for their states to face the loss of federal assistance while states that permit faster driving cannot be penalized for motorists speeding on 65 mph roads
anderson said he is writing a bill that would apply the penalties to 65 mph highways. an aide said the measure could be ready in a week
the states simply have no economic incentive to enforce the speed limit laws on higher speed routes,'' anderson said of present conditions
during a break in the hearing, howard said he is shaping a bill that could roll back the number of miles of roads where 65 mph driving is allowed, and make it easier for 65 mph states to be penalized for drivers violating the speed limit
it's a more dangerous speed,'' he said of 65 mph. europe</head>
the united states should give top priority to negotiating reductions of 50 percent to 75 percent in conventional military forces in the soviet union, and eastern and western europe, former u.n. ambassador jeane kirkpatrick said tuesday
mrs. kirkpatrick also said she believes the united states should continue restrictions on trade with moscow in an effort to win human rights improvements inside the soviet union
so long as the soviets do not permit the free flow of people across the borders i do not believe it is appropriate for us to permit the free flow of goods across borders,'' she said
at the same time, she said she is not opposed on principle to expanding u.s.-soviet trade ``as long as the trade is profitable to us and does not subsidize them.''
mrs. kirkpatrick commented at a hearing of the commission on security and cooperation in europe which was organized to monitor soviet compliance with the human rights provisions of the helsinki accords
she said it was not ``inappropriate'' for the united states to have signed the new intermediate-range nuclear forces agreement eliminating medium-range nuclear missiles worldwide
but she said she does not believe that agreements reducing specific nuclear weapons systems are very important as long as the soviet union and its warsaw pact allies retain superiority in conventional forces
i think the top priority of the united states should be to negotiate real reductions _ 50 percent to 75 percent _ in conventional forces in eastern europe, the soviet union and western europe,'' she said
the hearing was convened to explore the impact on the nations of eastern europe of the reforms insituted in the soviet union by mikhail s. gorbachev, general secretary of the soviet communist party
mrs. kirkpatrick called those reforms important, said they should not be belittled and said of gorbachev: ``i believe his sincerity cannot be reasonably questioned.''
i think in fact gorbachev is the kind of man who would like to dismantle the structure of oppression'' in order to revitalize the stagnant soviet economy and retain his nation's superpower status, she said
he has made ... significant steps toward the release of political prisoners and dissidents in the soviet union,'' she said
i think that for both internal and external reasons gorbachev has concluded that repression and reliance on force is undesirable,'' she said. ``what we don't know is how far he is willing to go.''
mrs. kirkpatrick said there is relatively little u.s. policy can do to influence the soviets as the gorbachev policies of glasnost (openness) and perestroika (restructuring) run their course
responding to questions, she said she does not believe that u.s. negotiators should hold agreement on reductions in intercontinental strategic nuclear weapons hostage to soviet agreement to make human rights improvements
i'm not personally in favor of using arms reduction to win concessions in human rights,'' she said
a colorful new english-language tabloid hit the streets tuesday in montreal, the best-served newspaper market in canada with six dailies
the splashy montreal daily news was an instant success in this bilingual city. many newsstands sold out of the first press run of 80,000 copies
with minority-interest financial backing from britain's robert maxwell, owner of the london daily mirror, the new tabloid features color pictures and the blue-collar standbys of sport, crime and sex
the lead headline was ``out _ no appeal for turk refugees,'' a story about the deportation of 40 turks
the principal owner of the paper is pierre peladeau, whose company quebecor inc. also produces canada's leading french-language daily, le journal de montreal
peladeau said he was prepared to invest $20 million in the tabloid in the next five years to firmly establish it in an english-language market previously monopolized by the serious-toned broadsheet montreal gazette, circulation 196,000
the daily news is the gazette's first direct competitor since the montreal star folded in 1979. canada's second-biggest city is also served by the french dailies la presse, le devoir and le matin
the gazette launched a new sunday edition feb. 28, but daily news publisher george maclaren said, ``we're not publishing on sunday. if the advertisers want to try us, they'll try us anyway.''
the new paper has an editorial staff of 76, many of whom sipped champagne as the first issue ran off the presses
we're starting from scratch, and just about everybody is under 30,'' said business reporter pierre goad, 26
cbs seems to have reclaimed the top spot in the news nielsens as the glow of the winter olympics wears off abc
for the week ending march 11, the ``cbs evening news'' had an average rating of 11.1 and a 21 share, its second win in a row. abc's ``world news tonight'' had a 10.2 and a 19 share. ``nbc nightly news'' had a 9.4 and 18 share
the rating is the percentage of the nation's 88.6 million households with televisions. the share is a percentage of sets in use
after a lengthy reign at the top of the news ratings last summer, nbc is now struggling in third, although the close ratings make the news race virtually a three-way tie
we're in the middle of a big investigation,'' said nbc analyst gerald jaffe. he said the network is awaiting more information from nielsen on the february sweeps before deciding whether the slide is a result of nielsen's new people-meter sample or a real decline in viewership
jaffe pointed out that results from the november sweeps showed nbc with a distinct disadvantage in local news lead-in. nbc affiliates had an average rating of 11.5, which ``nightly news'' improved on, to 11.9
cbs had the best advantage. its affiliates had an average rating of 12.9, and the network newscast improved on that to 13.1. abc affiliates averaged a 12.0 rating and the network broadcast was a 12.3
network news is an island in a sea of local news,'' said jaffe. ``if the local news is going down, there's not much you can do to keep the network news from going down, too.''
if the winter olympics helped abc to first in news, nbc can look forward to potentially the same boost when it carries the summer olympics
soviet foreign minister eduard a. shervardnadze will visit washington on march 20-23 to continue preparations for a superpower summit meeting, the soviet union said tuesday
shevardnadze's trip is part of a series of meetings with secretary of state george p. shultz to iron out differences on an agreement to cut the superpowers' long-range nuclear missiles by 50 percent and discuss other disagreements between the superpowers
at the end of shultz's visit to moscow on feb. 22, he told a news conference that shevardnadze would travel to washington on march 22-23. there was no immediate explanation why two days had been added to shevardnadze's visit
shultz said he and shevardnadze directed their arms negotiators in geneva to draft verification and other key parts of a treaty on strategic weapons by the time of shevardnadze's visit
he said is was ``extremely important'' to speed up work on the treaty if it is to be signed by soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev and president reagan during an expected summit meeting in moscow in late may or early june
gennady i. gerasimov, head of the soviet foreign ministry's information department, told a news briefing tuesday that shevardnadze will meet with reagan and hold several sessions with shultz
the soviet news agency tass said friday that u.s. assistant secretary of state richard murphy made no progress in talks with shevardnadze on the middle east conflict, and that the two sides had agreed to continue the discussion during shevardnadze's visit to washington
the white house, pushing for new aid to the nicaraguan rebels, told congressional leaders today the sandinista regime appears to be preparing ``an all-out death blow'' against the contras, spokesman marlin fitzwater said
describing a lengthy meeting in which president reagan discussed the possibility of a new contra aid package with lawmakers, spokesman marlin fitzwater quoted national security adviser colin powell as saying: ``the resistance program is on the verge of collapse. it's only a matter of weeks.''
fitzwater said reagan ``asked for bipartisan support to keep the resistance from withering away and to prevent a dismantling of the infrastructure that supports the contras.''
the spokesman said that in the cabinet room meeting, ``general powell outlined the buildup of sandindista forces for an offensive in the bocay valley, and it was indicated that sandinista forces appear to be preparing to launch an all-out death blow to the contras by destroying the supplies now in major contra camps.''
there was a considerable discussion of this turn of events .. and the implication that has for the peace process,'' fitzwater said. but he stressed that no decisions were reached in the meeting about how to proceed with a humanitarian aid package
i think everyone in there agreed it was a time to look forward and to talk about how to fashion a new package, and let the fights and arguments in the past stay there,'' the spokesman said. ``there was no anger. ... everyone, i think, was intense in the sense that they think this was a time of decision for the national government.''
i think it's important to point out that everyone in that session agreed a cease fire is what we're going after and that if you get a cease fire, that relieves the tension for lethal aid and for an awful lot of other kinds of aid,'' he said. ``the important thing now is the humanitarian package that we could use to meet their human needs.''
reagan, speaking to the prime ministers club earlier, accused the sandinistas of practicing religious oppression, particularly against jews. he said president daniel ortega's government had aligned itself with libya, cuba and the palestine liberation organization
house speaker jim wright, d-texas, talking to reporters following today's meeting reagan, reiterated that he would be willing to reconsider a $30 million humanitarian aid package that was defeated 216-208 in the house on march 3
we told the president that we had worked very diligently, democrats and republicans, to put together a package'' which was defeated, wright said. ``we would be glad to run it again if they (the house republicans) would be of a mind to vote for it.''
wright said it would be virtually impossible to suspend house rules to get a vote on a new package this week, as the administration wants
and one congressional supporter of renewed contra aid, sen. david boren, d-okla., said an aid package he has been working on was ``on hold'' for the moment while aid backers look for a way to get agreement in the house, always the most problematic hurdle on the contra issue
reagan, appearing before the prime ministers club, a group of approximately 150 supporters of the united jewish appeal, said that among other reasons the united states should support the contra rebels is the oppression of jews in nicaragua
few regimes today so blatantly sanction and practice official anti-semitism as the sandinista communists in nicaragua,'' reagan said. ``the jewish community has been forced out almost entirely. managua's one synagogue has been defaced and firebombed. ... ''
nicaragua has officially aligned itself with moammar gadhafi,'' he said, ``and, of course, the plo _ an organization that has again revealed its true colors, opposing our efforts for peace and trumpeting its responsibility for a sickening terrorist attack on a bus carrying israeli men, woman and children.''
reagan said the sandinistas ``have led the way in sponsoring anti-israel resolutions in united nations. so i think it's time that some in congress who want to turn away from the reality of left-wing anti-semitism face the facts about the anti-semitism of the sandinistas as well as their ties to the plo and other terrorist groups.''
it is the nicaraguan freedom fighters who are resisting this kind of moral corruption,'' he said. ``it is the freedom fighters who are fighting for the political, civil and human rights of jews and christians in nicaragua.''
the rebels and the sandinista government have agreed to sit down and talk about their 7-year-old civil war on march 21-23 in the town of sapoa, nicaragua, 90 miles south of managua near the costa rican border
adolfo calero, a political director of the umbrella opposition group the nicaraguan resistance, is expected to represent the rebels, and defense minister humberto ortega, brother of nicaraguan president daniel ortega, is to represent the leftist sandinista government
nicaraguan cardinal miguel obando y bravo, who was removed as mediator for the talks, will attend as a witness, along with joao baena soares, secretary general of the organization of american states
a severe dollar shortage forced the cuban government to ask western creditor nations earlier this year to reschedule its foreign debt over 15 years, including a five-year grace period, according to an official document made public tuesday
cuba's inability to meet it debt repayment obligations was blamed on ``extremely adverse external factors,'' the report by the cuban national bank said
the study was obtained by freedom house, a conservative human rights group, and copies were distributed at a news conference
the authenticity of the report could not be verified independently but it was similar in style and content to a study by the same bank several years ago which also was made available in washington. at the time, the cuban government acknowledged that the report was an official document
there has been no report of the outcome of cuba's request for debt rescheduling, but manuel sanchez perez, a former deputy minister of trade in cuba who defected in 1985, told the news conference the appeal was unsuccessful
sanchez said that cuba's dollar shortages stem partly from the decline in the world market price of oil
under a special arrangement with the soviet union, the kremlin sells oil on the open market and sends the earnings to cuba
sanchez said these revenues reached a high of $584 million in 1984 but dropped to $284 million in 1986, the last year for which figures are available
disputing the report's claim that external factors are unfavorable for cuba, sanchez said cuba's situation is ``exceptionally good'' compared with other countries because of soviet generosity
in addition to the oil sales bonus, sanchez said the soviets pay four times the world market price for cuban sugar. this subsidy amounted to $22 billion between 1975 and 1985, he said
sanchez listed cuba's debt to western creditors at $5.5 billion. most of that money is owed to spain, france, britain, west germany and japan, he said
the report was prepared for a january meeting of cuba's creditors in paris. it described 1987 as ``one of the worst years'' for cuba because of the combined impact of adverse weather conditions, the sustained slide of the dollar and ``the dramatic decrease in imports from the freely convertible currency area.''
it said a number of industries dependent on these imports suffered ``diminished performance'' as a result. ``spitfire,'' not the broadway show; note language of 5th graf</note>
when katharine hepburn was starring in the 1934 film ``spitfire,'' her mother was getting plenty of her own attention as a ``spitfire'' for her outspoken support of birth control for women
today, the 79-year-old miss hepburn, with her family's characteristic wit and keen intelligence, has taken on her mother's cause and become one of planned parenthood's staunchest advocates
in a tribute monday night, entitled ``celebrating two generations of individual courage,'' the actress and her late mother, katharine houghton hepburn, were honored by planned parenthood for their efforts to gain greater reproductive rights for women
it's a frightfully important subject,'' the actress told the 1,100 guests gathered at the waldorf-astoria for the black-tie event
and i'm damn lucky to have had a mother who waked me up at an early age.''
tickets for the gala were priced from $500 to $1,000, with proceeds going to planned parenthood dedicated to the actress' three priorities: keeping abortion safe and legal, preventing teen pregnancies and preserving family planning for the poor
former tv anchorman walter cronkite, tennis champion martina navratilova, tv journalist barbara walters and actor robert lindsay, star of the broadway musical ``me and my girl,'' were among the participants
as guests arrived, they encountered a small protest by the stop planned parenthood organization
guests rose to their feet and applauded as miss hepburn, elegantly attired in a black pantsuit, approached the podium
it's so touching to me, i can hardly begin to say what i have to say,'' she said. but she had much to say
when a girl becomes pregnant, should she be forced by law to have this baby? she's 13. she doesn't want it. she can't support it. her family doesn't want it. it would seem to me that she should be allowed to have an abortion.''
by the same token, if an older woman with several children gets pregnant and feels that she can't support it or care for another child, i cannot for the life of me see that anyone but this woman has the right to decide what she's going to do,'' miss hepburn said
it's certainly much harder to be a woman than it is to be a man,'' she lamented. ``but men got here first and arranged everything to suit themselves. and it's taking women a long time to ... try to catch up.''
miss hepburn became involved with planned parenthood in 1981. the group's president, faye wattleton, said she recruited her because she was ``someone who really had the public's respect.'' her participation in the organization has brought an additional 200,000 donors and supporters
it was only after the actress agreed to work for planned parenthood that, ms. wattleton said, she learned ``serendipitously'' that miss hepburn's mother had been an outspoken advocate of birth control at a time when it was illegal
mrs. hepburn worked alongside planned parenthood founder margaret sanger more than 70 years ago
a member of the houghton family that founded corning glass, she testified before the u.s. senate in the 1930s on the need for birth control, particularly for poor women
women want children but they want children they can properly take care of,'' she testified. she died in 1951 at age 73. background.</note>
george bush bid tuesday for an illinois primary victory that would doom the republican presidential campaign of sen. bob dole. sen. paul simon dueled jesse jackson in a battle of democratic favorite sons that made third place attractive to their rivals
in the first industrial state to vote, massachusetts gov. michael dukakis sought to leave sen. albert gore jr. and rep. richard gephardt far behind
the illinois primaries included presidential straw polls and separate elections of delegates to the nominating conventions next summer
bush, winner of 16 out of 17 super tuesday contests last week, led dole by huge margins in the pre-election polls in the land of lincoln. he looked for his first primary win on midwestern soil, and an increase in his seemingly insurmountable lead in convention delegates
kansas sen. dole spent the day campaigning in wisconsin and connecticut in a demonstration of his determination to stay the course _ even though he had speculated about withdrawing if he suffered another big defeat. he said he hoped to win 40 percent of the delegates at stake during the day
pat robertson, the former television evangelist campaigning as a conservative alternative to bush, said he might quit if he failed to pick up 5 percent of the vote. ``i'm not don quixote and i'm not going to tilt against windmills,'' he said
simon was rated the slight favorite on the democratic side as he sought a victory he said was essential to sustain his candidacy. he campaigned as the man to represent illinois at the bargaining table of what he said would be a brokered democratic national convention in atlanta
but pre-election polls suggested jackson's popularity among black voters could propel him to his first industrial-state victory, and the chicago-based civil rights activist forecast a ``significant breakthrough.'' he voted at a south side church in chicago
dukakis used a combination of personal campaigning and $250,000 worth of television ads in an appeal to simon supporters to reject simon's strategy of forcing a brokered nomination
dukakis' aides said they would be pleased if that made jackson the winner, since a simon withdrawal would eliminate a rival for white, liberal support in the next states to vote. michigan, connecticut, wisconsin, new york and pennsylvania all follow next weekend's kansas caucuses
simon cast a primary-day ballot in makanda in southern illinois and said, ``we have to win both'' the popular vote and the delegate contest to stay alive in the race. he said he would do both, and spokesman terry michael predicted the illinois senator would pick up 135 of the 173 national convention delegates at stake
dukakis was locked in a close race nationally with jackson for national delegate superiority and hoped to establish position over the field for the michigan caucuses on march 26. dukakis' campaign said he has a reserve of some 100 delegates won in caucuses in other states that have been held but have not yet been counted
going into illinois, dukakis had 462.5 of the 2,082 needed to win the nomination. jackson had 423.55, gore 352.8, gephardt 145 and simon 35.5
republicans elected 82 of their 92-member delegation tuesday. democrats picked 113, with an additional 60 to be allocated later at a state convention on the basis of the evening's results
bush began the day the prohibitive leader in the delegate competition on the republican side with 705 of the 1,139 needed to clinch the nomination. dole had 165, while robertson had 17
illinois' separate delegate elections looked like an easier contest for simon, although jackson was expected to virtually sweep the competition in the predominantly black congressional districts in chicago
most of simon's delegate candidates were well-known figures locally, and they urged him not to drop out of the race after earlier primary disappointments, at least partly so they could have a chance at attending the democratic national convention in atlanta this summer
thus ended the campaign in the first of the industrial states to vote, a battle that seemed as clear-cut on the republican side as it was complicated for the democrats
bush campaigned like the prohibitive front-runner that he was after his super tuesday rout, in which he won all 16 primary elections and lost nly a caucus state _ washington _ to robertson. he ignored dole's repeated demands for a lincoln-douglas-style debate without moderators and began tailoring his campaign to the independent voters and potential democratic converts likely to hold the balance of power in the fall election campaign
he seemed to be gently trying to nudge dole out of the race, declaring, ``i'm not sure i understand what he's doing.''
i've made a judgment that illinois, whatever happens, we're going to keep going,'' dole said at a news conference on monday. but he conceded candidates sometimes fail to understand when it is time to get out
now if you're out there and you've been twisting in the wind for six or eight months and you're starting to smell a little, somebody has to cut the rope,'' he said
nonetheless, his campaign was looking ahead to april 5, releasing this to the political hotline:
on wisconsin, on wisconsin, grand old badger state,
we thy loyal sons and daughters hail thee good and great
...on wisconsin, on wisconsin, fight on for her fame,
fight, fellows, fight fight fight
we'll win this game.''
robertson vowed to stay in the gop race until the convention in new orleans as ``a champion of conservatives.'' but he also said a finish of less than 5 percent likely would force him to reassess his vow
bush's illinois supporters ranged from gov. jim thompson to edward vrdolyak, once the democratic kingpin of chicago's cook county but now a republican. and bush spent $400,000 in television advertising to boost his vote
dole called illinois a ``recovery state'' after his super tuesday debacle and paid a memorable visit to the hospital where he recovered from crippling world war ii wounds 40 years ago to underscore his point
but he conceded, ``we're hanging by our fingernails'' and he staggered through the week. he laid off more than half his staff, canceled television advertisements and was reported by aides to have discussed quitting the campaign even before illinois voted
he decided to remain a candidate and gambled on a 30-minute paid television broadcast saturday night _ only to fall victim to a power failure that interrupted his statewide appeal in mid-sentence
the democratic race was fittingly byzantine in the land where local politics is a year-round sport
simon was attempting a tough campaign restart _ without funds for advertising _ after sitting out the 21 super tuesday contests. he urged his home state voters not to desert him in his hour of need, and said he wanted to represent them at a brokered convention this summer
but dukakis responded that a brokered convention would be a ``disaster'' for the democrats and plowed $250,000 into television advertising in a bid to whittle away at simon's support
jackson, who won five super tuesday states and followed up on saturday with a victory in the south carolina caucuses, said a victory in illinois would be a breakthrough _ his first in an industrial battleground
gore came to illinois hoping to ride the crest of a super tuesday-generated wave, but it failed to show up in the pre-election polls. he spent an estimated $200,000 to $300,000 on television advertising in search of a place to ``punch through'' in his battle to compete with dukakis
gephardt, the candidate with political momentum only five weeks ago when he won the iowa caucuses, gave short shrift top illinois. aides said he was conserving his cash and his energy for a last stand in the michigan caucuses on march 26
students at the university of akron are aiming for a breakthrough that has eluded some of the best minds in government and the professions: a tax form that can be understood without a college education
we know it can be done and we're going to prove it,'' professor nicholas j. creme, director of the center for taxation studies in the university's law school, said in an interview tuesday. ``we're not saying we could bring it down to a second-grade level, but we certainly can make it simpler
if you simplify the forms, people will be a lot less hostile toward the internal revenue service,'' he said. ``and you'll raise a lot more revenue.''
creme said about 20 students majoring in law, business or education will be put to work on the project. testifying before a senate finance subcommittee monday, some of the students and their leaders promised chairman david pryor, d-ark., that most of the work will be done by september
the students got interested after seeing estimates that nine of 10 people with less than a high school education cannot understand the instructions for the simplest tax form _ the one-page 1040ez. that study also determined that it takes less reading skill to get through a typical issue of the wall street journal than through a tax form
the reasons for the complexity are simple, say creme and professor james w. childs, director of the university's tax clinic. ``the average sentence length of these (irs) publications exceeds 25 words ... one-third of the words in these publications are multi-syllabled words.''
by reducing the number of syllables and the number of words in a sentence we can the forms and instructions significantly more readable,'' said creme. ``and we want to change how the forms look _ change the spacing so things don't look so crammed in.''
it is not just college students or even high school dropouts who are having trouble with tax forms. even tax professionals shake their heads at some instructions that were prompted by some of the more complex provisions in the 1986 tax overhaul
this sentence, for example, is in the instructions for form 8598, which up to 1 million taxpayers will have to file this year to calculate their mortgage-interest deduction:
if you received monthly statements that show either the closing balance or the average balance for the month, you may determine your average balance by taking the average of either the closing balances or average monthly balances shown on your monthly statement.''
creme said participants hope to develop more-readable versions of the w-4 withholding form; w-2 year-end wages-earned statement; 1099 interest-earned form and the basic 1040, 1040a and 1040ez forms
irs forms are developed in consultation with lawyers, accountants and educators. in changing its forms last year to reflect the new tax law, the irs hired a consultant and even went to some shopping malls for instant reaction from random taxpayers
irs spokesman steve pyrek, who helped develop the 1040ez several years ago, says that form is written to an eighth-grade reading level. that does not mean, however, that a typical student in the eighth grade could understand it, he said
it means a grownup that understands certain concepts can understand the form,'' pyrek said. ``a fourth grader doesn't understand the concept of taxation, for example, although a 40-year-old with a fourth-grade education who has been on the job for 20 years probably does.''
the irs concedes that many taxpayers find taxes puzzling. the agency's own statistics show that 46 percent of taxpayers paid professionals to fill out their returns last year
nevertheless, the irs contends that the forms and instructions are about as simple as they can be to reflect a complicated tax law
creme, a tax lawyer for 20 years, said the irs has nothing to lose by making its forms more understandable. ``when people can't figure out the right answer,'' he said, ``they will take the answer that gives them the best break.'' to rephrase 2nd graf, deleting reference to `alleged sex life'; picks up 2nd graf</note>
a witness for the prosecution at gov. evan mecham's impeachment trial said that a defense lawyer tried to intimidate him with obscene language shortly before he testified, according to an affidavit released today by prosecutors
prosecutor william french, replying to defense accusations that witnesses were being intimidated, released an affidavit saying that defense attorney fred craft had himself berated a witness and made accusations about the sex life of the governor's chief accuser
craft accused state department of public safety of ``a consistent pattern of an abuse by the police power'' by intimidating witnesses. ``we are afraid in this state today because we've got a runaway police state.''
but french contended that a defense move to dismiss an obstruction of justice charge was a ``smokescreen'' put up because the governor cannot disprove it
the impeachment allegations against mecham, a first-term republican, include that he tried to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by then-state prison construction chief lee watkins against a former state official, donna carlson
peggy griffith testified last week that watkins, a mecham confidant, told her that if ms. carlson did not keep her mouth shut about an unreported mecham campaign loan she might ``go on a long boat ride'' and come to harm
it has become apparent that there is no defense'' to the charge that mecham tried to obstruct the probe, french said today
the senate voted to take under advisement a defense motion to either dismiss the obstruction charge or declare a mistrial. a decision is expected wednesday
the house panel overseeing the prosecution released an affidavit from state official antonio corio, who said craft made statements about the alleged sex life of department of public safety director ralph milstead
milstead has testified mecham ordered him not to cooperate with the death threat probe, while corio testified friday that he had been asked to search for listening devices in the governor's office and found none
craft claimed that corio changed his planned testimony after being seen with milstead, but corio's affidavit said, ``i contacted dps on my own. i have not been tampered with by dps.''
corio's affidavit said craft used obscene language on friday in saying he did not have time to deal with him
according to corio's affidavit, craft also said to corio that milstead has sex with ``the widows of fallen officers to console them.''
corio also claimed that craft said that milstead made dps bureau chiefs put on his uniform so they could have sex with him. the affadivit did not specify the gender of the bureau chiefs alleged involved, and it also did not indicate whether the conversation was tape-recorded or how he remembered the quotes
milstead is in israel for an anti-terrorism seminar, but dps spokesman sgt. allan schmidt called the alleged statements ``disgusting.'' asked for further comment, he said, ``you can't print it.''
craft indicated in arguments before the senate that he had seen the document, but he did not say whether he made the statements or not
on monday, a former cabinet member and mecham confidante testified that a key prosecution witness lied about the alleged death threat
max hawkins, who was fired as state department of administration director by acting gov. rose mofford, told the senate that griffith's public statements and testimony about the alleged threat were ``substantially different'' from what she told him in november
i think peggy really detested lee watkins,'' hawkins, a onetime mecham campaign chairman, testified. ``i think she really had it in for lee watkins,'' possibly because he had said bad things about her friend ms. carlson before
hawkins repeatedly told the senate that he did not consider the alleged threat to be a serious matter. he said the story told to him by mrs. griffith was similar to what watkins told him: ``people are excitable out there on both sides and she (ms. carlson) could end up getting hurt.''
hawkins said he did not remember mrs. griffith telling him anything about watkins saying ms. carlson could get killed or go on a ``long boat ride.''
sen. carolyn walker, a democrat, chided hawkins, saying, ``you hear a threat and you don't have the intelligence to discern a threat?''
the defense has accused the department of public safety of trying to intimidate terri fields, a defense witness who testified she did not believe a death threat was made
ms. fields, who is mrs. griffith's secretary, was arrested friday night on a january warrant accusing her of not attending court-ordered alcoholics anonymous meetings required after a drunken driving arrest
the dps has denied attempting to intimidate any witness, but the fbi began a preliminary investigation monday into the allegation
mecham, who was impeached by the house on feb. 5, also is accused of concealing the $350,000 campaign loan and misusing $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership
he is the first u.s. governor to be impeached in six decades. a two-thirds vote of the 30-member senate is required to convict him
mecham faces an april 21 criminal trial on charges of concealing the $350,000 loan, and a may 17 recall election
buzzard spotters got a welcome sign of spring despite today's 20-degree temperatures when two birds drifted into a park, officially marking their annual return to hinckley
it stopped snowing for a brief moment there, for 20 minutes, and the sun came out and the birds came drifting in,'' said ralph woinset, a ranger at hinckley reservation. ``capt. roger lutz called in the official sighting at 12:02 p.m.''
they probably would have been in earlier if it hadn't been snowing, but they have trouble negotiating the snow. by sunday, there should be quite a few of them in for the crowd,'' woinset said
a flock of the large, long-necked black birds supposedly returns to its northern home at the park's buzzard roost each year on march 15. the annual buzzard search began in 1957 in an attempt to verify the legend that the birds return on the same day each year
lutz, a cleveland metroparks ranger captain, agreed that the annual buzzard news tends to ``build on the tradition,'' but he discounted the possibility that the buzzards stay in hinckley through the winter months
there's a flock of about 75 to 80 that stay in the hinckley area during the year. we believe they fly to dade county, fla., during the winter ... though it's difficult to verify,'' he said
according to local legend, buzzards were drawn to hinckley in 1819 because of tons of decaying game killed in the great hinckley varmint hunt
on dec. 24, 1818, 475 men and boys attempted to rid the 25-square mile community of predatory animals that had been attacking farm stock. the carcasses froze during the winter and thawed in the spring, attracting the buzzards
elisabeth zinser, whose brief appointment as president of gallaudet university triggered vehement protests by deaf people nationwide, said she wasn't bitter about her resignation
i'm sad that i'm not going to be able to become a part of that community, but i was privileged to be invited to be the president,'' zinser, who stepped down as head of the nation's only liberal arts college for the hearing impaired after less than a week last friday, told the charlotte observer
she's privileged, too, she said, that she ``had become a key figure in the playing out of this civil rights movement for deaf people. i thought, well, this was a short presidency, but maybe i've accomplished as much as if i had been there for years.''
zinser, who is vice chancellor for academics at the university of north carolina at greensboro, n.c., hasn't relinquinshed her ambitions
i know that i will be a president some day, but it has to be a special place. i'm not interested in just throwing my resume all over the country and being a president just to be a president.''
the news from lake wobegon was good tuesday: garrison keillor is bringing back ``a prairie home companion'' for a ``second annual farewell performance'' at radio city music hall
it was so much fun leaving that we're coming back to say goodbye again,'' keillor said in announcing he would take to the stage june 3 and 4
keillor's weekly show featuring the fictional minnesota town of lake wobegon had been on the air for 13 years when he called it quits last june 13
the reunion show will feature butch thompson, the pianist who was a fixture on the original show. it also will include guitarists chet atkins and leo kottke, the everly brothers, singers robin and linda williams and the 1920s sound of vince giordano and the nighthawks
austrian church officials gave nobel peace prize laureate mother teresa a check for more than $250,000 tuesday for her work on behalf of the poor
the check was handed to her by catholic prelate adalbert holenstein, head of a church charity organization in voralberg, austria's westernmost province
''it's the first time that i have received such a large sum from private donations,'' mother teresa told reporters
while in austria, she is scheduled to address a world peace day assembly organized by the united nations here
audrey hepburn, recently appointed a unicef special ambassador, arrived here tuesday for a tour of the country's drought-stricken regions
unicef officials said the actress will visit relief and rehabilitation centers in the hardest-hit northern provinces of tigre and eritrea. hepburn also is scheduled to visit development projects in central shoa province on her three-day visit
crop failures last year threaten 7 million people with famine in northern ethiopia, where rebels fighting the nation's marxist government have hampered relief efforts
former u.s. president carter arrived here tuesday on the third and final leg of an african tour to promote his international environmental organization, global 2000
carter and his wife, who visited ghana and nigeria earlier this week, is scheduled to attend a conference of the nairobi-based u.n. environmental program and talk with kenyan president daniel arap moi
in west africa, carter visited projects sponsored by his non-profit institution based in atlanta
carolyn chute, whose novel about a life of rual poverty, ``the beans of egypt, maine,'' won literary accalim four years ago, promises here second novel will have a happy ending
chute, 40, says the new book, ``letourneau's used auto parts,'' is about the plight of people who cannot afford to live in their own hometowns. the book, her second novel, will be released in may, she said
a jury awarded the estate of a prematurely born boy who lived only 24 hours $75,000 for pain and suffering after he received allegedly negligent treatment from a city ambulance crew
the six-member jury also awarded $350,000 to the child's mother, marlene canty
the jury had ruled jan. 15 that the baby was conscious enough to experience pain and suffering, but city lawyers argued that the finding was medically impossible and said they would appeal
manhattan supreme court justice kenneth shorter refused on feb. 29 to overturn the verdict, the daily news said tuesday
mrs. canty, then 21, went into labor in her home two months early on april 24, 1975. her husband, winslow, called the emergency medical service at least once, possibly three times, according to conflicting accounts
the baby, still in its amniotic sac and moving one appendage, ``lay between the mother's thighs visible to her during the alleged 45-minute delay and negligent treatment ...,'' the judge wrote in his decision
mrs. canty said the ems technician who finally arrived told her the baby was dead and refused to open the sac
finally i asked her (the technician) if the baby was a boy or a girl,'' mrs. canty said. ``at that point she took a small instrument and slit open the sac. ... she lifted one leg, saw the gender of the baby, threw the leg down and said the baby was a boy. ... she then picked up the baby, wrapped the baby in the plastic and threw the baby'' into a cardboard box
mrs. canty and the baby were taken to harlem hospital, where the infant lived for 24 hours on a respirator
the palatial home within the houston astrodome is making way for sports fans
roy hofheinz, former mayor, county judge and prime mover behind construction of the stadium, built the six-story apartment, including a barber shop, game room, bowling alley, putting greens and a shooting gallery, not to mention a superb view of the playing field
hofheinz died in 1982, and had not lived in his stadium home since 1975. much of it already has been converted to viewing areas and special viewing boxes. this week the rest will be torn down, and will become part of a new 15,000-seat area
in hofheinz's master bedroom and drawing room, there are 30-foot ceilings, gold-plated fixtures, handcarved woodwork and a bathroom with sunken tub and sauna
a slanting floor in the tipsy tavern gives guests a feeling being so before they take a drink. in the apartment's chapel, changeable windows offered worshipers their choice of a cross, a star of david or a buddhist symbol
hofheinz lived in the apartment off and on from 1965, when the astrodome was built, to 1975. he died at age 70
only one man has lived longer on florida's death row than willie jasper darden
howard v. douglas, who turns 52 on march 30, has been on death row since dec. 4, 1973. darden was sentenced to death seven weeks later and was executed tuesday
douglas was convicted of killing his ex-lover's husband after forcing the pair to engage in a series of sex acts while he watched, court records say
former gov. bob graham signed a death warrant on douglas for july 26, 1979, but that was stayed and subsequent legal steps resulted in the case being sent back to polk county for resentencing
douglas was again sentenced to death in august 1985, and the appeal from that hearing now is with the florida supreme court, which heard oral arguments in september 1986
the court could affirm the death sentence or reduce it to life, clerk sid white said tuesday
in the original trial, the jury found douglas guilty and recommended life, but the judge imposed the death penalty based on a finding of no mitigating circumstances. in florida, jury recommendations in death cases are advisory, and the final sentencing decision is up to the judge
although douglas has been on death row for more than 14 years, his case could to drag on for years more
he would have the right to start the process all over again as far as the new sentence is concerned,'' said assistant attorney general richard martell. ``it's a new death sentence that has not been reviewed by any court, so he would have a right to take a petition to the u.s. supreme court.''
douglas was convicted of killing jesse w. atkins on july 17, 1973
atkins' body was discovered by a hunter july 21, and five days later the victim's wife reported the killing to authorities
helen atkins later testified she once had lived with douglas but returned to her husband following the birth of a baby in june 1973
mrs. atkins said she and her husband were forced to commit various sexual acts at gunpoint before douglas struck atkins with the butt of a rifle, then shot him
douglas and mrs. atkins returned later to move and cover up the body. she said went along with douglas out of fear
a homeless man who refused to help his dying brother until he was offered $1,000 finally submitted to a blood test tuesday to determine his suitability as a bone-marrow donor, blood bank officials said
randy chapman, 32, who lives on the streets and earns money by submitting to medical experiments, had initially refused to help his brother in indianapolis
if he dies, he dies,'' chapman had said. ``he's about as much a brother to me as you are.''
but he changed his mind after an anonymous indiana man who also suffers from a blood disease offered him $1,000 to take the blood test
other family members had been tested but were found unsuitable
i wasn't too proud of myself when i read in the paper what i had said. i sounded cold, but i guess all my repressed feelings came out,'' said chapman, who had not been in contact with his family in 14 years
i don't wish my brother any harm. it's just that my family only wanted me when they needed something from me. where were they when i needed them?,'' he said in an interview with the miami news
chapman submitted to the blood test tuesday at the american red cross blood bank of south florida, said spokesman chris chidley
the test will determine if randy is a suitable match for his brother, steve chapman, 38, who is dying from leukemia
if he proves suitable, randy chapman stands to gain an additional $2,000 for donating marrow, the source of blood cells
i'm glad he did it and i hope it all works out after all this trouble,'' said the ill brother, steve chapman, who is married and the father of two. ``i just wish he hadn't raised such a ruckus. there was no sense in doing that. he's a little rough around the edges, i guess.''
steve chapman was released from st. vincent's hospital in indianapolis last week after chemotherapy treatment. his disease is in remission, but he must have the marrow transplant within three to four months, his doctor says
without the transplant, he will die within two years, said dr. richard fayssoux
the philanthropist said he hopes his offer will not only save steve's life, but also help randy turn his life around
i hope it works out well for both of them,'' he told the miami news
randy said he hopes the money will enable him to give direction to an aimless life
i'm planning to do something constructive with my life, rather than destructive,'' he said. ``i'm thinking about leaving miami.''
ethnic feuding between sinhalese and minority tamils killed 10 more people tuesday, indian authorities said, bringing the two-day death toll to 17
sinhalese attackers dragged away three tamil bus passengers near tampalagama in eastern trincomalee district and hacked them to death, according to a representative of the indian high commission in colombo
an hour later in nearby gomarankadawela, tamil rebels shot and dismembered seven sinhalese, including a child, according to the indian-sri lankan joint operations command
the rebels reportedly belonged to the liberation tigers of tamil eelam, who have been fighting for a separate homeland in northern and eastern sri lanka
an indian peacekeeping force of about 50,000 came to sri lanka at the government's invitation to stem such attacks after a peace accord was signed in july
the violence has persisted, however. sri lankan and indian authorities say 98 civilians have died in trincomalee so far this month
at least 12 sinhalese villagers were killed monday in an attack by suspected tamil rebels on the village of galmetiya, according to sri lankan military officials
tamils, who are mostly hindus, make up 18 percent of sri lanka's 16 million people. they claim they are discriminated against by the majority sinhalese buddhists, who control the government and military
militant tamils have been fighting since 1983 for a separate homeland. they have rejected the indian-brokered peace accord of july, saying it fails to protect their interests
india hopes to foster peace in sri lanka, an island just off its southern tip, because an estimated 60 million tamils live in india's southern states. many sympathize with tamils in sri lanka
convicted murderer willie jasper darden went to his death tuesday proclaiming his innocence and thanking people around the world, from andrei sakharov to jesse jackson, who aided his 14-year battle to escape the electric chair
for the widow of the man he shot between the eyes, darden's execution on an unprecedented seventh death warrant offered hope, finally, for peace of mind
i think it's long overdue,'' helen turman baum said minutes after the execution about 7 a.m. at the florida state prison. ``he did it to himself. i'm just thinking right now i want some peace of mind ... it's been a long time and i'm glad it's finally over.''
mrs. baum has remarried since her husband, james c. turman, was killed sept. 8, 1973, after turman walked into their lakeland furniture store and found his wife being robbed of $15
gov. bob martinez also was unmoved about the international attention darden attracted, from death penalty opponents and people who believed his conviction was racially tainted. darden was black; turman was white
among 1,600 telephone calls monday, the majority protesting, was one from jackson, a candidate for the democratic presidential nomination. nobel peace prize winner sakharov, actress margot kidder, rock star peter gabriel, amnesty international and other human rights and religious groups also all called for a halt to darden's execution
i think justice was served today,'' martinez said later. ``this was not someone out of a choir. he was a career criminal. this was a man who had a career of violent crimes.''
it was the 18th execution in florida and 96th in the nation since the u.s. supreme court ruled in 1976 that states could again invoke capital punishment
earlier tuesday, wayne robert felde was executed in louisiana's electric chair for the 1978 murder of a police officer. it was the first time two inmates were executed the same day in the united states since aug. 28, when executions were carried out in florida, alabama and utah
darden, 54, gave a final taped interview monday with abc-tv, broadcast on ``nightline.'' he had exchanged letters with many people and had become known as the ``sage of death row'' for the poetry he wrote as he pressed his claim that he was unjustly accused and convicted
but although he had promised in the ``nightline'' interview to be ``hollering `innocent, innocent' '' as he was strapped into the electric chair, darden instead offered, without notes, a firm, evenly delivered, last denial
i was not guilty for the charge for which i was arrested, and this morning i tell you i am not guilty of the charge for which i am about to be executed,'' darden said to 30 witnesses in the death chamber
i say to my friends and supporters around the world: i love each and every one of you. your love and support has been a great comfort to me, and my struggle for justice and freedom
i go this morning with a clear conscience. i bear no guilt. i'm at peace with myself, with the world, with each of you. god bless you.''
darden winked and nodded at one of his attorneys just before the hood was put over his head, and was declared dead at 7:12 a.m. after 2,000 volts of electricity flowed through his body for two minutes. two puffs of smoke rose from his right leg where one of the electrodes was attached
on monday, the u.s. supreme court, the 11th u.s. circuit court of appeals, a federal judge and the state supreme court rejected darden's appeals on his seventh warrant. no inmate on florida's death row had ever survived more than three warrants on the same crime
before dawn tuesday, 40 people gathered in a pasture across from the prison. the protesters maintained silence until the execution took place, then began singing ``we shall overcome.''
court records say that after shooting turman, darden ordered his wife to perform oral sex on him while turman lay dying a few feet away
a neighbor, philip arnold, also identified darden during the trial. arnold, then 16, entered the store after apparently hearing the shooting and the woman's cries. he was shot three times but survived
death penalty opponents, led by amnesty international, have said darden had an alibi proving his innocence. they claim statements from a minister and a woman show darden could not have committed the murder
in sweden, about a dozen people demonstrated monday outside the u.s. embassy in stockholm. the florida catholic conference and bishops in florida had urged a halt to the execution
darden was born in snow hill, n.c., the second of four children. his conviction record dated to 1964 and included attempted rape
only howard v. douglas had been on death row longer _ by seven weeks. douglas was convicted of the july 1973 shooting death of his former lover's husband. his case is currently on appeal
richard gephardt, hoping to regain the momentum he established in long-ago iowa, waited for the democratic presidential field in michigan, site of free-for-all caucuses uncluttered by any favorite-son bias
the stakes in the march 26 caucuses were high and the campaign was already in gear as illinois voted on tuesday
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis wrapped himself in influential endorsements and sought to establish himself as the democratic front-runner
sen. albert gore jr. sought a big-state victory outside his native south. and jesse jackson looked for delegates in a state that shorted him in 1984
illinois, the first contest post-super tuesday, was destined to leave no deep imprint on the democratic race, given its two-way favorite son loyalties to jackson and paul simon. so michigan looms as the next big contest, with 138 delegates at stake
gephardt skipped over illinois and headed straight for michigan, a state that would seem tailor-made for his tough-on-trade, save-the-farms message with its $15 billion agriculture industry and import-triggered auto industry layoffs
gephardt is hoping the message saves the messenger
if we don't do well here, obviously we're not going to be able to continue in this race,'' he told michigan supporters last week
gephardt was the first to hit the airwaves with a commercial featuring his tough talk on trade sanctions, his family farm legislation and an endorsement from elderly champion rep. claude pepper of florida. ``from the farms, the factories, the neighborhoods, comes the yearning for change, and now our cause finally has a voice,'' the ad says
the united auto workers support that gephardt cornered in iowa is missing here
unlike 1984, when the union endorsed walter mondale more than a year before the balloting, labor leadership has taken a vow of neutrality. the word to the rank-and-file has been ``support the candidate of your choice.'' the 650,000 michigan members appear to have taken that word to heart: their support is fractured
former united auto workers president douglas fraser, still popular with the rank-and-file, has endorsed massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, various union locals have donated telephones to jackson's phone bank, and other union leaders have asked for management favors to arrange short-notice plant tours for gephardt
even sen. albert gore jr. plays to the labor audience here, touting scorecards issued by the national afl-cio's political action committee
i have been a friend of organized labor ... in 12 years in the house and senate,'' he said monday night in detroit
in 1984, the michigan system left jackson's delegate winnings far short of his 16 percent popular vote. detroit mayor coleman young actively opposed him and mobilized the city's black vote for mondale
this time, the jackson campaign ambushed young by quietly winning over the ministers, unionists and party activists that form the backbone of the young machine. young favors dukakis in this race, but the mayor is unable to promise the turnout mondale enjoyed
the jackson campaign plans no television, instead concentrating on ethnic radio and making sure the core constituency of black democrats knows where to go to vote, said michigan campaign chief joel ferguson. he said jackson is also getting a good reception from white voters in michigan's campus communities
the gore campaign's goals seem to be twofold: prove a southerner can do well in the rust belt and siphon away enough votes to push gephardt below the 15 percent threshold for winning delegates
for a modest investment we can take enough votes to cut gephardt out of the race,'' one gore supporter said privately
illinois sen. paul simon had one of the first michigan campaign organizations in place, but his future was uncertain
a federal agency proposed to congress on tuesday that it be allowed to offer insurance to u.s. businesses to help them stay in countries threatened with political turmoil, such as the philippines and haiti
but the proposal by the overseas private investment corp. prompted rep. don bonker, d-wash., to say: ``wouldn't that be like offering health insurance to someone who's terminally ill?''
or like fire insurance on a house that's burning,'' agreed craig a. nalen, president of opic, which wants to sell the insurance against political risks
nalen was quick to add that such policies would only be offered in consultation with the state department
we would not go forward if molotov cocktails were coming through the windows of the plant,'' he told the house foreign affairs subcommittee on economic policy, which bonker chairs
nalen explained that an insurance policy would be offered in order to prevent a company leaving a country
that could be devastating to a country that's in difficulties,'' he said
bonker offered the philippines as an example and nalen suggested haiti as another
bonker said the idea needs further exploration
in testimony prepared for the subcommittee, nalen emphasized that the purpose of the insurance would be to keep the country concerned economically stable and would be offered only in rare circumstances
it is very unlikely that private insurers would be interested in underwriting the kinds of exposures opic would be considering under this authority,'' he said
the new authority would permit the agency to offer insurance to new or existing companies
nalen said members of his staff also have been discussing agreements for insurance of u.s. firms operating in the territory of two communist governments: poland and hungary
bonker reminded him of the u.s. law that prevents economic favors to countries that limit emigration of their citizens
opic's job is to insure u.s. investors in other countries against political risks, including war, domestic violence, confiscation and the freezing of their assets. it also makes loans for investment
nalen told the subcommittee that in the last three years it had promoted $8.7 billion worth of investment in 61 countries and turned a profit of $300 million. a motive</head>
the prosecutor in robert chambers' murder trial plans to suggest during closing arguments a motive that might have led him to deliberately kill jennifer levin in central park, a source said tuesday
assistant district attorney linda fairstein said at the beginning of the 11-week trial that she would prove chambers intended to kill miss levin, 18, and that it was not an accident during rough sex as he claimed
she told the jurors that the prosecution is not required to prove motive and that the real reasons for the killing might remain forever locked in the defendant's head
other lawyers, prosecutors and defense attorneys alike, agree generally that juries like to hear a motive when they are being asked to convict someone on a charge of intentional murder
chambers, 21, is charged with second-degree murder in the strangulation death of miss levin on aug. 26, 1986. chambers, a former drug abuser and boston university dropout who has been indicted on burglary charges in another case, admits he killed miss levin but says it was an accident after she attacked him sexually and hurt him
the summations by both sides are expected to take most or all of wednesday. state supreme court justice howard bell will likely give the jurors final instructions thursday before they begin deliberations
ms. fairstein said in her opening statement that chambers' assertion that the killing was an accident was ``ludicrous.''
a source said ms. fairstein, to emphasize the beating chambers allegedly gave miss levin before he killed her, might display a large color photograph of the teen-ager before she died next to a gruesome morgue picture showing red welts and bruises on her body
the judge has said he will instruct the jury to consider every category of homicide, including two charges that carry no mandatory minimum sentence
bell said that besides the two types of second-degree murder which with chambers is charged _ intentional and ``depraved indifference'' to life _ he will tell the jury to consider first-and second-degree manslaughter, and criminally negligent homicide
during tuesday morning's court session the jurors watched chambers' vidotaped admission for a second time so the lawyers would not have to interupt their summations to replay it
the replaying of the tape had an emotional effect on stephen and ellin levin, the victim's divorced parents. when ms. levin started crying, her ex-husband hugged her and eventually escorted her out of the courtroom. they had no comment as they left. reforms</head>
members of congress on tuesday proposed to impose a series of trade sanctions on haiti unless it takes steps toward establishing what the lawmakers regard as a more democratically elected government
the group introduced legislation to revoke haiti's 7,500-ton sugar quota, which enables the caribbean nation to sell sugar at a u.s. price-support level more than three times the prevailing world price; suspends other trade preferences; and directs the united states to oppose loans to haiti by international development banks
the bill also would formally continue in force the suspension of nearly $59 million in u.s. aid for haiti, would impose an embargo on any arms shipments from the united states, and would express concern about the growing use of haiti as a transshipment point for drugs from south america
rep. benjamin gilman, r-n.y., one of the backers of the legislation, said the current haitian regime of leslie manigat was the result of ``fraudulent elections'' held in january and that the military still rules the nation
many haitian citizens, in spite of the continuing oppression which they face, continue to work for democracy in their country,'' gilman said at a news conference. ``we must support them and their cause, and we should disassociate ourselves from the murderous thugs who unlawfully usurped the rights of the haitian people.''
sen. alfonse d'amato, r-n.y., another supporter of the bill, called for the dismissal of col. jean-claude paul, the haitian military chief
d'amato drew parallels between paul and panama's military leader, gen. manuel antonio noriega. both have been indicted in the united states on drug-related charges
