a lawyer planned an appeal and the government agreed tuesday to hear more calls for clemency for the ``sharpeville six,'' a group of blacks sentenced to hang in two days
west germany and britain joined the growing international call for mercy for the five men and one woman, who were convicted of complicity in the 1984 lynching of a black township official
i am not saying that a sign of mercy will solve the problems of south africa but it might be a little signal that human feelings have not died out altogether,'' west german president richard von weizsaecker told a news coference in harare, zimbabwe, where he was on a state visit
president p.w. botha has rejected all clemency bids for the six, the goverment said tuesday. but he agreed to meet thursday with two members of the anti-apartheid progressive federal party who oppose the executions, the south african press association reported
also, the justice ministry said tuesday that further petitions for mercy would be given ``careful consideration.''
prakash diar, attorney for the six, said he would file an appeal in the rand supreme court on wednesday to seek a stay of execution
british prime minister margaret thatcher, meanwhile, said she asked britain's ambassador to pretoria to meet with botha on tuesday in another bid for clemency
the condemned are theresa ramashamola, 26; mojalefa sefatsa, 32; reid mokoena, 24; oupa diniso, 32; duma khumalo, 28; and francis mokgesi, 30
they were convicted in the september 1984 killing of black township councilor jacob dlamini in sharpeville, about 40 miles south of johannesburg
no evidence was produced that the six were among those who hacked and burned dlamini to death. they were convicted under the doctrine of ``common purpose,'' which holds they were responsible for the killing by being part of the mob that gathered outside dlamini's home with the intent to kill him
one of the progressive federal party members that botha planned to meet on thursday was helen suzman, a member of parliament who called the executions ``sheer madness'' in remarks to the body on tuesday
suzman said the executions would have have a devastating effect on international opinion
what reputation do we have in the outside world anyway?'' responded joan hunter, a member of parliament from botha's national party
an example must be set,'' mrs. hunter said. ``we can't allow these people to roam the streets and intimidate the moderate black who is only too willing to negotiate with us.''
thatcher said british ambassador robin renwick was given instructions ``to express my hope that president botha will see fit, even at this late stage, to exercise the perogative of mercy.''
von weizsaecker told reporters that the executions would contribute to the violence and tension in south africa, where the system of apartheid gives control of the country to the white minority
amnesty international, the london-based human rights organization, also urged botha to spare the six. the organization expressed shock that 164 people, only nine of them white, were hanged in south africa last year
dlamini's killing came during riots that sparked a two-year outbreak of nationwide anti-apartheid unrest that left more than 2,000 blacks dead
black activists frequently targeted black township councilors, considering them collaborators with the white-led government. the sharpeville riots were provoked by the local council's decision to raise rents
william e. belk, one of the americans held hostage in iran, will seek the republican nomination as lexington county clerk of courts in the june 14 primary
belk, 52, who declared his ambitions on monday, has been working part-time as a communications officer for the state department and is keeping busy with a company he helped found, counts rescue equipment co. in ballentine
belk was working in the u.s. embassy in tehran on nov. 4, 1979, when iranians seized the embassy and took more than 60 americans hostage. fifty-two of them were held 444 days and released on the day of president reagan's first inauguration in january 1981
belk's wife died in september 1986, and he since then has worked in the sudan, cyprus and west germany for the state department. the past two months, he has been in baghdad, iraq
he said it now is time for him to settle down
i think the lord is trying to tell me something. every time i leave one of these countries, somebody blows them up. so i will try to find my niche in the united states, hopefully in lexington county government,'' belk said
president reagan will propose an alternative when he vetoes a sweeping civil rights bill passed by congress, the white house said tuesday
the president is scheduled to act on the bill wednesday
the senate passed the bill 75-14 and the house passed it 315-98, which are margins substantially greater than the two-thirds majority needed to override a presidential veto
the measure is designed to reverse a 1984 supreme court decision that limited the reach of laws protecting women, minorities, the elderly and the disabled
the bill would require entire colleges, school systems, government agencies and private entities to comply with anti-discrifminaion laws if any program or activity within them receives federal money
the court decision limited this requirement to the specific program or activity involved
the bill is known as the grove city bill after the pennsylvania college involved in the supreme court case
noting that wednesday is the deadline for vetoing the bill, white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said that ``at the time of that presidential action we will be offering an alternative administration proposal for overturning the grove city decision.''
the president has always believed that the grove city decision was a mistake and that the non-discrimination protection decisions that were available before that decision should be restored,'' he said
as far as the congressional bill is concerned, however, he said, ``we have said all along that we would veto.''
reagan has objected to the bill on grounds that it ``dramatically expands the scope of federal jurisdiction over state and local governments and the private sector'' and ``poses a particular threat to religious liberty.''
we think we have a very positive alternative bill that overturns the grove decision and also lays out our civil rights objectives in these areas and states the very important civil rights principles that we think need to be restored in terms of preventing discrimination,'' fitzwater said
the spokesman said white house officials ``believe that if this alternative bill has enough support that it would be voted instead of an override.''
fitzwater said the bill would be different from the republican alternative that was offered and defeated in the house. he declined to elaborate
albert gore jr. launched his campaign for michigan's democratic caucuses tuesday by trumpeting the endorsement of legislative leaders and depicting the race for the presidential nomination as a decision ``whether or not the democratic party is viable in national elections from here on out.''
gore, contending he stands a better chance than his rivals of attracting independent voters, was looking beyond tuesday's illinois primary _ to michigan's statewide caucuses on march 26
in a news conference near the state capitol, gore was endorsed by the speaker of the michigan house, gary m. owen, the democratic leader in the state senate, art miller, and other state legislators
this is a battle for the future of the democratic party, a battle that will determine whether or not the democratic party is viable in national elections from here on out,'' gore said
he was addressing his familiar appeal for support from ``working men and women'' to the state's heavily unionized work force, describing himself upon arrival in michigan monday night as a ``friend of organized labor.''
gore said he would use existing trade laws to bring down unfair barriers to trade overseas. however, drawing a distinction with rival richard gephardt's retaliatory policies, gore pointed to the reagan administration as bearing most of the blame for the nation's large trade deficit
now we must acknowledge that 80 percent of the problem is with our own policies and the policies of the reagan administration,'' gore said
he pointed to his own 88 percent approval rating by the afl-cio over his career in congress and said that was particularly noteworthy since he comes from tennessee, a state without the northern states' tradition of organized labor
it is a record that's been built up in the political fires and forces of a right-to-work state,'' gore said
gore said he backed the rights of states to have such laws banning compulsory union membership
i believe in the right to organize,'' he said, but ``what decisions states make, that's for them to determine.''
gore said he hoped to ``substantially exceed expectations'' in michigan but refused to predict a victory and said no state was make-or-break for him. ``we're starting at a point where other campaigns are ahead,'' he said of michigan
gore planned to fly to kansas to campaign wednesday and thursday toward that state's democratic caucuses march 19. aides said they were considering having gore go friday to puerto rico, where delegates are selected march 28
larry harrington, a gore strategist, described the race in puerto rico as between gore and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis
gore also met privately with michigan fund-raisers and said his fund raising has improved greatly since his victories in the south last week
it was the difference between night and day before and after super tuesday,'' he said
police investigating murders blamed on mob warfare arrested 15 men in raids that began before dawn tuesday in calabria, a news agency reported
prosecutors issued 24 arrest warrants for suspects on charges of criminal association, italian news agencies reported. by late afternoon, police had served 15 of them, including three for men already in prison
the ansa news agency said that seven men were charged in two murders last year in villa san giovanni, a town on the calabrian side of the strait of messina
reggio di calabria province, the southernmost part of the italian mainland, has been bloodied by hundreds of murders linked to the 'ndrangheta mob in recent years
investigators say mobsters are fighting among themselves for control of lucrative construction and other public contracts in underdeveloped calabria, where the 'ndrangheta is the local version of the sicilian mafia
about 200 black and white christians will live and worship together this week in an unusual attempt to break down the psychological and social barriers created by apartheid
most of the participants are whites coming from across south africa to stay wednesday night through sunday in mamelodi, the main black township outside pretoria. about 35 blacks from mamelodi will stay in white homes in the capital
the encounter, culminating with a community barbecue and and a church service, will be the largest interracial get-together of its type in south africa
one of the principal organizers is the rev. nico smith, a dutch reformed minister in mamelodi since 1982. he moved there two years ago after becoming the first white permitted by the government to live in a black township
smith says relations between the races in south africa are warped by fear and estrangement
since i'm living in the black community myself, i have become aware of the almost total alienation which has developed between whites and blacks,'' said smith
apartheid was successful. it brought about what it promised to do. it separated people,'' he said. ``if people are forced to live separately they become strangers ... eventually on both sides they have certain perceptions are totally different from the real people. this eventually turns into fear of one another.''
smith and other clergymen organizing the four days of socializing, bible study and prayer have brought smaller groups of whites into mamelodi in the past. they said men and women sometimes tremble with fear as they enter a township that two years ago was wracked by violent anti-apartheid protests, political killings and factional battles
there has been some opposition to the encounter from militant groups in mamelodi who say whites should be viewed as enemies. a right-wing white group called united christian action sent letters to mamelodi's mayor and the commissioner of police asking that the meeting be banned
smith said some black hosts have expressed fears that they will be arrested if they participate
most south african blacks know how whites live because they work at white homes and businesses. few whites know first-hand how blacks live because they seldom venture into the townships located on the periphery of the cities
one of the delegates, eddie prest, said he has had blacks in his house near cape town many times but has never visited a black home
the black culture is so set up that they don't invite people to come,'' said prest, retired director of a bible study program. ``they'll say, `why don't you just come,' and i'll say, `i've not been invited
it's just a cultural problem,'' prest said, ``and also a logistics problem. also, it's very hard for an african to have you home, because of their accommodation, their facilities.''
the number of black delegates is much lower than the whites, said baptist rev. kevin roy, because it is harder for blacks to take two or three days off work. the main goal, he said, is to expose whites to the black lifestyle, encourage them to think about positive action to change the apartheid system, and take their knowledge back to their communities
maybe for four days we will treat them (the white visitors) as blacks. they will start seeing things from the way we look at things, not the way they are used to looking at things,'' said dan ramakgadi, a field worker for koinonia, one of the organizing church groups. discouraged</head>
federal reserve board chairman alan greenspan told congress on tuesday that foreign investors make ``good corporate citizens'' and should not be discouraged from buying more u.s. assets
despite statistics showing the united state widening its lead as the world's largest debtor nation, greenspan said he had ``very little concern about the issue of direct foreign investment.''
we will find that foreign investment in the united states will be a plus,'' even at present record levels, greenspan told the house-senate joint economic committee
greenspan also suggested that a recession is unlikely throughout the next year. he cited recent positive economic statistics, including an unemployment rate that fell to 5.7 percent in february, its lowest level in almost nine years
he said the rate could drop further, probably somewhere between half a percentage point and a full percentage point, before triggering an increase in inflation
greenspan said foreign investments flowing into this country now from japan and from europe are a direct consequence of the large sums of money the united states spent in those areas in the aftermath of world war ii
he testified as the commerce department reported that the u.s. current account deficit _ the broadest measure of foreign trade _ surged to a record $160.7 billion in 1987. the figures add trade in services and investment flows to other export and import numbers
greenspan said direct investment in the united states by foreigners was preferable to them putting their dollars _ amassed through the trade imbalance _ into ``short term liquid holdings.''
greenspan was asked by sen. alfonse d'amato, r-n.y., whether he was troubled by the extent of the growing foreign investment in the united states, particularly by japanese companies. ``japan is buying america and leasing it back to us,'' d'amato suggested
on the contrary, the integration of the world economies ... is inevitable...and is a desirable trend,'' the fed chief said
greenspan said that foreign-owned businesses in the united states had become ``good corporate citizens in the localities in which they chose to locate.''
he noted that in terms of direct investment _ excluding government securities _ u.s. business holdings overseas remain about $50 billion above holdings by foreigners in this country
in terms of u.s. treasury securities, foreign investors held 16.4 percent of the total at the end of last year, greenspan said
greenspan also:
_urged taiwan to do more to reduce its trade surplus and bring its economic and monetary polices into equilibrium with the united states and other major trading partners
_said the british government took the ``correct action'' in not seeking to stem the recent sharp rise of the pound through heavy central-bank intervention
_praised japan for taking steps to stimulate its economy, but said that steps with a similar goal taken by west germany have not been as successful
_said the fed is keeping in close contact with the white house and the state department on the current turmoil in panama. the fed maintains an account for the government of panama in the new york federal reserve bank, greenspan said
bishop eugene a. marino, named tuesday as the first black roman catholic archbishop in the united states, said his appointment as head of the atlanta archdiocese is ``a great sign of hope to all our people.''
the appointment by pope john paul ii comes more than two years after marino and other black bishops wrote a pastoral letter calling on the church to increase the number of blacks in official positions
the church has spoken but has the church listened to itself?'' said the letter, suggesting that in the absence of a major appointment such as a black archbishop in a big city, ``the church's commitment to black leadership may be seen as half-hearted and superficial.''
the atlanta archdiocese has only 10,000 blacks among its 156,000 catholics. of 52 million catholics nationwide, 1.3 million are black
marino said he could see in his appointment ``a sign of hope to all men and women of good will that the church recognizes its wealth within its own ranks ...''
i think that this appointment is a sign of hope to all minorities that the church in general'' and the pope in particular are sensitive to the needs of blacks, marino told reporters
marino, 53, is one of 12 black bishops in the united states and has served as an auxiliary bishop in the washington, d.c., archdiocese since 1974. in 1985, he was elected secretary of the national conference of catholic bishops, the first black to hold an office in the organization. he is a member of the society of st. joseph, formed in the late 1800s to work in the black community
marino's selection was hailed by an advocacy group as an outstanding appointment
calling him ``quiet, but effective,'' walter t. hubbard, acting executive director of the national office of black catholics, said marino ``is a pastoral man and he is sensitive to the needs of lay people, especially the needs of black catholic lay people in the country
we have optimism that the church is showing us signs of being responsive to the call by black catholic lay people for black men to be elevated to positions of authority and responsibilty,'' hubbard said in a telephone interview from washington
hubbard noted that marino has represented the national conference of catholic bishops in congressional hearings, testifying about the needs of the unemployed and the homeless and for voting rights
marino said his appointment did not necessarily make him the church's spokesman on civil rights, despite atlanta's historical position in the civil rights movement
he also declined to be labeled an activist priest, saying he was ``not one to dodge issues; at the same time i am not one to go out and look for issues for issues' sake.''
marino, a native of biloxi, miss., said he hoped to be able to expand black membership in the catholic church
we (black bishops) feel that this is a good time for our sisters and brothers to come forward with their gifts to enrich the church,'' marino said
we have a rich tradition of spirituality in the african-american tradition ... but it is not a rich tradition that enriches the catholic church, unfortunately,'' he said. ``our people tend to be religious, our people tend to be spiritual, but they do not tend to be predominantly catholic and we feel that being catholic is something special.''
after meeting with some of the 200 priests in the archdiocese, marino led a noontime mass at the cathedral of christ the king before returning to washington
marino will be formally installed may 5, to succeed archbishop thomas a. donnellan, who died last oct. 15
the atlanta archdiocese covers 69 counties in north georgia and has some administrative responsibility for catholic dioceses in the rest of georgia and in north and south carolina
defense secretary frank c. carlucci met with his soviet counterpart tuesday, hoping to prod defense minister dmitri yazov into providing concrete evidence of a new soviet military doctrine
carlucci, speaking to reporters en route to meeting yazov in bern, said that despite publicity surrounding the kremlin doctrine of reasonable or defensive sufficiency, he had seen ``absolutely no practical change.''
if anything, their military continues to grow. they continue to modernize,'' carlucci said
yazov, who also arrived in bern on tuesday for the opening of the three-day session, said before he left moscow that he hoped for a ``frank, constructive discussion'' on arms control issues including strategic arms, nuclear testing, chemical and conventional weapons
carlucci emphasized that he did not want the meeting, the first business session between u.s. and soviet defense secretaries, to open a ``parallel channel'' to ongoing superpower arms negotiations in geneva
yazov and carlucci were attending a dinner by swiss defense minister arnold koller on tuesday night, and were to sit down for formal talks on wednesday and thursday
yazov and other soviet officials have said they are moving toward a new doctrine, relying on defense. but kremlin leader mikhail gorbachev, yazov, and other military and civilian commentators have offered different versions of the doctrine, puzzling western analysts
i'm still not sure what it is,'' said carlucci. ``that's a question, by the way, i intend to ask him.''
if yazov wants to prove that the kremlin is moving from an offensive to a defensive posture, said carlucci, he should seek ``a slacking off in tank production, in artillery production, maybe desisting from highly accurate follow-on systems like the ss-18'' intercontinental ballistic missile, which carries 10 nuclear warheads
u.s. negotiators have raised all those issues in the geneva talks, but it is not clear when agreements may be reached to cut strategic and conventional arsenals
carlucci said u.s. analysts were looking for unilateral soviet action to define the new kremlin doctrine
one of the most important indicators, i would think, would be tanks. but tanks continue to pour out. so there is no indication at the other end of the pipeline that there has been any change,'' said carlucci
yazov, in remarks reported from moscow by the official soviet news agency tass, said nothing about the doctrine
the goal'' of the session, he said, ``is to facilitate the search for ways of resolving the most acute and immediate issues of strategic offensive weapons and the (1972 anti-ballistic missile) treaty, reduction of the armed forces and conventional armaments in europe, termination of nuclear testing, and prohibition and elimination of chemical weapons.''
the two people whose identification and testimony sent willie jasper darden to the electric chair expressed relief tuesday that their ordeal had ended but anger that it had taken so long
i think it's long overdue,'' said helen turman baum, whose husband, jim, was shot dead in front of her in 1973. ``i need to get on with my life. ... he (darden) put me through torture. no one knows what i have suffered through his hands. ... it is torture when you see a loved one shot down in front of your eyes.''
a 16-year-old boy who came to her aid in the turmans' lakeland furniture store was shot three times but survived
justice has finally prevailed,'' phillip arnold said at the tampa asphalt company where he works. ``but it wasn't as swift and efficient as it's supposed to be.''
while death penalty opponents and darden supporters said his execution tuesday meant the judicial system had failed, the prosecutor, c. ray mcdaniel, criticized the length of the legal battles ``and the unnecessary waste of legal and judicial manpower that went into the case.''
those opponents of the death penalty simply hitched their wagon to the wrong mule,'' said mcdaniel, now a private attorney in bartow. ``i wish 10 percent of their efforts and the money spent could have gone to the victims. ... mrs. turman's life was ruined ... because of this.''
mrs. baum, 59, remarried four years ago
she was making breakfast and hurrying to take her husband, fred baum, to a doctor when she was called by a friend and told that darden had been executed. she cried a little
arnold and mrs. turman rejected recent statements by a baptist minister and a lakeland secretary, who disputed testimony about the attack. their statements provided ammunition for darden and supporters who said he had been wrongly identified as the killer
i identified him several days later (after the crime) because his face stood out to me. i know in my heart it was him,'' mrs. baum said
there's no doubt in my mind. there never has been,'' said arnold. association xxx a friend.'' ^by randolph e. schmid</note>
as summer edges over the horizon, millions of americans are contemplating exercise programs to help get into shape after a winter spent as couch potatoes; health experts also advise watcing the diet carefully
the american dietetic association has declared march to be national nutrition month, and is urging people to make good eating a personal way of life, not a dreaded prescription
we want everyone _ men, women and children of all ages _ to grasp one critical message: it's never too late to start reaping the benefits of healthy food choices,'' the association said in a statement
federal health officials, too, stress the importance of good diet, noting that food choices can be a major factor in having a healthy heart, avoiding cancer and in feeling well generally
to help, a variety of federal agencies have put together booklets which can be obtained from the consumer information center, pueblo, colo., 81009. among them are:
_ ``planning a diet for a healthy heart,'' item 521t, no charge
_ ``diet, nutrition and cancer prevention: the good news,'' item 517t, no charge
_ ``diet and the elderly,'' item 516t, no charge
_ ``food additives,'' item 518t, no charge
_ ``nutritive value of foods,'' item 119t, $2.75
_ ``some facts and myths about vitamins,'' item 523t, no charge
_ ``a word about low sodium diets,'' item 525t, no charge
generally, improving the diet should be done gradually, not all at once, says the dietetic association
set realistic goals and try to plan a diet with as much variety of food as possible
many very-low calorie diets can create potential problems by not supplying enough nutrition. in addition, while these semi-starvation diets may promote quick weight-loss, they don't promote a change in eating habits, so the weight is rapidly regained, the dietetic group points out
while many folks shy away from making sudden, major changes in their eating habits, the dietetic association says it can be simple to take small, healthful steps throughout the day
it's easy to skip breakfast in the morning rush, for example. so how about planning ahead by preparing breakfast the night before, including such foods as fruit juice, a whole-wheat bagel, yogurt or perhaps a banana
even if lunch means a business gathering, most restaurants offer dishes that are low in fat and cholesterol, such as chicken or fish or moderate portions of beef, as well as fresh steamed or raw vegetables
the association suggests ordering salad dressing on the side so you can control the amount put on the salad. if dessert is needed, consider fresh fruit or split a dessert with a friend
smart snacking doesn't mean going without, the group adds. snacks can include unsalted nuts, plain crackers, low-fat yogurt, seltzer water, fruit juice or ice water with lemon
popcorn _ leaving off the salt and butter _ also can make a good snack, as well as celery and carrot sticks or pieces of zucchini or green pepper
an irving berlin tribute on the composer's 100th birthday, may 11, will star an array of classical and popular musicians ranging from leonard bernstein to willie nelson, from isaac stern to frank sinatra
the tribute at carnegie hall will, at berlin's request, benefit the carnegie hall society and the american society of composers, authors and publishers foundation, ascap's ken sunshine announced tuesday
sunshine said the gala will be taped by cbs-tv and a broadcast date will be announced later. don mischer will be executive producer for the network
berlin is the last surviving founding member of ascap, which began at a dinner at luchow's restaurant on 14th street in manhattan in 1914. composers present, including berlin, victor herbert, jerome kern and john philip sousa, decided to form an organization to protect their copywrights
tickets to the concert and a ``top hat, white tie and tails'' dinner-dance afterwards are $1,000. tickets to the concert only are $250, $100, $75 and $50. the carnegie hall box office, taking its cue from berlin's ``easter parade,'' will start selling tickets on easter sunday. groups</head>
the senate sponsor of a $2.5 billion child care bill said tuesday he will change it to address complaints that it discriminates against religious groups who provide some of the nation's best child care
within the next week or so we are going to resolve that issue,'' said sen. christopher dodd, d-conn., sponsor of the act for better child care or abc bill. ``these concerns will be resolved to the satisfaction of all.''
the bill, which has 37 senate co-sponsors, would provide grants to nonprofit agencies to expand child care as well as money for child care certificates to working parents with incomes below a certain level
it would deny funding for ``any program or activity that has the purpose or effect of advancing or promoting a particular religion or religion generally.'' and it would cancel a civil rights act provision allowing religious institutions to hire employees on the basis of religion
john carr, an official with the u.s. catholic conference, said his group supports the goals of the abc bill and other child care legislation before congress but objects to those two provisions
we are working with the sponsors to see if the church-state problems can be resolved,'' carr, the conference's secretary for social development and world peace, said in an interview. ``much of the child care now provided is provided in churches and by religious groups, and we don't want to see an effort to broaden quality child care exclude those groups. we're quite hopeful a solution can be found.''
the abc bill was discussed at a hearing tuesday before the senate labor and human resources subcommittee on children, chaired by dodd
lawmakers across the ideological spectrum are reaching agreement that the nation needs more, better and expanded child care services to address what sen. orrin hatch called ``a bipartisan problem of families.'' the major points of contention are over how much to spend and whether states or the federal government should regulate day care
hatch, r-utah, has proposed a somewhat different and less expensive approach to the problem. he said the abc bill's price tag is prohibitive while its licensing requirements and religious provisions seem to discourage home-based care and participation by religious institutions
dodd said the bill's sponsors are ``strong supporters of home care. we just want to see minimum standards'' for day care workers, homes and centers. he said the religious problem would be worked out
the only witness against the bill was william bentley ball, a harrisburg, pa., lawyer representing the association of christian schools international, an organization of evangelical christian educational institutions including 1,000 preschools. ball said the schools on principle would not take federal money, but said parents otherwise eligible for aid should not be penalized for sending their children there
conservative activist phyllis schlafly, who opposes any federal encouragement of day care, led a protest outside the building where dodd was holding his hearing
in the february edition of her monthly newsletter, schlafly referred to the dodd bill as an attempt to ``sovietize the american family by warehousing babies in government-licensed institutions where they would be subjected to secular, unisex custodial care by government-trained personnel, while their mothers would be trapped full-time in the paid labor force.''
debra and and michael brooks of gunnison, colo., presented a different view inside the hearing room. the couple's first child was killed when his day care provider _ a woman with no training and little experience _ struck him on the head. the woman, now in prison, was ``not a stranger. i considered her a friend,'' said mrs. brooks
her husband said the experience shocked him into realizing that his government was not monitoring or regulating child care. ``i had no idea of the things that could go wrong,'' he told dodd. ``i trusted in a system that simply didn't exist.''
sen. david karnes said tuesday that he had reprimanded a member of his staff who met with palestine liberation organization leader yasser arafat
baker spring, a foreign policy assistant for the nebraska republican, met with arafat in baghdad during a trip to iraq in january. karnes said he was not aware of the meeting before it occurred. details of the two-hour meeting became public earlier this month
spring went to iraq under the sponsorship of a private group, the national council of u.s.-arab relations, and karnes said he approved the eight-day trip because it ``provided an opportunity for expanding trade with iraq.''
however, the meeting with arafat was not on the agenda, and karnes said he would not have allowed spring to go if it had been. karnes said the meeting was arranged after the group already was in iraq and that spring had no opportunity to contact him
meetings with known terrorists serve no purpose whatsoever, and should never be held,'' karnes said in a statement released from washington
karnes, named to the senate a year ago by republican gov. kay orr after the death of democratic sen. edward zorinsky, faces a may 10 primary battle against rep. hal daub. former gov. bob kerrey is favored to win the democratic nomination
wayne felde, who claimed post-vietnam war stress drove him to murder a rookie policeman, died in louisiana's electric chair tuesday after delivering a cryptic two-sentence message to those who watched him die
you can kill the messenger but you can't kill the message,'' he said slowly and matter of factly, giving three reporters separated from him by a glass window time to write down each word. ``sooner or later, you have to acknowledge it for what it means, not for what you want it to mean.''
the 38-year-old killer was then led by four guards a few steps from the microphone to the big oak electric chair. four alternating jolts of 2,400 volts and 500 volts of electricity were administered over one minute. doctors pronounced him deat at 12:14 a.m
felde died for killing officer glen tompkins in 1978, as felde was being driven to jail in shreveport. felde had been picked up on a drunkeness charge and apparently had not been throroughly searched. he pulled a gun from his clothes and shot three times through the front seat
three shreveport officers joined the few pro death penalty demonstrators who come to the remote prison each time the state schedules an execution
justice is being done tonight,'' said sgt. glenn ramsey. ``i hate it. it took 10 years.''
cpl. joe feconda, who drove tompkins' widow home from the hospital after the shooting, said he is still haunted by the memory. a third officer declined to be identified
felde was captured the night of tompkins' murder when a lawman's shotgun blast brought him down. scars from the blast could be seen on the lower right side of his chest as his body was examined in the electric chair
warden hilton butler told reporters shortly before the execution that felde did not desire or expect a last-minute stay of execution
at his 1980 trial, felde asked the jury that convicted him to recommend the death penalty, ``or other deaths will result.'' but he later helped in appeals that delayed his execution for eight years
felde had enlisted in the army at age 18 and was sent to war in 1967. the experience, he claimed, left him unable to tell right from wrong
felde's lawyers had hoped gov. buddy roemer _ who took office about 12 hours before the electrocution _ would grant felde a stay and a new pardon board hearing. but roemer, who had said last week he had no plans to delay felde's death, decided against stopping the execution after meeting late monday with bill quigley, a lawyer for felde
if you've been wondering why the u.s. space program has fizzled or why johnny can't multiply anymore, phil paeltz has an answer: the demise of the slide rule
the headmaster of the governor french academy is organizing a national slide rule museum in this southwestern illinois city as a shrine to the device, made virtually extinct by the onslaught of the pocket calculator in the early 1970s
the thing that frightens me to death is that we seemed to have gotten along a whole lot better with these than we are getting along with the computer,'' said paeltz
it was the slide rule that put together `e equals mc squared' and it was the slide rule that put together the beginning of the space program. much of what we talk about as america's pre-eminent technical position was all computed on slide rules.''
paeltz yearns for a return to pre-calculator days and thinks many schools put too much emphasis on machines
a slide rule is slower, but i wonder if it doesn't have some very beneficial things. when there is something physical as well as mental involved in a process i think people remember things better,'' paeltz said
there was only one thing the bi-state development agency could give edna schroeder to commemorate her retirement
the 73-year-old woman, who took public transportation to her downtown job for 55 years without missing a day or arriving late for work, received a lifetime bus pass in honor of her retirement last month
schroeder, who worked the whole time for norcliff thayer inc., the maker of tums, said she used to ride the street car before the bus came along. she said she never owned a car
we at bi-state take great pride in the fact that all that time you used the bus,'' said raymond jurkowski, bi-state's deputy director
schroeder said she would use the pass presented to her monday to ``ride the bus to places i've never ridden to before.''
bennion elementary school principal ken higgins has paid ``deerly'' for doubting his students' reading capabilities
the principal spent monday's lunch periods locked in a utah division of wildlife deer cage for losing a bet that students could not do 500,000 pages in outside reading. they ended up last week more than doubling that goal
after students hit an original target of 250,000 pages quickly, higgins raised the goal to 500,000 and offered a pizza party for the class that came up with the best penalty for higgins. eventually, he boosted the target to 1 million pages, a mark the students hit last week
what was really neat was everyone was into the project,'' he said
i was really nervous,'' he said about spending 90 minutes in the cage, ``but it worked out well. and the important thing was it got the kids reading.'' he spent the time chatting with students and reading to the younger students
higgins isn't done yet, however. one of the winning class suggestions was a ride in a hot air balloon. high winds monday grounded the plans, but the tire company that owns the balloon agreed to return when higgins can take the trip
the principal acknowledges a fear of heights, but has vowed to complete the agreement. ``i couldn't live with myself if i didn't do what i said i would do,'' he said
the deficit in the broadest measure of u.s. foreign trade surged to a record $160.7 billion in 1987 as america fell deeper into debt to the rest of the world, the commerce department reported tuesday
the deficit in the u.s. current account was 13.7 percent higher than the 1986 deficit of $141.4 billion and marked the fifth consecutive year that this trade deficit has hit a new record
the reagan administration has sought to downplay the significance of the trade deficits, but private economists contend that the rapid buildup of foreign debt could eventually topple the country into another recession, triggered by a plunge in the value of the dollar
the increasing indebtedness of the united states is the most insidious and potentially damaging long-run problem the country must deal with,'' said allen sinai, chief economist of the boston co
the current account is the broadest gauge of america's dealings with other countries because it measures not only the flow of merchandise across u.s. borders but also the flow of services, primarily investment earnings
for 16 of the past 17 years, the country has run deficits in the merchandise trade category. but the current account was in surplus as recently as 1981 because americans' earnings on overseas investments were enough to offset the merchandise deficits
but in this decade americans have handed over billions of dollars to foreigners in exchange for imported goods, transforming the country from the world's largest creditor to the world's largest debtor nation
that means that foreigners now own more in u.s. investments than americans hold in foreign investments. america was last a net debtor in 1914. it regained that status in 1985 with a foreign debt of $111.9 billion. that debt grew to $263.6 billion at the end of 1986
based on tuesday's current account statistics, jeff faux, president of the economic policy institute, estimated that the u.s. foreign debt now totaled $424.2 billion, more than four times the burden of the previous debt leader, brazil
treasury secretary james a. baker iii and other administration officials have argued that the country's debt status was not a cause for alarm because the debt was still a tiny fraction of the total u.s. economy
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan, testifying before congress on tuesday, said the fact that more and more u.s. assets are being acquired by japanese and other investors was a plus for the u.s. economy, providing american jobs
but private economists argue that the increase in foreign investment means that more american assets will be flowing into foreign hands in the years ahead to service the growing debt, lowering american standards of living and leaving the country increasingly vulnerable to the whims of foreign investors
the most profound and enduring legacy of the reagan period is its conversion of the united states from the largest creditor country in the world to the largest debtor,'' said c. fred bergsten, director of the institute for international economics. ``as long as the united states has to rely on foreign financing of such magnitudes, events could at literally any moment trigger a sharp turndown in our economy.''
bergsten said that america endured two such turbulent episodes in early 1987 and again in the fall when weakened foreign confidence sent the value of the dollar plunging and u.s. interest rates up sharply. the last such event has been blamed as a contributing factor in the record collapse of stock pricesd which occurred on oct. 19
the new report on the current account showed that the trade deficit actually narrowed somewhat in the final three months of the year, dropping to $39 billion, compared to record quarterly deficit of $43.4 billion in the third quarter, reflecting higher american earnings abroad because of the decline in the value of the dollar
but this improvement did little to shrink the deficit for the year, an imbalance reflecting a continued worsening in merchandise trade and a shrinking of the investment surplus
the merchandise trade deficit, on a current accounts basis, totaled $159.2 billion last year. adding to that deficit were u.s. foreign aid and other government transfer payments totaling $13.5 billion
the deficit was lowered slightly by a surplus of $12 billion in the service category. while foreigners now own more in u.s. investments, the payments still show a slight surplus in america's favor because many of the older u.s. investments are earning a higher rate of return
economists said the $12 billion surplus in 1987, down from $18.6 billion in 1986, will shrink even more in 1988 and by 1989 will drop into a deficit, further complicating the country's efforts to reduce its trade imbalance
bergsten estimated that total u.s. debt held by foreigners would rise to around $700 billion to $800 billion by 1995, requiring net interest payments of around $25 billion annually
education secretary william bennett congratulated the 50 winners of an annual national award for outstanding teen-agers tuesday and declared that ``there's no shortage of character in our young people.''
ten of the 50 recipients of the sea breeze awards, a public service project of clairol inc., were honored at a luncheon in the senate caucus room, where each received a $500 grant and a framed citation
the winners received the awards for acting ``with courage, heroism, integrity, compassion or in a spirit of public service to make their world a better place.''
the 10 recipients honored at the lunch were rochelle badger, 18, valmeyer, ill.; steven bonacorsi, 18, salem, n.h.; darla byrd, 17, rutledge, tenn.; sean t. fox, 18, winlock, wash.; jennifer gates, 16, north palm beach, fla.; rosa gonzalez, 18, castro valley, calif.; alphonso guest, 16, north little rock, ark.; michelle jones, 13, mountain home, ark.; audrey nenoff, 18, westwood, n.j., and quoc van-dong, 17, elk mound, wis
bennett said the awards honor ``excellence in character.'' he thanked each of the teens for ``helping us believe in the spiritual wealth of the world.''
whatever your circumstances in life, you'll have opportunities to show what you're made of, where your heart is,'' he said
high-altitude ozone, which protects humans from skin cancer, shows an unexplained thinning of about 2.3 percent since 1969 over mid-latitudes of the northern hemisphere _ an area that includes most of the united states, scientists said tuesday
the decline, which is at least twice as large in winter at high latitudes, was almost certainly the result of human use of ozone-destroying chemicals, the researchers said in what is believed to be the most definitive report on ozone concentrations to date
ozone, a pollutant at ground level, makes possible life on earth by blocking the harmful ultraviolet rays of the sun at high altitudes. the environmental protection agency has estimated that every 1 percent decline in ozone overhead means an eventual increase in skin cancer of 5 percent to 6 percent
satellite data from 1978 on are consistent with a similar shrinkage in the southern hemisphere, according to the report of a panel assembled by the national aeronautics and space administration
the satellite data show a similar unexplained decline in ozone around the middle of the globe in both hemispheres of about 0.5 percent to 1.8 percent from 1978 to 1987. the actual decline is larger, about 2.5 percent, but most of it results from variations in the output of the sun, the panel said
at this point there is no other culprit to blame'' but the chlorofluorocarbon compounds, said sherwood rowland of the university of california, irvine, and head of a panel subcommittee. ``we have taken out all the natural phenomena that are believed to affect ozone.''
the senate on monday approved, 83-0, a 31-nation treaty calling for 50 percent cuts by 1998 in production of chlorofluorocarbons, which are used for refrigeration fluids, cleaning solvents and foam blowing agents
since 1985, there have been several reports of ozone decline worldwide in addition to the well-established ozone ``hole'' over antarctica _ a 50 percent decline in springtime, followed by recovery
but the reports have not been widely accepted because of such problems as out-of-calibration satellite instruments or failure to account for the solar cycle
the nasa panel of more than 100 scientists, convened 17 months ago, went back to the original data, analyzing possible errors in observations, cross-checking ground and satellite observations and making particular use of ground data taken when a satellite was overhead
it particular, it tried to estimate the effect of the 11-year solar cycle, which could decrease ozone by 0.7 percent to 2.0 percent in the period in question, and the effect of the two-year cycle of upper atmosphere winds
the northern mid-latitude decline was estimated from ground-based data taken by stations mostly in the united states and europe. there are too few stations at high latitudes, in the tropics or in the southern hemisphere, the panel said
the decline reached 8 percent at the highest latitudes studied in january, averaging 6 percent in winter, and at higher northern latitudes ``limited data suggest that there has been a decrease comparable in magnitude,'' the report said
the agency's computer models predicted only a 4 percent to 5 percent peak decline, and researchers are asking, ``can we believe our models?'' said robert watson, nasa's chairman of the ozone panel
estimated average year-round ozone declines from 1969 through 1986 were reported from ground-based data for three bands in the northern hemisphere: latitude 30 degrees (about the latitude of houston, texas, cairo and shanghai) to 40 degrees (philadelphia and madrid), down 1.7 percent; 40 degrees to 53 degrees (edmonton, alberta, and berlin), down 3.0 percent; and 53 degrees to 64 degrees (fairbanks, alaska, and reykjavik, iceland), down 2.3 percent
no estimate was presented for all three bands as a whole, but rowland said the simple mean average of the three, a 2.3 percent decline, would be close
each estimate contains a margin of error of about one percentage point
the satellite data were presented similarly, with a decline of 2.5 percent before corrections for solar and other fluctuations estimated for the band between 53 degrees north and 53 degrees south (about punta arenas, chile). this band covers all of the inhabited southern hemisphere
the antarctic hole is so pronounced that scientists now think of it as a year-round phenomenon because of its effects elsewhere. no one knows whether a similar ``hole'' could develop over the north pole
watson said planned high-altitude research flights over the arctic next winter will be ``absolutely essential'' in deciding whether to accelerate or change the cuts called for under the chlorofluorocarbons treaty
declining to make policy recommendations, watson said, ``a fully implemented ... treaty can do absolutely nothing to remove the ozone hole over antarctica,'' which scientists earlier had estimated could last 100 years
about 450 gallons of highly flammable and toxic chemicals found in drums along a busy road probably were the waste product of an illegal drug laboratory, authorities said tuesday
the chemicals, which included acetone and ether, were found monday in 10 drums about 4 miles west of this northern california town, according to greg smith, coordinator of emergency services and assistant fire chief for mendocino county
the chemicals, along with another 400 gallons found on two other occasions in the past two months, probably came from a laboratory making methamphetamine, commonly known as speed, in the area, he said
the problem with these people is they don't take any consideration of waterways or school children waiting nearby,'' said smith. he noted there was a creek 50 feet from the drums and a school bus stop 150 yards away
there were no injuries, but smith said there was concern about the chemicals because the drums had small leaks and some of the chemicals were crystalizing and foaming
nancy reagan canceled plans to visit a school in nashville, tenn., after coming down with a ``bad case'' of laryngitis, a spokeswoman said tuesday
the visit had been scheduled for wednesday. it was the second time the first lady had been forced to cancel the visit to warner elementary school and a drug and alcohol abuse prevention program; a snowstorm had prevented mrs. reagan from visiting the city the first time
wendy weber toler, a spokeswoman for mrs. reagan, said the white house physician, dr. john hutton, had advised the first lady not to travel
she can't talk. it's a bad case of laryngitis,'' mrs. toler said of the first lady. ``she started losing her voice last night.''
mrs. toler said mrs. reagan was ``just resting'' in the white house residence and was ``gargling with salt water'' to treat the laryngitis
mayor john fedo has been charged with swindling, falsifying entries in his city expense records and lying to the state auditor about how city money was spent, but he says it's a case of dirty politics
the indictment ``is not going to have an effect on city hall,'' fedo said at a news conference monday, insisting that the charges are an elaborate ploy by his political enemies
the indictment, including 22 felonies, was returned thursday by a st. louis county grand jury and was made public after fedo, in office nearly nine years, was arraigned monday
the indictment includes one count of theft, one count of failure to pay over state funds, six counts of presenting false claims to a public officer or body, 13 counts of permitting false claims against the government, one count of obstructing the state auditor and one count of misconduct of a public employee
if convicted, fedo, 37, faces a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison on the theft charge and up to five years in prison on most of the other charges. he was freed on his own recognizance. a hearing is scheduled for may 3
fedo's lawyer, douglas sauter, said he will move for dismissal of the charges. fedo was ``tried once in the election and found not guilty,'' he said
fedo, a member of minnesota's democratic-farmer-labor party, won his first four-year term as mayor in 1979 and has been re-elected twice
the theft charge concerns $13,500 given to fedo by three businessmen to lobby for state funds for a convention center in the city
during the 1987 election campaign, fedo said he passed the funds to an unnamed twin cities businessman in 1985 in exchange for information about other cities' convention center proposals
duluth, a city of 85,000 on the western tip of lake superior, was never in competition for a $200 million convention center for which bloomington and minneapolis vied, according to the charges. the legislature awarded duluth a total of $17.2 million for its relatively small center
prosecutors say the mayor played a limited role in lobbying for the convention center which he later claimed to have won almost single-handedly
the soviet union said tuesday negotations on banning chemical weapons are stagnating, and blamed the united states and britain
yuri nazarkin, chief soviet delegate to the 40-nation conference on disarmament, said some western delegations ``unfortunately make an ever greater emphasis on the idea that allegedly there is no need to hurry, that there is a lot more work to be done.'' his reference was to recent statements by u.s. and british delegates
tessa solesby of britain responded by telling the conference: ``we have to cope with a formidable number of technical difficulties. this is why i am uneasy and my authorities are uneasy when we are told a solution lies just around the corner.''
u.s. envoy max friedersdorf agreed and urged the soviet union to provide more information on the size of its chemical weapons arsenal
the disarmament conference began negotiations in 1968 on a convention to bar production, stockpiling and use of chemical arms
nazarkin, in a declaration he said was aimed at helping the exchange of information, claimed the soviets have not transferred chemical arms equipment or technology to other states
the soviet delegation is concerned about a slowdown, even stagnation'' of negotiations, but a draft convention could be finished this year if there is a drastic change of pace, he told reporters later
nazarkin spoke of three main obstacles to an agreement: the order of destruction of weapons over a 10-year period, inspection provisions for commercial chemical plants, and mandatory inspection of weapons sites on short notice if a violation is suspected
nazarkin repeated the soviet claim that washington is blocking progress by seeking exemptions for private industry
the wife and son of disgraced evangelist jimmy swaggart pleaded with television viewers tuesday to send huge donations to keep the $140 million-a-year jimmy swaggart ministries afloat
the holy spirit is telling you right now to send a large gift of help to carry my word, my program and my message around the world,'' frances swaggart said on the ministry's weeklong telethon
don't walk, run to that phone'' to make a pledge, donnie swaggart urged
tuesday's pleas were made in the third day of a scheduled weeklong telethon aimed at raising money for the ministry. tuesday's show also coincided with swaggart's 54th birthday
donnie swaggart, often sobbing, wished his father happy birthday and pledged ``i'll never leave or forsake you.''
donnie and his mother said that unless the telethon raises enough money, some of the ministry's work in foreign countries will have to shut down. in earlier broadcasts they said that even the ministry's regular daily television show may have to stop
swaggart said in a jsm publication that the ministries were about $14.7 million in deficit through february. the announcement is made in the march 1988 edition of ``the evangelist,'' a magazine published by the ministry
in an article outlining the telethon, swaggart claimed expenses average $13 million a month. the article did not detail how the money is spent or explain how the deficit was created
swaggart has not participated in the telethon
he voluntarily stepped down from his pulpit at the 7,500-seat family worship center and his worldwide television ministry shortly after news reports of his alleged involvement with a prostitute. national leaders of the assemblies of god denomination will decide later this month whether to discipline him for committing sexual misconduct
swaggart has publicly confessed to his family, church and television congregation that he had committed a sin but has not publicly revealed what sin he committed
published reports, however, have alleged that swaggart was photographed leaving a seedy new orleans-area motel room with a prostitute. it also is reported that swaggart paid prostitutes to perform lewd acts while he watched
since swaggart stepped down, the ministry has stopped work on one of its construction projects, laid off some 100 employees and canceled at least two ministry crusades
mrs. swaggart and her son said record donations are crucial to keep the ministry alive
god is going to touch you to give the largest gift you have ever given,'' mrs. swaggart said. ``the last few weeks satan has pressed his hand down strong to destroy'' the ministries
family worship center co-pastor jim rentz said news reports about swaggart are ``not the truth. they are being sidetracked.'' he did not elaborate
in the magazine article, swaggart complained ``the news media is opposed to us. most of the world's religions are opposed to us. sometimes i think every single denomination in america is opposed to us.''
a judge on tuesday made formal an order reinstating a pastor accused by church elders of adultery stemming from his exhortations to build ``spiritual connections'' through dancing with other members' spouses
donald lee barnett has admitted he sinned, but says he repented and wants to remain as pastor of community chapel and bible training center, based in burien, south of seattle
the dispute spilled into court last week, and king county superior court judge jim bates on tuesday signed an order he issued verbally on friday, which reinstated barnett
a week earlier, church elders ``disfellowshipped'' barnett, accusing him of sexual misconduct with several women in the congregation and saying he would not follow restrictions against being alone with any female parishioner other than his wife
church elders filed a new motion tuesday for a more detailed restraining order, which would prevent both sides from: firing church employees; interfering with worship services scheduled by either side; authorizing expenditures except through the established system; giving keys to buildings, offices r files to unauthorized people; destroying church documents; and hiring new employees except through the established system. bates set a hearing thursday
barnett, 57, founded the 1,500-member church in 1967. he has an unpublished telephone number, and could not be reached for comment
competing services were held sunday, and an affidavit by elder scott hartley said that while barnett attracted 240 and 195 people to two services, the elders' services attracted 600 and 660 people
church spokesman chuck kerr said a note from barnett was posted at the school chapel, reading: ``anyone who walks in this building will be `disfellowshipped' and staff will be fired.'' when barnett heard how many attended the elders' service, he rescinded the order, according to kerr
a former boeing draftsman, barnett guided the church from a bible study group to an organization that once had members in this country, western canada, and several other countries. membership locally was once about 2,500
dissident members have said many problems resulted from barnett's preaching of ``spiritual connection,'' a relationship between church members of opposite sexes with partners other than their spouses. the members are encouraged to dance with regular partners, or ``connections.''
some former members have said relationships that developed between these partners have led to suicide and broken marriages. more than a half-dozen former members have sued, some alleging barnett sexually assaulted them under the pretense of ministerial counseling
on march 20, 1986, a woman drowned her 5-year-old daughter in a bathtub, believing it would save the child from demons. court records said the woman was tormented by her 18 years of involvement in the church. she was sent to an institution
jeb stuart magruder, who became a presbyterian minister after serving a prison term for his role in the watergate scandal, was named tuesday to head a mayoral commission on values and ethics
a lot of my time outside has been talking about these issues,'' magruder said. ``i talk about these issues to the kiwanises and the rotaries around here, as well as deal with these issues through the church, so i would hope that my background would be helpful.''
mayor dana rinehart said the 15-member commission, on which he also will sit, will attempt to stimulate conversations on ethics
a city-wide ethics debate was prompted last year after bags of money fell from an armored truck on a downtown freeway. police said many of those who stopped to scoop up the cash never returned it to authorities
magruder held several white house positions from 1969 to 1973, including deputy director of communications at the time of the 1972 watergate break-in
he spent seven months in prison after pleading guilty to perjury and conspiracy to obstruct justice
after his release from prison in 1976, he entered a seminary and was ordained in 1981
since 1984, magruder has been executive minister at first community church in suburban marble cliff
he will receive no pay for serving on the commission
a national summit meeting of educators, business leaders and politicians should be convened to combat low morale and high dropout rates in urban schools, the president of the carnegie foundation for the advancement of teaching said thursday
i see it as a kind of manhattan project for urban schools,'' said ernest boyer, referring to the task force of scientists who developed the atomic bomb during world war ii
boyer, speaking at a news conference to release a foundation's report on the nation's big-city schools, said schools must be extricated from ``a web of mindless authority and contradictory responsibilities.''
i wonder if we don't need a national forum ... of top educators, politicians, corporate leaders, as voices most heard and listened to,'' said boyer, a former u.s. commissioner of education
the report, the first issued by the foundation trustees, said urban schols were riddled with problems ranging from low morale and high dropout rates to dilapidated facilities and crippling bureaucratic regulations
the nation was challenged (by president kennedy) to reach for the moon within a decade and we did. and i think it's not impossible for us to dream to have inner-city schools of excellence by the year 2000,'' boyer said
in the 38-page report called, ``an imperiled generation: saving urban schools,'' the carnegie trustees said: ``many people have simply written off city schools as little more than human storehouses to keep young people off th streets.''
stanley o. ikenberry, foundation chairman and president of the univeristy of illinois, warned: `` if people in our cities don't believe that our students can succeed and that our schools can succeed, they won't support them and the problem will continue.''
the foundation called for a ``crusade on behalf of urban education'' including greater financial support for inner-city schools and more freedom and accountability for teachers and principals
principals and teachers ``should be given more authority to run the schools,'' but if urban schools do not shape up, ``there must be outside intervention,'' the report said
it is our deep conviction that when schools fail, swift changes must be made. no other crisis _ a flood, a health epidemic, a garbage strike or even snow removal _ would be as calmly accepted without full-scale emergency intervention,'' the report said
the trustees suggested that an evaluation team of educators, parents and others be dispatched to a troubled school, where it could recommend sweeping changes including removing the principal and, as a last resort, closing the school
school reform is failing in the inner city because the diagnosis is wrong,'' boyer said. ``formulas for renewal _ more homework, more testing, more requirements for graduation _ work best for schools that already are succeeding and for students who are college bound
but to require a troubled student in an urban ghetto to take another unit in math or foreign language, without more guidance and support, is like raising a hurdle in the high jump without giving more coaching to someone who has stumbled.''
secretary of education william j. bennett issued a statement saying: ``i am generally encouraged by this report. it's good to have major figures from the education establishment strongly endorse the principle of accountability. now let's see if agreement on this idea can be followed by the political courage required to put it into practice.''
support for the foundation's effort also came from the national education association and the american federation of teachers
carnegie surveyed teachers and visited schools in six cities: chicago, cleveland, houston, los angeles, new orleans and new york
it proposed fighting the problem on several fronts, including:
_setting high expectations for all students. it decried the 28 percent of urban teachers surveyed by carnegie who thought a 25 percent dropout rate was tolerable
_freeing principals and teachers ``from a system of red tape that causes them to scrounge for chalk and paper clips while bombarding them with a steady flow of procedural directives.''
_a national urban schools program that would feature expanded federal funds for head start, child nutrition, and the chapter 1 remedial program, as well as loans to refurbish buildings and other new aid targeted at the nation's 100 biggest cities, from worcester, mass. (population 160,000) to los angeles and new york
_expanded partnerships between the schools and colleges and corporations
opponents of prime minister rajiv gandhi shuttered businesses and took to the streets in six indian states tuesday, but the general strike failed to win widespread support
police arrested 7,000 people in the street clashes, which left seven dead and 200 injured, news reports said
shops and offices were closed and traffic was disrupted in bombay, india's business center, and calcutta, its largest city
there were few signs of support, however, for the opposition-led strike in the other 19 indian states. it drew little apparent backing in new delhi, where most businesses remained open
the strike was called by most major opposition parties to protest sectarian violence, rising prices and alleged corruption in government. the parties, which include two communist groups, demand that parliament be dissolved and new elections held
in parliament, proceedings were disrupted for more than an hour tuesday when opposition members raised anti-government slogans in the upper house. earlier, the entire opposition boycotted the first hour of business in both houses in support of the strike
gandhi's congress party holds more than 400 of 542 seats in the popularly elected lower house. the rest are divided among opposition parties which have been divided despite common demands that gandhi resign
at least five people were killed in clashes in eastern bihar state, according to the united news of india. the news agency also reported that two people were killed and seven injured when a flour mill owner opened fire at opposition party supporters attacking his mill near the coastal city of ernakulam in southern kerala state
the agency said at least 75 people were hurt in political violence in west bengal state
state-run television said only two people died in strike-connected violence
at least 1,500 people were arrested in central madhya pradesh state and another 1,000 in eastern assam state, uni said
it said 14 policemen were injured near the pakistani border in rajasthan state when they were pelted with stones as they tried to remove roadblacks
a woman who paid up to $200,000 to have commandos snatch her daughter from jordan fears her ex-husband may try a similar tactic to get the girl back in the custody dispute, people familiar with the case said tuesday
the woman hired retired u.s. commandos to help her whisk lauren bayan, 7, off a school bus in jerash, north of amman, in late january, and has kept her whereabouts secret, even from her husband, since returning to this country, family members confirmed
cathy phelps mahone now fears her husband could try a similar maneuver to get the girl back, said holly planells, who heads american children held hostage, a brentwood, n.y. advocacy group set up to provide help in international child custody cases
once you get the child back, it isn't over,'' said ms. planells, who has been seeking the return of her own 4-year-old son from jordan in a similar custody battle
ms. planells said she had been in contact with ms. mahone since she and her daughter returned from the middle east but did not know her whereabouts other than somewhere in texas
ms. mahone claims her ex-husband, jordanian-born mohammed ali bayan, failed to return the child to her mother after visiting last halloween. a dallas judge gave ms. mahone custody after her december 1980 divorce, but bayan reportedly claims custody under jordanian law
ms. mahone has not divulged her whereabouts even to her current husband, lytt, whom she married five years ago
the main thing is their safety and their being together and hopefully not having anything else happen,'' mahone said in an interview with the marshall (texas) news messenger
however, mahone said he was not in favor of the commando operation, saying he felt the odds his wife and stepdaughter would be injured were too great
ms. mahone has talked about possible movie and book deals about the raid to bring attention to 2,500 similar cases, ms. planells said
an official at the u.s. embassy in amman knew the group was in jordan, but was misled about their intentions, state department spokesman charles redman said. the embassy officer was recalled to washington for questioning, he said
redman also said the united states had expressed regrets over the officer's possible involvement in the violation of jordanian law
jordanian authorities have had no official comment on the case. but one official, who did not want his name used, said a jordanian citizen was involved in getting the girl out of the country
the man, an employee of an agency that does security work for the u.s. embassy, was held for questioning, the official said
the operation was planned and executed jan. 28 by corporate training unlimited, a fayetteville, n.c., company that specializes in ``hostage rescue training,'' the philadelphia inquirer reported saturday, quoting anonymous sources close to the participants
company president donald feeney denied involvement
ms. planells said the operation cost $200,000, but ms. mahone's brother, david phelps of niceville, fla., said he had been told the mercenaries were paid $100,000
another brother, danny phelps of woodbridge, n.j., confirmed reports of the rescue were generally correct
the phelpses and their sister helped pay some of the costs of the mission, the northwest florida daily news of fort walton beach reported
an 11-year-old boy who shot and killed two men who broke into his home and tried to steal a vcr had never been left home alone before the fatal day, his mother said tuesday
todd knight shot the two men with his .22-caliber rifle monday afternoon when they broke into his family's rural home and tried to steal a videocassette recorder, authorities said
ann knight said her son did not think he had even wounded the men and was very upset when he learned they were dead
i think he went to pieces after it was all over,'' she said
he has never been here by himself _ not even for a minute,'' mrs. knight said. she said the boy still was shaken and the family stayed home tuesday to be with him
the boy will not be charged, officials said
i feel sure he felt very much as having his life in danger and i certainly look at it as being justifiable,'' said spartanburg county sheriff's capt. john blackwood
his life was in danger, he looked for an escape and could not find one .... he was a very brave young man,'' said county coroner jim burnett
he ``acted very wisely,'' burnett said
todd, a fifth-grade student at woodruff elementary school, was left alone in the house when his sister, tammy, left to practice for a weekend beauty pageant, mrs. knight said
todd would normally have gotten off his school bus at mrs. knight's parents' home nearby until the rest of the family came home, but her parents were not home monday afternoon
mrs. knight works at a greenville insurance agency and said she left work early to minimize the time todd would be home alone
the boy told authorities that he was watching television when he heard noises at the front door. he said he got the .22-caliber rifle his father gave him for christmas and loaded four rounds
a man he described as ``rough'' was pounding on the door, but the man drove away and todd went back to watching cartoons, keeping his gun nearby
about 10 minutes later he heard banging at a dining room window. he saw two men this time; unaware of his presence, they climbed through the window
the boy went into a bathroom to climb out the window but saw the men's car parked outside
he went back to the hallway, peeked around the corner into the den and was spotted by one of the intruders as they were taking the vcr off the television set
todd fired three shots at the men, who dropped the vcr and fled through a door into the garage
todd immediately called 911 for help
police found one of the men face down in the back yard, about 50 to 75 feet from the house, while the second man was in the driver's seat of their car, burnett said
mrs. knight said she and her husband, william, were thankful their son was unharmed but they spent most of the night awake
there wasn't much sleeping here last night,'' mrs. knight said. ``there are so many `what ifs.'''
dead at the scene were danny ray abernathy, 35, and broadus petty, 39, both of spartanburg. police were searching for a third person they suspect might have been involved
government spokesman jerzy urban on tuesday disputed reports that riot police clubbed students last week to break up marches commemorating the anniversary of campus protests 20 years ago
he said no general orders were issued for police to use force to stop the march 8 student demonstrations in warsaw and krakow. if force was used, it was applied only sporadically when demonstrations turned violent, he added
i deny western reports that police used clubs to disperse demonstrations,'' said urban at his weekly news conference. ``police did not have any orders to use force without necessity, without some aggression from the side of illegal demonstrators.''
the demonstrations for more academic freedom coincided with the anniversary of march 1968 student protests against censorship and political repression that were violently broken up by police and pro-government workers
the outlawed solidarity union condemned the authorities' reaction to the march 8 demonstrations. it issued a statement saying that several people were hospitalized after they were beaten by police
the labor group, in a statement drawn up at a meeting sunday of its national executive commission, said the police action reflected ``a growth of repressive tendencies'' on the part of communist authorities
lech walesa, who won the nobel peace prize in 1983, heads the committee
so the situation of 20 years ago has been repeated, which finally puts the lie to the authorities' statements about a change of judgment of the disgraceful events of '68,'' said the statement, which was read over the telephone tuesday by solidarity's national spokesman janusz onyszkiewicz
at urban's news conference, western reporters said they had seen riot police charging demonstrators and hitting them with clubs to disperse a march by several hundred students after a mass at warsaw's st. anne's church
urban replied, ``you have an undoubted advantage over me ... but it's the task of police to prevent an illegal demonstration.''
the students were demanding restoration of academic freedoms won during the 1980-81 solidarity labor upheaval and legalization of the independent students union, which was outlawed under martial law in 1982
the government said police detained 83 people taking part in the student protests in warsaw and krakow
solidarity was chartered by the government during nationwide strikes in the fall of 1980. it was suspended in december 1981 and subsequently outlawed by parliament
a couple searching for aluminum cans stumbled on a set of bleached bones in the desert northeast of el paso where five young women have been found in shallow graves since september, police said tuesday
police were painstakinly removing the remains tuesday and did not know the victim's age or sex or how long ago the person had been buried
the bones were found a few hundred yards southeast of where the remains of five young women were discovered last fall, said police chief john scagno
the women's deaths could be the work of a serial killer, said police, who have resumed searching for additional bodies
the body has not been removed,'' scagno said tuesday morning. ``we're doing it inch by inch, like we've done in the past. we hope to have it out by this evening.''
the couple found exposed bones monday afternoon and told police, scagno said. scagno would not say whether clothing or a weapon were found
the only detail we're going to tell you is ... the body had braces (on the teeth),'' scagno said. ``the body itself is just skeletal remains.''
the bodies of maria rosa casio, 24, and karen baker, 20, were found buried close together sept. 4. the bodies of desiree wheatley, 15, and dawn smith, 14, were found oct. 20, about 200 yards away. on nov. 3, the body of angelica frausto, 17, was found between the first two pairs of graves. all were el paso residents except ms. casio, who was from the dallas suburb of addison
no one has been arrested, but a detective testified in january that david leonard wood of el paso is one of several suspects. wood's trial on an unrelated sexual assault charge began monday. he is accused of an assault last summer near where the bodies were found
after two bodies were found, police used dogs and airborne infrared cameras to find the other bodies. deputy chief gus massey and scagno said they were not surprised that their search did not turn up the sixth body
the dogs, of course, have difficulty, given a certain period of time a body has been out there,'' scagno said. ``the longer the period of time, the more difficult it is to locate.''
massey said strong winds may have uncovered the bones
the fbi and border patrol are assisting in the investigation, and a u.s. customs airplane circled the area tuesday. customs officials on tuesday ordered a plane carrying an el paso herald-post photographer to stop taking pictures and leave
scagno said residents of northeast el paso should be ``concerned and careful as always.''
do we think at this moment that there is any need for any type of panic? the answer is no,'' he said
an instructor's failure to keep his plane out of restricted airspace on a student training flight was the primary cause of a 1987 collision that killed 10 people in utah, a federal panel concluded tuesday
the single-engine training plane and a skywest commuter plane collided near kearns, utah, on jan. 15, 1987, while making an approach to salt lake city international airport after a flight from pocatello, idaho
the national transportation safety board absolved the air traffic controller handling the skywest plane. the other aircraft was flying under visual flight rules and was not under the direction of air traffic control
nevertheless, the ntsb said the accident might have been avoided if the private aircraft had equipment that would have provided the controller information on the plane's altitude. investigators said the single-engine mooney m-20c was on the radar screen, but without altitude information the controller would not have known the two planes were about to collide
the controller, in any case, insisted to investigators that he never saw the mooney on his screen
with a ``mode-c'' transponder the controller's screen would have shown a larger ``data bloc,'' including altitude information that might have caused the controller to notice the plane more easily, the report said. the plane did not require such equipment, however
the safety board put the primary blame for the accident on the instructor of the private aircraft's ``lack of navigational vigilance ... which led to the unauthorized intrusion'' into the restricted airspace that surrounds the salt lake city airport
a plane may not enter the airspace without permission from an air traffic controller. no contact was ever made between the mooney aircraft and the control tower, investigators said
the mooney had been making ``touch-and-go'' takeoffs and landings at salt lake airport no. 2 near the main airport and apparently strayed into the airspace being used by commercial aircraft, investigators said
the safety board cited as another contributing factor ``the limitations of the air traffic control system to provide collision protection under the circumstances of this accident'' although it did not blame the controller specifically
the mooney's pilot was chester baker of sandy, utah, and the flight instructor was paul lietz of salt lake county, utah
the crew of skywest flight 1834 was: capt. michael d. gambill of helena, mont., and first officer walter f. ray jr. of chubbuck, idaho
while the ntsb staff recommended in a draft report that blame be limited to the pilots of the mooney, one board member, john lauber, pushed for at least some blame being directed at the air traffic control system as well
lauber, while saying he wasn't blaming the controller, said he had ``fundamental concerns'' about the federal aviation administration policy that generally limits a controller's responsibilities to those aircraft that are flying under instrument flight rules under direct air traffic control
lauber and several other board members suggested that the two skywest pilots might have been preoccupied with trying to find a western airlines boeing 737 that also was in the area. shortly before the accident, air traffic control advised the crew about the boeing 737, but radio transmissions showed the pilots were having trouble finding the plane, which was several miles away
the u.s. embassy in panama has rejected an attempt by panama's two-week-old government to order an american embassy officer out of the country, the state department said tuesday
the panamanian government on monday asked terrence kneebone, director of the u.s. information service, to leave the country within 48 hours. no explanation was given
state department spokesman charles redman said the u.s. embassy rejected the panamanian note because it was delivered by representatives of a regime not recognized by the united states as the legitimate authority in panama
there was no immediate indication what panama's next step would be
in late february, president eric arturo delvalle was ousted and replaced by the education minister, manuel solis palma. the united states continues to recognize delvalle as panama's president
queen elizabeth ii and her 11 relatives received an average 4.6 percent pay raise in tuesday's annual government budget. prince andrew will get the biggest increase _ 73 percent
in all, the civil list section of the budget allocated $10,241,000 to the royal family. queen elizabeth received $8.3 million
the civil list, announced in parliament by chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson, gave the queen and nine other members of the royal family 4 percent raises
but 28-year-old prince andrew's pay went from $92,500 to $159,100. the share of prince edward, 24, who has been receiving $37,000, remained unchanged
the government said andrew's allowance, which more than doubled after he married sarah ferguson in july 1986 and became the duke of york, was insufficent to meet his royal expenses
before marrying his allowance had stood unchanged since 1972
andrew also earns $32,400 a year as a royal air force instructor in helicopter warfare
his new allowance pushed up the royal family's appropriation up 4.6 percent from $9,785,600 last year. the current inflation rate is 3.3 percent
money magazine last month listed the 61-year-old queen as britain's richest person, estimating her personal fortune at $5.87 billion
queen mother elizabeth, 87, received the second-largest sum of $722,050 in the budget. queen elizabeth's husband, prince philip, received $402,750
the civil list does not include such items as running the royal yacht britannia or royal aircraft, or money for prince charles, the 39-year-old heir who gave up his share to live on income from land and investments
royal family members officiate at public ceremonies and represent britain abroad in many trips each year. published reports have estimated that the country spends at least six times the civil list sum on the monarchy
staff costs account for up to 75 percent of the civil list, buckingham palace said. salaries in the royal households correspond whenever possible to their equivalents in the civil service, a spokesman said
twenty-three protesters in wheelchairs and a blind person were arrested tuesday after blocking buses during morning rush hour at the department of transportation, police said
the demonstrators, members of americans disabled for accessible public transit, were protesting the appeal by the transportation department of a judge's ruling that all public transit authorities provide services for the handicapped regardless of cost
the protesters had chained themselves to the entrances of the transportation building monday afternoon and stayed there through the night as temperatures dipped below freezing. in the morning, they wheeled themselves into the traffic, district of columbia police officer walter ferguson said
we kept warm with the thought we were sending the department of transportation a message that we will take any action necessary to obtain our civil rights,'' protester stephanie thomas told hearing commissioner john treanor after her arrest
treanor released the protesters on $10 bond each, saying they could forfeit the bond in lieu of a fine
the demonstrators were charged with obstructing traffic at about 9 a.m., police said
it is unfortunate disabled people have to take these actions. but we'll continue to do so until the federal government acknowledges our right to use public transit,'' said clayton jones, a protester from hartford, conn
the department of transportation is appealing the jan. 4 decision by u.s. district judge marvin katz in philadelphia which struck down the department's regulation that transit agencies spend 3 percent of their budgets on the disabled
katz called the 3 percent an ``arbitrary and capricious'' figure that was so low it denied the handicapped ``the minimum quality of service mandated by the congress.''
transportation secretary jim burnley spoke briefly with the demonstrators monday and offered to meet them again next week, said hal paris, spokesman for the department
we haven't heard anything from them,'' burnley said tuesday
he confirmed that the department was appealing katz' decision but would not elaborate while the case is pending
wilson ferreira aldunate, head of the national party, the largest opposition party in uruguay, died tuesday of cancer, his family said. he was 69
the government declared 24 hours of national mourning
his wife, susana sienra, sons gonzalo and juan raul and daughter silvia were at his side when he died. hundreds of mourners gathered outside his home in the seaside suburb of pocitos to pay respects to the political leader, who had been ill since july
ferreira aldunate ran for president in 1971 and narrowly lost to juan bordaberry of the colorado party
he went into exile in 1973 and lived abroad for 11 years after the military seized power
an outspoken critic of the right-wing military regime, he was imprisoned upon his return to uruguay in 1984. the military government refused to let him run for president in 1985, but released him five days after the elections
ferreira aldunate, son of a rancher and rural doctor, studied for the law, but then went into politics. he was a member of congress for 34 years and was agriculture minister from 1963-67
he consolidated control over the centrist national party in the 1960s while in the senate
president raul alfonsin of argentina mourned the death of his friend ferreira aldunate as the loss of ``a notable figure in uruguayan democracy and in latin america.''
a mass is planned tuesday in the metropolitan cathedral. burial will be wednesday in montevideo. nixon</head>
a group of judges that makes policy for the federal courts urged the house on tuesday to consider impeaching u.s. district judge walter l. nixon of mississippi, who is scheduled to go to prison for perjury on march 23
the group, the judicial conference of the united states, unanimously supported a resolution that says ``consideration of impeachment may be warranted.''
nixon, 59, sentenced to five years in prison following his 1986 perjury conviction, has remained a judge but has not been hearing cases since he was indicted in 1985. he continues to be paid his annual salary of $89,500
nixon would forfeit his salary and his eligibility for a pension at age 65 if he is impeached by the house and removed from office by the senate
the recommendation that the house consider impeaching him was approved by a vote of 24-0 by the judges' group. three members abstained, including chief justice william h. rehnquist, who traditionally does not vote on such matters
nixon has been a federal judge since 1968 and chief judge for mississippi's southern district since 1982
his legal problems stemmed from his business relationship with wiley fairchild, a wealthy investor who sold three oil well properties to nixon in 1980 at bargain prices
nixon, who netted more than $50,000 from the deal, testified he bought the oil and gas rights in three wells for $9,500 in a legitimate transaction and promised no favor to fairchild in return
he was acquitted of bribery by a federal jury, but was convicted of lying to a grand jury when he denied discussing drug charges against fairchild's son with the elder fairchild and with a mississippi prosecutor
the supreme court on jan. 19 denied nixon's appeal, clearing the way for his imprisonment
nixon is the third federal judge ever to be indicted for crimes allegedly committed while in office
u.s. district judge alcee hastings of florida was acquitted of bribery in 1983 and impeachment proceedings against him are pending in the house
former federal judge harry claiborne of nevada was convicted in 1984 of failing to report $106,000 on his federal income tax returns and was sentenced to two years in prison. he was impeached and removed from office in 1986
processors who make hotdogs, bologna and other cooked sausages soon will be allowed to make leaner products by substituting water for fat, so long as there is no loss of nutritional value, the agriculture department said tuesday
the leaner products can be labeled as ``lite,'' ``light,'' or ``lower fat'' if they contain at least a fourth less fat than similar cooked sausage products on the market, officials said. the labels must include a comparison that explains the term
for example, the label for lower-fat hotdogs might say: ``this product contains 20 percent fat, while usda allows 30 percent fat in meat hotdogs.''
lester m. crawford, administrator of the department's food safety and inspection service, said the change in regulations will be effective on april 14 and ``reflects our desire to facilitate the marketing of lower-fat products.''
current federal rules for cooked sausages limit fat to 30 percent and ``added'' water to 10 percent. the new rule will limit the combination of fat and added water to 40 percent of the product
the maximum fat content in the finished product will continue to be limited to 30 percent, but the water restriction will be removed so that processors can substitute some of the water for fat _ and wind up with a lower-fat product, crawford said
protein content, which is indirectly controlled by the limits on fat and added water, will remain unchanged and will be comparable to other cooked sausages, he said
the rule change is being made at the request of the american meat institute, a private trade association, which asked usda to develop a standard for light frankfurters and similar cooked sausages. the proposed change was announced by the agency on nov. 25, 1986
the senate voted 88-4 on tuesday for legislation that would expand legal immigration to the united states and open the gates wider for western europeans who once dominated the flow of foreigners to this country
the bill went to the house, where its future is uncertain. rep. charles e. schumer, d-n.y. has introduced a similar bill to the senate measure. he said there may be attempts to link the bill with proposals to extend an amnesty program for some of those who came here illegally
the senate rolled up its overwhelming majority because the two leading immigration authorities in the chamber, democrat edward m. kennedy of massachusetts and republican alan k. simpson of wyoming, teamed up as bipartisan sponsors
sen. dennis deconcini of arizona was the only democrat to oppose the bill. three republicans voted against it: jesse helms of north carolina, pete wilson of california and mark hatfield of oregon
simpson and kennedy took aim at a legal immigration system in which 90 percent of those granted visas are admitted because they have close family members living legally in this country. only 10 percent of the immigration visas are granted to fill the needs of the labor market
this system has resulted in 85 percent of u.s. immigrants coming from asia and latin america. a new ``independent'' category, based on labor skills and other factors, would be expected to admit large numbers of western europeans
the legislation would apply to those who try to obtain legal residency through normal u.s. government channels. sixteen months ago, congress ended a six-year debate by enacting legislation to curb massive illegal entries into the united states
the 1986 law included the provision granting amnesty to those who came here illegally, but resided continuously in this country since before jan. 1, 1982. the one-year legalization program ends may 4, and schumer and others believe it should be extended
kennedy and simpson agreed not to link an extension to their bill to avoid a possible filibuster led by sen. phil gramm, r-texas
the senate legislation would maintain priority for applicants with close relatives here and significantly expand available visas for the new independent category
the bill also would establish an overall cap on immigration
the level for the first three years would be 590,000 annually, which is 100,000 higher than the current number of visas
under this umbrella, 470,000 visas in each of the first three years (440,000 thereafter) would be reserved for family immigration, and 120,000 (150,000 after three years) would be for the new ``independent'' category
currently, spouses and minor children of u.s. citizens can enter the country without limitation
sen. rudy boschwitz, r-minn., a refugee from nazi germany, said he was concerned that the limitation could someday close the doors to many wishing to come here. but simpson said the cap is more than adequate to handle today's applicants, and pointed out the cap could be changed every three years
schumer's bill would address this problem with a cap of 750,000, including refugees fleeing from persecution. the senate cap does not include refugees, who now are admitted under a separte law that sets annual limits. the current refugee cap is 68,500
the senate bill also would:
_revise family preferences to give higher priority to the closest family members of citizens and permanent residents
_require the administration to report every year on the effects of immigration, and to recommend changes in the level of immigration every three years
_create the independent visas by combining: existing preferences for professionals, persons of exceptional merit, and those with needed skills; and establish a new 55,000-visa category based on a point system
points would be awarded for education, work experience, english language skills and age
_establish a conditional visa for those who will invest at least $2 million in this country and employ at least 10 americans or legal residents. up to 4,800 conditional visas would be available annually, requiring the investor to return to immigration authorities in two years for adjustment to permanent resident alien status
the applicant would face deportation unless he or she continued to meet the job-creation requirement. details</note>
mikhail s. gorbachev toured a factory tuesday that exports industrial robots to the soviets and americans and told the workers the soviet union is too big to give up all central control
the yugoslav factory operates under the government's local-management system
the reform-minded soviet leader is on a five-day visit to yugoslavia, getting his first look at this independent communist country's freer economy
soviet officials said gorbachev was ``very satisfied'' with his first two days of talks with yugoslav leaders and seeks ways of developing closer relations with the country moscow once denounced for ``revisionist'' policies
president tito broke with soviet dictator josef stalin in 1948, defying the kremlin's authority in the communist world, and developed ties to the west. years of plots and threats from moscow followed
relations were mended in the 1950s, with nikita s. khrushchev in charge at the kremlin, but the last visit to yugoslavia by a soviet leader was in 1980, when leonid i. brezhnev attended tito's funeral
during a brief photo session tuesday, gorbachev told reporters: ``we got off to a good start.''
the two sides exchanged copies of a new declaration acknowledging yugoslavia's independence from soviet control, which replaces similar statements issued in 1955 and 1956. a yugoslav spokesman said the document would not be made public until the end of gorbachev's visit friday
fyodor burlatsky, a soviet columnist traveling with gorbachev, said the kremlin is preparing to adopt some practices similar to those in yugoslavia, among them allowing the open sale of international newspapers and magazines
everybody can hear many voices'' in yugoslavia, burlatsky said in an interview. ``i believe there will be new decisions taken in a short time'' to let soviet newstands sell non-soviet publications
he also praised progress yugoslavia has made ``from bureaucracy to self-managing socialism.''
public interest remained high in the visit by gorbachev and his wife, raisa
crowds gathered to watch the motorcade pass. when word spread tuesday evening that the soviet leader would stop in a downtown square, several thousand people turned up, but the stop turned out not to be on his schedule
earlier in the day, the gorbachevs visited the park of peace to plant a tree, a customary practice
to a group of children attending the ceremony, gorbachev said the park contains trees planted by many leaders of the non-aligned movement, of which tito was a founder
you take care of this park,'' he said, and carefully shoveled every bit of dirt from a small pile set aside for the planting
after chatting and joking with the children, the gorbachevs lined up with them for photographs. he promised the children they would receive copies
at the ivo lola ribar factory outside belgrade, the gorbachevs were shown modern machine tools and robots used by auto-assembly plants in both the east and west
gorbachev met with the factory worker council, which is responsible for plant operations
his ``perestroika'' program, designed to modernize the soviet economy, proposes reducing central planning and giving managers and workers more control over their own factories, but he told the workers some central control will remain
we have to maintain a regulatory role at the center to safeguard us against mistakes, particularly because the country of the soviet union is so large,'' gorbachev said
he brushed off a reporter's question about what useful knowledge he might take back to the soviet union. gorbachev said his schedule was too tight for questions
in a dinner toast, gorbachev said ``eastern and western europe are gradually becoming less and less suspicious of each other.''
he criticized what he called unfounded charges in the western media that he is trying ``to drive a wedge'' between the united states and its nato allies
i have already stated and will repeat once again: we never had, nor do we now have any such ideas,'' gorbachev said
the soviet union is yugoslavia's largest trading partner. it ships raw materials in exchange for manufactured goods that generally are of higher quality than those made at home
in contrast to perennial soviet shortages of consumer goods, yugoslavia's shops and markets brim with domestic and imported products. inflation is running at about 170 percent, however, the unemployment rate is 15 percent and yugoslavia has a $20 billion debt to foreign creditors
farm lawmakers drafting a compromise trade bill agreed tuesday to expand by more than $1 billion an export subsidy program designed to spur worldwide sales of u.s. agricultural commodities
with this action, congress has demonstrated that it will continue to fight european economic community subsidization and give american farmers a fair chance to compete in world trade,'' senate agriculture committee chairman patrick j. leahy, d-vt., said in a statement
the decision to expand to $2.5 billion the export enhancement program came at a subcommittee session of the house-senate conference committee that is seeking a compromise version of 1,000-page trade bills passed by both houses
under the program, which was first established by the 1985 farm law, grain exporters are provided with government bonuses in the form of surplus commodities in return for shipping american farm goods. proponents say the bonuses offset the difference between u.s. prices and lower price tags abroad
but the panel put off action on the most controversial issue it faces, a senate plan to prod the european community to drop export subsidies with the threat of a so-called marketing loan program for wheat, corn and soybeans
marketing loans represent a form of subsidy that provides producers with the u.s. price while selling the commodities abroad at world prices. the government makes up the difference
marketing loans established by the 1985 farm law sent exports of american cotton and rice skyrocketing while stemming a surge in honey imports
being weighed by the panel is a so-called ``triggered marketing loan'' that would be put into effect only if current negotiations under the 92-nation general agreement on tariffs and trade failed to produce an agreement on eliminating agricultural export subsidies by the 1990 wheat marketing year
supporters of the concept said a congressional visit to the gatt talks in geneva last week found european negotiators dug in over the subsidy issue and added that american negotiators want the ``club'' of a triggered marketing loan to hold over the heads of their counterparts
if you were talking to some of the people we have to negotiate with, then you might think we need it, too,'' said leahy. he said the attitude of some of the europeans has become ``arrogant.''
critics said however that such a plan would strain the budget
this is potentially a huge amount of money we're talking about in agricultural programs,'' said rep. sam gibbons, d-fla., whose export-minded home-district citrus producers have traditionally been as wary of import curbs as they have of barriers to their products overseas
gibbons distributed a letter signed by agriculture secretary richard lyng, u.s. trade representative clayton k. yeutter, white house council of economic advisers chairman beryl sprinkel and james miller, director of the office of management and budget
it described the triggered marketing loan as a concept that could bring about a presidential veto of the trade bill. it was designed to counter claims that american negotiators in geneva are encouraging the proposal
rep. leon panetta, d-calif., whose home district includes numerous fruit and vegetable producers, described the concept as one that could boomerang on the lawmakers politically
i can see us passing a $600 million marketing loan and the administration saying on the record that they don't want it,'' panetta said. ``we get attacked on that point and there's no mention that this was a bargaining chip for the gatt negotiations. i sense that coming.''
wheat belt lawmakers countered that the proposal would cost the treasury nothing because it would merely serve as ammunition to hasten agreement on subsidy reductions
we're not asking you to take her home,'' said rep. pat roberts, r-kan. ``we're just asking you to dance with her. then when it's closing time, you can go out the back door.''
arctic air broke or tied low-temperature records in 38 cities across the south on tuesday, while snow was scattered from the great lakes to the southern appalachians and a new storm was brewing in the west
more record cold was forecast for wednesday morning and freeze warnings were posted across georgia, most of mississippi and northern florida. a hard freeze was forecast for northern and central georgia, threatening damage to fruit trees
tuesday's record or record-tying lows were 31 at alexandria, la., a tie; 33 at apalachicola, fla.; 23 at auburn, ala.; 33 at austin, texas, tie; 19 at batesville, ark., tie; 31 at baton rouge, la., tie; 24 at birmingham, ala.; 19 at bristol, tenn.; 33 at bryan-college station, texas, tie; 13 at calico rock, ark.; 19 at conway, ark.; 22 at el dorado, ark.; 15 at fayetteville, ark.; 48 at fort myers, fla., tie; 20 at fort smith, ark., tie; 23 at greer, s.c., tie; 32 at houston, texas;
and 22 at huntsville, ala.; 22 at jackson, miss.; 21 at jonesboro, ark.; 20 at knoxville, tenn., tie; 31 at lake charles, la.; 27 at little rock, ark.; 27 at macon, ga.; 20 at mena, ark.;25 at memphis, tenn.; 20 at meridian, miss.; 27 at mobile, ala.; 26 at monroe, la.; 25 at montgomery, ala.; 40 at new orleans, tie; 30 at pensacola, fla.; 26 at pine bluff, ark.; 18 at pinson, ala.; 31 at san antonio, texas; 31 at savannah, ga.,tie; 27 at shreveport, la.; and 25 at texarkana, ark
snow showers fell during the afternoon across much of the northeast, especially near the great lakes and from western illinois across the ohio valley and the central and southern appalachians to the mid atlantic coast
four to 6 inches of snow fell in some lakeshore counties of northeastern ohio, while 2 to 4 inches fell across southern west virginia and around an inch at boone and west jefferson, n.c
snow also fell in parts of michigan, where marquette got 2 inches of snow during the six hours up to 1 p.m. est, bringing their total snow depth to 43 inches
a storm system developing in the west was centered over western utah, spreading snow across sections of wyoming, utah, idaho and nevada
up to 3 inches of snow was reported at hill air force base in northern utah during the six hours up to 1 p.m. est, while 3 to 6 inches fell in the mountains of northern utah
a winter storm watch was posted for central and southwestern wyoming overnight and into wednesday
the storm in utah also generated high wind in sections of the southwest, with gusts to 66 mph at mammoth lakes, and gusts to 45 mph in the owens valley of california and in sections of the mojave valley near las vegas, nev
unseasonably cold weather also moved into the pacific northwest during the morning, dropping temperatures near the freezing mark in the seattle and portland areas
astoria, ore., tied its record low of 28 and olympia, wash., dipped to a record 24 degrees
temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. est ranged from 16 degrees at ellsworth air force base outside rapid city, s.d., to 75 in the california desert at blythe, imperial and thermal. the early morning low for the day was 9 degrees below zero at dickinson, n.d
for wednesday, snow showers were forecast from much of new england across the northern and central appalachians to northern indiana and michigan. snow or snow showers also were forecast in utah, and from the northern and central rockies to much of kansas. showers were forecast in oklahoma and northern texas
highs in the 20s or 30s were predicted from new england across the northern and central appalachians, the great lakes, the upper mississippi valley and the northern and central plains to the northern half of the rockies; in the 60s in florida and louisiana, and in parts of western oregon; in the 60s or 70s across most of texas, southern new mexico, southern arizona and much of california; and in the 40s or 50s elsewhere
