israel imposed a travel ban tuesday, one of several moves a moderate arab mayor said would increase bitterness and hatred in the occupied lands. hospital officials said soldiers killed two arabs and wounded 12
the military administration also cut telephone lines connecting the occupied west bank and gaza strip with foreign countries, israel radio reported. it said the measure apparently was to prevent ``plo members in europe from passing orders to residents of the territories.''
the military command declined to comment on the reason for the action, saying only that the army ``is taking different steps to treat problems in the territories.''
according to u.n. figures, 96 palestinians have been killed since violence began dec. 8 in the territories israel occupied during the 1967 middle east war, three from the effects of tear gas and the rest from gunfire or beatings
as the ban on travel between the occupied west bank and gaza strip took effect, arabs began a two-day general strike that kept most of the 110,000 who work in israel away from their jobs
the travel ban is one of several restrictions israel hopes will reduce the underground palestinian leadership's success in running strikes and forcing the resignations of arab police and tax collectors
others include a nightly five-hour curfew on the gaza strip's 650,000 residents and selectively cutting off electricity as punishment
what is the result? more bitterness, more hatred, more friction between the two peoples,'' said elias freij, a palestinian christian who is mayor of bethlehem, the west bank town where christ was born
the israelis have to realize that after 100 days of uprising, the palestinians don't want the occupation,'' freij said. ``if they keep rejecting our demands the unrest will go on.''
hashem al shawa, director of the bank of palestine in gaza, said the latest measures could hamper gaza's ability to export citrus, its major earner of hard currency. half the territory's 52,118 tons of citrus exports last year went to jordan over the west bank bridges
the economy is in a very bad situation. merchants cannot meet their obligations,'' he said, adding that the bank's depositors wrote $10 million worth of bad checks last month
an official in the army-run territorial administration said the travel ban was designed to keep agitators and anti-israeli leaflets from moving freely between the west bank and gaza strip
the latest strike coincided with prime minister yitzhak shamir's visit to the united states. underground leaflet no. 10, said the strike slogan was: ``no alternative to an independent state led by the plo, our sole respresentative.''
a campaign inspired by the palestine liberation organization caused hundreds of arab police to resign. israel radio said tuesday that 500 officers had quit, 300 of them in gaza city, but added that 40 later returned to work
police spokesman rafi levy said seven arab officers in jerusalem turned in their badges tuesday, the first resignations in the holy city
hamza turkmani, the israeli-appointed mayor of gaza city, said he had threatened to shut down the municipal government and services if israeli authorities withheld power or other utilities from residents
he said the israeli army cut power monday to the shati refugee camp next to gaza city as punishment for a demonstration
the israelis cut the electricity because they want to show everybody that they need the state of israel,'' turkmani declared
army spokesmen said soldiers shot one palestinian dead in the west bank village of deir jarir and wounded four in a separate clashes in qalqilya
hospital officials said two arabs were killed and 12 wounded in street battles that swept the gaza strip and west bank
among those wounded tuesday were rahme muklad, 50, shot in the leg, and his sons, jamal, 20, who was shot in the stomach, and rasfat, 22, with a bullet in the back. both young men were in serious condition, said officials at qalqilya hospital
the army said tuesday a military judge sentenced two soldiers monday after they were convicted in the brutal beating of palestinian detainees photographed by a cbs news crew feb. 25
a spokesman said ronnen sasson was sentenced to 21 days in jail and arieh moalem to 10 days, minus four days spent in detention. two other soldiers and their commanding officer face more serious penalties if convicted
according to the army, an investigation showed moalem and sasson played a relatively minor part in the beating. lautenberg quoting shamir as saying nothing is off the table; picks up 19th graf pvs, shultz set</note>
secretary of state george p. shultz said tuesday he was unable to bridge differences with israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir over a u.s. plan for opening mideast peace negotiations by may 1
but he called the first of three days of talks with shamir constructive and said ``we feel encouraged to continue our efforts to work with israel and others in the middle east.''
shamir underscored one of the main differences. he said that in israel's view, the middle east peace conference shultz wants to convene next month to set the stage for negotiations could not play ``any positive role.''
president reagan sought, meanwhile, to reassure shamir he would not be put under u.s. pressure to agree to any particular solution to israel's 40-year dispute with the arabs
but reagan stressed that ``making progress toward peace in the middle east not only serves mutual interests, it is urgent.''
in a speech to the united jewish appeal, the president said he would tell shamir at the white house on wednesday that ``peace will not be imposed by us or anyone else.''
shultz met with shamir for about three hours, first over blueberry pancakes at the secretary's home in suburban maryland and then at his state department office
we haven't found our way to bridge all of the differences,'' shultz said afterward. ``i see quite clearly what the nature of the differences are and what they aren't.''
shultz did not offer any details, but shamir restated his opposition to an international forum that would include the soviet union and china, which do not have diplomatic relations with israel and usually support arab positions
we are interested, first of all, to negotiate directly with all the parties concerned,'' shamir said. ``we don't see any positive role for an international conference.''
the prime minister described his first round with shultz as ``very serious and thorough.'' he pledged to cooperate ``to get peace and to enhance the prospects for peace in our area.''
but, he added, the arabs were not willing to negotiate with israel
avi pazner, a spokesman for shamir, said the u.s. proposal for an international conference was ``a sticking point that has to be resolved if we are going to go ahead.''
king hussein of jordan has demanded the conference. pazner said hussein sees it as ``an instrument which would be used by the enemies of israel, both arabs and non-arabs, like countries that do not have diplomatic relations with israel, to put pressure on israel, to try to bring israel to agree to solutions it would not agree to in free negotiations.''
shamir offered last october to hold israeli-jordanian negotiations in washington with u.s. and soviet ``blessing.'' pazner said shamir stands by the offer even though it was rejected by the king
the israeli spokesman said shamir did not give shultz ``an answer'' to the overall proposal for negotiations. ``he did not say yes, he did not say no,'' he said
speaking a half-mile away, at the old executive office building next to the white house, reagan said he would tell shamir that ``when it comes to israel the united states is not a bargainer or a broker; the united states is a friend and an ally.''
the president offered assurances to the jewish gathering that ``we will not leave israel to stand alone, nor will we acquiesce in any effort to gang up on israel.'' he added: ``peace will not be imposed by us or by anyone else. it will and must come from the genuine give-and-take of negotiations. that's what we're working to set in motion now.''
in a meeting with a small group of senators at the capitol, shamir was quoted as saying he was not ruling out any issue or proposal as the subject for negotiations
the prime minister said there is nothing that is off the table in terms of negotiations,'' said sen. frank lautenberg, d-n.j
lautenberg said shamir was asked whether he was ruling out trading territory for peace with israel's arab nations
i didn't hear anything that said territory is excluded,'' lautenberg said
lautenberg said he got the impression that shamir would be prepared to be ``a lot more flexible'' in direct talks with arab states than he is in ``this pre-negotiation period.'' but he added: ``i don't think the prime minister's obstinancy about an international conference is any less than it was earlier.''
he said shamir indicated he might be able to accept ``a ceremonial group'' of other nations at the opening of discussions. ``but once serious discussions started he wanted to talk only to israel's (arab) neighbors,'' the senator said
shultz set this week as a deadline for a reply from israel and jordan, which would form a delegation with palestinians for the negotiations
in amman, a senior jordanian official told the associated press that jordan was not yet ready to give a final response to shultz's plan
we are consulting with other arab leaders,'' said the official, who demanded anonymity. asked when he expected the jordanian stand to be announced, he said: ``in the next 10 days or so.''
on capitol hill, assistant secretary of state richard w. murphy sought to reassure supporters of israel that an international conference would not dictate solutions to any side. ``we won't tolerate efforts _ such as ones by the soviets or the syrians _ to turn this into an authoritative, plenipotentiary forum,'' he told a house foreign affairs subcommittee
murphy said the administration still has questions about the terms under which the soviets could participate in such a forum, and these would be discussed next week when foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze visits washington for talks with shultz
pressed by several congressmen why shultz had softened his opposition to soviet participation, murphy said no arab state would enter peace talks without a soviet presence. ``they're (the soviets) in the region, and we have to find a way to deal with them,'' he said
meanwhile, nine senators made public the text of a letter to shultz urging him not to subject shamir to u .s. criticism or pressure
american support should not be used ``as a lever to force israel's leaders to adopt a policy which they see as dangerous to the national security of their country _ especially when such policy entails injecting the soviet union into the peace process,'' the letter said
the letter was signed by sens. chic hecht, r-nev.; jesse helms, r-n.c.; steven symms, r-idaho; david karnes, r-neb.; william l. armstrong, r-colo.; gordon j. humphrey, r-n.h.; phil gramm, r-texas; larry pressler, r-s.d.; and christopher bond, r-mo
shultz's plan for peace talks anticipates israel relinquishing at least part of the west bank and gaza strip it has held since the 1967 six-day war in exchange for arab recognition of the jewish state
in a tough speech monday night to another uja group, shamir said yielding territory would invite another attempt by the arabs to destroy israel
these matters are questions of life and death, of our very existence,'' he said
also on shamir's schedule tuesday were meetings with treasury secretary james a. baker iii, republican presidential aspirant pat robertson and congressional leaders
a new york congressman proposed on tuesday a bill to require the internal revenue service to send taxpayers a ``credit card statement'' highlighting the cost of federal deficit spending
rep. joe dioguardi, r-n.y., who is a certified public accountant, would require the irs to put the national balance sheet in the format of an individual's regular monthly credit bill. the statement would be mailed with the government's annual income tax forms
and i am sorry to report that the bottom line is that the average american owes uncle sam $18,569.10 from all the unpaid bills we have allowed to pile up,'' he said. the national debt is about $2.5 trillion
dioguardi's sample statement for fiscal 1987 includes the previous balance of $17,118.08. it then details the purchases ranging from $2,769.34 per taxpayer toward social security to $73.60 for criminal justice
it then subtracts payments _ taxes _ and adds in the debt's finance charge of $1,358,03 per taxpayer
ari fleischer, a spokesman for dioguardi, said the congressman had not determined how much producing and mailing the annual statement would add to government spending. but it would be minimized by including it with the other tax forms, he said
a south african military plane landed tuesday in luanda and released 12 angolan soldiers in exchange for the bodies of two south african corporals killed in northern angola in 1985, angolan officials said
they also said u.s. envoy chester crocker was expected to arrive in this angolan capital by wednesday for talks with angolan leaders following his meetings in geneva on a southern african peace settlement with south african foreign minister roelof f. botha
the officials, who spoke on condition of not being identified, said tuesday's exchange took place at luanda airport. they said 12 angolan soldiers were freed. the south african military said 12 captured angolans were freed, but refused to say if they were soldiers or civilians
south africa identified the two dead soldiers as cpls. rowland liebenberg and louis van breda, both 25. angola said they were killed in cabinda province may 21, 1985, when angolan troops surprised their commando unit outside an oil depot
the unit leader, maj. wynard du toit, was captured. he said the commandos were sent to blow up the depot belonging to cabinda gulf oil, a subsidiary of the u.s. oil company chevron
du toit was exchanged last september for 133 angolan soldiers reportedly captured by the national union for the total independence of angola, the south african-backed rebel movement known as unita
the tuesday exchange appeared to be a further step in intense diplomatic efforts to reach a settlement in marxist angola's 13-year conflict. unita, which also is supported by the united states, is fighting to force the cuban- and soviet-backed government to share power
the talks monday between crocker, assistant secretary of state for african affairs, and botha focused on efforts for an agreement on withdrawal of an estimated 40,000 cuban soldiers stationed in angola
crocker is trying to negotiate a withdrawal of the cubans in return for south african withdrawal from neighboring south-west africa, also known as namibia. south africa administers namibia under a post-world war i mandate from the defunct league of nations and has rejected united nations's resolutions demanding that the territory be independent
south africa recently acknowledged having troops in southern angola, but said they were in the process of withdrawing
however, president p.w. botha of south africa was quoted in the washington times newspaper monday as saying south african troops would not leave angola unless cuban troops also left
angola says it will send the cubans home only when south africa pulls its troops out of southern angola, america halts aid for unita and an independence settlement is reached for namibia
president jose eduardo dos santos of angola says 9,000 south african soldiers are in southern angola
unita said tuesday in a statement distributed in lisbon, portugal, that its guerrillas captured the town of kiwaba-n'zogi in northern malange province, killing 12 soldiers and seizing arms
it said guerrillas attacked the town 42 miles north of the provincial capital of malange on sunday
the rebels said they also captured three angolan soldiers and destroyed five trucks in an attack saturday on a military convoy in malange province. they claimed to have killed 10 angolan soldiers in an attack on an army post at elola in southwestern huila province, but did not say when
unita gave rebel casualties in the clashes as three killed and eight wounded. there was no independent confirmation of the claims
in brussels, belgian professor aubin heyndrickx, a specialist in toxicology, claimed that cuban troops were using chemical weapons in angola
heyndrickx visited southeast angola three weeks ago at the invitation of jonas savimbi, leader of unita, and examined eight unita soldiers in a field hospital in the mavinga area
he said in stories published tuesday that examinations showed the soldiers were victims of toxic gas and further laboratory checks made later in ghent confirmed that diagnosis. bgng: as is ...</note>
the senate, trying to avoid another iran-contra affair, voted 71-19 approval tuesday of a bill requiring a president to tell congress about all covert operations within 48 hours after the action begins
the decision came after the democratic-controlled chamber voted overwhelmingly to invoke cloture and end an attempt by republican conservatives to block final action on the measure
the chamber also voted down, 60-32, a move to permit up to 10 days, instead of 48 hours, for notification
the house is considering a similar bill, but president reagan has threatened to veto the legislation because he argues that it is an unconstitutional restriction on his authority in the foreign policy field
the bill overhauls procedures for informing congress about intelligence activities. the most controversial provision was the one requiring that capitol hill be told about covert operations within 48 hours after they begin
the bill was chiefly written by sen. william cohen, r-maine, vice chairman of the intelligence committee and also a member of the committee which last summer investigated the iran-contra affair
reagan withheld notice from capitol hill for 10 months that u.s. arms were secretly being sold to iran. some of the money was diverted to the anti-nicaraguan contra guerrillas
current law requires only that the president give ``timely notice'' to capitol hill about covert action, but does not define the term
cohen and other backers of the legislation have argued that had reagan told congress about the planned sale of weapons to iran, the legislators might have complained so loudly that the deal would have been scuttled
cohen said the 48-hour time period was suggested by intelligence officials, who said it could be met
as it returned to the bill, the senate voted 73-18 to limit debate. that was 13 more votes than needed to invoke cloture and halt the senate practice of unlimited debate
then, the chamber killed, by a 60-32 margin, an amendment proposed by sen. john chafee, r-r.i., to extend to up to 10 days the period during which information about covert actions can be withheld. chafee said, ``i think this is a sufficient time'' for the completion of covert actions such as a hostage rescue, but it would block anything like the iran-contra situation
the house intelligence committee is considering a similar bill, but reagan has already decided to veto any such legislation because he believes it is an unconstitutional restriction on his authority to conduct foreign policy, defense secretary frank c. carlucci said last week
carlucci took over as reagan's national security adviser in the wake of the iran-contra affair
sen. malcolm wallop, r-wyo., told his colleagues tuesday that ``this bill is badly drafted, badly conceived, and the worst of its conceptions is that somehow you can legislate intelligence. ... it's hard for me to believe that one piece of legislation can obviate stupid activity.''
if the measure passes, ``we can perhaps prevent another iran-contra,'' said wallop, but ``we would deny some very wholesome activity.''
wallop claimed that the bill ``would substitute our judgment for that of the president.''
but cohen said, ``nothing could be further from the truth'' and argued that the senate ``should not abdicate its constitutional responsibility.''
the senate is a ``co-equal'' to the white house and should shoulder the burden of overseeing actions by the intelligence agencies, cohen said
an american photographer has been accused by the army of throwing stones at israeli soldiers during a violent palestinian protest in the occupied west bank
the army on tuesday identified the photographer as william biggart, and israel radio said he had been on assignment for the village voice, a weekly newspaper published in new york city. biggart and the newspaper denied the army allegations
biggart was detained last week during a palestinian riot in nablus, the west bank's largest arab town, the army said. a spokesman said the photographer was wearing a traditional checkered arab headdress and was seen throwing stones at soldiers
the army filed a complaint with nablus police, the spokesman said, refusing to let his name be used because of military regulations
martin gottlieb, editor of the village voice, said in new york that biggart apparently went to the west bank to see if he could take pictures to sell to other news organizations
he's a free-lance photographer on assignment from us to take some very routine head-and-shoulder shots and real estate pictures of the knesset (the israeli parliament),'' gottlieb said
he adamantly denies the charges. our position here is one of outrage. we think that although he wasn't specifically working for us on the west bank, we would have been anxious to see the photos he took.''
gottlieb quoted the photographer as saying: ``it's ridiculous. i'm 40 years old. i have three kids. i didn't come to israel to thrown stones.''
we think he did absolutely nothing wrong and one can only wonder why israeli soldiers would concoct charges against this man at a time when every effort is being made to keep the area closed to the press,'' gottlieb said. ``the democratic freedom of the press seem to be under a severe attack in israel.''
he said the paper would lodge a protest with the israeli consulate in new york
israel radio said soldiers confiscated biggart's u.s. passport and israeli-issued press card but a senior officer ordered the passport returned. it said biggart described himself as a staff photographer for the village voice
biggart had applied twice for an israeli government press office card, once with a beard and the second time clean-shaven, the radio said, and quoted the photographer as saying he ``did not want to look like a jewish settler.''
it said a policeman went to the american colony hotel in east jerusalem, where biggert was staying, last saturday and presented a summons for a court appearance the next day but biggart left the country sunday
a senior official at the u.s. consulate said biggart was in touch with a duty officer saturday night and ``said that he was summoned to court and that he was due to leave on sunday. the officer said he can't give a legal advice.''
gottlieb said biggart gave this description of events:
on march 7, he was on a street in the balata refugee camp when israeli soldiers began lobbing tear gas grenades. the soldiers later charged into the street
like everybody else on the street, i began to run. i slipped. i was the only one who didn't get away.''
after an israeli soldier struck him on the legs and ripped the film out of his camera, an officer took him to a military post and accused him of throwing rocks
his passport was returned but the soldiers kept the press card. he was presented with a document, written in hebrew, by a police officer who spoke only arabic
he left israel on sunday after a u.s. consulate official told him he could leave the country but might have trouble returning
from 1975 on, wedtech corp. deceived federal agencies into believing it was a minority-controlled business that qualified for no-bid government contracts, a former company executive testified tuesday at the racketeering trial of rep. mario biaggi
mario moreno, one of four ex-wedtech officials who have pleaded guilty to bribery and other state and federal charges, was the first prosecution witness to testify at the trial of biaggi and six co-defendants
biaggi, a 10-term bronx democrat; his eldest son; his former law partner; and four others are charged with turning wedtech into a racketeering enterprise that paid millions of dollars in bribes to win government contracts. since the allegations became public, the company has filed for protection under bankruptcy laws and suspended most operations
moreno, who is cooperating with the government in return for leniency, also described biaggi's lobbying efforts on wedtech's behalf in 1980 when the company was trying to win an army contract to build small engines
prosecutors have charged that wedtech grew from a small bronx machine shop into a $100 million-a-year government contractor, in part, by falsely portraying itself as minority-controlled, in order to qualify for a small business administration program that gave out government contracts without competitive bidding
moreno said he met wedtech co-founders john mariotta and fred neuberger in 1976 when he served as consultant for a local program that assisted small minority-owned businesses
moreno said the pair later told him that mariotta, who is of hispanic descent, owned two-thirds of wedtech, then known as welbilt electronics die corp., and neuberger owned the other third
mariotta is one of those on trial with biaggi. neuberger is one of the four ex-wedtech officials cooperating with prosecutors after pleading guilty to state and federal charges
in 1979, moreno testified, mariotta and neuberger ``told me they each owned 50 percent of the company'' and that they had a ``handshake agreement'' dating back to 1975
but the pair did not reveal that mariotta no longer controlled the company in records presented to the small business administration ``in order to comply with the ... regulations,'' moreno said
the witness also said that in 1979, the company had gross revenues of $1.5 million and about 60 employees but by the following year ``the company was going bankrupt any minute'' because of a scarcity of funds
moreno said wedtech was in line to get more than $4 million in loans through the federal economic development administration in january 1980, but the loan approval was bottlenecked by an overworked eda official in philadelphia
we looked for assistance from several people,'' said moreno, adding that it came from biaggi's former law partner and current co-defendant, bernard ehrlich, who took moreno and mariotta to seek the congressman
biaggi turned the matter over to an aide who knew the philadelphia eda official's boss and a month later wedtech had the loans approved, said moreno
wedtech also tried to win an army contract through the minority business program. the contract was for small, gasoline-powered engines even though wedtech had neither the experience or facilities to build the engines
when the army turned down wedtech's first proposal as too high, company officials again went to biaggi and ehrlich for help, said moreno
biaggi enlisted the help of sen. alfonse d'amato, r-n.y., and the late rep. joseph addabbo, a powerful queens democrat, who wrote the secretary of the army on behalf of wedtech, which eventually got the contract
moreno was scheduled to returned to the stand wednesday
iran lashed out at the security council again tuesday, accusing it of wasting time on an arms embargo proposal instead of ending the deadly missile duel between tehran and baghdad
the security council is responsible for every drop of blood of iranian people, innocent civilians who are the victims of inhuman attacks,'' said iran's u.n. envoy, mohammad ja'afar mahallati
mahallati spoke at a news conference after delivering a protest to secretary-general javier perez de cuellar that accused the council of taking no action to stop the surface-to-surface missile attacks on the iranian and iraqi capitals known as the ``war of the cities.''
the most recent phase of the duel began in late february. after a two day halt, it started again monday. iran and iraq both claim hundreds of civilian casualties
mahallati blamed the united states for encouraging the attacks on cities by pushing for a worldwide arms embargo against iran
the embargo would punish iran for failing to honor the council's july 20 resolution demanding a cease-fire and withdrawal to pre-war boundaries as the first step in a negotiated end to the 7{-year-old iran-iraq war
mahallati told reporters that questions about iran's position on the resolution are ``outdated questions.'' instead, he said, the council should condemn iraq for starting the latest round in the ``war of the cities'' and take action to stop the attacks
he also accused iraq of using chemical weapons and intensifying attacks on neutral shipping in the persian gulf
mahallati would not say precisely what iran wants the council to do other than condemn iraq and stop talking about an embargo
iraq blames iran for starting the missile duel that has killed scores of civilians since feb. 29. both sides describe their attacks as retaliatory and defensive
the united states increased its pressure for an embargo after perez de cuellar ended months of negotiations late last year proclaiming frustration at iran's recalcitrance
the soviet union, which wants better relations with neighboring iran, has not agreed to support an embargo. last week the soviets called for more negotiations and a new security council resolution dealing only with the attacks on cities
the soviets acknowledged monday that they had failed to win council support for that plan
iran and iraq blasted each other's cities tuesday with missiles, bombs and artillery in apparent attempts to terrorize each other into submission in a new ``war of the cities.''
communiques from both sides, monitored in nicosia, reported scores of civilians killed or wounded in the third straight day of new attacks on population centers
we are determined to turn tehran into a hell, the like of which the barbaric scoundrels have never seen before,'' said the iraqi news agency following another barrage of missiles into tehran
persian gulf shipping executives said iraqi warplanes attacked a liberian-flag tanker, chartered by iran, off the iranian coast
they had no details on casualties or damage aboard the 249,223-ton trade fortitude, the second ship damaged in iraqi raids in the gulf since march 8
iraq, which has long held the technological edge in the deadly duel, said it fired six long-range missiles tuesday into tehran, the iranian capital, while its air force bombed seven cities in western iran
iran said it bombarded the southern iraqi port city of basra and nashwa, 12 miles to the north, with 11 short-range missiles and artillery fire and hit four other cities in the northeast and southeast with air raids
the iranians reported no long-range missile attacks on baghdad, the iraqi capital, or any other cities
the absence of any missile attack on baghdad prompted speculation that the iranians may have exhausted their arsenal of long-range missiles in an exchange with the iraqis that began feb. 29 and ended for two days last friday
so far, the iraqis have reported shooting 86 long-range missiles into tehran and other iranian cities in the last 16 days. in contrast, iran has claimed to have fired 31 in that period
in the gulf, the kuwaiti tanker gas prince, one of 11 kuwait tankers reflagged with the stars and stripes to afford them u.s. navy protection from iranian attack, sailed northward in the 17th convoy operation this year
the convoy was the 39th since july, when the navy began escorting the kuwaiti tankers
in riyadh, saudi arabia, foreign ministers of six conservative gulf arab states met to discuss the iran-iraq war
iran's islamic republic news agency said a number of civilians were killed in missile attacks on residential areas of the capital, but did not say how many rockets hit the city of 6 million
iraq also reported civilian casualties in several cities, but gave no figures beyond nine killed and 20 wounded in basra
ap reporter salah nasrawi reported from basra on tuesday that the city was rocked throughout the day by exploding artillery shells and soviet-made katyusha rockets fired by iranian forces east of the city
iranian revolutionary guards battled to within six miles of the city a year ago in a major offensive and have held onto their bridgehead despite iraqi counter-attacks
basra's governor, anwar al-hadithi, said that more than 2,900 shells and nearly 200 rockets have hit the city since feb. 28, killing 50 civilians and wounding around 250 others
the katyushas are the worst,'' al-hadithi said. ``the iranians use truck-mounted launchers which means they can fire and run before our people can locate them. the shrapnel bursts from the rockets is worse than the shells and they kill more people.''
basra was once iraq's second largest city. but its pre-war population of 1 million has dwindled to around 300,000 in the last two years as people fled the iranian bombardment
western military analysts believe baghdad, which began hitting tehran with missiles for the first time feb. 29, wants to provoke iran into retaliation that will intensify pressure on the u.n. security council to impose an arms embargo on iran
western diplomats believe the iraqi strategy is ill-advised because it has provided the soviet union with an excuse to stall on swinging behind u.s. efforts to secure the embargo
moscow is iraq's main arms supplier, but has been at pains in the last two years to improve its relations with tehran in an apparent effort to mediate a cease-fire in the war
in new york, the soviets' u.n. ambassador, alexander belonogov, acknowledged monday that the soviet bid for a resolution calling for an end to the ``war of the cities'' had failed. the united states saw the proposal as a maneuver designed to deflect attention from the american drive for the embargo on iran
and iran's u.n. envoy lashed out at the security council, accusing it of ``wasting'' time on the arms embargo proposal instead of ending the missile duel between tehran and baghdad
the security council is responsible for every drop of blood of iranian people, innocent civilians who are the victims of inhuman attacks,'' said the envoy, mohammad ja'afar mahallati. update with funeral mass. pick up 7th graf, `their bodies ...' adds byline.</note>
two roman catholics were shot dead and hearses bearing the coffins of three irish republican army guerrillas were pelted with stones by jeering protestants, police said tuesday
charles mcgrillan was gunned down from a motorcycle outside a belfast supermarket as he arrived for work tuesday, police said
his death bore the hallmarks of a sectarian murder by protestant terrorists, they said
the night before, police said, troops shot a gunman who fired on an army patrol near the belfast home of one of the dead guerrillas. kevin mccracken, 33, who had a record of ira activity, died later in the hospital
the three guerrillas, killed in gibraltar march 6 by a british anti-terrorism squad as they were planning a car bombing, were to be buried wednesday in the biggest such funeral since 1981, when 10 guerrillas died in prison hunger strikes
catholic sympathy for mairead farrell, 31, sean savage, 24, and daniel mccann, 30, is heightened by the fact that they were unarmed, and the irish government has protested they shouldn't have been killed
the rev. raymond murray, chaplain of the armagh jail where miss farrell spent 10 years on a bombing charge, denounced the killings at a mass for her tuesday night in west belfast
she was done to death, barbarously assaulted by a gunman as she walked in public on a sunny sunday afternoon,'' he told 2,000 people crowded into a catholic church
the three bodies were flown from gibraltar to dublin on monday and driven for nine hours in a cortege to belfast, 100 miles north
thousands of ira sympathizers waved black flags of mourning along highway, while at six points along the 40-mile northern ireland segment of the route, the three hearses were stoned and jeered by protestants to whom the predominantly catholic ira is a mortal enemy
at the ireland-ulster border, the procession ran into northern ireland police demanding the removal of irish flags draped over the coffins. after 30 minutes of argument the mourners compromised by folding the flags, replacing them on the coffins and covering them in wreathes
the tricolor, ireland's national flag, is identified in most protestant minds with the ira
the outlawed ira's legal political wing, sinn fein, said police tried to break up the cortege and twice crashed a vehicle into a hearse
at newry, five miles inside northern ireland, the hearses were paraded around the largely catholic town for two hours in front of cheering ira supporters
on newry's outskirts, protestant crowds jeered, waved british flags and hurled bricks, bottles and stones at the cortege, breaking some car windows
similar scenes repeated themselves along the road to belfast
on monday the ira said its members fired a volley over a makeshift shrine in belfast as a farewell salute to the guerrillas
the traditional paramilitary salute, which is banned in northern ireland as an illegal display of firearms, was fired monday as the bodies landed in dublin, the ira said in a statement issued through sinn fein
the royal ulster constabulary, northern ireland's police force, promised in newspaper advertisements not to interfere with the funerals if the ira did not mount a gunfire salute over the coffins
sinn fein president gerry adams accused the the police of partially splitting up the convoy, sending cars with relatives of the three guerrillas into mainly protestant lisburn, eight miles outside belfast where they were stoned
in belfast, adams said, the ruc ``hijacked the three hearses by forcing them down to broadway and refused to allow the remaining relatives to accompany their loved ones.''
police said that near belfast they separated the hearses from the rest of the slow-moving funeral procession, which had grown to several miles in length
the coffins were taken to the homes of the guerrillas' families in belfast. they will be buried at belfast's catholic milltown cemetery alongside many other ira guerrillas killed in nearly 20 years of strife in the province
since 1969, 2,630 people have died in sectarian violence. the ira is fighting to rid northern ireland of british rule and unite the province with ireland
a democratic fund-raiser on whose behalf house speaker jim wright once interceded was indicted tuesday in an alleged scheme to defraud an iowa thrift institution in a land deal
thomas merrill gaubert, 48, of desoto, texas, was accused by a federal grand jury in des moines, iowa, of arranging for the capitol savings and loan association of mount pleasant, iowa, to unwittingly finance a ``land flip'' in dallas county, texas
gaubert bought some 44 acres of the dallas county land at less than 50 cents per square foot, then sold it the same day through a middleman to 22 buyers at $5.25 per square foot, the indictment alleged
he also was accused of denying involvement in the project and failing to disclose to s&amp;l regulators, as well as state and federal regulators, that during the transaction he was to be a buyer and a seller of the land
the real estate developer was accused of wire fraud, making false statements to a federally insured financial institution and making a false statement to the government
gaubert is a prominent democratic fund-raiser and former owner of the independent american savings association in irving, texas, who contributed $7,000 to a pair of wright political committees in 1985
in the fall of 1986, wright, d-texas, then house majority leader, urged federal home loan bank board chairman edwin gray to meet with gaubert to hear his complaints about the board's treatment of independent american
at wright's urging, gray spent 2{ hours with gaubert. wright said he was simply encouraging gray to ensure that his agency was being fair to one of wright's constituents
the s&amp;l industry in texas is focus of a massive federal criminal investigative effort that has resulted in a number of indictments of prominent businessmen. gaubert has called the federal effort ``a witchunt.''
texas leads the nation in s&amp;l losses and failures, and federal insurance officials say fraud, inside abuse and gross mismanagement have contributed to the problem as well as the economic recession in texas
the maximum penalty for wire fraud is a $1,000 fine and five years in prison. making false statements to a federally insured financial institution carries a maximum $5,000 fine and two years in prison. making false statements to the government carries a maximum $10,000 fine and 10 years in prison
former national security council staff aide roger w. robinson made a 2{-hour federal grand jury appearance tuesday in the criminal investigation of attorney general edwin meese iii and a proposed $1 billion iraqi oil pipeline
robinson declined to discuss his testimony following his appearance. he was the aide designated by then-national security adviser robert mcfarlane in june 1985 to work on expediting the pipeline, which was floundering for lack of an insurance package sought by iraq to insure it from israeli attack
robinson was assigned to get the project back on track following a meeting by mcfarlane, longtime meese friend e. robert wallach and wallach's client swiss oilman bruce rappaport, a partner in the proposed pipeline. meese had referred wallach to mcfarlane the previous month
working with wallach, robinson tried unsuccessfully to help assemble a $400 million bank-backed insurance package acceptable to the overseas private investment corp
the government agency insures foreign investments by u.s. firms such as bechtel group inc., which was going to build the project. opic officials wanted guarantees that funds would be available from some source to cover losses if the pipeline were destroyed
robinson is the second nsc aide in two weeks to testify in the probe of meese being conducted by independent counsel james mckay. the other was david wigg, who took robinson's place on the project
two former aides in meese's office, john richardson and john harrison, testified last week before the grand jury to which mckay's office is presenting evidence. richardson was meese's chief of staff before leaving the justice department several months ago. harrison, now with the solicitor general's office, worked on meese's staff in mid-1985
the probe of meese revolves around whether he may have violated the 1977 foreign corrupt practices act, which prohibits bribes by u.s. companies or their agents to foreign officials
wallach wrote a memo to the attorney general in september 1985 saying that a portion of up to $700 million from the pipeline would be paid to the israeli labor party of then-prime minister shimon peres. meese says he doesn't recall reading the portion of the memo relating to labor party payments
robinson left the nsc on sept. 14, 1985, and his place on the pipeline project was taken by wigg, who worked with wallach on alternative proposals. those included pledging u.s. aid to israel as a guarantee for the pipeline and seeking to put pentagon budget money for israel in an overseas escrow account as insurance
none of the insurance proposals was adopted and the pipeline wasn't built
on tuesday afternoon, john h. mcneill of the pentagon office of general counsel appeared before the grand jury
mcneill worked with wigg on the pentagon budget proposal, according to sources familiar with mckay's probe, speaking on condition of anonymity. mcneill, who declined comment on his testimony, is the assistant general counsel for international and intelligence matters
mcneill and robinson are both witnesses in the probe rather than subjects or targets and do not have legal counsel. name of kneebone to terence, not terrence. no pickup</note>
by reid g. miller
medical workers hurled firebombs at police outside a hospital on tuesday, joining a wave of public employees rallying against the cash-strapped government of gen. manuel antonio noriega
sections of the capital were turned into battlegrounds as hundreds of civil servants took to the streets to demand their paychecks. riot squads fired tear gas, water cannons and shotguns loaded with birdshot. at least a dozen people were injured
americans became involved
_panama ordered terence kneebone, director of the u.s. information service here, to leave the country within 48 hours, a u.s. embassy source said. the united states said it would ignore the directive because it was delivered by a regime not recognized by the united states as the legitimate authority
_the u.s. southern command said panamanian police detained three american soldiers in the port of colon, at the caribbean entrance of the panama canal, but released them several hours later. the command also said it upgraded the alert status for its 10,000 personnel and 20,000 dependents
_a photographer for the dallas morning news, david leeson, was among those hurt in the worst demonstration at the main social security institute hospital in northern panama city. a shotgun pellet pierced his cheek and chipped a tooth
leeson was treated at the hospital's emergency room, along with at least seven othe people. three were hit in the face by birdshot and two children were overcome by tear gas
other slightly wounded demonstrators spurned hospital care
medical workers hurled molotov cocktails at police just outside the grounds of the sprawling facility and riot police responded with shotgun fire and tear gas grenades. fumes penetrated the interior of the 500-bed hospital
assassins,'' cried hospital employees. ``noriega, tyrant, your end is near!''
the complex includes the six-story hospital, a specialized clinic and administrative offices
several miles away, in the heart of the city, police spraying diluted tear gas from a water cannon broke up a demonstration by about 300 teachers and employees of the ministry of education
disturbances flared monday when thousands of public employees failed to receive semimonthly paychecks. strikes begun by teachers, telephone workers and longshoremen were joined tuesday by employees of the ministry of treasury and finance
the government announced it would begin making at least partial salary payments tuesday to its employees. but workers at the hospital, the treasury and education departments said they had not heard of the plan
it was not known late tuesday how many workers actually got paid, either in full or partially
we were protesting peacefully because we were supposed to get paid yesterday (monday) and we still do not know anything,'' said a nurse, who refused to give her name. ``i had to borrow money from my grandfather to come to work.''
in washington, the reagan administration has let it be known it hopes panama's difficulties in meeting its payrolls will lead to strongman noriega's removal as head of the 15,000-member defense forces
two u.s. grand juries indicted noriega last month on charges of trafficking in drugs. noriega denied the charges
riot police stepped in to quell the demonstration at the social security hospital when workers built barricades of rubbish across a four-lane, divided highway, halting heavy morning rush-hour traffic in both directions
firing tear gas grenades, police moved the workers back behind a heavy wire fence surrounding the hospital. some employees, wearing surgical masks against the gas, used metal tabletops as shields to throw rocks at the police
then some workers, mostly young men, made firebombs and hurled them at police. they used surgical gauze for wicks after pouring gasoline into empty rum bottles
other employees were seen throwing furniture from upstairs windows of the six-story hospital. at least one policeman was struck on the head by a rock
this is a hospital!,'' cried a nurse. ``how can they do this! we are under siege!''
students threw rocks at police from a university building across the highway
treasury minister hector alexander said the government planned to pay workers on a sliding scale. employees making less than $200 a month would get full wages. those getting up to $999 would get $75. people making more than $1000 would get nothing
more than 1,000 dockworkers remained on strike at colon and panama city, the entrances to the the 50-mile-long panama canal that links the pacific and atlantic oceans
the panama canal commission said tuesday the walkout had not affected transit through the waterway, which handles an average 30 ships a day
the reagan administration hopes government inability to pay its workers will bring down noriega, who engineered the ouster of president eric arturo delvalle on feb. 26 after delvalle tried to fire him
the united states imposed new economic sanctions on panama last friday, including withholding $6.5 million in canal fees due this week. it earlier cut off all economic and military aid to panama
foreign and local banks have remained closed in panama
in washington, the panamanian embassy said delvalle instructed ambassador juan b. sosa that once noriega is gone, ``all funds that have been frozen in escrow will be primarily used to pay the salary of public workers, a duty that the illegimate government has been unable to accomplish.''
sosa refused to recognize the feb. 26 change in government and continues to support delvalle
asked tuesday about the possibility of waiving extradition to speed noriega's departure from panama, president reagan said, ``we do want noriega out of there and a return to a civilian democratic government.''
the pilot of a soviet jetliner that crashed killing 11 passengers allowed his co-pilot to try a difficult night landing for which he was not prepared, a government commission said tuesday
the government newspaper izvestia published the findings of a commission that studied the crash of an aeroflot tu-154b at the caspian sea port of krasnovodsk on jan. 18
it said prosecutors have started criminal proceedings in the case
the three-engine jet, carrying 137 passengers from moscow to krasnovodsk and then on to ashkabad was flying normally until the approach to krasnovodsk in the early morning hours, the report said
pilot v.s. churayev permitted co-pilot v.d. yegorov to land the plan, even though yegorov was not trained sufficiently for landing in the difficult conditions at krasnovodsk, according to the report
the report did not say why the landing in krasnovodsk was difficult
it said yegorov made mistakes in his approach that brought the plane down too rapidly from a height of 150 feet and even though churayev took over the controls at the last minute, the plane flipped over on landing and broke in two
it was one of three times this year that passengers were killed in aeroflot flight crashes reported by the soviet media
on feb. 27 a tupolev 134 crashed at the siberian city of sumgut. the media said there were casualties, but did not say how many
on march 8, a family musical group from irkutsk tried to hijack a tupolev 154 bound for leningrad. a stewardess, three passengers and five of the hijackers were killed before the plane was retaken by security officers
the head of the justice department's criminal division said tuesday that an early draft of a federal prosecution strategy against drugs would have targeted resources almost exclusively at the world's 150 biggest narcotics rings
assistant attorney general william weld said the approach has been broadened after extensive discussions with u.s. attorneys so that smaller operations will be targeted in federal drug prosecutions
i want that dealer in lowell, mass., not to be sure he won't be picked up in a federal undercover operation,'' weld, a former u.s. attorney in boston, said in an interview. ``i don't want people to be able to relax anywhere.''
weld said that when he first considered focusing exclusively on the largest drug rings, ``i ran into a little bit of a buzz saw'' from some u.s. attorneys
committing ``an untoward percentage of those resources to miami, new york, chicago'' and the other major drug centers ``creates the public perception of gaps in enforcement,'' said weld. ``the bad guys are going to play hit 'em where they ain't.''
if we were going to be entirely logical we might say the only purpose of prosecution is to disrupt the supply'' by aiming ``at the top-most levels of supply in the world,'' weld said. abandoning regions of the country would send a mixed signal that ``it's not ok to be a member of the medillin cartel, but it is ok to be a little fish.''
of the refinements, he said: ``frankly, i'm happier with the compromise than i was with my own first draft.''
the prosecution strategy is one proposed piece of the federal drug-fighting effort now being mapped out by a number of agencies. the proposals, now in final form, will be presented to the national drug policy board for approval and will be publicly announced by early next month
the 159-nation general assembly is expected to ask the world court to rule on whether the united states can close the plo's u.n. observer mission in new york, an arab league spokesman said tuesday
league spokesman clovis maksoud and u.n. sources said the assembly would convene friday
the u.s. justice department has said it would move on or around monday to enforce a new anti-terrorism law calling for the closure of the palestine liberation organization's mission office
maksoud said the league will ask the assembly to take a cautious approach
he said it will not ask the assembly to suspend israel from debates on the middle east, as the plo has suggested, or to move to another country. both would be premature, he said
the provocation was reckless. we don't want to respond with recklessness,'' maksoud said in an interview
scores of nations said during a special session earlier this month on the plo dispute that the independence of the united nations is at stake
the increasingly bitter confrontation has prompted some calls to move the world body to geneva, which western diplomats say is unlikely
nobody wants to move the headquarters,'' maksoud said
u.n. sources said tuesday that preliminary studies show the cost of moving the assembly to geneva would be ``excessive,'' in part because u.n. facilities there are not adequate
both the united nations and the u.s. state department have said closing the plo mission would violate the 1947 treaty under which the united states became u.n. headquarters
maksoud said the arab league will not ask the united nations to go to federal court to fight the justice department
he said the united nations should not subject itself to the jurisdiction of a domestic court
instead, the league will ask the assembly to request a ruling from the world court in the hague on whether the united states has the right to close down any mission to the united nations
the plo, an official observer at the general assembly since 1974, has said it will apppear in a u.s. court only if ``dragged in,'' and then only to challenge the court's jurisdiction over a u.n. matter. accuser</head> background on trial, defense contention on milstead sex life, picking up 19th graf, `house prosecutor...'. subs grafs 25-28 bgng `before mrs...'. with 2 grafs to add that no decision on motion to increase length of sessions, deleting material to trim. should stand for ams.</note>
a woman who claims she was a lover of gov. evan mecham's chief accuser testified at mecham's impeachment trial tuesday about the relationship despite the presiding officer's order to keep sex out of the trial
defense witness christina johnston told senators she was ``intimate'' with the state's top lawman, department of public safety director ralph milstead
milstead has testified that mecham ordered him not to cooperate with an investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official against a prospective grand jury witness. milstead has said he did cooperate
the alleged obstruction of the death-threat probe is one of three broad charges against mecham at his impeachment trial. he also is accused of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan and of misusing $80,000 from a state fund by loaning it to his auto dealership
mecham, 63, a first-term republican and the first u.s. governor to face an impeachment trial in six decades, has not attended since the proceedings began feb. 29
the defense has claimed it can raise milstead's sexual activities to attack his crediblity and character, but arizona supreme court chief justice frank x. gordon jr. earlier ruled the issue irrelevant
prosecuting attorney paul eckstein repeatedly objected tuesday that mrs. johnston's testimony, elicited by mecham lawyer fred craft, violated gordon's order, but she managed some comment on their relationship
mrs. johnston testified she had known milstead since 1979 and had no professional relationship with him
have you had a personal relationship with him?'' asked craft
intimate and personal,'' she answered in a forceful voice before a prosecutor could object
milstead has said he knew her as a dps informant, but he was not asked about a sexual relationship
mrs. johnston and her husband, mark, a former dps officer, have said publicly they are ``out to get'' milstead
craft angrily declared tuesday he was being prevented from ``getting at the truth'' as he asked mrs. johnston personal questions, including why she had been married six times. she said she was not married when she met ralph milstead
was he married?'' craft asked
he told me he wasn't,'' she said with a smile as the prosecution objected
the judge began sustaining a blizzard of prosecution objections, and craft finally sputtered: ``maybe i just don't understand the rules.''
that may be a good statement,'' said gordon
mrs. johnston was permitted to denounce milstead as a liar
he's a liar. he's corrupt. he's an egomaniac and he's power-hungry,'' mrs. johnston declared as she was asked by mecham's lawyer to evaluate milstead's truthfulness. ``i'm sorry, but that's the truth,'' she added softly
milstead has said that mark johnston quit the force under strange circumstances, disappearing for about a week while on duty. he said that mrs. johnston recently had sought her husband's reinstatement with the dps but that he had failed a psychological test
house prosecutor william french accused craft of creating a smokescreen with claims of witness-tampering to disguise that ``apparently there is no defense.''
among craft's allegations was the arrest of defense witness terri fields on friday, the day after she testified, on an outstanding warrant charging that she failed to attend court-ordered alcoholics anonymous meetings following a driving-while-intoxicated conviction. she was released on $1,000 bond. the dps has denied the arrest was an attempt to intimidate impeachment trial witnesses
french, in response to craft's claim that dps officers were intimidating witnesses, submitted an explosive affidavit from a defense witness
antonio corio claimed that craft spewed profanity at him, made bizarre claims about milstead's sex life and threatened to ``tear up'' the witness if he didn't give the right answers
craft later called those allegations ``scurrilous in the extreme. ... it's a lie.''
milstead is in israel for an anti-terrorism seminar, but dps spokesman sgt. allan schmidt called the alleged statements by craft ``disgusting.'' asked for further comment, he said, ``you can't print it.''
the senate did not immediately rule on a mistrial motion by craft based on the tampering allegations, and continued the proceedings
the senate also made no decision tuesday on a proposal to extend the length of the trial day by two hours to speed up the proceedings. craft said it would be a hardship for defense attorneys and the judge indicated he felt the current schedule already is longer and more arduous than a normal trial schedule
senate republican majority leader robert usdane said the matter would be reconsidered later in the week
it would take a two-thirds vote of the senate to convict mecham. the senators could vote again and bar the governor from holding state office again. mecham also faces an april 21 criminal trial on the charge that he concealed the $350,000 loan, and a recall election is scheduled may 17
lord hugh rupert courtenay sold his bookshelves and got to keep them, too, on tuesday, for a record-setting $841,750
london's victoria and albert museum bought the two antique bookcases but agreed to let courtenay keep them so long as they are on show to the public in his library
the museum said the price was a record for a piece of english furniture sold in britain
the bookcases will stay in courtenay's ancestral home, powderham castle, devon, which courtenay runs for his father, the 17th earl of devon
the bookcases were made in 1740 by john channon of exeter. the museum was given the money by the national heritage fund, a charity which preserves historic objects for the nation
courtenay, 46, said he loses $74,000 a year on the castle and needs more than $1.85 million to pay taxes and fund improvements in the castle. details of later rally, dissident says he was released. picks up 10th graf pvs, hungary dissidents ...</note>
about 10,000 people chanting ``democracy! democracy!'' marched through the streets of this communist capital tuesday and called for a free press and free elections
police turned out in force, but took no action as protesters yelled anti-government slogans and speakers criticized the soviet system
the throng marched several miles down budapest's main boulevards, blocking traffic and waving red, white and green hungarian flags
the unofficial protest followed a rally organized earlier in the day by the communist party to mark the anniversary of hungary's abortive 1848 revolution against austria, one of this east european nation's biggest holidays
the time is over for self-appointed governments,'' prominent dissident gabor miklos tamas told the throng, in a reference to the nation's communist authorities. ``a modern democracy has to be created with a new constitution and free elections.''
the crowd marched to monuments of hungarian national heroes and paid particular tribute to firebrand poet sandor petoefi, whose name is symbolic of resistance to foreign suppression in hungary
protesters chanted ``democracy! democracy!'' and waved banners reading, ``we want real reforms'' or ``we demand freedom of the press.''
later tuesday night, a crowd of about 1,500, most of them young people, gathered at the petoefi monument and then moved across the margaret bridge to the castle hill, where they repeated calls for democracy and press freedom
about 150 people then moved back to the chain bridge, intending to return to the petoefi monument, but witnesses said the demonstrators were dispersed by waiting riot police, who held clubs but did not hit anybody
hours after the unofficial demonstration was over, the state news agency mti reported that eight people, mostly dissident intellectuals, were arrested. the five-line report gave only their names
they were writer miklos haraszti, sociologist ottlia solt, publisher gabor demszky, artist tamas molnar, gyoergy gado, jenoe nagy and two lesser known dissidents, sandor racz and robert palinkas
haraszti later said he had been released and that he assumed the others had also been set free, but this could not be confirmed immediately
hungarian dissidents have staged unofficial demonstrations on march 15 since 1973. police generally have shown restraint, although dozens of officers clashed violently with protesters in 1986
hungary has won a reputation as a relatively liberal soviet bloc country, although far less dissent is tolerated than in western countries
at tuesday's rally, groups of protesters whistled and applauded rhythmically as police vehicles passed by, but authorities did not react to what appeared to be attempts to provoke them
roza demszky, the wife of one of the arrested dissidents, read her husband's speech to the crowd
the soviet system has led hungary into a crisis ``and does not show any way out,'' she said
the reforms promised by the hungarian revolution of 1848 ``have not yet been realized in this country,'' she added
speakers gathered at a monument to lajos kossuth, the leader of the 1848 revolt, to read poems by petoefi
in the earlier official rally, a crowd of 5,000 people gathered near budapest's national museum, where the 1848 revolution first began
communist party speakers called for more national unity and economic progress, and laid a plaque commemorating the revolution
small groups dressed in folk costumes sang national songs and told events of the aborted revolution
hungary recently has imposed an austerity program to try to reverse economic stagnation, and its leadership is contemplating political reforms
george bush won the illinois republican presidential primary tuesday and received an early evening concession from sen. bob dole's campaign manager. as the votes were being counted, dole vowed ``to keep working'' in the primary states to come
an american communications satellite launched into a low orbit last week rocketed successfully tuesday into a geosynchronous orbit 22,300 miles above the earth's equator
the satellite, spacenet iii, owned by gte corp., fired its apogee kick motor, a small rocket engine, at 11:57 a.m. est, some 90 hours after its launch friday night by a french ariane rocket
gte officials said the 1,562-pound spacenet iii would initiate a stabilizing spin tuesday night. this will lock its antennae into contact with earth. once that is accomplished and verified, the satellite will deploy an array of solar power cells that provide the craft with electricity
gte engineers will conduct a series of tests of the craft and the the satellite will start operations early in april
spacenet iii provides a communications link between points in all 50 of the united states. clients include the associated press and the television groups of abc, cbs, cnn and gannett
the u.s. satellite and a french communications satellite were launched together on friday aboard an ariane rocket from the european space agency launch site in kourou, french guiana. gte spacenet is the first american client of arianespace, the operating arm of the european space agency. routine aids tests legal in california.</note>
all blood samples taken for routine clinical testing at 40 hospitals in 30 states now are also being tested for aids, the director of centers for disease control said tuesday
dr. james mason, director of the cdc, said at a congressional hearing that ``blinded'' blood tests are being conducted at the hospitals in an effort to help determine the incidence of aids, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome
rep. william e. dannemeyer, r-calif., a member of the house energy and commerce subcommittee on health and the environment, asked mason if he was aware that california has a law that forbids aids testing without consent
then i sure am committing lots of crimes every day,'' said mason
an official with the california state committee on aids such certain ``blinded'' tests are legal
mason said the tests were under way in hospitals in both san francisco and los angeles
mason said results of the testing are now being compiled and will be released to the public in two to three weeks
in the ``blinded'' tests, said mason, a portion of each routine blood sample taken at the hospitals is separated out and then tested for aids. he said the blood used for the aids testing carries no identification of the patient who provided the sample, hence the identity of the donor is ``blinded'' to the laboratory conducting the tests
debra smith, administrative secretary to a california state committee on aids, said the ``blinded'' tests are legal. she said a statute passed in 1987 permits such tests for statistical purposes
mason's statement came during hearings chaired by rep. henry a. waxman, d-calif., into the way that the nation's aids research dollars are being spent
mason, along with dr. frank young, commissioner of the food and drug administration, and dr. james wyngaarden, director of the national institutes of health, all said they were experiencing difficulty in hiring scientists and other health care professionals because the federal salaries are below those offered in universities or in industry
wyngaarden said that the turnover among investigators is about 2 percent a year
we're losing some of our most outstanding people,'' he said, for reasons that involved salary, laboratory facilities and other ``complex'' reasons
he said this is particularly true of allied health workers, such as nurses, laboratory technicians and x-ray technicians. he said there is a salary differential among those workers of about 25 percent
they will stay through the training period and then leave for more money,'' said wyngaarden
dr. tony fauci, deputy director for aids research at nih, said top investigators frequently receive offers to move to university or industry positions that offer a higher salary, better facilities and more laboratory personnel
there is a rather significant difference in salaries (between federal and private),'' he said. ``we are constantly fighting that battle.''
fauci said the outpatient clinic at the nih treated 4,500 aids patients during 1987 and that more and more of them are becoming critically ill and in need of intensive care
the staff problems will have a negative impact'' on the amount of care available at the clinics, he said
young said his agency is experiencing difficulty in recruiting personnel trained to evaluate drugs and medical issues. he said it typically takes about two years to train personnel, and they often leave the fda shortly after the training is completed in order to receive higher pay elsewhere
frustrated, angry and unwilling to admit defeat, bob dole insisted there was a turning point out there, a state where voters would say, ``wait a minute, we don't want george bush.'' but dole's campaign was hard-pressed to identify that turnaround state
it wasn't likely to happen in connecticut, one of the states bush calls home. and the republican presidential polls don't look promising for dole in wisconsin, new york or pennsylvania
so that takes us another month and a half without a big opportunity for a victory,'' said one top dole adviser, insisting on anonymity
before the polls opened tuesday in illinois, dole conceded that big state to bush
with bush continuing to build his delegate lead, dole was dogged by the question of how long he could or would stay in the race
when dole returned to washington tuesday night, he insisted, ``we're just going to hang in there. ... we're staying in, we're staying in.''
was there a realistic chance of catching the vice president?
the numbers suggested there wasn't
going into the illinois primary, bush already had 705 of the 1,139 delegates needed for the nomination. dole had 165
bush would need only one-third of the 1,318 delegates still to be chosen
obviously, if dole started winning two-thirds of the delegates in upcoming contests, the vice president's huge lead would evaporate. but there was no sign of that happening
the iran-contra affair appeared to offer a bit of hope to dole
when robert mcfarlane agreed to cooperate with the special counsel investigating the affair, it renewed the hope within the dole campaign that attention once again would focus on what role bush had in deliberations that led to the sale of arms to iran and diversion of funds to the contras
in a speech to the chicago council on foreign relations, dole referred to presidential advisers ``peddling arms to the ayatollah while others hear no evil, see no evil.''
but he later conceded that iran-contra was not an issue among republicans, though he predicted it would be used against the party's nominee by the democrats
dole's frustration was apparent when he was asked why he didn't attack bush more directly on iran-contra
if i hit him, i get ronald reagan first and then they say, oh, oh, he's out there attacking ronald reagan,'' he replied
nothing so frustrates and angers dole as bush's success in tying himself to reagan, a president who remains enormously popular among republicans
dole referred to bush commercials that show the vice president conferring with reagan and, in one scene, the president putting an arm over bush's shoulders
i don't have nearly as many pictures of ronald reagan as george bush has,'' said dole. ``he must have a pile six feet deep. i can't match him in photos. but i can match him in record.''
bush blew the republican race open with his sweeping victory on super tuesday
but dole is reluctant to give the vice president credit for accomplishing anything on his own. ``super tuesday was, in my view, a referendum on ronald reagan and reagan won,'' said the senator
he sees bush as someone who has ``sort of had a charmed life in politics. he's gotten quite a ways without ever doing much.''
that view may contribute to dole's belief that it could all unravel for bush if he can ``get people to stop and think.''
the senator admitted he has considered various tactics that might blunt the bush momentum, including borrowing one from ronald reagan _ naming his running mate. reagan tried that in 1976 when he challenged incumbent republican president ford
reagan, fighting to overcome a perception that he was too conservative, said early in the race he would name moderate republican sen. richard schweicker of pennsylvania as his running mate
it didn't work for reagan, but as dole said, ``when you're looking for ways to catch up, you think of maybe naming your running mate.'' one of the names on dole's list was former gov. lamar alexander of tennessee. he said there were others, but he didn't name them
on election day in illinois, dole campaigned in wisconsin and connecticut
but connecticut, with 35 delegates, is the state where bush grew up and where his father served as a senator. connecticut didn't look like a good state for dole, said the senator's adviser
polls in wisconsin, which chooses 47 delegates in a primary on april 5, gave bush a big lead. only a dole victory in illinois seemed likely to turn it around
the biggest upcoming prize is new york, which elects 102 gop delegates on april 19. bush has already been credited with 24 of those because his backers are running unopposed in several districts
a week later, pennsylvania, with 78 delegates, votes, and the dole adviser described the state as ``controlled pretty tightly'' by bush
even while claiming he was going to fight on, dole showed glimpses of the political realist
he referred to candidates who don't realize when it's time to bow out
he said, ``now if you're out there and you've been twisting in the wind for six or eight months and you're starting to smell a little, maybe somebody has to cut the rope.'' also strangled, giving victim's name, hometown; no one else believed missing from the ship. picks up 5th graf pvs, `a search...'.</note>
a naval paymaster was found beaten and strangled tuesday aboard the destroyer uss john hancock and $120,000 was stolen from the ship's safe, a naval spokesman said
the officer's body was found stuffed into a sea locker in another part of the ship, said chief petty officer art riccio. ``he was beaten up pretty bad.'' later, officials said the victim, identified as for lt. ratish prasad, 24, of park forest, ill., also had been strangled
the search for prasad began when he failed to report to muster at 7:15 a.m., said riccio. mayport petty officer billy hill said tuesday evening that nobody else was known to be missing from the ship
a search of the disbursement office found the safe open and $120,000 in cash and an undetermined number of blank checks missing, riccio said
tuesday was payday for navy personnel, who are paid the first and 15th of each month, said riccio. ``an audit of the ship's funds is pending and alternate arrangements have been made to pay the crew,'' he said
navy and jacksonville sheriff's investigators were working on the case, he said
mayport is the hancock's home port. access to the ship, which was tied in the port, is strictly controlled, said riccio. anyone wanting to board must pass checkpoints at the base entrance, the pier area and the ship itself
only relatives and friends of the crew who have been previously cleared are allowed aboard the ship in port, he said. even navy personnel who do not have business on the ships cannot board, he said
construction workers doing repairs can go aboard, but riccio said the hancock had no repair work scheduled
the navy refuses to comment on whether nuclear weapons are aboard a vessel, but destroyers do not ususally carry such arms. to update with nicaraguan officials confirming offensive, denying that honduran territory penetrated; picks up 4th graf pvs bgng: the operation ....</note>
nicaraguan forces, using aerial bombardment and heavy artillery, launched a major offensive tuesday against contra rebels in the northern part of the country and sent troops into neighboring honduras, u.s. and contra officials said
they have overrun certain of our positions,'' said ernesto palazio, director of the contra's washington office
palazio estimated that about 3,500 front line sandinista forces aided by 4,000 backup troops were involved
in managua, nicaraguan officials confirmed that a ``major military offensive'' had been launched, but denied that sandinista forces had penetrated into honduran territory
the operation occurred less than a week before the rescheduled resumption of cease-fire talks and some democrats in congress pictured it as a sandinista attempt to go into the negotiations from a stronger position
one state department official, speaking on condition he not be identified, said initial reports suggested the sandinistas hoped to deliver a ``knockout blow'' against the contras
the military engagements came shortly after a 1{-hour white house meeting at which president reagan pleaded with congressional leaders for a renewal of american aid to the contras, but met an icy reception from democrats
congressional sources, declining to be identified, said reagan pounded the table and said, ``there are some people around this table who don't seem to know who the bad guys are down there.''
contra spokesman bosco matamoros said the sandinistas' soviet-made antonov planes dropped 500 to 1,000-pound bombs on contra troop concentrations
he said contra air resupply capability is extremely limited. the rebels are low on food and lack the ability to evacuate their wounded, he said
in miami, marta sacasa, another spokesman for the resistance, said the sandinistas struck at contra positions with heavy artillery, including multiple rocket launchers
the situation is critical,'' she said
the state department said earlier that preparations by government forces appeared to foreshadow ``the largest offensive we have seen the sandinistas undertake.''
but house democratic aides, also speaking on condition of anonymity, said the offensive by sandinista troops was merely ``business as usual'' and an attempt to ``soften up'' the contras before the cease-fire negotiations resume
house majority leader thomas foley, d-wash., acknowledged that ``there is some military activity'' in the country, but declined to elaborate
we don't know their intentions, and they (the administration) don't know their intentions,'' said one democratic congressional source
another democratic congressional source said it was clear that the contras are having supply problems, in part because of an administration decision to spend the last aid money on long-term truck and air delivery contracts, anticipating that a house-drafted ``humanitarian'' aid package would be approved. instead, the package was voted down on march 3
after the white house session, house speaker jim wright said reagan's plea for a renewal of aid puzzled him
it doesn't really seem to make total sense,'' wright, d-texas, said
he said it was house republicans, acting in concert with reagan, who defeated a $30 million package of food and clothing for the rebels two weeks ago, just after their u.s. aid pipeline had run dry
he expressed ``amazement'' that reagan would cheer the defeat of that package, then two weeks later come to congress with an urgent request for new supplies. ``i can't conceive of it,'' wright said
wright quoted reagan's national security adviser, colin powell, as telling congressional leaders that ``virtually all aspects'' of the contra effort are ``in crisis and on the verge of collapse, that food for the contra families will run out the first of april. the program is drying up and dying before our very eyes.''
in december, 1986, honduran warplanes and artillery pounded sandinista soldiers who mounted an incursion into honduras to attack contra bases. on that occasion, u.s. army helicopters were brought in to ferry honduran infantrymen to the front
at that time, honduras charged that 800 to 2,500 sandinista soldiers crossed the border and penetrated up to nine miles into honduras before returning to nicaragua about a week later
since u.s. aid to the rebels expired feb. 29 and the house voted narrowly on march 3 against a new ``humanitarian'' aid package, the contras have fallen back toward border areas to defend supply caches, state department spokesman charles redman said. that means ``they cannot use normal guerrilla tactics to disperse and escape superior sandinista firepower and manpower being brought to bear on them,'' he said
wright said he did not know the extent of any sandinista preparations, but said he has ``earnestly implored'' the managua government to act in good faith. he said his message for the sandinistas was: ``you are in a position of strength. do not abuse that strength.''
democratic house leaders said they had offered to revive the $30 million ``humanitarian'' aid proposal they had offered on march 3, but got no immediate response from white house officials. they said if they were to revive the package, it would be only with the guaranteed backing of gop members who opposed it the last time around
but wright appeared unwilling to budge on the central issue of whether any aid package would include the right for the president, under certain conditions, to ask for and get a quick, guaranteed congressional vote on additional military aid for the rebels
the bottom line is ... members are not willing to vote for another expedited procedure,'' as the guaranteed vote is called, he said
sen. paul simon cashed in on home-state loyalties in the illinois democratic presidential primary and won support even from voters who doubt he can win the nomination or the presidency, exit polls said tuesday
jesse jackson, another illinois resident, again won overwhelming support from black voters, and increased his share of the white vote to about 8 percent, three percentage points better than he did in illinois in 1984, polls said
the way i'm looking at the numbers, hometown boys do good,'' said doug muzzio, an abc news poll analyst
among republicans, vice president george bush defeated sen. bob dole among virtually all ideological and demographic groups. dole kept pace with bush only among independents who voted in the gop primary
bush once again defeated former television evangelist pat robertson even among his most likely supporters, born-again christians and those concerned with moral values, abc, nbc news and cbs news-new york times polls said
overwhelmingly, supporters of jackson and of massachusetts gov. michael dukakis said their candidate had the best chance to win in november, abc said. but only 40 percent of simon's supporters gave him the best chance, and 35 percent named dukakis even though they voted for simon
simon's voters don't think he has the best chance in november but they're voting for him anyway,'' said muzzio. ``his vote seems to be a home-state favorite vote.''
similarly, nbc news found that 80 percent of dukakis' supporters and 60 percent of jackson's thought their man would win the nomination, while only 35 percent of simon's voters thought he would be nominated. more simon voters _ 39 percent _ thought dukakis eventually would win the nomination
simon is a true favorite-son type candidate,'' said sheldon gawiser, an nbc poll analyst. ``he has a 67 percent favorable opinion rating. they think he's doing a good job as senator.''
though dukakis finished third in the voting, abc said a plurality of democrats, 35 percent, thought he was the democrat most likely to win the general election in november. next was jackson with 27 percent; simon had 18 percent and 12 percent selected gov. mario cuomo of new york, who is not a candidate but has refused to rule out a convention draft
about a quarter of the electorate was black, and jackson won 91 percent of the black vote, 20 points better than in 1984, abc said
jackson improved his showing among whites, but less so, winning 8 percent compared to 5 percent in 1984, muzzio said. the racial division was so dramatic, said gawiser, ``there are two electorates: black and white.''
the groups had somewhat different concerns. the cbs news-new york times poll found that 53 percent of blacks cited unemployment as one of their two greatest concerns and 45 percent cited poverty. unemployment also led among white concerns, at 39 percent; protecting social security was second, cited by 29 percent
in the republican vote, the cbs-times poll said 70 percent of the voters had selected their candidate before super tuesday, when bush won 16 of 17 states. the polls again indicated that good will toward president reagan had translated into support for the vice president
nbc said 27 percent of the republican voters said they were born-again protestants, and 54 percent voted for bush, to 27 percent for dole and 17 percent for robertson. abc said 17 percent were white born-again christians; bush got 37 percent, dole 35, robertson 26 percent
robertson is not doing well among his core constituency, and he's not moving beyond it,'' muzzio said
the cbs-times poll said 21 percent of the republican voters cited traditional moral values as one of their chief concerns, and bush won that group with 43 percent, to 29 percent for robertson and 25 percent for dole
it's a very broad bush victory,'' said gawiser. ``he's solid across the board.''
the surveys were conducted by interviewing a random sample of voters as they left their polling places. the margin of sampling error for the results was about 5 points
a radio journalist was suspended tuesday for breaking broadcast laws by interviewing a sympathizer of the irish republican army, considered a ``subversive group.''
ireland's state-run rte broadcasting network took jenny mcgeever off the air by after the broadcast of her interview with martin mcguinness
mcguinness, a vice president of the ira's political arm sinn fein, commented on the return of the bodies of three ira members killed in gibraltar while on an alleged bombing mission
her suspension followed an irish government request for an investigation of the broadcast
the irish broadcasting act prohibits interviews with or comments from subversive groups
these include the ira and its splinter group, the irish national liberation army, which are both outlawed; sinn fein, which is legal, and northern ireland paramilitary groups
aiming for a third straight victory as the 1,150-mile iditarod trail sled dog race neared its end, susan butcher left this eskimo village tuesday with martin buser just two hours behind her
on the trail to koyuk, butcher and her 11-dog team overcame a one-hour deficit, passing buser and building a lead of five hours by the time she reached this village, 171 miles from the finish line in nome. butcher rested and fed her weary dogs for more than five hours, leaving at 7:43 a.m
buser, of big lake, made up time by cutting his stay in koyuk short. with 12 of his 20 original dogs still in harness, he followed butcher out at 9:55 a.m
subzero temperatures and biting winds still hindered the leaders, and forecasters said the wind chill factor could sink to minus 70 degrees along the trail's final miles into nome
the winner is expected to cross the finish line at midmorning wednesday
butcher, of manley, has won the last two iditarods, each time proving the strength and endurance of her team in the final, windswept miles along the barren bering sea coast. she set a course record with each victory, last year burning up the trail in 11 days, 2 hours
her closest rival last year was four-time iditarod champion rick swenson, who waged a neck-and-neck race with butcher until his dogs staged a sit-down strike just 22 miles from the finish
this year, swenson, of two rivers, about six hours behind butcher at last report, leaving koyuk at 2 p.m. in third place. running in fourth was joe garnie of teller, who arrived in koyuk at 11:49 a.m
herbie nayokpuk of shishmaref was fifth. seventy-year-old joe redington of knik, credited with organizing the race but never a winner, was running sixth. he had captured an early-race lead and held onto it for more than 400 miles before falling back
