nicaraguan troops launched a major offensive tuesday against u.s.-supported rebel forces in northern nicaragua, a defense ministry spokesman said
leaders of the rebels, known as contras, claimed sandinista troops entered honduran territory. the sandinistas denied the claim and a honduran military spokesman in tegucigalpa, the honduran capital, said he had received no reports of incursions into his country's territory
the defense ministry spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said ``the army has undertaken major offensive operations ... reports that the army has penetrated honduras are not true.''
the army is developing a major military offensive at this moment. we will inform you in due time,'' he added
contra spokesmen in washington and miami claimed that sandinista troops had crossed into neighboring honduran territory in pursuit of rebel forces, who have secret base camps across the border
col. manuel suarez benavides, a spokesman for the honduran armed forces, said he had no reports of sandinista incursions
nevertheless, tomorrow we will probably be able to report on the situation (along the border),'' he said
a honduran government source, who spoke with the condition he not be identified, said president jose azcona hoyo was watching the situation closely and a government team ``is monitoring reports on the subject.''
in a speech to celebrate women's day, president daniel ortega said on march 8 that ``the sandinista army is on combat alert'' but gave no details at the time
ortega at the time said the combat alert was in response to the contras' refusal to join the sandinistas in cease-fire talks they had planned beginning march 9 in the small southern nicaraguan town of sapoa
ortega said his government had information the rebels were planning to attack the sandinista army ``at border points on the honduran frontier.''
vice president sergio ramirez confirmed to reporters monday that the sandinista army was engaged ``in actions of a certain size'' in different points in the country, but did not specify what locations were involved
the contras' clandestine liberation radio claimed tuesday there was heavy fighting for the past week in the northern 5th military region that includes boaco, chontales, rio san juan and zelaya south provinces
sandinista military sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said about 6,000 government troops were involved in what they called ``an important anti-insurgent operation.''
contra radio claimed the sandinista army was carrying out ``genocidal bombardments'' in chontales province, dropping 500- and 1,000-pound bombs from helicopters
many peasants had to flee for fear of being torn to pieces,'' the radio said
sandinista military sources in juigalpa, capital of chontales province, told the associated press on tuesday the sandinista army was using ``various military means, including helicopters'' to dislodge contra rebels who had been dominating the region for months
sandinista and contra leaders had agreed to hold cease-fire talks, for the first time inside nicaraguan territory, at sapoa march 21-23. the offensive appeared to be an effort by the sandinista regime to start negotiating from a position of strength
other military sources in managua, who also spoke on condition of anonymity, said the sandinista army ``unleashed a great offensive in the northern part of the country,'' but the defense ministry issued no reports
up until tuesday afternoon, the ministry and military sources limited themselves to issuing ``routine'' news bulletins and other reports to keep the offensive a secret, the sources said
in washington, contra leaders said nicaraguan forces were knocking the contras back
they have overrun certain of our positions,'' said ernesto palazio, director of the contras' washington office
sandinista sources said the army sent reinforcements to chontales province, where fighting appeared to be heaviest, and government troops were using helicopters and heavy artillery against the rebels
defense ministry reports tuesday said two rebels were killed monday near rio blanco, a town in northern matagalpa province, where a civilian was also killed by the contras. they said two other rebels were shot dead near the town of pancasan
an additional 31 contras were killed in scattered fighting in chontales, rio san juan and the southeastern province of zelaya south since friday, the reports said. they said a rebel ambush killed seven sandinista soldiers and wounded eight near the zelaya south town of nueva guinea
by a wide margin, the massachusetts senate on tuesday approved a revised version of a universal health care bill championed by gov. michael s. dukakis to launch the state on an experiment in ``health care for all.''
dukakis has touted the proposal in his democratic presidential campaign as a model for the nation
the senate endorsed the measure 23-11, sending the bill to a house-senate conference committee to iron out differences with a house version that would exempt many small businesses and shower favors on certain hospitals
sen. patricia mcgovern, the senate ways and means chairwoman and the chief architect of the senate bill, said she was confident a compromise could be worked out swiftly
there are an estimated 600,000 uninsured residents in the state, more than half of them working people whose employers don't provide health benefits. among other things, the bill would provide incentives for businesses to offer their own health insurance
senate supporters fought off repeated challenges throughout the day. in a key test, a republican effort to strip the huge health care bill of provisions guaranteeing health care protection to all massachusetts residents by 1992 was defeated by a 27-9 vote
senate minority leader john parker, who championed the amendment, tried again later, offering an amendment to match the house language and exempt all businesses with nine or fewer employees. that amendment fell short on a vote of 17-19
the exemption, included in the house measure, has been criticized as leaving the entire program open to a challenge on the grounds that it makes the benefits mandatory for some employees and not others
the universal health care proposal has been tied to a bill renewing the state's hospital financing law, providing nearly $1 billion in revenue increases for the state's 106 acute-care hospitals over the next four years
the house passed the health care bill two weeks ago, with a maximum price tag for the state of about $1 billion over four years to provide insurance coverage for uninsured and incentives to business to offer the benefit to employees
the senate has estimated the state's cost at about $540 million over the same period
president corazon aquino said wednesday she was prepared for new talks with moslem insurgents as her government sought to head off a bid by the rebels for international islamic support
mrs. aquino told reporters she was willing to talk with the moro national liberation front and ``all moslem leaders of mindanao,'' the country's second largest island and stronghold of the 5-million member moslem community
on tuesday, zain jali, a religious adviser to the liberation front, told reporters that his group would resume peace talks but threatened to establish a government-in-exile if the aquino administration did not agree to negotiations by next week
the front, largest of three moslem rebel groups, is expected to seek full membership in the organization of islamic conference when ministers of the worldwide moslem group meet next week in amman, jordan
filipino officials have said the move would be tantamount to recognition of the front as a ``state within a state'' and full membership could lead to civil war
the front has been waging a campaign for 16 years for self-rule, but the rebellion has been largely limited to small-scale ambushes and raids. the revolt peaked in the mid-1970s after claiming more than 50,000 lives
before wednesday's cabinet meeting, mrs. aquino said she had received no formal request from the front for new talks. negotiations broke down last may because of differences over the conditions and scope of self-rule
a former front official, zacaria candao, left tuesday for saudi arabia for talks with other rebel leaders. candao, governor of maguindanao province, said he would seek a meeting with secretary-general shariffudin pirzada of the islamic organization to discourage full front membership in the organization
meanwhile, a rival moslem rebel group announced it also was seeking full membership in the islamic group. officials of the moro islamic liberation front told reporters in mindanao that their organization was more stable than the moro national liberation front
last april, the moro islamic liberation front organized a series of attacks across central mindanao to protest the decision of the government to hold talks only with the moro national liberation front
sen. paul simon defeated jesse jackson on tuesday in the illinois democratic presidential primary, claiming the victory he said he needed to sustain his candidacy. michael dukakis said he was satisfied with ``a respectable third'' behind the two favorite sons
michael dukakis tried to put the best face on a third-place finish in the illinois democratic primary tuesday night, saying ``it's not a setback because we ran against two favorite sons.''
after numerous questions about whether his showing in illinois was a disappointment, the massachusetts governor was making no predictions about the next big contest, the michigan democratic caucuses on march 26
i don't believe we have any front-runners, i don't think we're going to have a front-runner until the convention,'' he said
dukakis said he didn't think the illinois results increased the chances of a brokered convention
i've been making a number of calls around the country to key democrats, and there is an overwhelming sentiment that we should get behind a nominee,'' he said
illinois sen. paul simon and jesse jackson took first and second respectively in the illinois primary, leaving dukakis third in the popular vote
it's not a setback, because we ran against two favorite sons who started off with a lead and stayed there,'' dukakis said. ``we did what i can characterize was a respectable third.''
the seven days between super tuesday and the illinois primary left dukakis too little time to attract strong support in illinois, the massachusetts governor said at a news conference at a local television station. dukakis spent $246,000 in media advertising in illinois
during the illinois campaign, dukakis had said a vote for simon would increase the chances of a brokered democratic national convention, something he said would be a ``disaster.''
but tuesday night, dukakis said he had spent the days on the telephone with congressmen, senators and other leading democrats, and most told him they favored a decision by the voters, not by convention negotiators
dukakis' demeanor was in marked contrast to his gala celebration the night of super tuesday, when he won the most delegates and the most states
smiling tightly, dukakis said with apparent relief: ``now, we move on to michigan, where there are no favorite sons. the field is wide open.'' news digest: washington _ pm-us-israel, a0491; jerusalem _ pm-israel, a0422. panama city, panama _ pm-panama, a0471; chicago _ pm-primary rdp, a0443; washington _ pm-dole's problems, a0473; belgrade, yugoslavia _ pm-gorbachev, a0493; starke, fla. _ pm-darden execution, a0507; salyersville, ky. _ pm-sex-abuse, a0488; washington _ pm-foreign trade, a0420; new york _ pm-biaggi-wedtech, a0495; phoenix, ariz. _ pm-mecham, a0499; sumner, wash. _ pm-back from a coma, a0489
