the bill went to the house, where its future is uncertain. rep. charles e. schumer, d-n.y. has introduced a similar bill to the senate measure. he said there may be attempts to link the bill with proposals to extend an amnesty program for some of those who came here illegally
the senate rolled up its overwhelming majority because the two leading immigration authorities in the chamber, democrat edward m. kennedy of massachusetts and republican alan k. simpson of wyoming, teamed up as bipartisan sponsors
nasa revised its schedule of space shuttle flights and cargoes tuesday, adding a mission that will retrieve a bus-size experimental station left in space in 1984 for what was to have been a one-year stay
the orbit of the satellite, which gauged the effects of space's hostile environment on 13 million seeds, metal coatings and surfaces, is decaying and there were fears it would crash through the atmosphere and burn up if it weren't recaptured in time
the new schedule makes no change in the date of the much-delayed first post-challenger flight, now set for aug. 4. there have been no american manned missions in space since the challenger _ the 25th shuttle mission _ exploded on jan. 28, 1986 and killed its seven-member crew as it lifted off from kennedy space center in florida
bishop eugene a. marino, named tuesday as the first black roman catholic archbishop in the united states, said his appointment as head of the atlanta archdiocese is ``a great sign of hope to all our people.''
the appointment by pope john paul ii comes more than two years after marino and other black bishops wrote a pastoral letter calling on the church to increase the number of blacks in official positions
the church has spoken but has the church listened to itself?'' said the letter, suggesting that in the absence of a major appointment such as a black archbishop in a big city, ``the church's commitment to black leadership may be seen as half-hearted and superficial.''
convicted murderer willie jasper darden went to his death tuesday proclaiming his innocence and thanking people around the world, from andrei sakharov to jesse jackson, who aided his 14-year battle to escape the electric chair
for the widow of the man he shot between the eyes, darden's execution on an unprecedented seventh death warrant offered hope, finally, for peace of mind
i think it's long overdue,'' helen turman baum said minutes after the execution about 7 a.m. at the florida state prison. ``he did it to himself. i'm just thinking right now i want some peace of mind ... it's been a long time and i'm glad it's finally over.''
the deficit in the broadest measure of u.s. foreign trade surged to a record $160.7 billion in 1987 as america fell deeper into debt to the rest of the world, the commerce department reported tuesday
the deficit in the u.s. current account was 13.7 percent higher than the 1986 deficit of $141.4 billion and marked the fifth consecutive year that this trade deficit has hit a new record
the reagan administration has sought to downplay the significance of the trade deficits, but private economists contend that the rapid buildup of foreign debt could eventually topple the country into another recession, triggered by a plunge in the value of the dollar
students at the university of akron are aiming for a breakthrough that has eluded some of the best minds in government and the professions: a tax form that can be understood without a college education
we know it can be done and we're going to prove it,'' professor nicholas j. creme, director of the center for taxation studies in the university's law school, said in an interview tuesday. ``we're not saying we could bring it down to a second-grade level, but we certainly can make it simpler
if you simplify the forms, people will be a lot less hostile toward the internal revenue service,'' he said. ``and you'll raise a lot more revenue.''
american journalist terry anderson, the longest-held of 22 foreign hostages in lebanon, was kidnapped three years ago wednesday, and there has been no word of him for three months
gunmen believed to be shiite moslem zealots abducted him march 16, 1985, a saturday morning, as he was returning home from a game of tennis. it was before kidnappings became epidemic in moslem west beirut, and many foreigners lived there
police say they have no information on anderson, chief middle east correspondent of the associated press, or any of the other missing foreigners, who include eight other americans. most are held by shiite moslems loyal to ayatollah ruhollah khomeini, the revolutionary patriarch of iran
students who skip professor gerald m. phillips' opening lecture in his course on group decision-making may find themselves searching the campus in vain for any trace of him the rest of the semester
that's because the penn state university professor communicates with his speech communications 350 class only through the school's computer system, by electronic mail or ``e-mail.''
the class does get weekly lectures, from two graduate students, and other graduate students sit in on group discussions as ``consultants.''
once a young couple obtains the down payment for a house, the cost of operating it may be no more than might be needed for rent and maintenance of an apartment
moreover, the benefits of homeownership are great
owners become member of the elite tax-privileged class, since mortgage interest and real estate taxes are deductions on federal income tax returns. they build equity. and their house is a good hedge against inflation
it is for such reasons, and several more, that suggestions are now pouring into congress on ways to help young folks get a financial foot in the door of their own house. what they seek, in effect, is government sponsorship
this wouldn't be the first time that government provided such assistance, of course, but in recent years it has indicated a desire to reduce, not add to, its programs. but, say proponents of aid, there are special factors today
indeed there are
first on the list is the down payment. housing prices have risen sharply in recent years, far outperforming the after-tax paychecks of young workers. as a consequence, ownership is down
between world war ii and 1980 the ownership rate rose without significant interruption, reaching 65.6 percent in 1980. but then it began receding again, settling at 63.8 percent in 1986
even more disturbing, according to the national association of realtors, the rate for people under age 25 and for those in the prime homebuying ages of 25 to 43, fell more steeply. for the former, the rate dropped to 21.6 percent from 26.4 percent; for the latter, the drop was to 45.4 percent from 55 percent
these figures have become the cue for proponents of government assistance, and the realtors are among the most insistent, as witness the statement by nestor weigand jr., realtor president, that ``it is time for the federal government to recognize that homeownerhip is beneficial to everyone.''
everyone'' includes lumber suppliers, plumbers, carpenters, roofers, appliance and carpet manufacturers, real estate agents, lawyers and many other folks besides the young couples seeking a home of their own
their efforts, especially when coordinated, can mean formidable pressure for another housing program, even in the face of opposition from those, such as the white house, that would like government out of private-sector matters
out of this self-interest _ which isn't to deny an element of true public concern _ some creative, though not especially new, proposals have emerged, such as these from the realtors:
_a program to enable first-time homebuyers to withdraw without penalty a certain amount from their individual retirement accounts or other tax-deferred savings to be used only for a down payment
_establishment of an individual housing account, the money from which would mean eligibility for an income tax credit if used as a down payment
_creation of a national employee homeownership program to allow employers to provide down payment assistance to employees, with tax advantages to both
but just as creative is a strictly private-sector plan that also might be considered. it is simple, informal, responsible, familial and probably beneficial not just to the individuals involved but for all society, too
proponents of this plan observe that many homeowner parents have built up tremendous equity, in part because of the sharp rise in prices that denies their children the opportunity for a home of their own
many of these parents are at peak earning power, simultaneous with a reduction in their expenses. couldn't they tap some of that equity in order to lend a down payment to their children? don't they owe it to their offspring?
a main feature of the plan, say its proponents, is its non-bureaucratic nature. the only way uncle sam gets into the act is to allow a tax deduction to the parents who borrow the money
in an explosive time about a tense issue _ israel's dealings with palestinians _ a highly unusual american religious alliance has been formed to press for solutions to the crisis
moslem, jewish and christian leaders are included in the new u.s. interreligious committee for peace in the middle east
what made possible the unlikely combination on the keenly divisive problem was that ``it was an idea whose time had come,'' says ronald j. young, executive director of the organization
it couldn't have happened, he adds, ``unless the time was ripe for it.''
in any case, prominent u.s. jews and moslems, who have been on opposing sides in middle east conflict, along with top protestant and roman catholic officials, are extensively involved in the common effort
about 600 religious leaders are initial backers, with other being enlisted, to work for a ``moral climate'' that would spur politicians to take initiatives regarded necessary for middle eastern peace
seeking to set forth a middle ground in the conflict, which has particularly divided jews and moslems, the committee's joint statement affirms these principles:
_ support of israel's right to secure borders, and also of u.n. resolution 242 calling for israel's withdrawal from the now violence-racked west bank and gaza taken in the 1967 war, and security of all states in the region
_ the palestinian people's right to self-determination and to choose their own leadership
_ the urgency of an international conference for peace involving all parties in the conflict, as well as members of the u.n. security council, including the u.s. and the soviet union
the reagan administration has been reluctant about taking these positions,'' young said in an interview. ``it has given a higher priority to keeping the russians out, and this has not been helpful.''
he also said that the u.s. administration also has not explicitly supported the palestinians' right to self-determination, although such a right ``has a history that started in this country.''
young said discussions about a joint approach by american christians, jews and moslems started last june, before the outbreak of riots in gaza and the west bank, but events there gave the cause increased urgency
they ``dramatically demonstrate that the current situation is disastrous for the palestinians and, in the long run, will be disastrous for israel as well,'' he said
he said local units of the new organization have formed in st. louis, kansas city, portland, ore., and syracuse, n. y., and are being planned in 11 other cities _ atlanta, los angeles, san francisco, seattle, chicago, boston, atlanta, philadelphia, pittsburgh, new york and washington, d.c
he said the aim is to build up a national mood of jews, moslems and christians that would encourage political leaders to act on the problem
in dealing with the middle east, we are dealing not just with the complexities of the particular situation, but with the whole history of prejudice against jews and also against arabs and moslems,'' young said
as a result, he said, ``they have a strong fear against trusting anyone else with the welfare of their people. there also is a great deal of insensitivity among christians about how deep those fears are.''
the alliance maintains it is urgent that the u.s. make middle eastern peace a priority of foreign policy
among backers listed of the new effort:
moslem _ dawud assad, president of the council of mosques, and fahd m. al-nassar, president of the moslem world league, both of new york; iman w. deen muhammad of chicago, and cherif sedky, an american-arab attorney of washington, d.c
jewish _ rabbi alexander schindler, president of the union of american hebrew congregations; its senior vice president, albert vorspan; rabbi wolfe kelman, executive of the rabbinical assembly; rabbi eugene lipman, present of the central conference of american rabbis, and rabbi arthur schneier, president of the freedom of conscience foundation
christian _ archbishop roger mahony of los angles; the rev. theodore m. hesburgh, president emeritus of notre dame; eugene fisher, head of the u.s. catholic bishops' committee on catholic-jewish relations; greek orthodox archbishop iakovos; episcopal presiding bishop edmund l. browning; the rev. avery post, president of the united church of christ; the rev. john humbert, president of the christian church (disciples of christ) and united methodist bishop george bashore of boston
young, a quaker, formerly director of peace programs for the american friends service committe, said jews and moslems have differed on mid-east issues, but ``see effort for peace as not contradicting their consistency.''
he said:
we are committed to challenging historic and persistent prejudices against the jewish people, moslems and arabs _ prejudices that inhibit the kind of cooperation for justice and peace that clearly is a moral imperative of our common abrahamic faith.''
fourteen-year-old tiffany salzer got an ``a'' on her book report without opening the book. she watched the movie instead
it only took me three hours to watch the movie and it would have taken me 12 hours to read the book,'' said the ninth-grader from ventura, calif
her father, jim, owner of salzer's video store and a board member of the video softwares dealers association, is familiar with the situation
it's a problem,'' he said in a telephone interview. ``a kid essentially can rent a classic movie and do a book report from it. kids are taking shortcuts.''
videotape retailers across the nation say many teen-agers, children of the television generation, are taking study guides that summarize literature one step further and turning to videotapes for help with homework, renting rather than reading
tiffany said her teachers sometimes show movies in class, but only after students presumably have read the corresponding literature. she said she watched ``clan of the cave bear'' the night before a report on the book was due
the teachers say the movie is different. sometimes it is, but students don't really care,'' she said. ``it's better to get a `c' than an `f.'''
at parents' requests, art marra pulled ``to kill a mockingbird'' from the shelves at his hto video store in suburban pittsburgh after students were assigned to read the book
since then, marra periodically has refused to rent certain videotapes to youths because he learned the corresponding books were homework assignments
we're a community-oriented shop. we try to give the community any cooperation we can,'' marra said
mike petraglia noticed young people make sporadic runs on certain films at his video-o-video store in pittsburgh. he said a popular videotape among teens is ``dirty dancing,'' but when assignments dictate, he can't find enough copies of ``death of a salesman,'' ``treasure island,'' ``grapes of wrath'' and ``billy budd.''
`gone with the wind' has been picking up a little bit. i think it's book-related,'' he said
students always have searched for the easier way, and the video scholar is just a variation of the cliff notes customer, said scott treibitz, spokesman for the american federation of teachers, based in washington, d.c
for 29 years, students have used cliff notes to provide summaries and analysis of books, and sales of the study guides still are growing, said doug lincoln, spokesman for cliff notes inc. of lincoln, neb
the problem now is with the access of video cassette recorders and with the access of video stores,'' treibitz said
lincoln said cliff notes may produce its own videotapes, but he declined to discuss details
the generation that is in elementary school now, they're certainly in the video age,'' lincoln said. ``i would have to say the (use) of video will probably only increase.''
teachers are increasingly using videotapes in the classroom, and as a supplement the tapes are helpful, said judi boren, spokeswoman for the north allegheny county school district in suburban pittsburgh
you can't use the video as a cliff note kind of crutch,'' ms. boren said. ``there's a saying, `i read the book. i don't need to see the movie.' if you make some comparisons, maybe you need to do both.''
a teacher can give a lecture on the grand canyon, niagara falls, space exploration,'' treibitz said. ``a video not only gives that same material, but shows the visuals to reinforce that material
it can't replace reading, it can't replace writing and there are times it can't replace the lecture,'' he said
the white house plans to create a new group that will make final, unified reagan administration recommendations on how to prevent another stock market collapse, according to a published report
the new york times reported in its tuesday editions that the white house, whose brady commission task force already has made such recommendations, is creating a new interagency committee to develop a consolidated administration position in the next 60 to 90 days
the committee, which would be headed by treasury secretary james a. baker iii, would include top officials of the federal reserve, securities and exchange commission and commodity futures trading commission, the newspaper stated, quoting unidentified white house aides
it was hoped the new committee, details of which still are being worked out, would be able to smooth over conflicts among the various regulatory agencies over how best to prevent another market crash, the newspaper stated
since the brady commission came out with its recommendations in early january, federal regulators have been engaged in often-public sniping over what regulatory changes should be made to prevent a repeat of the oct. 19 market debacle
sec chairman david s. ruder, for example, has indicated he believed his agency should be chief regulator of stock index futures traded in the commodity markets, a position vehemently opposed by the cftc
congressional aides suggested that the white house might view such divisiveness as weakening its influence over any legislative response to the october crash
the brady commission, headed by former new jersey senator nicholas brady, essentially recommended a coordinated, intermarket system of ``circuit breakers'' to prevent wild price swings; higher margin requirements on stock index futures; unified clearing and settlement operations in the stock and futures markets; and giving the fed superagency authority over key issues affecting the stock and futures markets
the times said details of the interagency committee were contained in letters sent friday by senate banking committee chairman william proxmire to white house chief of staff howard h. baker jr., and the chairmen of the fed, sec and cftc. in those letters, proxmire referred to a conversation with baker regarding the committee
proxmire indicated he was pleased with the idea, but also stated that 90 days might be too long for congress to wait for the new group's recommendations, given that the agencies involved already had conducted their own studies of the crash and made recommendations
proxmire also stated he planned to ask the fed, sec and cftc top submit their legislative proposals in time for a march 31 hearing on the issue
r.h. macy &amp; co. has sweetened its friendly merger deal with federated department stores inc. by $200 million cash to $6.3 billion, giving it an edge over hostile competitor campeau corp
campeau indicated monday it had no immediate plans to revise its own $6.2 billion offer, but extended the bid _ which was to expire today _ through friday
in addition to sweetening its buyout offer, macy received a ``lock-up'' option to buy federated's bullock's-bullock's wilshire and i. magnin retail divisions if the merger falls through
j.p. stevens &amp; co. accepted a nearly $1 billion cash buyout bid from a private investment group, spurning offers from its own management and rival west point-pepperell inc
in active trading monday on the new york stock exchange, stevens stock jumped $5.37{ a share to close at $61.12{, or just under the offer by odyssey partners
odyssey and other private investors agreed to pay $61.50 in cash for each of stevens' 15.5 million shares outstanding, or around $953.2 million
mesa limited partnership's second foray into the gold industry fell short when the group, controlled by oilman t. boone pickens, withdrew its $1.88 billion cash offer for homestake mining co
mesa said monday it retracted its offer to acquire homestake, a leading gold producer, in a negotiated transaction for a price of $20 a share in cash
homestake previously had rejected mesa's offer
business inventories rose 0.4 percent in january, less than half the increase of the previous month, as a rebound in car sales helped to reduce a huge backlog of unsold cars, the government has reported
the commerce department said monday that inventories increased by $3 billion in january, pushing the total of unsold items on store shelves and backlots to a seasonally adjusted $705.85 billion
analysts said the slowdown in the rate of increase was an encouraging sign and indicated economic growth may not weaken in the first part of this year as much as had been feared
polaroid corp. has a stronger-than-expected case in its $5.7 billion damage lawsuit against eastman kodak co., placing the instant photography pioneer in its best position in years, some analysts say
the damage claim filed last month in federal court has sent polaroid's stock soaring on wall street, even though kodak has dismissed polaroid's claim as ``ludicrous.''
the two companies are meeting in court this week to discuss a trial date in the damage portion of the case. in 1985, kodak was found guilty of infringing on polaroid patents when it entered the instant camera business in 1976
internal documents indicate g.d. searle &amp; co. may have misled doctors and a federal regulatory agency about safety characteristics of its copper-7 contraceptive, according to an attorney representing a woman who claims that the device made her sterile
wall street reacted monday by knocking the stock of monsanto co., searle's parent, down $3.12{ a share to $83.37{
according to the documents, searle apparently hid complaints about the copper-7 from the u.s. food and drug administration
texas has lost another round in its battle to keep florida citrus out of the state, with a federal judge's refusal to block those shipments
u.s. district judge filemon vela said monday he needed more time to study the state's request for a stay of a u.s. department of agriculture decision lifting a ban on florida citrus to other producing states
texas sought the stay until its suit against u.s. secretary of agriculture richard e. lyng could be heard
the teamsters union has set a new target of march 29 for its 6,700 member flight attendants to strike northwest airlines after getting a pledge that the carrier's mechanics and baggage handlers will honor picket lines
anyone who thinks they are going to fly northwest during the easter holidays should forget it,'' william genoese, director of the teamsters' airline division, said monday
northwest officials described the union's announcement as ``continuing rhetoric'' and said they doubted the attendants would strike
a new settlement calling for more than $8 million in corrective advertising and continuing the ban on three-wheel all-terrain vehicles has been disclosed by the consumer product safety commission
the commission and justice department reached the settlement disclosed monday with five manufacturers of the off-road vehicles, which have been implicated in hundreds of deaths and thousands of injuries in recent years
u.s. district court judge gerhard a. gesell will hold a hearing on the settlement april 18 and could order it into effect immediately after that session
the internal revenue service has pledged to support a review of tax penalties assessed last year in some 27 million cases _ penalties that have been criticized as a special burden on the poor
at the opening of a public inquiry monday into the maze of 154 penalties the irs can impose, irs commissioner lawrence b. gibbs expressed the agency's own concern about the penalties, many of which were enacted by congress over the past seven years in an effort to increase compliance with the tax laws
several witnesses accused the government of using penalties to raise revenues, rather than to assure compliance with the laws
the communist world gets its first mcdonald's next week, and some people here are wondering whether its american hamburgers will be as popular as the local fast-food treat, pljeskavica
the long-awaited opening of the restaurant on one of belgrade's main downtown squares will take place march 24, the yugoslav news agency tanjug reported, and it will offer big macs, fries and the other specialties familiar to mcdonald's customers in the west
stock prices showed no clear trend monday in the quietest trading of the year. the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 15.09 points to 2,050.07
the dollar was mixed against other major currencies. gold prices edged higher
bond prices finished mixed in lackluster trading
soybean futures prices soared as fears about increased soybean acreage eased. grain futures also closed higher
stock prices were little changed today in light, lackluster trading
analysts said the market drifted in a narrow range as both institutional and retail investors remained on the sidelines while awaiting fresh economic news due out later in the week
the government is scheduled to release january's merchandise trade figures on thursday, just ahead of the year's first ``triple witching hour,'' when a group of options and futures on stock indexes will expire simultaneously
while concern over the two events dampened activity in the previous trading session, analysts indicated market participants may be overestimating the impact both the trade figures and the witching hour might have
analysts noted that the market reacted quickly when trade figures were released in the previous two months. similarly, the past couple of witching hours have been rather uneventful with the adoption of new procedures designed to spread out the impact of last-minute maneuvering by computer program traders
the dow jones average of 30 industrials fell 2.66 to 2,047.41
gainers outpaced losers by about a 10-to-9 margin on the new york stock exchange
big board volume totaled 133.17 million shares, against 131.89 million million in the previous session
the nyse's composite index fell 0.07 to 149.99
at the american stock exchange, the market value index was off 0.19 to 296.75
textile industry analysts say the bidding may not be over for j.p. stevens &amp; co., even though the company has accepted a nearly $1 billion cash buyout offer from an investment group
a group led by odyssey partners of new york announced monday it agreed to pay $61.50 in cash for each of stevens' 15.5 million shares outstanding, or about $953.24 million
the offer is subject to a majority of the shares being tendered and the necessary financing being obtained
analysts called odyssey's bid fair, although some said they thought the bidding could continue
in active trading on the new york stock exchange, stevens' stock jumped $5.37{ a share to close at $61.12{
over the past few weeks, stevens has fielded rival offers from atlanta-based west point-pepperell inc. and a group led by its own senior management, including chairman whitney stevens, a fifth generation member of the family that founded the company in 1813
the management group offered $55 a share in cash and securities in a leveraged buyout about two weeks ago, up from its initial offer of $43 a share. in a leveraged buyout, a company is acquired largely with borrowed money repaid with a target company's profits or the sales of assets
west point-pepperell, a major household fabrics maker with brands that include arrow, martex and lady pepperell, offered to buy stevens for $56 a share in cash, or about $867 million. the company confirmed monday it had considered raising its offer to $62.50 a share, but had not made a formal bid at the higher price
west point-pepperell refused to comment on what, if any, further action it might take
the arbitragers think there could be more bidding,'' said edward johnson, a textile analyst with johnson redbook, a division of prescott, ball &amp; turben inc. ``a deal is never done until all the stock is signed over.''
george o. zimmerman, an analyst with gruntal &amp; co., said a higher offer could torpedo the deal with odyssey. ``i think they'll have to take the highest bid,'' he said
odyssey is a private investment company. its deals have included the purchase of a controlling interest in lucky stores inc.'s eagle food stores, located in the midwest, and a leveraged buyout of research cottrell inc., a pollution control, engineering and construction company
odyssey said it would finance the deal with a $600 million loan from citibank, $570 million from the sale subordinated debt and preferred stock and $100 million in equity investment
should the deal go through, johnson predicted, odyssey likely could sell parts of stevens to pay off its debt
stevens already undertook a major restructuring about five years ago, selling off some of its finished fabrics divisions to concentrate more on home furnishings
new york-based stevens, one of the nation's biggest textile makers with 23,000 employees, produces home fashion textiles such as sheets, towels and carpets under the brand names ralph lauren, laura ashley and pierre cardin. the company also makes automotive products and industrial products
the company had an after-tax profit of $56 million on sales of $1.6 billion in the fiscal year ended oct. 31. for growth</head>
its victories in overseas markets have brought honda motor co. worldwide recognition, but the company still is waging an uphill battle to become a dominant automaker in its own backyard
in sharp contrast with honda's success abroad _ it holds about 3.5 percent of the world auto market _ the company has had trouble penetrating the japanese market dominated by the ``big two'' of toyota motor corp. and nissan motor co., which together control nearly a 50 percent share
in recent years, honda's domestic sales have been growing, often faster than the rate of japan's overall motor-vehicle market expansion
to boost growth further, the company will add new cars and models to its product line and increase the number of honda dealers and salesmen each year into the 1990s, says honda president takashi kume
by 1991, honda expects its domestic network to grow about 25 percent from now to 3,000 dealers and more than double the number of salesmen to 18,000
new products will allow honda to sell 800,000 cars and mini-vehicles a year at home by 1991 and 1 million by the mid-1990s, kume says. these projections compare with last year's sales of 546,979 units and this year's forecast of 620,000 vehicles
honda's domestic market share rose to 9.1 percent in 1987 from 7.0 percent in 1986
but in a market where overall demand for cars, trucks and buses, exceeded 6 million units for the first time last year, honda still lags far behind toyota and nissan
analysts say japanese culture and honda's own history have contributed to its domestic struggle
honda _ originally a motorcycle manufacturer _ had a late start in the auto business, entering the four-wheeled vehicle market in 1963 some 30 years after the big two. analysts say this still haunts the company: honda's sales network of 2,400 dealers and 8,200 salespeople is dwarfed, for example, by toyota's 4,000 dealers and 41,000 salespeople
takamori matsuda, vice president of prudential-bache securities (japan) ltd., says japan's ``unspoken dealer loyalty'' is a major obstacle to honda's expansion in the domestic market
unlike the u.s. market, where car retailers are mostly independent (from manufacturers) and often switch makers or brands they handle, there is virtually no betrayal on the part of dealers in this country,'' matsuda said
japanese automakers generally maintain high capital participation in their dealers and thus enjoy more control over them. that condition makes a switch, say, from toyota to honda, virtually impossible, matsuda said
tetsuo sakiya, author of the book ``honda motor: the men, the management, the machines'' and professor of international relations at musashino womens college in tokyo, contends honda could have closed the gap with the big two if company founder shoichiro honda and his senior officials in the late 1960s had more foresight
honda early on had decided to rely on an air-cooled engine and missed out on the first full-fledged wave of japanese motorization in the late 1960s and the early 1970s because it did not have the ``right product,'' a car with a quieter and cleaner water-cooled engine, sakiya said
if honda hadn't chosen an air-cooled engine, its standing would've been a lot better against toyota and nissan today,'' sakiya said
honda introduced its 1300 model, a sedan powered by an air-cooled engine, in 1969 but replaced it two years later with a lightweight car, the honda life, with a much-acclaimed water-cooled cvcc engine
a more conspicuous cause of honda's weakness at home, and in overseas markets to some extent, has been its lack of a full product line and diversity in the styling and size of its cars, according to analysts. not until october 1985 did honda, a thriving maker of economical subcompacts, decide to pursue affluent consumers with the legend, a 2.7 liter-engine luxury car
because of its relatively limited lineup of models in the over 2 liter engine class, honda will not benefit as much as the big two from the boom in the market for bigger, more powerful and more expensive cars, analysts say
to expand its lineup further, honda also recently re-entered the minicar market and is scheduled to launch japanese sales of a version of the accord series assembled at its facilities in marysville, ohio. it is also widely rumored to be planning to introduce a sports car powered by a six-cylinder or eight-cylinder engine next year
honda also is believed to be planning a line of luxury models by the 1990s featuring a flagship sedan with a v-8 or v-12 engine
matsuda says to compete domestically honda also must deal with japanese upbringing that fosters more conformity and harmony among individuals, compared with the u.s. system that stresses individuality
it's easier to sell to americans who aren't afraid of making their own decisions and accepting the unknown, compared with japanese consumers who are often oversensitive to impressions they make on others through the purchase of a product,'' matsuda said. ``the upshot of this (japanese) attitude is that people are driving cars, often white, from the same familiar makers.''
but analysts think honda's potential for sustained growth at home is strong. they concur that honda is pulling ahead to emerge as the definite winner in a three-way battle for the slot of japan's third biggest automaker with mitsubishi motors corp. and mazda motor co
r.h macy &amp; co. has raised the stakes in its battle to acquire federated department stores inc., boosting its proposed payout and locking up the option to purchase two prize federated divisions regardless of who wins control of the retailing company
macy on monday sweetened its merger agreement with federated by $200 million in cash, raising the value of the offer to $6.3 billion and topping a rival, hostile $6.2 billion proposal by campeau corp
separately, a federal judge indicated he would not rule before wednesday in suits filed by macy and campeau in connection with their war over federated, but effectively extended campeau's buyout offer into next week
macy _ whose own offer expires april 4 _ had sought to delay expiration of campeau's offer by 20 days to lessen the pressure on federated shareholders to accept the hostile bid
toronto-based campeau extended its offer through friday from today's original expiration, but stated monday it had no immediate intention to revise its bid in response to the sweetened offer from macy
under terms of the amended merger agreement unanimously approved by the federated board, macy will offer $77.35 a share in cash for 80 percent of federated's stock, up from $74.50 per share in its original offer
macy plans to swap shares in the merged company and issue convertible debt securities for the remaining 20 percent of federated shares
federated stock closed unchanged at $66 a share on the new york stock exchange
federated also granted macy the option to purchase its bullock's-bullock's wilshire and i. magnin retail divisions if the merger fell through. such ``lockup'' options frequently are used to discourage hostile suitors
federated said the divisions would sell for at least $800 million and $150 million, respectively, although campeau has valued those divisions at a total of about $1.25 billion
macy also granted federated's board sole discretion over whether to maintain its ``poison pill'' anti-takeover plan. under its previous agreement, cincinnati-based federated would have rescinded the plan in a merger with macy
federated recommended its shareholders tender their stock to macy, calling the new offer ``substantially more favorable to federated stockholders than macy's previous offer and the coercive campeau two-tier offer.''
campeau is offering to pay $75 cash a share for 70.5 million of federated's common shares outstanding, or 80 percent, through friday
the remaining 20 percent of federated stock would be acquired later for $44 cash per share in a subsequent merger, giving the deal an aggregate value of $68 per share
shortly after campeau extended its offer, federated urged its shareholders to hold onto their stock, reversing the unusual recommendation it made sunday for stockholders to tender their shares to the hostile bidder
federated is opposed to merging with campeau, but the retailer had intended to prevent its shareholders from having to accept the lower, $44 price under the ``back end'' of campeau's two-tier bid
at monday night's hearing, u.s. district judge leonard sand indicated he would not rule before wednesday either on macy's request to force campeau to extend its tender offer past friday or on campeau's challenge to federated's ``poison pill'' takeover defense
sand said he was seeking an opinion from the securities and exchange commission on macy's contention that campeau's latest tender offer, which was revised from a previous lower bid, constituted a brand-new offer. if the judge sides with macy, campeau would have to delay its offer _ and the date when it could acquire tendered shares _ to give shareholders time to consider the new bid
the judge said he would not get the sec opinion before wednesday and would not rule on either issue before then
however, sand stated both buyout offers would have to remain in effect for at least three business days after he ruled on the poison pill issue, effectively extending campeau's offer through next week
buoyed by prospects of a billion-dollar court settlement in a 12-year-old patent infringement case and by takeover speculation, polaroid corp.'s stock has soared on wall street in recent weeks
the instant photography pioneer is seeking $5.7 billion in damages from eastman kodak co., which was found guilty in 1985 of violating seven of 150 polaroid patents when it entered the instant camera business in 1976
after reviewing papers filed in u.s. district court here last month, analysts increased their estimates for a possible settlement to above $1 billion from their initial $300 million to $500 million range
after reading the documents, a number of people said that polaroid's case is stronger than we had expected,'' said eugene glazer, an analyst with dean witter reynolds inc
the companies are to meet friday with judge rya zobel and may discuss setting a trial date on the damages issue
analysts said the possibility of a large award has attracted investors and also invited speculation that a corporate raider might bid for the company in hopes of realizing a windfall on a big settlement
polaroid, based in cambridge, was trading in the low $20s a share until the damage request was disclosed feb. 19. since then polaroid has climbed, topping $36 a share at one point. polaroid rose 25 cents to $34 a share monday in new york stock exchange trading
purchasing patterns have been in small blocks, however, and no individual buyer has notified the securities and exchange commission that it holds as much as 5 percent of the stock
polaroid won't comment on stock activity, takeover rumors or a settlement
we have indicated from the very beginning 12 years ago that we were always open to an out-of-court settlement,'' spokesman harry johnson said. ``talking about such matters in the media has a chilling effect on that possibility.''
in court documents, polaroid argues it is entitled to $3.2 billion in lost camera and film sales. the company is seeking $2.5 billion more for lost opportunities to develop and market new products
kodak, which was ordered out if its $200 million a year instant camera business in january 1986, has dismissed the claim as ``ludicrous and ridiculously inflated.'' the rochester, n.y.-based photo giant argues polaroid is entitled to a reasonable royalty, not lost profits
if zobel finds kodak guilty of willfully infringing on polaroid's patents, pre-tax damages can be tripled under federal law, raising the potential maximum award to $11 billion
no one expects the settlement to be that large, but a $1 billion award _ equal to about $10 a share _ would allow polaroid to diversify into fields such as information retrieval or conventional photography
along with the polaroid brand name, the possibility that the company could run better under new management is keeping takeover interest high, analysts said
it has the characteristics of the type of company that could be run to generate greater cash flow,'' glazer said
polaroid founder edwin h. land invented instant photography in 1947 and first marketed it in 1948. polaroid held a monopoly for almost 30 years until kodak entered the field
polaroid camera sales peaked at 7.5 million units in 1978 before sinking to 3.4 million in 1984. sales jumped to 4.4 million in 1986 after the company introduced the spectra camera, with quality closer to that of 35 millimeter prints, but fell by 16 percent last year
polaroid had entered the 1970s with high expectations due to technology for its sx-70 camera, which produced fast, dry color prints. but polaroid never was able to bring the cost of film down enough, which hurt instant photography sales
analysts said polaroid could get a boost next month with the introduction of the spectra 600, priced at $40 to $60, and the image, which promises better quality for $60 to $80
the dollar gained against most major currencies in early european trading today
gold prices were mixed
dealers said the dollar was trading quietly in a narrow range as market participants awaited thursday's report of the u.s. merchandise trade deficit for january
the british pound, which soared 10 cents against the dollar in a month, slipped back ahead of the presentation to parliament this afternoon of the conservative government's annual spring budget
dealers in europe said they were waiting to see whether the budget delivered expected tax cuts and led to lower interest rates. an interest rate cut would rein in the pound
