at a meeting of the house of councillor's budget committee today, finance minister kiichi miyazawa predicted: ``the dollar will appreciate against the yen in the future, rather than stabilize.''
stock prices moved higher tuesday morning on optimism about chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson's budget statement for fiscal 1989, due later in the day
the financial times-stock exchange 100-share index was up 19.2 points, or 1 percent, at 1,838.7 at midday
volume was a moderate 241.3 million shares at midday, up from 176.3 million shares at the same time a day earlier
prices advanced gradually through the morning because of optimism about the contents of lawson's budget statement, dealers said
in addition to tax rate cuts, investors were expecting lawson to outline financial targets which might provide a further boost for the pound, dealers said. that might force the government to cut british base lending rates in order to stabilize the currency, they added
but some analysts discounted the idea because of concern that an interest rate cut would boost inflation
the idea of a base rate cut seems to be gaining credibility in the market,'' said kevin gardiner, an economist at warburg securities. ``but we still don't think it's very likely.'' shaky</head>
firestone tire &amp; rubber co. says the pirelli group's unsolicited $1.8 billion takeover offer will likely force it to abandon a previous agreement to sell most of its tire operations to bridgestone corp. of japan
but firestone said its board of directors has authorized management to explore alternatives to the pirelli bid that possibly could include a new deal with bridgestone
firestone said monday that its board met to consider pirelli's $58-a-share tender offer but took no action
the company said that in light of pirelli's offer it was unlikely to consummate the joint venture agreement it announced with the japanese tiremaker on feb. 16. under that agreement, bridgestone would pay about $1.25 billion to buy 75 percent of firestone's tire operations
pirelli's offer is contingent on firestone dropping its plans to enter the joint venture with bridgestone
firestone said that in seeking alternatives to the pirelli offer, its advisers had begun discussions with bridgestone. the board indicated it would meet again this week to complete its review of pirelli's offer
the board also reiterated its stance that shareholders should not tender their shares until it issued its recommendation. firestone had stated previously the board would make its recommendation by friday
firestone stock dipped 87{ cents to $61.62{ a share in active trading monday on the new york stock exchange
earlier, a federal court in cleveland heard arguments over pirelli's lawsuit attempting to declare ohio's anti-takeover law unconstitutional
pirelli is seeking a temporary restraining order to keep the ohio control share acquisition act from affecting its bid for firestone. the act requires a hostile bidder to wait up to 50 days for shareholders to vote before he can acquire tendered shares
a lawsuit challenging the law was filed last week by veere inc., a holding company owned by pirelli that is incorporated in delaware
dennis orr, an attorney for veere, said the law is a burden on interstate commerce and could hurt shareholders by giving firestone time to defeat pirelli's tender offer, launched a week ago
firestone attorney patrick f. mccartan countered orr's argument by saying, ``control is one of the most valuable assets a shareholder can possess. it is a collective asset and should be (given up) in a collective manner.''
u.s. district judge alice batchelder did not issue a ruling on the temporary restraining order monday
prudential-bache securities inc. lost $164 million, more than previously estimated
prudential insurance co. of america, the securities firm's parent, said monday its own profit from operations, before dividends and federal income tax, rose to $2.65 billion from $2.55 billion. prudential did not announce a net income figure
prudential, the nation's largest insurer, did not detail the reasons for the loss at prudential-bache except to say it included a charge of $47 million from the closing of an international trade unit
prudential-bache told its employees in january it had taken an unspecified charge related to litigation involving the alleged attempt by the hunt brothers of texas to corner the silver market in early 1980
the securities subsidiary also said it had taken substantial charges hiring investment bankers and had losses in the october stock market crash and its aftermath
atari corp. of sunnyvale has charged micron technology inc. of boise, idaho, with illegally exploiting a shortage of computer memory chips
the computer and video company on monday filed suit in u.s. district court, seeking an order to make the idaho semiconductor manufacturer pay the california company an unspecified amount of damages. the suit charges breach of contract, bad faith and violation of federal antitrust law
there was no immediate response from micron technology
micron technology is one of only two u.s.-based companies that make the most common kind of computer memory chip, known as dynamic random access memory chips, or d-rams. the other is texas instruments inc. of dallas
the shortage of the chips has been caused by strong sales of personal computers, the changeover to a new generation of chips, and a 1986 accord between the united states and japan aimed at ending japanese ``dumping'' of the chips at unfairly low prices
south korea plans to sharply cut its tariffs on imports during the next five years as part of its efforts to boost foreign sales here, government officials said tuesday
officials at the ministry of finance said a plan under study calls for the country's average import tariffs of 16.9 percent to be cut by half by 1993
details of the plan would be completed by june, the officials said
the plan, they added, is aimed at stimulating imports, thereby cutting south korea's growing current account surplus, which reached $10 billion last year. the imbalance has led to complaints from trading partners
the stock market was little changed today in early, quiet trading
