the deficit in the broadest measure of u.s. foreign trade surged 13.7 percent last year to a record $160.7 billion, the government reported today
the commerce department said the current account deficit grew from the previous record of $141.4 billion in 1986 even though the deficit for the final three months of the year narrowed slightly
the current account covers not only the flow of merchandise across the u.s. border but also the flow of services, primarily investment earnings between countries
while the united states has run deficits in merchandise trade for 16 of the past 17 years, the current account was in surplus as recently as 1981 as americans' earnings on overseas investments were enough to offset the merchandise deficits
on monday the commerce department reported a 0.4 percent rise in january business inventories, less than half the december increase, reflecting a rebound in car sales that reduced backlogs of unsold vehicles
analysts said the slower growth suggested the economy may not weaken or lapse into recession in the first half of this year, as had been widely feared following the stock market crash in october
higher business inventories and sluggish consumer spending are considered a negative trend because they eventually collide to cause production cutbacks and layoffs
the news was ignored by wall street, where stocks showed no clear trend in the quietest trading this year. the dow jones industrial average gained 15.09 points to 2,050.07, in a session influenced largely by takeover news and speculation
volume on the new york stock exchange totaled 131.89 million shares, the lightest since a 111.58 million-share day on dec. 29
prices barely budged in the bond market, a sensitive barometer of interest rates and the economy. the treasury's closely watched 30-year bond declined [ point, or about $1.25 for every $1,000 in face amount. its yield, which moves inversely to price, edged up to 8.51 percent from 8.50 percent late friday
traders were reluctant to buy or sell aggressively, largely because of uncertainty about the january trade deficit numbers to be released by the commerce department on thursday
the markets have been fixated on the trade deficit for months because the economy's unprecedented reliance on imports is considered one of the most visible symbols of economic weakness and declining competitiveness
but the deficit narrowed in november and december, suggesting the protracted decline of the dollar over the past two years was helping u.s. manufacturers reclaim foreign and domestic markets from overseas competition
coleco industries inc., which is expected to miss an april 1 interest payment on its debentures, says that unless it can restructure its finances it may have to seek bankruptcy court protection
the toymaker announced monday it lost $98.8 million in the final quarter of 1987 and $105.4 million for the whole year
and chairman arnold c. greenberg said coleco has a $19 million interest payment due on debentures april 1, but will not make that payment
coleco and other major toy manufacturers were hit hard by declining sales last year. the losses announced by coleco monday follow deficits of $110.6 in fourth-quarter 1986 and $111.2 million for all of that year
the toymaker reported sales of $69 million in the last quarter of 1987, compared with $73.7 million for the same period a year earlier. its 1987 sales totaled $504.5 million, up slightly from $500.7 million in 1986
coleco said it planned to announce a restructuring plan by the end of this week. however, if all parties to the restructuring do not agree to the plan, ``the company could find itself in reorganization,'' said morton e. handel, coleco's executive vice president for corporate development
the company's short-term bank debt increased from $90.7 million in 1986 to $142.1 million in 1987. overall, coleco paid $59.6 million in interest during 1987, compared with $42.7 million in 1986
nearly $40 million of the 1987 interest was due to the $300 million in subordinated debentures coleco has outstanding. handel said the company will propose to replace those debentures with a combination of common stock, new debentures and debentures convertible into stock
if the owners of the debentures accept the proposed exchange, it would reduce some of coleco's interest expenses and convert some debt into positive ownership interest in the company
the company needs to get out from underneath its significant debt load to obtain profitibility. the company needs to take steps to ensure its survival,'' said gary jacobson, an analyst with kidder peabody &amp; co. in new york city
coleco has laid off more than 300 workers and taken other steps to cut costs
ford motor co. is recalling about 28,000 1987 and 1988 ford crown victoria and mercury grand marquis station wagons for inspection of seat belts that may have improperly installed retractors
ford also is recalling 9,300 1988-model lincoln continental cars for installation of spring seats on the rear torsion springs
seat belts in the station wagons' optional rear-facing auxiliary seats will be inspected and replaced, if necessary, ford said in a news release monday. the belts might fit too loosely or retract slowly if retractors were found to be installed on the wrong side of the seats, the statement said
the spring seats on the continentals are meant to prevent the spring from touching the rear tire if the spring breaks while in service, it said
of the 9,300 continentals being recalled, about 5,000 will be inspected to see whether inboard attachments of the driver's and right front seat belt assemblies were properly secured, the statement said. belts not properly secured to the anchor attachment could loosen or pull free in a collision, it said
inspections and necessary modifications will be made by ford or lincoln-mercury dealers at no cost to owners, the statement said. there were no reports of accidents or injuries involving any of the components involved with the recalls, the company said. pacific</head> bgng: the railroads; also moving on general news wires</note>
the interstate commerce commission today postponed a decision on whether to approve a $110 million merger that would make the regional missouri-kansas-texas railroad co. a part of the giant union pacific corp
icc chairman heather j. gradison canceled a scheduled vote, saying that commissioner j.j. simmons iii had failed to give his fellow commission members adequate time to review his proposed conditions for the merger
under agency rules, commissioners must distribute any amendments the day before a planned vote. simmons did not outline his proposals at today's brief session and, under commission rules, amendments are not made public until they are discussed at a meeting
no new meeting to consider the merger was scheduled immediately, and al brown, an icc spokesman, said it was unlikely that another vote will be set before next week
the railroads contend that consolidating operations would provide improved service at lower costs and ensure reliable long-term transportation, especially for midwestern grain shippers relying on the 3,100-mile mkt system known as the ``katy.''
other railroads have questioned whether the proposed merger will reduce competition, because the katy's lines generally parallel some union pacific routes from kansas and missouri to southern texas and the gulf coast. the union pacific is a 21,500-mile network formed by a rail merger six years ago
to address those concerns, union pacific has offered competing railroads the rights to use some trackage on proposed merger routes
without the merger, the icc has been told, the financially ailing katy could face problems surviving against bigger competitors. operating income for the katy declined from $37 million in 1981 to $5 million in 1986
the union pacific, the nation's third largest railroad system in terms of track mileage, serves about 20 states with routes from los angeles, san francisco and seattle in the west to chicago and new orleans. the company was formed in 1982 with the merger of the union pacific, missouri pacific and western pacific railroads
the katy serves six states, with mostly north-south routes running from omaha to the gulf coast in texas. a separate east-west route extends between kansas city and st. louis
union pacific, which filed an application in november 1986 seeking government approval of the katy acquisition, says the merger would produce operating savings of $61 million a year. company officials say grain shippers would benefit through a shorter, more direct single-line route to export markets in texas gulf ports
however, the merger would eliminate about 1,100 katy jobs because of closings of rail yards and repair shops. union pacific also plans to abandon 405 miles of track, mostly operated by katy, if the merger is approved
union pacific has taken steps to ease objections to the merger. for example, the company has agreed to pay $1 million to the southeast kansas community of parson in exchange for not opposing the merger. the city would lose about 300 katy jobs, with an estimated $8 million payroll, under the merger
united artists communications inc., an entertainment conglomerate with cable television systems and the nation's no. 1 theater chain, has announced the creation of new york-based corsair pictures
the subsidiary firm will develop films that cost between $3 million and $10 million, an amount considered modest by hollywood standards
stewart d. blair, president and chief executive officer of united artists, announced monday that corsair picture's first production would be ``the miss firecracker contest,'' a comedy written by pulitzer prize-winning playwright beth henley. actress holly hunter, who was nominated for an oscar for her role as a newscast producer in ``broadcast news,'' has been signed to star in the film
blair said the venture was a ``low-key experiment.''
we think there is a window for modestly priced, high-demographic films,'' blair said
we're looking for class. not art films, but not slash and gash movies either. we're not into teen exploitation films.''
frank perry, who was nominated for an oscar as best director for the movie ``david and lisa'' has been named to head corsair. perry had directed for pyramid films, also a subsidiary of united artists. corsair replaces pyramid films
blair expects to produce three or four films a year, he said
frank (perry) has done 17 movies and he's only been over budget once, and that was only be two percent,'' he said
most of the firm's movies will be for theater distribution, followed by sale to pay television or the video market. finally they will be sold to cable, he said
united artists owns 2,000 movie screens, making it the largest chain in the country
certainly having that number of screens gives you a leg up,'' blair said. ``but a movie has to be released across the board to the most screens for it to generally make sense.''
the stock market was unchanged in the early going today as reluctance by traders to take positions ahead of the government's upcoming release of trade data continued to dampen activity
